INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (7,'Agriculture','<p>Apprenticeships offer a huge range of opportunities for\r\nworking on livestock or arable farms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Farms vary enormously, from hill farms with a flock of\r\nsheep, to vast mechanised arable farms that grow crops for bio-fuel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you could learn how to prepare sites for\r\nplanting crops, operate a tractor with attachments, harvest and store crops,\r\nand maintain equipment and machines.</p><p>You\r\nmight learn how to look after large numbers of livestock, load and unload\r\nanimals for transport, and maintain the health and welfare of animals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra</p>\r\n','Farm worker, Tractor driver, Stock person, Machinery operator, Livestock technician, Shepherd','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,300 to £13,000','2012-11-07 10:56:51','2013-11-25 10:26:42',12,'Agriculture','This Apprenticeship offers a huge range of opportunities for working on livestock or arable farms.\r\nFarms vary enormously, from hill farms with a flock of sheep, to vast mechanised arable farms that may be growing crops for bio-fuel.\r\nAs an apprentice, the nature of your work will depend on your employer. Working for a small company could mean you handle a wide range of responsibilities – alternatively, working for a large company might mean you take on a more specialised role.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you might learn skills like how to prepare and cultivate sites for planting crops; operate a tractor with attachments; harvest and store crops; and maintain equipment and machines. If your employer deals with livestock, you might learn how to look after large numbers of livestock, load and unload animals for transport, and maintain the health and welfare of animals.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn more specialised skills like how to monitor crops or livestock and promote their growth. You could also learn how to apply pesticides and manage habitats.\r\nMost farm businesses are small, so you’ll find yourself playing an important role in a variety of tasks and developing plenty of useful skills along the way.','Level: Intermediate Apprenticeship (Level 2), Advanced Apprenticeship (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate\r\nLevel – Farm worker, Tractor driver, Stock person, Pig technician, Hatchery\r\nstaff\r\nAdvanced Level – Section head (pigs, dairy or beef), Agriculture machinery operator, Assistant farm manager, Livestock technician, Hatchery supervisor/charge hand (poultry), Shepherd','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,300–£13,000 depending on experience');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (8,'Animal care','<p>The animal care industry offers a range of opportunities,\r\nfrom working in large kennels and catteries, to training guide dogs for the\r\nblind, and dog handling within the armed forces.</p><p>Generally, you will deal with the health, welfare, handling\r\nand supervision of small animals – whether that’s working in a zoo or wildlife\r\npark, or for the RSPCA. It’s a dedicated profession, as animals need to be\r\nlooked after 365 days a year.</p><p>As an apprentice you could learn about:</p><ul><li>health checking</li><li>basic animal training</li><li>transporting animals</li><li>feeding, watering and exercise</li><li>advising customers and owners</li></ul><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra\r\n</p>','Animal groomer, Pet shop assistant, Dog handler, Zookeeper, Dog warden, Animal management technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £14,000','2012-11-07 11:14:54','2013-11-25 11:40:01',12,'Animal Care','This Apprenticeship is perfect for anyone wishing to work with animals. Many consider work in the animal care industry as one of the most fulfilling roles within the land-based sector, offering opportunities from working in large kennels and catteries to training guide dogs for the blind and dog handling within the armed forces.\r\nGenerally, work in this industry deals with the health, welfare, handling and supervision of small animals – whether that’s working in a zoo or wildlife park, or for the RSPCA. It’s a dedicated profession, as animals need to be looked after 365 days a year.\r\nAs an apprentice, you could find yourself working in many settings and with a range of different animals. You could be grooming dogs; looking after animals in a pet shop, kennel or cattery; assisting the breeding of pedigree animals; training guide dogs; or even taking\r\ncare of exotic animals in a zoo or wildlife park.\r\nYour Apprenticeship will vary depending on your employer, but you could learn about health checking; basic animal training; transporting animals; feeding, watering and exercising animals; advising customers and owners; or maintaining a clean and safe working environment.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship it is likely that you will take on more of a specialised or supervisory role and be involved in planning various activities. Particular health and safety training may be required for different areas of work.\r\nNo matter what type of animal you encounter on this Apprenticeship, they will all need the skilled attention of devoted and well-trained staff.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate\r\nLevel – Animal/Dog groomer, Pet shop assistant/Retail assistant, Animal care\r\nassistant, Dog handler (Uniformed Forces), Animal boarding assistant\r\nAdvanced Level – Zoo/ animal keeper, Dog groomer, Animal/dog trainer, Dog warden, Animal management technician','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000–£14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (9,'Environmental conservation','<p>This Apprenticeship covers roles that deal with the\r\nprotection of rural and urban landscapes, plants and animals, and countryside.</p><p>Environmental conservation covers a range of activities from recycling\r\nhousehold waste to habitat management and deals with local issues such as community recycling and national ones such as global warming.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you can choose between four routes:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>environmental conservation</li><li>access and recreation</li><li>rivers, coasts and waterways/ flood risk management</li><li>dry stone walling</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Upon completion of your training, you could work for a range\r\nof organisations from government departments to the voluntary sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra</p>\r\n','Estate worker, Ranger, Recycling officer, Conservation officer, Education officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000','2012-11-14 13:24:01','2013-11-25 11:57:27',12,'Environmental conservation','This Apprenticeship covers roles that deal with the protection of rural and urban landscapes, plants and animals, and countryside. Environmental conservation covers a range of activities from recycling household waste to habitat management. While ‘green’ issues play an important role in conservation, it’s really about using scientific knowledge to achieve solutions that will provide a sustainable environment. The scope of environmental conservation stretches from local issues (e.g. community recycling) to national ones (e.g. global warming).\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll choose between four routes: environmental conservation; access and recreation; rivers, coasts and waterways/flood risk management; or dry stone walling. The nature of the work depends on your employer, but you could be surveying and reporting on the condition of an outdoor area; encouraging people to enjoy the environments around them; carrying out habitat management work; or monitoring a section of river prone to floods.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn how to use environmental good practice at work, develop good working relations with community groups and others, and organise environmental projects. You might learn other advanced skills, like how to manage a team of volunteers, report on environmental change or produce site management plans.\r\nUpon completion of your training, you could work for a range of organisations from government departments to the voluntary sector.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Estate worker, Ranger, Recycling officer, Conservation officer\r\nAdvanced Level – Access/ recreation officer, Ecologist, Senior ranger, Education/interpretation officer, Senior estate worker, Environmental management officer','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (10,'Equine','<p>The equine industry is diverse and offers opportunities for working in livery yards, riding\r\nschools, racing yards, training yards or using harnessed horses.</p><p>Horses\r\nrepresent a major asset for their owners and need the skilled attention of\r\ndevoted and well-trained staff.</p><p>This Apprenticeship covers many\r\nspecialisms, all of which deal with the welfare, supervision and riding of horses.</p><p>Training will focus on either general horse care, racehorse care or harness\r\nhorse care, depending on the employer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra</p>\r\n','Groom, Trek assistant, Harness horse trainer, Jockey','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Minimum wage up to £18,000','2012-11-14 13:27:49','2013-11-25 12:02:35',12,'Equine','This Apprenticeship is suitable for those looking to work in the equine industry. It’s one of the most diverse industries within the land-based sector with opportunities for working in livery yards, riding schools, racing yards, training yards or using harnessed horses.\r\nHorses represent a major asset for their owners and need the skilled attention of devoted and well-trained staff.\r\nWhile this Apprenticeship covers many specialisms, all deal with the welfare, supervision and riding of horses. Your training will focus on either general horse care, racehorse care or harness horse care, depending on your employer. As an apprentice, you could find yourself in one of many job roles such as stable hand, groom, stud assistant or riding instructor. You’ll learn how to take care of horses, which will include everything from feeding and grooming through to exercising.\r\nThere are plenty of roles away from the stables, too: for example, trek assistants who help organise riding groups and ensure everyone stays safe.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll take on more responsibilities. You could be working towards becoming a trek leader, riding instructor or a performance rider.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Assistant groom (non-ride or ride), Assistant stud groom/hand, Trek assistant, Supporting harness horse trainer, Assistant groom (agriculture), Apprentice jockey, Conditional jockey\r\nAdvanced Level – Groom, Assistant yard manager, Trek leader, Intermediate instructor/ Level 3 coach, Jockey, Harness horse groom, Harness horse driver, Assistant harness horse trainer, Harness horse groom (agriculture)','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: National minimum wage up to £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (11,'Farriery','<p>This Advanced Level Apprenticeship is the only route in\r\nGreat Britain to become qualified as a registered farrier.</p><p>A farrier is a skilled craftsperson who makes and fits shoes\r\nfor horses’ feet according to the needs and welfare of the animal.</p><p>Increasingly, farriers work with vets and equine\r\nhospitals to provide corrective shoeing and surgical farriery.</p><p>This is an ancient craft that is still in\r\nhigh demand.</p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra\r\n','Farrier','Level 3 (Adv)','£30,000 (after 2 years training)','2012-11-14 13:30:26','2013-11-25 12:04:54',12,'Farriery','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship is the only route in Great Britain to become qualified as a registered farrier. Farriery, or the shoeing of horses and similar animals, is an ancient craft that is still in high demand.\r\nA farrier is a skilled craftsperson who makes and fits shoes for horses’ feet according to the needs and welfare of the animal. Increasingly, farriers are working with veterinary surgeons and equine hospitals to provide corrective shoeing and surgical farriery. Though a farrier is not a blacksmith (blacksmiths cannot fit shoes to the horse), they still\r\nneed training in blacksmithing in order to make or modify the shoes correctly.\r\nRoughly 100 apprentices are taken on in the industry every year, and competition for places is quite strong. Candidates must serve a period of Apprenticeship of four years and two months while employed by an Approved Training Farrier (ATF). Apprentices will learn specialist skills, such as how to assess the needs of a particular animal, making and modifying tools and shoes by forging, and trimming and shoeing equine feet.\r\nOnce qualified and registered, you can become your own boss and work hours that suit you and your clients – you’ll also be working outdoors and visiting a variety of people and places.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles:Registered farrier','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary:Most farriers are self-employed. If you’re good at your job, within a couple of years of graduating you should be turning over about £60,000 annually, from which you can expect an income of about £30,000.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (12,'Fencing','<p>Fences can be simple or incredibly hi-tech – from motorway barriers\r\nand zoo enclosures to prison perimeters and garden fences.</p><p>Installers need to\r\nknow how to work with all types of fencing and related construction materials,\r\nsuch as concrete. They must also be able to locate services and know how to\r\ncontact electricity, gas, phone and water companies to make sure post\r\nfoundations are clear of pipes and cables.</p><p>As an apprentice, you’ll learn how to operate and maintain\r\nrelevant tools; how to prepare sites for fence erection works; and how to\r\ncomplete work to customer requirements. You could also choose to learn how to\r\nerect specialist fencing, such as high-security fencing.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra <br></p>\r\n','Fence installer, Agricultural fencing contractor','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £14,000','2012-11-14 13:33:06','2013-11-25 12:11:15',12,'Fencing','This Apprenticeship deals with the construction and repair of fences. Fences can be simple or incredibly hi-tech, serving a variety of purposes – from motorway barriers and zoo enclosures to prison perimeters and garden fences. The range of projects is very broad, and so installers need to know how to work with all types of fencing and related\r\nconstruction materials, such as concrete. They must also be able to locate services and know how to contact electricity, gas, phone and water companies to make sure post foundations are clear of pipes and cables.\r\nA fence installer begins work by levelling and setting out, excavating and digging holes to take the posts (which could be made from concrete, timber, metal, or plastic), and then securing the posts. After cutting the fencing or panels to size, installers fix them to the posts and then sometimes paint and weatherproof the finished fence.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll assist a fence installer and learn how to operate and maintain relevant tools; how to prepare sites for fence erection works; and how to complete work to customer requirements. You could also choose to learn how to erect specialist fencing, such as high-security fencing.\r\nAs an Advanced Level apprentice you will learn to supervise others who are installing or maintaining fences.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: General fence installer, Lead fence installer, Agricultural fencing contractor, Contracts supervisor','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary:£10,000–£14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (13,'Floristry','<p>Florists use creativity and knowledge of plants and flowers\r\nto design and assemble floral displays.</p><p>Florists work indoors in a workroom or shop, or outdoors if running\r\na market stall or delivering floral arrangements to customers.</p><p>The industry is mostly made up of small businesses that are\r\noften linked together by larger organisations like Interflora and Flowergram\r\nUK.</p><p> Because businesses are small, florists must possess a variety of skills\r\nincluding sales, marketing, promotion, accounts and stock ordering.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Florist, Florist manager','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Minimum wage up to £25,000','2012-11-14 13:34:31','2013-11-25 12:17:43',12,'Floristry','Florists use creativity and knowledge of plants and flowers to design and assemble floral displays. These can be sold to the general public through shops and market stalls and can also be sold to businesses and event organisers.\r\nFlorists normally work between 35 and 40 hours per week, during normal shop opening times. There may be some early starts for delivery of flowers and extra hours\r\nto be worked at busy periods such as Valentine’s Day and Mother’s Day. Self-employed florists will need to work flexible hours to meet customer needs and there may be additional duties such as staff management, administration, and customer care.\r\nFlorists work indoors in a workroom or shop, or outdoors if running a market stall or delivering floral arrangements to customers. The industry is mostly made up of small businesses that are often linked together by larger organisations like Interflora and Flowergram UK. Because businesses are small, florists must possess a variety of skills including sales, marketing, promotion, accounts and\r\nstock ordering.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you’ll study units on how to maintain the condition of plants for sale, how to construct a variety of wedding and funeral arrangements, and how to process payments.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, your responsibilities will grow to include management, negotiation and sales techniques, and stock control. Florists require hardworking and trained staff, because the quality of their work directly affects the business.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Junior florist, Florist\r\nAdvanced Level – Florist manager, Senior florist','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: National minimum wage up to £25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (14,'Fish husbandry & fisheries management','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the day-to-day care of fish\r\nin a wide range of habitats and environments.</p><p>The industry is very broad,\r\ncovering river catchments, reservoirs, fish farms, aquaria and retail outlets.</p><p>As an apprentice, you’ll assist in maintaining fish health\r\nand welfare and may learn how to operate and maintain equipment; how to prepare\r\nfish for transport; and how the local environment may influence the work to be\r\ncompleted. You could also work on specific local projects, helping to improve\r\nhabitats for fish.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br></p>\r\n','Aquatics assistant, Fishery assistant, Water bailiff','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,000 to £16,000','2012-11-14 13:35:58','2013-11-25 12:14:39',12,'Fish husbandry and fisheries management','This Apprenticeship deals with the day-to-day care of fish in a wide range of habitats and environments. The industry is very broad, covering river catchments, reservoirs, fish farms, aquaria and retail outlets. The activities covered by related job roles are very diverse, ranging from monitoring, conserving and enhancing freshwater fish stocks and habitats, to helping both anglers and aquarium visitors enjoy their experience, to advising customers about their choice of species, equipment and care.\r\nOne of the main roles of any job in this industry is fish health and welfare, which includes:\r\n• Food and feeding\r\n• Handling and transportation\r\n• Environmental conditions\r\n• Predators\r\n• Stocking density\r\n• Disease prevention and control\r\n• Pollution prevention and control\r\n• Monitoring and record-keeping\r\n\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll assist in maintaining fish health and welfare and may learn how to operate and maintain relevant equipment; how to prepare fish for transport; and how the local environment may influence the work to be completed. You could also work on specific local projects, helping to improve habitats for fish.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)\r\n','Job roles: Aquatics assistant, Fishery assistant, Water bailiff','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £12,000–£16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (15,'Game & wildlife management','<p>Gamekeepers work in the countryside looking after areas\r\nmanaged for shooting. They make sure that there is\r\nenough game (such as grouse or pheasants) for shooting to take place.</p><p>Gamekeepers also manage wildlife habitats, working\r\nclosely with farm managers and forestry workers.</p><p>Their main tasks are rearing young birds from hatcheries, making sure\r\ngame is kept safe from predators, and making necessary repairs to equipment,\r\nbuildings and release pens. In the shooting season, they arrange shoots and\r\nhire beaters.</p><p>Other work includes managing woodland or burning heather,\r\nbuilding fences and clearing ponds and ditches.</p><p>Gamekeepers work flexible hours according to the season and\r\nwhen jobs need completing.</p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra\r\n','Beat keeper, Stalker, Ghillie, Gamekeeper','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £20,500','2012-11-14 13:37:25','2013-11-25 12:21:05',12,'Game and wildlife management','Gamekeepers work in the countryside looking after areas managed for shooting called beats or estates. They make sure that there is enough game on their shoots for shooting to take place. Game includes deer, and birds such as grouse, partridge and pheasant. Gamekeepers also actively manage wildlife habitats.\r\nGamekeepers work closely with farm managers and forestry workers, as well as clients who come to shoot. Their main tasks are rearing young birds from hatcheries, making sure game is kept safe from predators, and making necessary repairs to equipment, buildings and release pens. In the shooting season, they arrange shoots and hire beaters and pickers up.\r\nOther work includes managing woodland or burning heather, clearing land using power saws and other equipment, building fences and clearing ponds and ditches.\r\nGamekeepers work flexible hours according to the season and when jobs need completing. It may involve working long hours and can include early morning, evening and weekend\r\nwork. Most of their working time is spent outdoors in all weather conditions. There is a lot of walking, and work can involve a great deal of physical effort.\r\nYou’ll follow one of four routes within the Apprenticeship: upland/grouse, lowland, deer, or game rearing. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll choose\r\nbetween a general route, deer, or game rearing.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Under-keeper/beat keeper, Game farm worker, Understalker/ghillie\r\nAdvanced Level – Single-handed gamekeeper/head keeper, Game farm manager, Head stalker','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £12,000–£20,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (16,'Horticulture','<p>Horticulture is a great choice for anyone interested in\r\nworking outdoors and with plants.</p><p><b>Amenity horticulture</b> covers the\r\nplanning, creation and maintenance of urban and\r\nrural landscapes, including golf courses, parks and domestic\r\ngardens. Some businesses work on large projects like motorway landscape\r\nconstruction, while others provide services like domestic gardening.</p><p><b>Production horticulture</b> deals with the large-scale\r\nproduction of plants for food and ornamental purposes. This includes fruit,\r\nvegetables, herbs, mushrooms, plants, flowers and trees for sale.</p><p>Depending on your employer you could find yourself working\r\nas a landscaper or gardener. You may learn how to clear sites for planting or\r\nhow to maintain equipment.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra\r\n\r\n</p>\r\n','Gardener, Landscaper, Nursery worker, Groundsperson, Garden designer, Parks officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £15,000','2012-11-14 13:39:12','2013-11-25 12:24:40',12,'Horticulture','This Apprenticeship covers both Amenity and Production Horticulture which in turn covers a vast range of horticulture occupations, and would be a good choice for anyone interested in working outdoors and with plants.\r\nAmenity Horticulture includes landscaping, which covers the planning, creation and maintenance of designed landscapes, both urban and rural. A designed landscape is basically any piece of ground that had been changed to make it fit for purpose, rather than left in its wild state. Amenity horticulture also includes sports turf, golf courses, parks and planning of domestic gardens. It is possible that some businesses work on large projects like motorway landscape construction, while others provide services like domestic gardening.\r\nProduction Horticulture deals with the large-scale production of plants for food and ornamental purposes. This includes fruit, vegetables, herbs, mushrooms, plants, flowers and trees for sale. Businesses that an apprentice may be working in will range in size from small private nurseries to specialist farms. Horticulture is a major UK industry experiencing constant development through research.\r\nThe nature of the Apprenticeship will depend on your employer – you could find yourself working as a landscaper or gardener. You may learn how to clear sites for planting or how to maintain equipment.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you could move into a specialist or supervisory role and be involved in planning various activities. Particular health and safety training may be required for different areas of work.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles:Intermediate Level – Gardener, Landscaper, Nursery worker, Fruit and vegetable production worker, Machinery operator, Greenkeeper, Groundsperson\r\nAdvanced Level – Horticultural technician, Deputy head greenkeeper, Deputy head groundsman, Garden designer, Senior gardener, Gardener (historic and botanic), Parks officer','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £11,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (17,'Land-based engineering','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the maintenance and repair of\r\na range of mechanised equipment used in agriculture, horticulture and other\r\nland-based industries.</p><p>Land-based engineers work to solve problems using a\r\ncombination of scientific, technical and engineering knowledge.</p><p>There is a wide range of opportunities in this area.\r\nPossibilities include design development, manufacturing, field engineering,\r\nservice engineering, and sales and marketing.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra</p>\r\n','Groundcare technician, Service technician, Workshop supervisor','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000 to £24,000','2012-11-14 13:40:22','2013-11-25 12:27:25',12,'Land-based engineering','This Apprenticeship deals with the maintenance and repair of a range of mechanised equipment used in agriculture, horticulture and other land-based industries.\r\nLand-based engineers work to solve problems using a combination of scientific, technical and engineering knowledge.\r\nThere is a wide range of opportunities in this area. Possibilities include design development, manufacturing, field engineering, service engineering, and sales\r\nand marketing.\r\nAs an Apprentice, you’ll train as a technician and learn how to maintain a variety of machines. The exact nature of your work will depend on your employer – landbased engineers can work on complex agricultural machinery (e.g. tractors, combine harvesters, sprayers, planters and cultivators); ground care machinery (e.g. mowers, compact tractors); forestry machinery (e.g. chainsaws, wood chippers); fixed machinery (e.g. milking equipment); and construction machinery (e.g. trucks and mini diggers).\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn how to diagnose and repair more complex faults. To succeed in this area you’ll need a good level of mechanical\r\nskill and the ability to work from technical manuals. You’ll develop a thorough understanding of agricultural principles, and plenty of technical know-how.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Sports/groundcare technician, Service technician\r\nAdvanced Level – Demonstrator, Independent technician, Workshop supervisor','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £18,000–£24,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (18,'Nursing assistants in a veterinary environment','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the daily care of animals\r\nwithin a veterinary environment.</p><p>Most work centres around\r\ndomestic animals such as dogs, cats, rabbits and caged birds, but there may be\r\nother animals that require care including reptiles\r\nwhich are increasingly popular as pets.</p><p>As an apprentice, you’ll assist veterinary nurses and\r\nveterinary surgeons and learn how to maintain the health and welfare of animal\r\npatients including cleaning, feeding, handling and exercise.</p><p>You will also\r\nlearn about the codes of practice and will need to keep up-to-date with changes\r\nin the industry.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra</p>\r\n','Animal nursing assistant, Veterinary care assistant','Level 2 (Int)','From £10,500 to £12,500','2012-11-14 13:42:04','2013-11-25 12:32:01',12,'Nursing assistants in a veterinary environment','This Apprenticeship deals with the daily care of animals within a veterinary environment. Although the work will be mainly around domestic animals such as dogs, cats, rabbits and caged birds, there may be other animals that will require care including exotic species such as reptiles which are increasingly popular as pets. A nursing assistant in a veterinary environment apprentice can be employed by any veterinary practice, or centre with a veterinary clinic. All work undertaken by the apprentice will be under the direction of a veterinary surgeon and is subject to the Veterinary Surgeons Act 1966.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll assist veterinary nurses and veterinary surgeons and learn how to maintain the health and welfare of animal patients including cleaning, feeding, handling and exercise. You will also learn about the codes of practice and will need to keep up-todate with changes in the industry.\r\nIt is important to note that apprentices completing this Apprenticeship will not become a veterinary nurse upon completion but this Apprenticeship could allow\r\nprogression onto the Veterinary Nursing Apprenticeship subject to meeting the entry requirements of the Royal College of Veterinary Surgeons.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)\r\n','Job roles: Animal nursing assistant, Veterinary care assistant','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,500–£12,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (19,'Trees and timber','<p>The trees and timber industry includes the care, maintenance and management of trees, woodlands and forests, as well as\r\nthe production of wood and timber products.</p><p>Apprentices can chose to focus on:</p><p><b>Forestry</b> – managing forests and woodlands. Activities include maintaining woodlands, thinning and felling trees using\r\nchainsaws or harvesting machines.</p><p><b>Coppicing</b> – involves maintaining woodlands and the cutting of\r\ntree shoots at different stages for products such as firewood,\r\nwoodworking and craft materials.</p><p><b>Arboriculture</b> – the care and maintenance of trees for the\r\nconservation of landscapes and the preservation and safety of trees.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Lantra<br></p>','Forest worker, Forest ranger, Ground worker, Arboricultural officer, Woodland manager','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £14,000','2012-11-14 13:45:34','2013-11-25 12:35:09',12,'Trees and Timber','This Apprenticeship covers the main occupations within the trees and timber industry. This industry includes the establishment, care, maintenance and management of trees, woodlands and forests, as well as the production of wood and timber products. Trees are one of the world’s major natural resources, and an essential part of the environment.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll have the choice to focus on one of the main areas within the industry. One is forestry, or the science and practice of managing forests and woodlands – this covers everything from creating and caring for a community forest to raising young trees in a nursery and delivering timber to businesses that use wood. Forestry activities include maintaining woodlands, thinning and felling trees using chainsaws or harvesting machines.\r\nAnother area is coppicing, which involves maintaining woodlands and the cutting of tree shoots at different stages and times for a range of products such as firewood, woodworking and craft materials.\r\nLastly, arboriculture covers the care and maintenance of trees for the conservation of landscapes and the preservation and safety of trees.\r\nIn all of these areas, apprentices are required to take certificates of competency for the use of pesticides, chainsaws, and other machinery related to the job. In this line of work, you’ll need very good health and safety awareness and you will enjoy working outdoors.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Greenwood forest worker, Forest worker, Forest ranger, General worker, Base-level arborist (Ground worker)\r\nAdvanced Level – Community forester, Assistant arboricultural officer, Assistant head forester, Contractor (harvesting and/ or establishment), Social forester, Woodland manager, Team leader/supervisor','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: from £12,000–£14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (20,'Veterinary nursing','<p>Veterinary nursing is the care of\r\nanimals receiving treatment within a veterinary practice.</p><p>Veterinary nurses carry out a range of diagnostic tests, medical treatments and minor\r\nsurgical procedures under the supervision of a veterinary surgeon. They also educate owners about maintaining the health of their pets.</p><p>Veterinary nurse\r\ntraining involves clinically based training and at least two years of work\r\nwithin an approved training practice.</p><p>You’ll probably work with domestic animals such as cats,\r\ndogs, rabbits and caged birds – although you could find yourself working with\r\nhorses and farm animals too.</p><p>This is a job that requires compassion, scientific knowledge, confidence and a willingness to help out with some\r\nof the more unpleasant tasks involved in getting sick animals back to full\r\nhealth.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Lantra</p>\r\n','Veterinary nurse – small animal or equine','Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000','2012-11-14 13:47:39','2013-11-25 12:38:17',12,'Veterinary nursing','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship covers a range of skills and duties that support a veterinary surgeon. Veterinary nursing is the care of animals receiving treatment within a veterinary practice. Veterinary nurses will carry out a range of diagnostic tests, medical treatments and minor surgical procedures under the supervision of a veterinary surgeon; as well as educating owners about maintaining the health of their pets.\r\nVeterinary nurse training involves clinically based training and at least two years of work within an approved veterinary nurse training practice.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll be employed as a veterinary nursing assistant. You’ll probably work with domestic animals such as cats, dogs, rabbits and caged birds – although you could be working with horses and farm animals too.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll either be a senior veterinary nurse or vet practice manager helping to run the business side of things.\r\nIt’s a job that can be incredibly rewarding, but you’ll also have to deal with seriously sick or injured animals, and sometimes have to put them down. It’s a job that requires compassion, but not sentimentality; scientific knowledge; confidence when handling animals; and a willingness to help out with some of the more unpleasant tasks involved in getting sick animals back to full health.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Veterinary nurse – small animal/equine, Head veterinary nurse\r\n','Issuing Authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (21,'Barbering','<p>The demand for skilled barbers to cut and\r\nstyle hair is on the rise.</p><p>Aprentices learn to:</p><ul><li> give client\r\nconsultations</li><li>cut hair</li><li>trim &amp; shape facial hair</li><li>shampoo and condition\r\nhair &amp; scalp</li></ul><p>You could also learn to colour hair or cut basic\r\npatterns in hair.</p><p>You’ll be on your feet and working to please all sorts of\r\ncustomers, so a friendly nature and good sense of humour will come in handy.\r\nYour own appearance is also&nbsp; important, since customers want to know\r\nthat creating a good impression matters to you.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills Active</p>\r\n','Barber','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-14 14:33:58','2013-11-25 13:13:52',13,'Barbering','This Apprenticeship is for those interested in cutting and styling the hair of men and boys (those who also want to work on female hair should investigate the Hairdressing Apprenticeship). You’ll also learn about (and be tested on) other issues related to barbering, like hygiene, disposing of chemicals and working in a team.\r\nWith men putting almost as much effort into their appearances as women these days, the demand for skilled barbers to cut and style hair is on the rise.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you’ll learn how to give client consultations, cut hair, trim and shape facial hair and shampoo and condition hair and scalp. You could also choose to learn how to colour hair or cut basic patterns in hair.\r\nIf you take this as an Advanced Level Apprenticeship you may learn how to carry out a shave or provide facial massage.\r\nYou’ll be on your feet and working to please all sorts of customers, so a friendly nature and good sense of humour will come in handy. Your own appearance will also be important, since customers will want to know that creating a good impression matters to you.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Junior barber\r\nAdvanced level – Barber, Senior barber','Issuing Authority: Skills Active – www.skillsactive.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000–£16,000 depending on experience');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (22,'Beauty therapy','<p>Beauty therapy covers a range of treatments that improve\r\npeople’s wellbeing by making them look and feel better, from simple facials and\r\nmake-up jobs to waxing.</p><p>As a beauty therapy apprentice, you’ll learn a range of\r\nskills and techniques, such as how to improve facial skin conditions, wax body\r\nhair, spray tan, shape and colour brows, perform hand and foot treatments, and\r\napply make-up.</p><p>Most therapists are based in salons, although some can work\r\nin hospitals, resorts and even cruise liners.</p><p>After successfully completing an Apprenticeship, you could\r\ngo on to study specialist areas like massage, aromatherapy, hydrotherapy or\r\nreflexology.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills Active</p>\r\n\r\n<p><br></p>\r\n','Beauty therapist, Massage therapist, Make-up artist','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £17,000','2012-11-14 14:35:38','2013-11-25 13:39:05',13,'Beauty therapy','This Apprenticeship is about improving people’s wellbeing by making them look and feel better. Beauty Therapy covers a range of treatments, from simple facials and make-up jobs to waxing.\r\nAs a Beauty Therapy apprentice, you’ll assist senior therapists and learn a range of skills and techniques, such as how to improve facial skin conditions, wax body hair, spray tan, shape and colour brows, perform hand and foot treatments, and apply make-up.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll work as a beauty therapist, learning techniques like body massage as well as more complicated electronic treatments to remove unwanted hair or improve skin condition.\r\nYou’ll work closely with clients and will need the ability to put them at ease, and generally be pleasant and personable.\r\nMost therapists are based in salons, although some can work in hospitals, resorts and even cruise liners. It can be a glamorous career choice: with further training you might become a make-up artist for film and TV, or help develop new products. In the future you might run your own salon, or work for individual clients.\r\nAfter successful completion of an Apprenticeship, you could go on to study specialist areas like massage, aromatherapy, hydrotherapy or reflexology.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Junior beauty therapist\r\nAdvanced level – Beauty therapist, Beauty massage therapist, Make-up artist','Issuing Authority: Skills Active – www.skillsactive.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (23,'Hairdressing','<p>This Apprenticeship covers all the basics of hairdressing.</p><p>As an apprentice, your duties are likely to include booking\r\nappointments, shampooing, conditioning, drying and styling hair, and mixing and\r\napplying hair colouring.</p><p>You’ll study topics such as hair and skin testing, the\r\neffects of chemicals on hair and skin, and the principles of hair colour\r\nselection. There’s also the option to learn about promoting products, perming,\r\nor relaxing different types of hair.</p><p>You’ll spend a lot of time on your feet, and it’s important\r\nthat you look smart (and have an even better hairstyle). Good communication\r\nplays a role, too – you’ll need to understand exactly what your customer wants\r\nin order to make them happy.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills Active</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Junior stylist, Stylist, Hairdresser','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-14 14:37:23','2013-11-25 13:41:37',13,'Hairdressing','This Apprenticeship covers all the basics of hairdressing. As a Hairdressing apprentice, you’ll work as a salon junior, assisting senior staff while training as a junior stylist.\r\nDuties are likely to include booking appointments, shampooing, conditioning, drying and styling hair, and mixing and applying hair colouring. You’ll study hairdressing topics such as hair and skin testing, the effects of chemicals on hair and skin, and the principles of hair colour selection – there’s also the option to learn about promoting products, perming, or relaxing different types\r\nof hair.\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices take their learning a step further by developing their cutting and colouring skills so they can carry out all the latest fashion techniques – and maybe even determine the fashion looks of the future.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you’ll spend a lot of time on your feet, and it’s important that you look smart (and have an even better hairstyle). Good communication plays a role, too – you’ll need to understand exactly what your customer wants in order to make them happy.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Junior stylist\r\nAdvanced level – Stylist, Hairdresser','Issuing Authority: Skills Active – www.skillsactive.co.uk ','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £10,000–£16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (24,'Nail services','<p>Nail technicians use a variety of techniques to clean, decorate, extend and pamper nails.</p><p>As an apprentice you’ll learn to perform manicures,\r\npedicures, natural nail wraps, hand and nail treatments, nail extensions and\r\nbasic nail art techniques.</p><p>Working as a nail technician requires social skills as\r\ntechnical ones – you’ll need to enjoy working with people in addition to\r\nmanaging appointments, creating new designs, and following strict health and\r\nsafety procedures.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills Active</p>\r\n','Junior nail technician, Nail technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £15,000','2012-11-14 14:38:35','2013-11-25 13:46:01',13,'Nail services','This Apprenticeship covers a range of creative skills used in nail services, such as cleaning, decorating, extending and pampering nails. Nail technicians use a variety of techniques, from hot oil treatments to airbrushing. They can also spot, and in some cases treat, certain nail and skin diseases.\r\nAs a Nail Services apprentice, you’ll work as a junior nail technician. You’ll assist senior nail technicians in performing manicures, pedicures, natural nail wraps, hand and nail treatments, nail extensions and basic nail art techniques.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you could work as a nail technician or even a session and photographic nail artist. You’ll have the opportunity to develop specialist skills in creative nail work by planning, designing and creating images for nail art – you may even get involved with photoshoots or competitions. You’ll also learn how to maintain and repair a range of artificial nail systems. Working as a nail technician requires social skills as technical ones – you’ll need to enjoy working with people in addition to managing appointments, creating new designs, and following strict health and safety procedures.\r\nThis career offers opportunities to progress into salon management or sales and marketing for product companies.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Junior nail technician\r\nAdvanced level – Nail technician','Issuing Authority: Skills Active – www.skillsactive.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £10,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (25,'Spa therapy','<p>Spa therapists help to improve their clients’ overall\r\nwellbeing by providing a variety of body treatments, from facials to water\r\ntreatments. They can offer relaxation treatments or focus on health and fitness\r\nby working alongside nutritionists.</p><p>This is an Advanced Level Apprenticeship, so you must first\r\ncomplete a Level 2 qualification in another subject, such as Beauty Therapy or\r\nNail Services, or be able to show relevant experience.</p><p>Working as a spa therapist, you might carry out spa\r\ntreatments, body and head massage, tanning and electrotherapy treatments.\r\nYou’ll also learn about heat and wet treatments – including flotation, sauna,\r\nsteam and hot tub.</p><p>Jobs are available at home and abroad, in resorts, cruise\r\nliners, and health clubs.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills Active</p><p></p>\r\n','Spa therapist','Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £14,000','2012-11-14 14:40:04','2013-11-25 13:48:52',13,'Spa therapy','Spa therapists help to improve their clients’ overall wellbeing by providing a variety of body treatments, from facials to water treatments. They can offer relaxation treatments or focus on health and fitness by working alongside nutritionists.\r\nThis is an Advanced Level Apprenticeship, so apprentices must first complete a Level 2 qualification in another subject, such as Beauty Therapy or Nail Services, or be able to show relevant experience (this could include a background in hairdressing, fitness or nutrition, as spa therapy is a diverse industry).\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices will work as spa therapists and carry out spa treatments, body and head massage, tanning, and electrotherapy treatments. You’ll also become knowledgeable in all aspects of heat and wet treatments – including flotation, sauna, steam and hot tub – and learn how to set up and monitor spa facilities. You might specialise in one or two areas, or have a broader role – either way; this Advanced Level Apprenticeship is a good step up the ladder.\r\nThe spa therapy industry is diverse and growing, with jobs available at home and abroad in resorts, cruise liners, and health clubs. There’s also plenty of room for growth – you can extend your skills by gaining qualifications in holistic therapies, nutrition and first aid.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Spa therapist','Issuing Authority: Skills Active – www.skillsactive.co.uk','','25/11/13','','  Starting salary: £12,000–£14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (26,'Business & administration','<p>Administrators handle the day-to-day tasks in an office and\r\nmake sure things run smoothly. Without them, information would be hard to find,\r\nmeetings would be missed and businesses would be less productive.</p><p>Your exact duties will depend on your employer. You may be\r\ntyping up board meeting documents, putting financial information together in\r\nspreadsheets, sending the daily post, negotiating with customers, managing\r\nprojects or coordinating events. You need a strong sense of responsibility,\r\naccuracy and attention to detail.</p><p>Administration roles are an excellent starting point to move\r\ninto management once you have more experience.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills CFA</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Secretary, Administration assistant, Clerical assistant, PA','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £12,000 to £18,000','2012-11-15 11:17:04','2013-11-25 13:55:22',1,'Business and Administration','Administrators handle the day-to-day tasks in an office and make sure things run smoothly – 97% of employers say that effective administration is essential to their business, so they do a crucial job.\r\nThe term ‘administration’ covers roles that involve organising people and resources, including executive assistants, secretaries, office supervisors, administration team leaders, administration assistants, data entry clerks and office juniors. Without them, information would be hard to find, meetings would be missed and businesses would be less productive.\r\nAs a business and administration apprentice, your exact duties will depend on your employer. It’s likely that you’ll be working with a team or member of staff to handle various tasks. You may be typing up board meeting documents, putting financial information together in spreadsheets, sending the daily post, negotiating with customers, managing projects or coordinating events. This sort of work requires a strong sense of responsibility, accuracy and attention to detail.\r\nOne of the great things about business and administration is that you can work almost anywhere. With your transferable skills, you could be working in a record company or a charity. Administration roles are also an excellent starting point to move into management once you have more experience.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Junior secretary, Administration assistant, Clerical assistant\r\nAdvanced Level – PA/ Secretary, Office administrator, Administration clerk\r\nHigher – Office manager, Administration team leader, Personal assistant, Business development executive','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (27,'Human resource management','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n\r\n<p>Human resources (HR) professionals recruit, train and develop employees, and look at how they get rewarded.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They deal with legal issues, help to shape the culture of an organisation, and focus on what keeps their colleagues productive and engaged.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an HR apprentice, you may work on areas such as:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>performance and reward</li>\r\n	<li>employee engagement</li>\r\n	<li>employee relations</li>\r\n	<li>organisation development</li>\r\n	<li>learning and talent development</li>\r\n	<li>recruitment and resourcing</li>\r\n	<li>talent planning</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>After completing this Apprenticeship, you will attain Associate Member status of the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>I<b>ssuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p>','HR officer, HR assistant, HR executive','Level 5 (Higher)','From £25,000','2012-11-15 11:18:38','2013-11-25 14:00:26',1,'Human resource management','HR covers a wide range of interconnected activities, but essentially it is about generating performance through people. HR professionals recruit, train and develop employees, and look at how they get rewarded. They’re dealing with legal issues, helping to shape the culture of their organisations, and focusing on what keeps their colleagues productive and engaged.\r\nEvery organisation is different and so is the way their HR function operates. From generalist roles to specialist positions, there are many different functions, depending on the job role and the organisation’s size and needs. As an HR apprentice, you may work on areas such as performance and reward, employee engagement, employee relations, organisation development, learning and talent development, recruitment and resourcing, and talent planning.\r\nWhether you are a young person, changing careers or up-skilling, the Higher Apprenticeship in Human Resource Management promises to provide you with the knowledge and experience to develop a long-lasting career in HR. On completion of this Apprenticeship, apprentices will attain Associate Member status of the Chartered Institute of Personnel and Development (CIPD).','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: HR officer, HR assistant, HR executive','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): Average HR salaries start at £24,375 for a graduate-level HR officer, rising to £100,000 for an HR director and £200,000 or more for a group HR director. Some FTSE20 group HR directors can earn £500,000+');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (28,'Enterprise','<p>Enterprising skills such as decision-making, negotiating and\r\nnetworking are vital for any business that wants to stay competitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn to develop\r\nbusiness opportunities, manage finances, develop and manage people, and manage\r\noperations.</p><p>You will learn to be resourceful and innovative, to turn an\r\nopportunity into a business idea and to make things happen within a business\r\nenvironment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a smaller company you could be involved in aspects of\r\nrunning and managing the business, while in a larger organisation you might be\r\nallocated to specific projects within a department.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p><p></p>\r\n','Trainee business development consultant, Junior enterprise consultant','Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-15 11:21:52','2013-11-25 13:57:35',1,'Enterprise','Enterprise can take many forms, but is most often associated with business enterprise, involving the ownership and management of your own business. The development of successful enterprises plays a key role in stimulating economic growth in the UK, creating jobs and wealth as well as encouraging innovation, competitiveness and market diversity.\r\nEnterprising skills such as decision-making, negotiating and networking are vital for any business that wants to stay competitive, and the application of these skills within an organisation is essential if businesses are to survive and grow, improve the performance of their best staff and address weaknesses that can affect productivity and performance.\r\nAs an Enterprise apprentice you will gain knowledge and a set of skills around developing business opportunities, managing finances, developing and managing people, and managing operations. You will learn to be resourceful and innovative, to turn an opportunity into a business idea and to make things happen within a business environment. By proposing new and different ways of working you will help to add value to a business.\r\nThe roles you take on will depend very much on the business that you work for. In a smaller company you could be involved in a variety of aspects of running and managing the business, while in a larger organisation you could be allocated to specific projects within a department, perhaps planning, supporting team members, monitoring work or presenting ideas to members of staff and giving feedback.\r\nYou will need to have plenty of energy and enthusiasm as well as a ‘can do’ attitude and a desire to learn and contribute. Good basic numeracy, literacy and communication skills are a must, as is a basic understanding of how business works and different ways of doing business. If you have previously been involved in any kind of enterprising task – such as running a club at school, a work placement or voluntary work – this will also stand you in good stead.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Trainee business development consultant, Junior enterprise consultant, Team member, Business development assistant, Enterprise consultant','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: The varied nature of the job roles suitable for the Enterprise Apprenticeship means that salaries will vary considerably.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (29,'Business innovation & growth','<pre>&lt;span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"&gt;&lt;span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"&gt;&lt;b&gt; Higher Apprenticeship &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</pre><p>\r\n\r\nInnovation and growth allow businesses and organisations to successfully compete locally, nationally and in the global market where appropriate.\r\n</p><p>Innovation is more than creating brand new products and services; it is about improving what already exists, developing a new mindset for conducting business and providing a foundation for growing businesses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you are an innovative and creative thinker, able to multi-task, communicate, take responsibility and make decisions, then you may have the skills needed to become a Business innovation &amp; growth apprentice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p>\r\n','Business development manager, Marketing manager, Product development technician','Level 5 (Higher)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-15 11:23:14','2013-11-25 13:59:17',1,'Business innovation and growth','Innovation and growth are central drivers of economic development. They allow businesses and organisations to successfully compete locally, nationally and in the global market where appropriate, and are a source of improvement to the quality of everyday life. Innovation is more than creating brand new products and services; it is about improving what already exists, developing a new mindset for conducting business and providing a foundation for growing businesses.\r\nIf you are an innovative and creative thinker, able to multi-task, communicate, take responsibility and make decisions, then you may have the skills needed to become a Business Innovation and Growth apprentice. \r\nAs an apprentice you will be developing your entrepreneurial talent. Your exact duties will depend on your employer, job role and the sector in which you are working. However, you may be involved in reviewing business processes, undertaking product and service development, conducting research and much more.\r\nThe Business Innovation and Growth Higher Apprenticeship is suitable for a large range of jobs across all sectors, both internal and external facing. Roles may involve business development, business improvement, change management, strategic planning, research and development, and product and service development.','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: roles may be very innovation focused, e.g. Business development manager, Marketing manager, Product development technician, Head of innovation. More general roles would include Manager, Customer service officer, Operations manager, Supervisor.','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): the varied nature of the job roles suitable mean that salaries will vary considerably. Salaries start at around £10,000 p.a. for junior positions, rising to £30,000 for mid-level positions. Someone holding a permanent sen');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (30,'IT application specialist','<p>Over 20 million people in the UK use IT in their jobs, but\r\nmany struggle with applications and general computing skills.</p><p>This\r\nApprenticeship will help you develop the skills you need to teach someone in\r\nfinance to process account details more efficiently, help stock controllers\r\nkeep track of merchandise, or helping a secretary set up an online company\r\ndiary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll learn how to operate computers and databases, as well\r\nas how to use and maintain IT systems and networks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever role you take on you’ll be part of a fast-moving,\r\never-changing sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> e-skills UK</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','IT clerk, Website technician, Data administrator, Digital assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-15 11:27:00','2013-11-25 14:16:58',1,'IT application specialist','This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of general computing and IT skills that can be applied in many job roles and industries.\r\nIt’s almost impossible to picture a world without computers – businesses would grind to a halt, information would be incredibly slow to find, and there would be loads of paper to file away. Luckily, computers are here to stay, and each day their capabilities become more complex and powerful. That’s why IT is one of the most important industries out there.\r\nOver 20 million people in the UK use IT in their jobs, but many struggle with applications and general computing skills. This Apprenticeship will help you develop the skills you need for your job – whether for teaching someone in finance to process account details more efficiently; helping stock controllers keep track of merchandise; or helping a secretary set up an online company diary.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll learn how to operate computers and databases, as well as how to use and maintain IT systems and networks.\r\nIT is an increasingly important area, and whatever role you take you’ll be part of a fast-moving, ever-changing sector.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: IT clerk, Website technician, Data administrator, Digital assistant','Issuing Authority: e-skills UK – www.e-skills.com','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): varies once qualified');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (31,'IT, software, web & telecoms L2/L3','<p>IT, software, web &amp; telecoms professionals work in a broad range of digital\r\ntechnologies that help us use and share information.</p><p>All jobs require good people skills as well as \r\ntechnical skills.\r\n\r\n</p><p>Apprentices can focus on telecoms or IT:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Telecoms</b> covers\r\nbroadband, mobile phones and satellite communications. Apprentices learn about\r\ncustomer care, system security, managing software development, and basic IT\r\napplications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>IT</b> professionals\r\ndevelop software or websites, help companies set up new systems, or train\r\npeople to use IT facilities. IT apprentices study software installation,\r\ncommunication skills and technical fault diagnosis, and gain an IT\r\nqualification from a recognised group such as Microsoft or CompTIA<b>.</b></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> e-skills UK <br></p>\r\n','Business analyst, IT trainer, Software developer, Web designer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £15,000','2012-11-15 11:29:10','2013-11-25 14:09:12',1,'IT, software, web and telecoms professionals','The Intermediate and Advanced level Apprenticeships cover work in a broad range of digital technologies that help us use and share information, such as mobile phones, computers, broadband provision, and satellite communications. IT and telecoms jobs are no longer just about the technology. All jobs now require you to have good people skills as well as the technical skills you’ll gain during your Apprenticeship.\r\nApprentices have the choice of focusing on either telecoms or IT. Telecoms covers broadband, mobile phones and satellite communications. It’s a fast-moving sector, so apprentices should have a keen interest in new technology. Telecoms apprentices will learn things like customer care, system security, managing software development, and basic IT applications.\r\nThe IT industry develops computer solutions that help businesses and individuals become more successful in their work. IT professionals serve customers in all types of business. They could be developing software or websites, helping companies set up new systems, or training people to use their IT facilities. IT apprentices will study software installation, communication skills and technical fault diagnosis, and gain an IT qualification from a recognised group such as Microsoft or CompTIA.\r\nThe industry is looking for 142,000 new workers over the next three years, so the career prospects are excellent.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Business analyst, Help desk operator, IT trainer, Software developer, Technical author, System support technician/Engineer, Web designer, IT architecture and security, Aerial rigging, Equipment wirer and assembler, Field operations, International networks, Mobile switching engineer, Network management, Network planning, Radio base station engineer, Radio repair technician, Radio systems design engineer, Satellite communications, Systems production','Issuing Authority: e-skills UK – www.e-skills.com','','25/11/13','','Starting salaries vary: The minimum is about £100 a week, although the average is £200, and salaries are often up to £12,000–£15,000 a year.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (32,'IT, software, web & telecoms L4','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n \r\n<p>If you want an exciting and rewarding career in IT, this is a great new way to get experience and qualifications while earning a salary.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll be employed by an organisation that has technology at its heart and you will train for recognised qualifications. You’ll use your new skills to tackle real business tasks in the workplace and you will learn from the best minds in the industry in a fast-paced environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Roles for apprentices include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>IT project manager</b> – oversee the development of computer systems to meet clients’ needs</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Analyst developer</b> –&nbsp; research, design and write new software programs</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Security analyst</b> – assess risks to systems, develop and design security plans</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Entry requirements:</b> two A-levels or an Advanced Apprenticeship in ICT</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> e-skills UK</p>','IT project manager, IT consultant, Database analyst, IT security analyst','Level 4 (Higher)','Average starting salary £200/week','2012-11-15 11:32:24','2013-11-25 14:08:43',1,'IT, software, web and telecoms professionals – Higher Apprenticeship','If you want an exciting and rewarding career in IT, this Higher Apprenticeship is a great new way to get the experience and qualifications you need while earning a salary. You’ll be employed by an organisation that has technology at its heart and you will train for recognised qualifications. From day one, you’ll use your new skills to tackle real business tasks in the workplace and you will learn from the best minds in the industry in a fast-paced environment.\r\nThe mix of qualifications and experience you will gain will stand you in good stead for a rewarding and successful career in IT and as an apprentice you could work in any one of a broad variety of roles. For example, you might work as an IT project manager, overseeing the development of computer systems to meet a client’s business needs, or as an analyst developer, researching, designing and writing new software programs. As a security analyst you would be responsible for assessing risks to systems, and developing and designing security plans to minimise potential threats.\r\nThere are tough requirements to get onto this Higher Apprenticeship – you will need two A-levels (or an equivalent qualification) or to have successfully completed an Advanced Apprenticeship in ICT – and you will need to be prepared to work hard as you will be studying for a qualification while working full time. Some higher apprentices do a Foundation Degree, while many others do qualifications such as HNCs or HNDs.\r\nOnce you have completed your Apprenticeship, however, you will be in a good position to progress into managerial or team leader roles. Career prospects are good as IT skills are always in demand and employers recognise the energy, creativity and passion that apprentices bring to the business.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: IT project manager, IT consultant, Software and applications developer, Database analyst, IT security analyst, Network professional, Business analyst; fast-track progression into manager/team leader roles','Issuing Authority: e-skills UK – www.e-skills.com','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salaries vary: The minimum is about £100 a week, although the average is £200, and salaries are often up to £12,000–£15,000 a year.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (33,'Learning & development','<p>Training and developing people in the workplace is a growing\r\nfield of employment.</p><p>Skilled personnel are often required to train others and this Apprenticeship will give you the\r\nskills you need to be a workplace trainer.</p><p>This Apprenticeship would also be for you if\r\nyou were wanted to take on a wider training role and eventually move into\r\nmanagement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills for Justice<br></p>\r\n','Training development officer, Learning centre supervisor, Assessor, Skills trainer, Instructor','Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000 to £18,000','2012-11-15 11:33:30','2013-11-25 14:18:32',1,'Learning and development','This Apprenticeship is designed for those interested in the training/learning and development/work-based learning industry.\r\nEncouraged by Government initiatives aimed at re-skilling and up-skilling the national workforce, involvement in training and developing others in the workplace is a growing field of employment. It is often the case that skilled personnel are required to train others without themselves receiving training in how to train. This Apprenticeship has been developed to redress this balance and would give you recognition of the skills of the workplace trainer. This Apprenticeship would also be for you if you were wishing to take on a wider training role and move on eventually into management.\r\nAt the end of your Apprenticeship, you could be working in a stand-alone training organisation, in a corporate training department or as an in-house stand-alone trainer. An Apprenticeship in Learning and Development would also provide a sound basis to undertake further learning and development of your career.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Training development officer, Training officer, Learning centre supervisor, Assessor/Verifier, Work-based learning co-ordinator, Learning and development advisor, Skills trainer/Instructor','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','','25/11/13','',' Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (34,'LARIMS','<p>This Apprenticeship covers roles in <b>libraries, archives,\r\nrecords and information management services (LARIMS)</b>.</p><p>Working in a library you could find yourself organising a storytelling\r\nsession for children, helping people learn to use a computer, or working with\r\nsomeone to trace their family tree as well as cataloguing and indexing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Archivists take care of collections of historical items and\r\ndocuments in companies and communities, working with all types of materials,\r\nfrom books and maps to film and electronic files.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Information services work can involve writing reports,\r\nmanaging intranets or website content, or running workshops for staff.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All roles requires organisation and excellent customer\r\nservice skills to help people find what they’re looking for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice<br></p>\r\n','Information assistant, Library assistant, Archive assistant, Learning support assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000','2012-11-15 11:34:43','2013-11-25 14:43:22',1,'Libraries, archives, records and information management services','This Apprenticeship covers roles in libraries, archives, records and information management services (LARIMS) – all of which exist to give people the information they want to find.\r\nPeople working in libraries undertake a wide range of functions – you’re as likely to be organising a storytelling session for children, helping people learn to use a computer, or working with someone to trace their family tree, as you are to be cataloguing and indexing resources.\r\nArchivists take care of collections of historical items and documents in companies and communities, working with all types of materials, from books and maps to film and electronic files.\r\nIncreasingly, the best companies are those which make the best use of knowledge and information, with specialist staff ensuring that the right information is easily available to colleagues and customers. Information services work can involve writing reports, managing intranets or website content, running workshops for staff on adopting best practice, or helping people find the right information.\r\nWorking in information services and libraries requires organisation and excellent customer service skills in order to help people find what they’re looking for. This Apprenticeship is a good base for accessing a wide range of opportunities and occupational choices in the LARIMS sector, for undertaking further learning and development in the LARIMS sector or other related sectors, or for moving on to further education.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Information assistant, Library assistant, Archive assistant, Records assistant, Learning support assistant\r\nAdvanced Level – Archive coordinator, Senior library assistant, Information services coordinator, Library services supervisor','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (35,'Management','<p>The best leaders and managers are innovative, creative, and\r\ninspirational.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Managers and team leaders oversee employees or departments\r\nto make sure they carry out their duties as required. It’s up to them to make\r\nthe most of company resources (products, people, money, time) to keep the\r\nwheels turning and generate a profit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your role may involve:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>planning and allocating work</li><li>giving feedback</li><li>managing conflict</li><li>resolving problems</li><li>project management</li><li>agreeing budgets</li><li>improving customer service.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>It helps to be a natural leader and good communication\r\nskills are a must. In some small businesses there may be only one manager,\r\nwhile large organisations will have several ranks of junior managers, finance\r\nmanagers, sales managers and so on.</p>\r\n<p>The following Apprenticeships are available:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Team leading</b> – Level 2 (Int)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Management</b> – Level 3 (Adv), Level 4 (Higher)<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Leadership &amp; management</b> – Level 5 (Higher)</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p><p></p>\r\n','Team leader, Floor manager, Supervisor, Assistant manager, Junior NCO (armed forces)','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4,5 (Higher)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-15 11:45:03','2013-11-25 14:46:05',1,'Management','Management and leadership skills have a major impact on the development, productivity and performance of organisations of all sizes and across all sectors of the economy. The best leaders and managers are innovative, creative, visionary and inspirational.\r\nManagers and team leaders oversee one or more employees or departments to make sure they carry out assigned duties as required. It’s up to them to make the most of company resources (products, people, money, time) in order to keep the wheels turning and generate a profit.\r\nManagers need a good understanding of business strategy to make smart decisions. It’s a big job involving many tasks, motivating employees to reach their potential and creating a strong corporate culture so that people will want to work for the company.\r\nAs an apprentice your role will vary depending on the level and sector in which you are employed. You may be involved in planning, allocating and monitoring the work of the team, giving feedback, briefing teams, supporting team members, managing conflict, resolving problems, procuring supplies, project management, agreeing budgets and managing and improving customer service. You will need to be sensitive to issues such as ethnicity, culture, gender and disability and be aware of the potential for different and more creative approaches that diversity in general brings.\r\nIt helps to be a natural leader and good communication skills are a must. There are many types of management roles. In some small businesses there may be only one manager, while large organisations will have several ranks of junior managers, finance managers, sales managers and so on.\r\nGood managers are essential to the success of any business (this is reflected in their pay packets each month) and the skills gained on this Apprenticeship are transferable to any business or industry sector.\r\nTeam Leading (Intermediate Apprenticeship) – The Intermediate Level Apprenticeship in Team Leading has been developed to support those working as team leaders, section leaders, floor managers, help desk managers, trainee supervisors, team co-ordinators and other team leader positions.\r\nManagement (Advanced Apprenticeship, Higher Apprenticeship) – The Advanced Level Apprenticeship has been developed to support those working as first line managers, section managers, assistant managers, trainee managers, senior supervisors, junior non-commissioned officers (armed forces) and other management positions. At Higher Level, apprentices might take on a roles as a manager, head of function or area manager.\r\nLeadership & Management (Higher Apprenticeship) – The Leadership & Management Higher Apprenticeship has been developed to support those working as managers, senior managers, heads of department, directors and other senior management positions.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4, Level 5)','Job roles: Intermediate – Team leader, Floor manager, Trainee supervisor\r\nAdvanced – Section manager, Assistant manager, Senior supervisor, Junior noncommissioned officer (armed forces)\r\nHigher – Area manager, Senior manager, Head of department, Director','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org ','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: Managers work in all industries, so salaries vary');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (36,'Marketing','<p>You may not realise it, but your everyday life is affected\r\nby the work of marketers: it is in the adverts you see, the websites you visit.\r\n\r\n</p><p>Every time you think of a brand, or slogan, you are responding\r\nto marketing activities. Marketing is the foundation of business activity and\r\nessential to commercial success.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Marketing involves:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>direct marketing (via mail, email or telephone)</li><li>market research</li><li>public relations</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you might learn to create a marketing plan\r\nfor products/services, manage budgets, and carry out research.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p><p></p>\r\n','Junior marketing executive, Market researcher, Advertising account executive, PR officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000 to £18,000','2012-11-15 11:46:18','2013-11-25 14:44:47',1,'Marketing','Marketing is a creative industry at the heart of business. It is concerned with finding the needs and wants of people, developing a product or service that meets that need and helping create a desire for what has been created. You may not realise it, but your everyday life is affected by the work of marketers: it is in the adverts you see, the websites you visit. Every time you think of a brand, or slogan, you are responding to marketing activities.\r\nMarketing is the foundation of business activity and essential to commercial success. It is hard to imagine a successful organisation that does not heed marketing principles. Marketing involves several specialisms including: direct marketing (communicating directly with the consumer via mailings, emails or telephone calls); market research (gathering and analysing information on customers, competitors and the market); and public relations (the public image of your product or organisation). The Intermediate Level Apprenticeship and Advanced Level Apprenticeship in Marketing cover all these areas.\r\nWithin the Apprenticeship, the nature of the work will depend on your employer. However you are likely to be working as a marketing or market research assistant/ executive or perhaps in event management. You may learn how to create and execute a marketing plan for products/services; help manage budgets, distribution plans and carry out research.\r\nAs an Advanced Level apprentice, you may be employed in a more senior marketing/ market research role or be working in the areas of advertising or public relations.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Event management assistant, Junior marketing executive, Market researcher Advanced Level – Marketing assistant, Marketing coordinator, Marketing officer, Marketing manager, Advertising account executive, Market research executive, Public relations officer','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (37,'Public relations','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>Public relations (PR) manages the flow of information between an organisation and the public.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The aim of PR is to inform the public about the company, its leadership, products or political decisions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People that work in PR are excellent communicators and great problem-solvers; they are creative and often naturally gifted at sales. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you could learn to plan and deliver a PR campaign, organise events, write press releases, and learn about digital PR, selling to the media and brand management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p>','PR officer, Account executive','Level 4 (Higher)','From £15,000','2012-11-15 11:47:24','2013-11-26 10:23:27',1,'Public relations','Public Relations, or PR, is the practice of managing the flow of information between an organisation and the public. The aim of PR is often to persuade the public, investors, partners, employees and other stakeholders to hold or maintain a certain point of view about the company, its leadership, products or political decisions.\r\nPeople that work in PR are excellent communicators and great problem-solvers; they are creative and often naturally gifted at sales. There are over 60,000 people working in PR in the UK.\r\nWithin this Apprenticeship, the nature of the work will depend on whether your employer is a small or large agency, or whether you work for an in-house PR team. If you work for an agency, the clients you work with may be specialised within a single sector or field, or may work in a broad range of sectors. As an apprentice, you could learn how to plan and deliver a PR campaign, organise events, write press releases, and learn about digital PR, selling to the media and brand management.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Public relations account executive, Public relations officer, Press officer, Trainee account executive, Account director, Communication director','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): Starting salaries of around £15,000 for junior positions. Permanent and senior positions within an agency will earn from £30,000, rising to £60,000 for permanent senior positions within an agency.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (38,'Project management','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>From high-profile sporting events to organising a party, it is the role of project managers to plan, execute and close any project.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The best project managers are organised, disciplined and team players. They know how to motivate a team and deliver to expectations. They have excellent communication, organisational and influencing skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>schedule management</li>\r\n	<li>financial management</li>\r\n	<li>risk management</li>\r\n	<li>quality management</li>\r\n	<li>project management</li>\r\n	<li>contract management</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>After completing the Apprenticeship, you will be able to work towards full membership of the Association of Project Management.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p>','Project manager, Project support officer, Project coordinator','Level 4 (Higher)','From £25,000','2012-11-15 11:48:45','2013-11-26 10:59:33',1,'Project management','Successful project delivery is at the heart of many businesses and organisations. Everything with a defined start, end and purpose – from a high-profile sporting event to organising a party – can be considered a project.\r\nIt is the role of project managers to plan, execute and close any project. The best project managers are organised, disciplined and team players. They know how to motivate a team and deliver to expectations. They have excellent communication, organisational and influencing skills.\r\nAs a Project Management apprentice, your role may vary depending on the role and sector in which you are employed. You may be involved in problem-solving, allocating resources, assigning tasks, forecasting future trends or analysing and designing objectives and events.\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship covers schedule management, financial management, risk management, quality management, principles and challenges of project management, scope management, contract management and much more. This Apprenticeship will equip you with the knowledge and skills necessary to have a long career in project management and has been designed to support those who want to enter the field as well as those working as project managers, directors and support officers.\r\nOn completion of this Apprenticeship, you will have gained significant experience and knowledge and will be able to work towards full membership of the Association of Project Management.\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Project manager, Project support officer, Project coordinator, Senior project manager, Manager','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): average project manager salaries start at around £25,000, while senior project managers can earn £50,000+');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (39,'Social media & digital marketing','<p>Digital marketing and the use of social and digital media is\r\na key part of the marketing strategy for most businesses today.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Digital marketing uses online advertising to promote\r\nproducts and services to potential customers. This can be via any\r\nInternet-connected devices, including smart phones and game consoles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The social media industry is still young, but many companies\r\nare already seeing the benefits of using Facebook, Twitter and LinkedIn to\r\ntarget potential clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice your tasks could include managing online\r\ncommunities, using the Internet or social media for marketing campaigns,\r\nwriting copy and creating websites, or managing blogs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p><p></p>','Social media assistant/ consultant/ analyst, Digital marketing assistant','Level 3 (Adv)','From £35,000','2012-11-15 11:50:00','2013-11-26 11:05:03',1,'Social media & digital marketing','Digital marketing and the use of social and digital media is a key part of the marketing strategy for most businesses today.\r\nDigital marketing uses online advertising to promote products and services to potential customers. This can be via any Internet-connected devices, including smart phones and game consoles, and as technology continues to develop, the digital marketing potential will only increase.\r\nAlthough the social media industry is still relatively young, many companies are already seeing the benefits of using it as a platform to target over 500 million active Facebook users, 105 million registered users on Twitter and 75 million professionals on LinkedIn.\r\nBusinesses need the support of a skilled workforce to enable them to make the best use of this new marketing device. The growth of social media and digital marketing has been rapid and the majority of users are self-taught. This Apprenticeship provides more formal training for the industry and will help to broaden knowledge and skills as the sector emerges and grows.\r\nA Social Media and Digital Marketing Apprenticeship could see you working in roles such as a social media assistant, social media analyst, digital marketing assistant or digital communications officer. Your tasks could include managing online communities, using the Internet or social media for marketing campaigns, writing copy and creating websites, or managing blogs.\r\nIn all roles you will be helping your business to promote, utilise and increase its presence through the Internet and social media. You will also be contributing to the Government’s Digital Britain strategy, which aims to ensure that Britain stays at the leading edge of the global digital economy.\r\nA Level 3 diploma in Digital Marketing for e-Commerce is also now available.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Social media assistant, Social media consultant, Social media analyst, Digital account assistant, Digital marketing assistant, Digital communications officer, Community engagement officer','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): average starting salary is around £35,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (40,'Campaigning','<p>Campaigning is about trying to change things, whether that’s\r\nchild protection, the environment or human rights.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Campaigners help to raise awareness of issues by influencing\r\ngovernments, companies or the general public. Campaigners work for charities,\r\npressure groups and other organisations campaigning for change.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Campaigning tactics include organising a public meeting,\r\nsigning a petition, writing to the press, contacting a local councillor, using\r\nsocial media, or boycotting a product. Some campaigns are very high profile and\r\ninvolve national media and celebrity supporters; others will be smaller and work\r\nto make change happen locally.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills – Third Sector</p><p></p>','Campaigns officer, Advocacy officer','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £22,000','2012-11-15 12:45:09','2013-11-26 11:13:03',3,'Campaigning','From child protection to the environment and climate change to human rights, campaigning is about trying to change things. Campaigners help people to speak out or to raise awareness of issues by influencing governments, companies or the general public. All sorts of employers have campaigners working for them including charities, pressure groups and other organisations campaigning for change.\r\nCampaign tactics can be as varied as organising a public meeting, signing a petition, writing to the press, contacting a local councillor, using social media (such as Twitter or Facebook), or boycotting a product. In most cases a campaign will use a combination of these activities. Some campaigns are very high profile and may involve national media and celebrity supporters; others will be smaller and work to make change happen locally. Campaigning is a very varied role and you need a lot of different skills to be an effective campaigner.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship in Campaigning will develop your skills in the key areas of campaigning, including prioritising issues on which to campaign; understanding campaign strategies; developing campaign communications; conducting campaign research; developing campaign workplans; and monitoring and evaluating campaigns. Upon completion you could work for a charity or community organisation; or even a political or corporate lobby group which works to change things in society.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Campaigns officer or coordinator, Campaigns and public affairs officer or coordinator, Advocacy officer','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £16,000–£22,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (41,'Fundraising','<p>Charities need funding to pay for staff, premises,\r\nequipment, websites etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Staff with good fundraising skills make the difference\r\nbetween a charity being able to carry out its work or not. Fundraisers also\r\nwork in education and health organisations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In a fundraising role you will build and manage\r\nrelationships with people and organisations that have the money to support your\r\norganisation’s work and the people it helps. You will show how the money will\r\nbenefit the people and causes that your charity supports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can specialise in at least two areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>local and community fundraising</li><li><span></span>events</li><li><span></span>raising money through large donations</li><li><span></span>applying for grants</li><li><span></span>working with businesses</li><li><span></span>e-media and direct mail</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b>\r\nSkills CFA </p>\r\n','Fundraising officer, Fundraising coordinator','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £21,000','2012-11-15 12:46:42','2013-11-26 11:19:37',3,'Fundraising','Fundraising is absolutely critical to charities and voluntary organisations. Charities need funding in order to operate – to pay for staff, premises, equipment, websites etc. Having paid staff with good fundraising skills makes the difference between a charity being able to help or not – it’s at the heart of everything these organisations do. Fundraisers also work in education and health organisations.\r\nBeing in paid employment in a fundraising role is about building and managing relationships with people and organisations that have money to support your organisation’s work and the people it helps. A fundraiser shows how the funder’s money will benefit the people and the causes that their charity supports. Funders might be individuals, businesses, trusts and foundations, local authorities or the Government.\r\nThis Advanced Level Apprenticeship will give you skills to be an effective fundraiser – developing and implementing fundraising plans, and monitoring and sustaining relationships with donors. In addition, you can specialise in at least two fundraising areas: local and community fundraising, fundraising events, raising money through large donations, applying for funding grants, fundraising through working with businesses, raising funds through using e-media and using direct mail to attract donors.\r\nThis Apprenticeship is endorsed by The Institute of Fundraising – the professional body for fundraisers.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Fundraiser, Fundraising officer, Fundraising coordinator, Fundraising support officer','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £16,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (42,'Volunteer management','<p>Volunteering is very important in the UK. Over 24 million\r\npeople volunteer every year to help out in charities, hospitals, schools,\r\nprisons etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good volunteer managers ensure that volunteers get the most\r\nout of volunteering and that organisations make the best use of their\r\nvolunteers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a volunteer manager you will match the right people to\r\nthe right opportunities and support them to do that role well. It’s a busy job\r\nthat involves a lot of different tasks from writing job descriptions to finding\r\ntraining opportunities and developing volunteer programmes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Apprenticeship is open to all, but people below the age\r\nof 21 might not have the breadth of experience needed to undertake the\r\nApprenticeship successfully.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills – Third Sector</p><p></p>','Volunteer manager, Volunteer coordinator, Volunteer advisor, Volunteer team leader','Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000 to £20,000','2012-11-15 12:47:51','2013-11-26 11:20:56',3,'Volunteer Management','Volunteering is very important in the UK. Over 40% of people volunteer once a year and 25% volunteer once a month – which adds up to 24.7 million volunteers each year. Good volunteer managers are essential to make sure volunteers get the most out of volunteering and that organisations make the best use of their volunteers.\r\nThe majority of volunteering happens in charities, social enterprises and voluntary organisations as well as in hospitals, schools and other public organisations, and in companies that run volunteering schemes for employees. Volunteers might help out in community activities, support after-school activities, or offer help in libraries, hospitals and prisons, for example. Volunteers bring to their volunteering roles a large range of skills and abilities. Some volunteers are well educated while others have literacy and numeracy problems. Managing this diversity makes good volunteer managers essential.\r\nVolunteer management is experiencing a very important time of change. It is a key part of the Coalition Government’s Big Society plans to increase the number of people who are volunteering and to involve volunteers more in running public services, particularly at a local level.\r\nBeing in paid employment as a volunteer manager is about matching the right people to the right volunteering opportunities and then supporting them to do that role well. You need to enjoy working with people and seeing them succeed. Volunteer management is a busy job that involves a lot of different tasks. It is becoming increasingly sophisticated and now includes tasks like writing role descriptions, finding training opportunities and developing volunteer programmes.\r\nThis Advanced Level Apprenticeship will develop your skills and knowledge in the key areas you need to be a good volunteer manager, including how to supervise and support volunteers; promote volunteering opportunities; motivate volunteers; manage risks associated with volunteering; and develop structures, systems and procedures to support volunteering. Although the Apprenticeship is open to all, it is envisaged that people below the age of 21 would not have the breadth of experience or attributes needed to undertake the Apprenticeship successfully.\r\nThe Apprenticeship is endorsed by the Association of Volunteer Managers.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Volunteer manager, Volunteer coordinator, Volunteer advisor, Volunteer team leader','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (43,'Construction – specialist','<p>Over one-third of UK construction workers are self-employed. The industry employs almost 2 million people in England.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices learn a skilled profession from a range that\r\nincludes plastering &amp; dry lining, flooring, scaffolding and construction\r\nmanagement.</p>\r\n<p><b>Intermediate Level</b> <b>pathways</b>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>accessing and rigging</li><li>applied waterproof membranes</li><li>cladding occupations</li><li>wall and floor tiling</li><li>fitted interiors</li><li>floorcovering</li><li>heritage skills<br></li><li>insulation and building treatments<br></li><li>interior systems</li><li>mastic asphalt</li><li>plastering</li><li>roofing occupations</li><li>stonemasonry</li><li>thermal insulation<br></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Advanced Level pathways</b>:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>heritage skills<br></li><li>plastering</li><li>roofing occupations</li><li>stonemasonry</li><li>wall and floor tiling</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship offers excellent opportunities for career progression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> CITB<br></p>\r\n','Scaffolder, Tiler, Thatcher, Stonemason, Plasterer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-15 14:27:51','2013-11-26 11:31:02',2,'Construction – Specialist','The role of this Apprenticeship is to supply a skilled and qualified workforce to the construction industry. Over one-third of the construction workforce in England is self-employed and the industry employs almost 2 million people in England.\r\nApprentices learn a skilled profession from a range that includes plastering and dry lining, flooring, scaffolding and construction management. Vocational training will enable you to develop skills and knowledge which you can use in a real construction environment. For example, scaffolding erection allows other workers to gain access to parts of structures they are working on. Safety is critical, both for those erecting the scaffold and the people working on the scaffold. Scaffolders work outside in all weather conditions and a good head for heights is essential! You might work on a construction site or in a domestic setting fitting kitchen, bathroom and bedroom furniture from flat packs or bespoke built units. Or you could learn to install ceilings, walls and floors using a variety of different materials and methods.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship includes the following occupations: accessing and rigging; applied waterproof membranes; cladding occupations; wall and floor tiling; fitted interiors; floorcovering; heritage skills; insulation and building treatments; interior systems; mastic asphalt; plastering; roofing occupations; stonemasonry and thermal insulation. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you could learn one of the following trades: plastering; roofing occupations; stonemasonry; and wall and floor tiling. An Advanced Apprenticeship in heritage skills is also available.\r\nFrom thatching to plastering, tiling to stonemasonry, the possibilities are endless with this Apprenticeship and opportunities for career progression are excellent.\r\nSuccessful apprentices will have good hand-eye coordination and be able to follow instructions accurately. Many roles are physically demanding and it helps to have a good level of fitness. You will need to have good maths skills for calculating areas and volumes.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Scaffolder, Tiler, Thatcher, Stonemason, Plasterer','Issuing Authority: CITB – www.citb.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000– £16,000 (exact salaries will vary depending on location and other factors)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (44,'Construction – building','<p>Training is\r\navailable in painting &amp; decorating, bricklaying, craft masonry, carpentry, shopfitting, maintenance and woodmachining.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These roles are carried out in workshops or construction\r\nsites, within domestic or commercial premises.</p>\r\n<p><b>Intermediate Level pathways:</b><br></p><ul><li>decorative finishing &amp; industrial painting</li><li>maintenance operations</li><li>trowel occupations</li><li>wood occupations</li><li>woodmachining</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Advanced Level pathways:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>trowel occupations</li><li>wood occupations</li><li>bricklaying</li><li>site carpentry</li><li>bench joinery</li><li>shopfitting</li><li>decorative finishing<br></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> CITB</p>\r\n','Painter, Bricklayer, Site carpenter, Bench joiner, Shopfitter','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-15 14:30:15','2013-11-26 11:25:01',2,'Construction – Building','For many years the construction industry has had a traditional Apprenticeship programme covering the craft occupations in a range of traditional roles.\r\nOn the Construction Building Apprenticeship you will be given the opportunity to progress to supervisory and management level in the construction industry, becoming part of a well-trained, productive workforce. Training is available in painting and decorating, bricklaying, craft masonry, carpentry, joinery, shopfitting, maintenance and woodmachining, and these roles are carried out in either workshops or construction sites, within domestic or commercial premises.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship has pathways in: Decorative Finishing and Industrial Painting; Maintenance Operations; Trowel Occupations; Wood Occupations; and Woodmachining. The role you train for will vary according to the pathway you choose.\r\nYou will be assessed continually to gauge your suitability for progression to an Advanced Level Apprenticeship, where you could specialise in Trowel Occupations or Wood Occupations, training to become a bricklayer, site carpenter, bench joiner or shopfitter. Alternatively you could take an Advanced Apprenticeship in Decorative Finishing (painting and decorating).\r\nA good head for heights is essential and you should be prepared to work outside in all seasonal weather conditions. You might need to travel to sites or, in some cases, stay in lodgings while working away from home. Many of these occupations are physically demanding so you should have a good level of fitness and be able to work quickly while paying close attention to detail. Good maths skills are necessary to take measurements as well as the ability to follow plans and written/spoken instructions.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Painter, Industrial painter, Maintenance operative, Bricklayer, Site carpenter, Bench joiner, Shopfitter','Issuing Authority: CITB – www.citb.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000– £16,000 (exact salaries will depend on occupation, location and other factors)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (45,'Construction – civil engineering','<p>Civil engineering deals with the design and construction of\r\nbuildings, bridges, pipelines, railways, water supply networks, roads and other\r\ncrucial parts of our infrastructure.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Intermediate Level pathways:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Construction operative –</b> lay drainage and pavements, place street iron\r\nworks, excavate holes and trenches.</li><li><b>Formworker –</b> fabricate and repair forms for concrete pouring.</li><li><b>Highways maintenance operative –</b> repair surfaces, lay\r\ndrainage, place kerbs and pavements, install safety\r\nfencing.</li><li><b>Plant mechanic –</b> repair vehicles such as excavators, folklifts, telescopic handlers and dumper trucks.</li><li><b>Plant operations</b> – operate machinery to transfer\r\nloads, excavate, lift and move materials.</li><li><b>Tunnelling operations </b>– work underground, spraying concrete onto tunnel\r\nlinings, or stabilising rock structures</li><li><b>Specialist concrete occupations – </b>work on\r\nconstruction sites spraying concrete onto prepared surfaces.</li><li><b>Roadbuilding </b>– apply and remove pavement markings,\r\napply specialist road surfacing and instal and remove permanent road\r\nstuds.</li><li><b>Steelfixing – </b>follow engineering drawings to position and secure steel reinforcing bars and\r\nsteel mesh.</li></ul><p><b>Advanced Level:</b></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the <b>Plant Maintenance</b> Advanced Level Apprenticeship you\r\nmight specialise in hydraulics and electrical components.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> CITB<br></p><p></p>\r\n','Construction operative, Formworker, Highways maintenance operative, Plant mechanic','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-15 14:32:16','2013-11-26 11:38:02',2,'Construction – Civil engineering','Civil engineering deals with the design and construction of buildings, bridges, pipelines, railways, water supply networks, roads and other crucial parts of our society. Civil engineers turn complex designs into reality while building our country’s infrastructure – and they rely on civil engineering technicians to provide technical support on construction projects.\r\nAs a Construction Civil Engineering apprentice there are various pathways that you can choose from. Every day on the job will be different, as all sorts of circumstances and issues arise on any large-scale project that involves so many people and resources.\r\nIntermediate Level\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship has nine different pathways and, depending on the pathway you choose, your role will vary considerably.\r\nConstruction Operations – As a construction operative you would work on a construction site or public place, laying drainage, placing street iron works, laying pavements and excavating holes and trenches.\r\nFormwork Occupations – Formworkers work on construction sites moving and handling resources to fabricate and repair forms for concrete pouring and to dismantle the formwork afterwards.\r\nHighways Maintenance – You will work in a public place or highway, repairing surfaces, laying drainage, placing street iron works, kerbs and pavements, installing vehicle safety fencing on highways, excavating and repairing.\r\nPlant Maintenance – Plant mechanics are based either on a construction site or in a workshop, repairing vehicles for various construction operations such as excavators, earth movers, folklifts, telescopic handlers and dumper trucks.\r\nPlant operations – Working on a construction site, in a public place or on the highway, you will operate machinery to transfer loads, excavate, lift and move materials to given specifications.\r\nTunnelling operations – You could find yourself working underground, spraying concrete onto prepared surfaces such as tunnel linings, and stabilising rock structures. Tunnelling operatives are responsible for installing back-up services and operating tunnelling machinery.\r\nSpecialist concrete occupations – Operatives work on construction sites spraying concrete onto prepared surfaces such as excavated areas or water-retaining structures.\r\nRoadbuilding – As in Highways Maintenance, you will work in a public place or highway applying and removing pavement markings, applying specialist road surfacing and installing and removing permanent road studs.\r\nSteelfixing – Steel fixers are required to follow engineering drawings that detail the type of steel bar and spacing used as well as setting-out work to position and secure steel reinforcing bars and steel mesh used in reinforced concrete on construction projects.\r\n\r\nAdvanced Level\r\nOn the Plant Maintenance Advanced Level Apprenticeship you might learn to specialise in hydraulics and electrical components.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship is a perfect springboard for further qualifications that could lead to a degree in Civil Engineering or management roles.\r\nIn all roles you will need to be willing to travel to sites or, in some cases, stay in lodgings while working away from home. You will also need to have a reasonable level of fitness as many occupations are physically demanding. You should be able to work quickly while paying close attention to detail. Good maths skills are needed to take measurements as well as the ability to follow plans and written/spoken instructions. An awareness of Health and Safety is also necessary.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Construction operative, Formworker, Highways maintenance operative, Plant mechanic, Plant operative, Steel fixer','Issuing Authority: CITB – www.citb.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: £10,000– £16,000 (exact salaries will depend on location and other factors)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (46,'Construction – technical & professional','<p>There are eight pathways at Advanced Level as well as a Higher Apprenticeship pathway in Sustainable Built Environment.</p><p>Advanced level pathways:<br></p><p><b>Building control</b> – learn to assess building projects and inspect site work for compliance\r\nwith building regulations.<br>\r\n\r\n</p><p><b>Built environment &amp; design</b> – learn to produce detailed\r\ndesign solutions, surveys and drawings, and prepare and assess tenders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Construction contracting operations</b> – get skills in\r\nestimating, buying, planning and technical support.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Construction site supervision</b> – develop personnel skills\r\nsuch as team working, planning building operations and supervising safety.</p><p><b>Geomatics data analysis – </b>support the\r\nproduction of navigational products and services.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Occupational work supervision</b> – organise work operations,\r\nmanage work activities, manage health &amp; safety.</p><p><b>Town planning</b> – technical and administrative support to planning services,\r\nliaising with customers and providing advice and guidance.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Civil engineering for technicians</b> – working on a construction\r\nsite, develop and finalise civil\r\nengineering solutions, and learn about health &amp; safety.</p><p>At Higher Level, on the <b>Sustainable Built Environment</b> pathway you could work as a site manager, project manager or\r\nsite engineer. Responsibilities could include\r\nmanaging staff and budgets, ensuring the site is operated in a safe and secure\r\nmanner and that contracts are delivered on time, or surveying sites, and\r\nchecking drawings and quantities to ensure accuracy.<br></p>\r\n<p>Middlesex University offers a Foundation Degree in \'Professional practice in construction\r\noperations management\'.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> CITB</p><p></p>\r\n','Site technician, Civil engineering technician, Construction operations manager','Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 & 5 (Higher) ','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-15 14:36:09','2013-11-26 11:41:12',2,'Construction – Technical and professional','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship has eight pathways: Building Control, Built Environment and Design, Construction Contracting Operations, Construction Site Supervision, Geomatics Data Analysis, Occupational Work Supervision, Town Planning and Civil Engineering for Technicians. There is also a Higher (Level 4/5) pathway: Sustainable Built Environment. Whichever pathway you choose, you will be most likely to work as a site technician, but the nature of your role will vary considerably.\r\nBuilding Control – You would learn to assess building projects and inspect site work for compliance with building regulations. Your role might also involve providing technical support to a building control surveyor.\r\nBuilt Environment and Design – As an apprentice following the Built Environment and Design pathway you would learn to produce detailed design solutions, surveys and drawings, and to prepare and assess tenders in the built environment.\r\nConstruction Contracting Operations – On this pathway your role as site technician would be based on a construction site where you would acquire skills in estimating, buying, planning and technical support.\r\nConstruction Site Supervision – The Construction Site Supervision pathway would develop your personnel skills such as team working, planning building operations, organising and controlling, supervising safety in the workplace and working with people.\r\nGeomatics Data Analysis – Analysts provide cartographic support to mapping and charting activities that are fundamental to the production of navigational and marine products and services.\r\nOccupational Work Supervision – This pathway is designed to enable the organising of work operations, managing work activities, managing health and safety and developing good working relationships.\r\nTown Planning – Town planning technical support officers provide technical, administrative and clerical support to planning services, liaising with customers and providing advice and guidance.\r\nCivil Engineering for Technicians – On the Civil Engineering for Technicians pathway you would work on a construction site carrying out civil engineering tasks, developing and finalising civil engineering solutions, and learning about health and safety for civil engineers.\r\nSustainable Built Environment – Finally, on the Sustainable Built Environment pathway you could work as a site manager, project manager or site engineer. Depending on your role, your responsibilities could include managing staff and budgets, ensuring the site is operated in a safe and secure manner and that the contractis delivered on time, or surveying sites, and checking drawings and quantities to ensure accuracy.\r\n\r\nCareer progression from any of the pathways is good and there is a wide range of opportunities for apprentices to follow a structured career path in building, civil engineering and other specialist occupations.\r\nAfter gaining work experience in your chosen area you could move on to further qualifications in, for example, construction contracting operation or construction site management, or to higher education in areas such as civil engineering, architecture/design or building surveying.\r\nThere is also a Foundation Degree – Professional Practice in Construction Operations Management – which is offered through Middlesex University. The delivery is a blended learning approach with emphasis on work-based projects. It is designed for progression from Level 3 or for those with appropriate prior experience of the sector. This qualification is not suitable for learners below the age of 18.\r\nTo be successful in any of these roles, you will need to be able to understand and interpret technical drawings and principles. A creative approach to problem solving and the ability to work as part of a team are also necessary. You should have good communication and organisational skills and be able to demonstrate close attention to detail.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3); Higher (Level 4, Level 5)','Job roles: Site technician, Civil engineering technician, Construction operations manager, Project manager, Site engineer, Data analyst','Issuing Authority: CITB – www.citb.co.uk','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: £10,000–16,000, or higher in management roles depending upon the company (exact salaries will vary according to location and other factors)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (47,'Surveying','<p>Surveying is a diverse profession and covers a wide range of\r\ndisciplines.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>Apprentices learn about health &amp; safety,\r\nhow to assess the condition of a property, how\r\nto monitor the maintenance of the property and how to collect and present\r\nsurvey data.</p><p>The Apprenticeship contains five pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Maintenance</li><li>Quantity surveying</li><li>General practice</li><li>Building surveying</li><li>Valuation</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Asset Skills</p><p></p>\r\n','Surveyor technician','Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000','2012-11-15 14:37:55','2013-11-26 11:57:49',2,'Surveying','Surveying is a diverse profession and covers a wide range of disciplines. This Advanced Surveying Apprenticeship contains five pathways of specialism: Maintenance, Quantity surveying, General practice, Building surveying and Valuation. Depending on your pathway you could learn how to assess the condition of a property or help manage the development of land.\r\nThe nature of your learning will depend on your employer’s scope of operation. As an apprentice, you’ll probably learn health and safety; how to manage your own workload; how to help assess the condition of a property; how to help monitor the maintenance of the property; and how to collect, analyse and present measured survey data. You may have the option to learn other skills like cost control, solving disputes and building regulations.\r\nAfter successful completion of the Advanced Apprenticeship, you’ll be well placed in a varied profession with excellent prospects.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: General practice surveyor technician, Building surveyor technician, Quantity surveyor technician, Valuation surveyor technician, Maintenance surveyor technician','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (48,'Costume & wardrobe','<p>This Apprenticeship will introduce you to working\r\nbackstage in a theatre or live event and provide a basis for a career in the\r\ncostume and wardrobe aspects of theatre production.</p><p>You will gain experience of working as part of a\r\nwardrobe team, seeing a production wardrobe through from initial idea to final\r\ncostume production.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices learn to:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>make and alter clothes<br></li><li>help cutters</li><li>search for hired costumes &amp; accessories</li><li>clean, wash &amp; iron costumes</li><li>keep records of accessories</li><li>source costumes, materials &amp; equipment</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>\r\n','Costume/ wardrobe assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:23:01','2013-11-26 12:20:14',20,'Costume and wardrobe','All theatrical performances such as plays, musicals, TV or film productions rely on scenery, props and costumes to make them a success. Those working in costume and wardrobe play a key role in making sure that costumes accurately represent the period. They work with artistic directors, producers, set designers, technical and lighting departments, as well as designing, altering and sourcing costumes.\r\nThe Costume and Wardrobe Apprenticeship will introduce you to working backstage in a theatre or live event setting and provide a basis for a career in the costume and wardrobe aspects of theatre production. You will gain real experience of working as part of a wardrobe team, seeing a production wardrobe through from initial idea, via development to final costume production.\r\nIntermediate Level apprentices will train as Costume/Wardrobe Assistants, supporting assembling, making and altering clothes for actors and assisting them to dress; helping cutters; searching for hired costumes and accessories; helping with cleaning, washing and ironing of costumes; keeping records of accessories; and helping to source costumes, materials and equipment.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you will train as an Assistant Costume/Wardrobe Manager, researching the type of clothes and accessories worn for a production; attending meetings with the artistic director, producer, set designer and technical and lighting departments; assisting with presentation of design ideas to the production team; briefing and monitoring the team; and supporting the making and finishing of costumes.\r\nYou will have a keen interest in working in costume and wardrobe, a creative flair and an interest in history. You will need to understand the importance of working in teams and of tact and diplomacy when working with actors. You will also be willing to work shifts. Some job roles may require you to be CRB checked.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Costume/Wardrobe assistant, Assistant costume/ wardrobe manager','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (49,'Community arts','<p>Community arts enrich the lives of local\r\ncommunities by planning, promoting and running events and exhibitions for people of all ages.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices learn about:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>organising events &amp; exhibitions</li><li>publicising events</li><li>financial record keeping</li><li>customer care</li><li>dealing with touring bands</li><li>management of the building</li><li>general office work</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p><p></p>\r\n','Community arts administration assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:27:12','2013-11-26 12:18:34',20,'Community arts','Community arts helps to enrich the lives of local communities by planning, promoting and running participatory events, exhibitions and projects to engage individuals and groups of all ages.\r\nThis Apprenticeship will provide you with a flexible entry route into the Community Arts industry. As an apprentice you will work to develop business, administrative, problem solving, communication, team working, literacy, numeracy and ICT skills, which are a priority for the business. There will be opportunities for career progression across the creative and cultural sector into senior jobs through further training and development, Further Education and Higher Education programmes.\r\nYou will need to demonstrate that you have a keen interest in working in community arts and in providing high standards of customer service. You will have good communication skills and will understand the importance of working in teams. Some job roles may require you to undergo a CRB check.\r\nAs an Intermediate Level Apprentice you will train as a Community Arts Administration Assistant helping to organise and publicise events and exhibitions, assisting with financial record keeping, customer care, dealing with touring and resident groups bands/orchestras, assisting with the management of the building and general office work including using a range of IT software.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you will train as a Community Arts Administrator responsible for assisting with the efficient running of the organisation, to ensure that the local community benefits from a range of arts programmes. This includes assisting with the recruitment of administrators, artist services, maintenance and security, external relationship management and bookkeeping.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Community arts administration assistant, Community arts administrator','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (50,'Cultural & heritage venue operations','<p>The cultural heritage sector includes museums,\r\ngalleries, built heritage, conservation, heritage landscape and archeology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The sector collects and preserves the past, and provides\r\nopportunities for learning and engagement, inspiration\r\nand enjoyment. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Conservation assistants</b> – oversee cleaning and\r\nrestoration projects, host tours for groups and support curators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Exhibition guides</b> – explain displays/exhibitions to an\r\naudience and help visitors understand about a time in history.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Visitor services assistants</b> – meet customers, and\r\nexplain displays and exhibits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could also join the front of house and\r\nadministration support staff, handling ticket sales or dealing with\r\ncustomers, finance, staff records and visitor numbers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>\r\n','Conservation assistant, Exhibition guide, Visitor services assistant, Front of house staff, Assistant archivist','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:28:42','2013-11-26 12:28:37',20,'Cultural and heritage venue operations','The cultural heritage sector includes museums, galleries, built heritage, conservation, heritage landscape and archeology. The sector collects and preserves the past, provides opportunities for learning and engagement and provides creativity, inspiration, and enjoyment.\r\nCultural heritage helps us to understand how society has evolved and contributes to shaping the future. It is a broad area, encompassing historic buildings, landscapes and collections – from towns, cities and rural spaces in the UK, to collections from across the world. It includes languages, customs and practices.\r\nAs an Intermediate Level Apprentice you might train as a Conservation Assistant, perhaps overseeing cleaning and restoration projects, hosting tours for groups and supporting curators. You could also work as an Exhibition Guide, explaining displays/exhibitions to a range of audiences, demonstrating skills or practices (e.g. ancient crafts or costumes) and helping visitors to understand about a time in history. Visitor Services Assistants meet customers, and explain displays and exhibits. Or you might join the front of house and administration support staff, handling ticket sales, or dealing with customers, finance, staff records and visitor numbers.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you would train as an Assistant Archivist, Assistant Exhibition Organiser, or Assistant Museum/Art Gallery Curator.\r\nYou will have an interest in history and the arts as well as good communication skills on which this Apprenticeship will build. Some job roles may require a CRB check.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Conservation assistant, Exhibition guide, Visitor services assistant, Front of house administration support\r\nAdvanced Level – Assistant archivist, Assistant exhibition organiser, Assistant museum/art gallery curator','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (51,'Creative & digital media','<p>The Internet and\r\nother digital technologies have changed the way media content is created,\r\npackaged, distributed and used.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The creative media industries supply the audiovisual\r\ncontent, designs and innovation to entertain and educate us all and\r\nhelp the economy keep pace and grow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creative media is an exciting mix of ideas applied and\r\nbrought to life by technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers new entrant roles in:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>TV</li><li>archives</li><li>animation</li><li>interactive media</li><li>film</li><li>radio </li><li>photo imaging</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative\r\nSkillset</p><p></p>\r\n','Animation assistant, Archive assistant, Broadcast assistant, Junior designer, Production runner','Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £17,000','2012-11-20 12:30:55','2013-11-26 12:22:30',20,'Creative and digital media','The creative and digital media industries supply the audiovisual content, designs and innovation to entertain, educate and instruct us all and help the economy keep pace and grow.\r\nThe industries are constantly evolving. We live in a digital world, where the Internet and other digital technologies are changing the way media content is created, packaged, distributed and consumed by a wide variety of audiences and users. For example, the Xbox 360 isn’t just a gaming console, it is also a web browser and social networking tool; mobile phones aren’t just used for conversations, but are now digital cameras, voice recorders and music players.\r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship in Creative and Digital Media covers new entrant roles in a range of sectors including TV, archives, animation, interactive media, film, radio and photo imaging. The Apprenticeship is also relevant to employers outside of creative media – possibly those who have team members responsible for using digital technology for creative purposes.\r\nCreative and digital media is an exciting mix of ideas applied and brought to life by technology. Employers expect that apprentices coming into their business will be digitally savvy, multi-skilled and able to work across different technologies.\r\nYou must be able to hit the ground running with new ideas and a real understanding of what the audience, user or your company needs, and you should be able to add value to the business, as soon as possible, and work with your employer to take advantage of new technologies. In return, employers will support your growing talent and ability to develop your career.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Animation assistant, Archive assistant, Assistant to the camera crew, Broadcast assistant, Digital assistant, Junior designer, Junior researcher, Post-production runner, Production runner/assistant, Production secretary, Trainee/assistant photographer, Web coordinator','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','','26/11/13','','  Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (52,'Jewellery, silversmithing & allied trades','<p>If you have a keen interest in working in the\r\njewellery industry, an interest in engineering and design, and good technical\r\nand creative skills, this could be the Apprenticeship for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could work as a:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Jewellery technician</b> – maintain tools and machinery\r\nwithin the workshop and learn basic jewellery techniques</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Silversmith</b> – learn to design and make a wide range of\r\nobjects, including cutlery, trophies and badges</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Jobbing jeweller</b> – learn to repair, renovate and\r\nalter jewellery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Other roles include engraving, setting gemstones and\r\npolishing and finishing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>\r\n','Goldsmith, Jeweller, Silversmith, Gem setter, Jewellery technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:33:03','2013-11-26 12:39:29',20,'Jewellery, silversmithing and allied trades','Over 9,000 people work in the UK’s 1,445 jewellery businesses, often as sole traders as well as in retail. Many more work in areas such as wholesale jewellery manufacture and distribution. Many designer-makers work in important creative roles but the sector lacks young people with an interest and aptitude for the manufacturing and technical roles within the industry.\r\nIf you have a keen interest in working in the jewellery industry, an interest in the engineering, making, producing and design process, and good technical and creative skills, and/or strong hand-eye coordination, this could be the Apprenticeship for you.\r\nOn the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship in Jewellery Manufacturing you could work as a Jewellery Technician, maintaining tools and machinery within the workshop and learning basic jewellery techniques. As a Silversmith you would learn to design and make a wide range of objects, including cutlery, trophies and badges. Jobbing Jewellers learn to repair, renovate and alter jewellery. Other roles include engraving, setting gemstones and polishing and finishing.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship has pathways in Jewellery Manufacturing, Silversmithing, Precious Metal CAD/CAM, Enamelling, Engraving, Precious Metal Polishing & Finishing and Gem Setting. These pathways lead to more specialised roles within the industry. For example, on the Jewellery Manufacturing pathway you might train as a Diamond Mounter, creating precise items for expensive precious stones, often in traditional styles. Whichever pathway you follow you might work with machinery or by hand, using traditional techniques or state-of-the-art technology such as computer-aided design.\r\nA Higher Level (Level 4) Apprenticeship will be coming soon.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level Apprenticeship – Goldsmith/Jeweller, Silversmith, Enameller, Engraver, Gem setter, CAD CAM worker, Polisher & finisher, Jobbing jeweller/Jewellery technician\r\nAdvanced Level – Diamond mounter, Goldsmith, Gem setter, Patternmaker, Silver spinner, Precious stone setter','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): Variable – for specific job roles check the Creative Skillset website');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (53,'Design','<p>Design can have a significant impact on business\r\nproductivity, as well as addressing social and environmental issues.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers all the main design areas,\r\nfrom graphics to product design. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Designers can work in a range of industries including\r\nfashion, furniture, manufacturing and media.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>While each industry requires specific skills, all\r\ndesigners work to come up with a concept that both serves a purpose and looks\r\ngood. It’s a challenging and creative role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p><p></p>','Design assistant, Graphic design assistant, Junior artworker','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:34:15','2013-11-26 12:30:28',20,'Design','The UK design industry is young, fragmented and has a huge variety of talents. Designers are generally well qualified and their skills and creativity are valued by clients in the UK and abroad.\r\nDesign can have a significant impact on business productivity, as well as addressing social and environmental issues. In recent years, designers have helped influence new areas including high-tech innovation, environmental sustainability and education and health services.\r\nThis Apprenticeship covers all the main design areas, from graphics to product design. Design is a broad term, and designers can work in a range of industries including fashion, furniture, manufacturing and media. While each industry requires specific skills, all designers work to come up with a concept that both serves a purpose and looks good. It’s a challenging and creative role.\r\nEmployers will be particularly interested in those who show a keen interest in working in the industry and who can show a creative flair. As well as having good communication and problem-solving skills, you will also need to show that you understand the importance of providing high standards of customer service and of working in a team.\r\nOn the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship you could train as a Design Assistant, Trainee Technical Illustrator, Graphic Design Assistant or Junior Artworker. You would probably work as part of a team, supporting designers with the design and production of projects including leaflets, stationery, brochures, logos, packaging or other products. You may be writing briefs, producing marketing material or liaising with technical staff from other departments. You will need to be confident to bring your own ideas to the table.\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices might train as Desktop Publishing Assistants, Technical Illustrators, Junior Product Designers or Assistant Copywriters. Working online and offline, in print-based materials and other media, they learn to take projects from initial brief through to completion.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Design assistant, Trainee technical illustrator, Graphic design assistant, Junior artworker\r\nAdvanced Level – Desktop publishing assistant, Technical assistant, Junior graphic designer, Assistant copywriter','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (54,'Fashion & textiles: technical','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>The technical textiles industry is at the centre of a range of technological advancements including:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Technical clothing – smart textiles, bullet-proof vests, spacesuits</li><li>Medical applications – artificial veins and implants</li><li>Automotive industry – developing lightweight components for use in the next generation of supercars</li><li>Electronics – flexible integrated screens and touch pads</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Don’t miss the chance to work with some of the most innovative employers in the world!</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Technical Textiles pathway</b> – technical textile fibres, yarns, fabrics and finishes, as well as their application in functions such as antimicrobial, breathability, fire and heat resistance, stain resistance, biodegradability and conductivity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Product Development and Sourcing pathway</b> – Planning and managing the outsourcing process in manufacturing; Outsourcing costs; Planning skills; Design development; Leadership and people management; and Finance for designers and creatives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For manufacturing roles, see also Fashion and Textiles under Manufacturing</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Creative Skillset</p>\r\n','R&D manager, Quality manager, Fibre technologist, Process engineer, Warehouse manager','Level 4 (Higher)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:37:19','2013-11-26 12:33:00',20,'Fashion and textiles: technical','The fashion and textiles sector in the UK is currently thriving. Technology is constantly evolving and fashion is getting faster, so it is essential that there are the right people, with the right skills, to capitalise on these changes, now and into the future.\r\nThis Higher Apprenticeship has two specialised pathways: Technical Textiles and Product Development and Sourcing.\r\n\r\nTechnical Textiles\r\nThe technical textiles industry is at the centre of breakthrough technological advancements across a range of sectors. These sectors and activities rely on nanotechnology, electronics or other innovations, and include a wide range of uses, from protective clothing for emergency services, to medical splints and surgical tools, and carbon fibre for aircraft frames.\r\nThe industry needs individuals capable of developing and commercialising new, innovative products and processes, and a scientific mind mixed with a creative drive is essential for a career in technical textiles.\r\nThis pathway will enable you to learn about the production of textiles created for their performance rather than their visual appearance. You will gain a working knowledge of technical textile fibres, yarns, fabrics and finishes, as well as their application in functions such as antimicrobial, breathability, fire and heat resistance, stain resistance, biodegradability and conductivity.\r\n\r\nProduct Development and Sourcing\r\nAs companies try to respond quickly to trends and celebrity fashion, production and distribution times for suppliers and manufacturers get shorter. In many cases, designs are developed for production for each of the four seasons with lead production times of as little as 15 days from concept to stock in retail stores.\r\nFor fashion and textile businesses to be able respond quickly to the latest trends, they need to have product development and sourcing apprentices who can combine creativity with commercial awareness.\r\nThe product development and sourcing pathway requires people who can understand the supply chain and critical path of the design and manufacturing process. Flexibility within this process is essential for businesses to react quickly to changing demands. There is also a need for creative sourcing to find cost-effective and commercial products for the designers to develop.\r\nThe pathway has been specifically designed to give a working knowledge of how to plan new products, plan and manage the outsourcing process in manufacturing and outsource costs in manufacturing. Apprentices will also gain skills in strategic marketing planning, business planning and financial projection, design development, creativity and business development, leadership and people management, intellectual property management, design project management; doing business globally and finance for designers.\r\n\r\nFor roles in the manufacturing side of Fashion and Textiles, see page ???\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles:\r\nTechnical Textiles – Fabric technologist, Fibre technologist, Senior technologist, Textile technical designer, Senior testing technologist, Textile product development technologist, Textile support analyst, Technical textile researcher, Textile quality controller, Technical manager (Production)\r\nProduct Development and Sourcing – New product development manager, Process engineer, Procurement manager (apparel and textiles goods), Sales manager (apparel and textiles goods), Logistics manager (textile finished goods), Technical manager (production), Research and development manager (textiles and apparel goods), Marketing manager (apparel and textile goods), Quality manager','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): Varies according to individual roles, see www.creativeskillset.org/fashion_and_textiles/careers/jobs');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (55,'Live events & promotion','<p>Live events can be indoor or outdoors, one-off events\r\nor tours, and small- to large-scale productions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship offers you an opportunity to\r\nprovide the industry with the technical, artistic and administrative skills it\r\nneeds.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Roles are diverse and you could end up setting up the\r\nstage, instruments, sound and lighting for an event; undertaking activities to\r\nsecure funding; or researching and assessing a venue and contributing to the\r\npreparation of contracts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For all roles you will need to understand the\r\nimportance of working in teams and be willing to work shifts and travel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>','Venue & stage support, Sales & marketing assistant, Booking agents assistant, Promotions assistant, Events officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:42:46','2013-11-26 12:35:24',20,'Live events and promotion','Live Events and Promotion involves everything to do with putting on a show or event – from promoting the event to staging it. Live events can be indoor or outdoors, one-off events or tours, and small- to large-scale productions.\r\nIn recent years there has been a growth in live outdoor and other special events, often on a grand scale – from Proms in the Park to Glastonbury – and these have often relied on unqualified and untrained staff to build temporary or travelling stages and to run spectacular events. This Apprenticeship offers you an opportunity to get your foot in the door and to provide the industry with the technical, artistic and administrative skills it needs.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship is suitable for those working in an administrative and/or support capacity. It addresses common skills and knowledge required in all aspects of putting on a show or event. Roles are diverse and you could train as Venue and Stage Crew Support, setting up the stage, instruments, sound and lighting for the live event, or as a Sales and Marketing Assistant or Booking Agents Assistant.\r\nAs an Advanced Level apprentice you could undertake activities to secure funding for a live event, support the licensing and permissions application processes, research and assess the appropriateness of a venue and contribute to the preparation of contracts. You might train as a Music Promotions Assistant, Events Promotions Assistant, Events Assistant, Events/Entertainment Officer or Production Assistant, supporting the Production Manager to coordinate budgets, support the preparation of the performance and identify suppliers.\r\nFor all roles you will need to understand the importance of working in teams and be willing to work shifts and travel.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Venue and stage support, Sales and marketing assistant, Booking agents assistant\r\nAdvanced Level – Music promotions assistant, Events promotions assistant, Events assistants, Events/Entertainment officer, Production assistant','  Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (56,'Advertising & marketing communications','<pre>&lt;span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"&gt;&lt;span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"&gt;&lt;b&gt; Higher Apprenticeship &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</pre>\r\n<p>The advertising and marketing industry focuses on the client and their need for marketing or advertising for a brand or product in a truly digital, multi-platform world.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Creative skills and ideas are channelled into all forms of media – from TV, radio and printed material to billboard advertising, online and interactive media.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship focuses on creatives, creative services and client services, i.e. developing ideas, account handling, liaising with clients and maintaining relationships.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Creatives </b>generate ideas and concepts for a campaign</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Account managers </b>work with creatives to develop solutions that meet the client’s brief</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Production assistants </b>ensure projects are delivered on time and on budget.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn how successful project management, teamwork and creativity combine to fulfil the client’s needs in this fast-moving sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Creative Skillset</p>\r\n','Trainee art director, Trainee copywriter, Production assistant, Junior artworker, Advertising account executive','Level 4 (Higher)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:44:24','2013-11-26 12:16:10',20,'Advertising and marketing communications','Advertising is a form of communication intended to persuade an audience (viewers, readers or listeners) to take some action, usually to purchase or consume a product or service. It is totally driven by and focused on the client and the client\'s marketing or advertising need for a brand or product. It leads the way with cross-platform innovation as campaigns cross boundaries between TV, radio, print, billboard and interactive media.\r\nThe advertising sector is large and diverse, ranging from creative agencies to sales departments. There are around 13,000 companies and almost 250,000 individuals working in the industry, which generates £6.2 billion annually for the UK economy.\r\nThis Higher Apprenticeship has been developed in response to the industry\'s current and future skills needs, including the move to integrated digital functions within agencies and increasing diversity within the industry. Employers will expect you to be prepared for, and possibly have previous experience in a working environment. \r\nJob roles within advertising are varied and include copywriting, visual creative, media planning and buying, account management, production and client service. If you are working for a large agency you may specialise in a specific area, or in smaller agencies you may undertake various aspects of these roles.\r\nJob roles are broken down into three main areas: creative, creative service and client service.\r\nCreative\r\nCreatives within the advertising and marketing communications industry are responsible for the creative ideas and communications solutions developed for clients. You could be involved in producing concepts, writing copy for varied media, developing visual designs or developing and maintaining interactive content.\r\nCreative Service\r\nThe creative service role helps to ensure the smooth running of campaigns supporting the creative team so that projects are managed on time and on budget. As an apprentice you would expect to be involved in all aspects of producing a campaign, from sourcing photography through to TV commercial production.\r\nClient Service \r\nThe client service role provides quality marketing solutions and is the main day-to-day contact for clients. You would work closely with the creative department developing ideas and will need a good understanding of the target audience as well as all media channels and platforms.\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Trainee art director, Trainee copywriter, Production assistant, Junior artworker, Advertising account executive\r\n','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset –  www.creativeskillset.org','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000 ');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (57,'Photo imaging','<p>As an apprentice you will gain the skills you need to work in the photo-imaging sector, in both photographer and non-photographer roles. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Photography demands a good eye and a creative\r\nsense of what makes a good image, as well as a raft of digital skills to keep up\r\nto date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are job opportunities for photographers in the\r\narmed forces and the police, in photographic studios or as schools or event\r\nphotographers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Non-photographer roles include minilab printer,\r\ndigital imaging technician and picture library keyworder.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Creative Skillset</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Photographer, Minilab printer, Picture library keyworder','Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £14,000','2012-11-20 12:47:10','2013-11-26 12:54:41',20,'Photo imaging','The photo-imaging sector requires a workforce with a wide-ranging skill set, combining technical proficiency with creativity, visual awareness and business acumen. If you enter the industry you will need to be motivated and self-sufficient, committed and enthusiastic. Employers are looking for dedicated people, so it is important that you can show an active interest in what they do.\r\nCareer success typically requires a strong passion for the subject and a high level of entrepreneurial ability. Competition is vigorous, especially for photographers, and the rewards vary greatly depending on the skills and specialisms of the individual photographer. That said, the work is usually interesting and seldom routine. \r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship in Photo Imaging is designed to give you the skills to work in the photo-imaging sector, within photographer or non-photographer roles, in a range of settings.\r\nThere are job opportunities for photographers in the armed forces and the police, in photographic studios or as schools or event photographers. Non-photographer roles for apprentices include minilab printer, digital imaging technician and picture library keyworder. Freelancing is common within the sector so you will also need to consider this form of employment to progress your career.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Trainee/assistant photographer, Trainee/assistant staff photographer, Trainee investigative/crime scene photographer, Junior minilab printer, Junior digital imaging technician, Picture library keyworder','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–£14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (58,'Music business','<p>This Apprenticeship is aimed at those working in the\r\nmusic industry in promotions, management and agency-related jobs who work with\r\na range of specialists to plan, book and promote artists or bands.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn a range of technical\r\nand specialist skills to help your career progression through the\r\nindustry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need to show an interest in the entertainment\r\nbusiness, in music in general, or in a particular music form, and in publicity\r\nand public relations. You will also be willing to travel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>\r\n<p></p>','Marketing/promotions assistant, Assistant publicist, Music publishing assistant, Radio plugger, PR assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:48:52','2013-11-26 12:37:07',20,'Music business','This Apprenticeship is aimed at those working in the music industry in promotions, management and agency-related jobs who work with a range of specialists to plan, book and promote artists or bands.\r\nThe wider music industry includes jobs in the following occupations: Composition of musical works and music publishing; Live performance; Musical education; Production, retail and distribution of musical instruments/audio equipment; Recording; and Retail and distribution of recordings. As an apprentice in Music Business you will gain a foothold in a growing sector of the industry and will learn a range of technical and specialist skills to facilitate your career progression through the industry. \r\nIntermediate Level apprentices could work as Marketing/Promotions Assistants or Assistant Publicists, supporting promotional activities and marketing campaigns utilising social media and social networks and provide administrative support to their teams.\r\nAs an Advanced Level apprentice you might train in A&R (Artists & Repertoire), or as a Music Publishing Assistant, Radio Plugger, Marketing Assistant, Assistant Publicist or Public Relations Assistant. You will need to show an interest in the entertainment business, in music in general, or in a particular music form, and in publicity and public relations. You will also be willing to travel.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced Level Apprenticeship (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Marketing/Promotions assistant, Assistant publicist\r\nAdvanced Level – Music publishing assistant, Radio plugger, Marketing assistant, Assistant publicist, Public relations assistant','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (60,'Technical theatre','<p>Technical theatre plays a vital role in creating the\r\nright ambiance for audiences to enjoy theatrical performances.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Sound, lighting and special effects can dramatically\r\nalter the mood and shape of a performance to delight audiences.</p>\r\n<p>There are three pathways to choose from:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Lighting</b></li><li><b>Sound</b></li><li><b>Stage</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Technicians have to handle equipment and be prepared\r\nto work at heights and in cramped conditions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Creative and\r\nCultural Skills</p>\r\n','Assistant electrician, Lighting technician, Board/console operator, Maintenance technician, Sound technician, Stage technician, Flyman','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 12:53:10','2013-11-26 12:59:35',20,'Technical theatre','Technical Theatre plays a vital role in creating the right ambiance for audiences to enjoy theatrical performances. Sound, lighting and special effects can dramatically alter the mood and shape of a performance to delight audiences.\r\nThis Apprenticeship has been designed to attract talent into off-stage/backstage roles and to provide apprentices with the specialised skills they need for career progression and future employment. There are three pathways in Technical Theatre to choose from: Lighting, Sound and Stage.\r\nAs an Intermediate Level apprentice on the Lighting pathway you could train as an assistant electrician, board/console operator, followspot operator or maintenance technician. On the Sound pathway you will train as an assistant sound technician. Those taking the Stage pathway will train as stage technicians or flymen.\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices on the Lighting pathway will train as senior electricians, lighting technicians or maintenance supervisors/managers. On the Sound pathway you could train as a senior sound technician, while if you opted for the Stage pathway you could train as a senior stage technician or head flyman.\r\nYou will need to show a keen interest in working in backstage roles. You will also understand the importance of working in teams and be willing to work shifts. Technicians have to handle equipment and be prepared to work at heights and in cramped conditions.\r\nTechnical theatre is part of the performing arts industry which has around 5,500 businesses, employing 100,000 people. The industry is growing rapidly and it is anticipated that 30,000 skilled workers will be needed in off-stage/backstage roles by 2017.\r\nSee also www.creativechoices.co.uk and www.getintotheatre.org','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Assistant electrician, Lighting technician, Board/ console operator, Maintenance technician, Sound technician, Stage technician, Flyman','Issuing Authority: Creative and Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk ','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Salaries vary across the sector');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (61,'Contact centre operations','<p>Contact centres or ‘call centres’ provide a way for people to get in\r\ntouch with businesses and organisations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry is one of the fastest growing in the UK, with job\r\nopportunities in most urban areas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn about your employer’s services and\r\nproducts so you can assist customers as helpfully as possible.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>No matter where you end up, the same sets of skills will apply: you’ll\r\nwork the phones and computer systems; listen and communicate; solve problems;\r\nand work with a team in a fastpaced environment. You will need to be helpful,\r\nfriendly and well and have an excellent phone manner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA</p>\r\n<p></p>','Contact centre agent, Help desk operative, Sales advisor, Customer service advisor, Telephone banking advisor, Telesales operator','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £12,000 to £30,000','2012-11-20 14:11:51','2013-11-26 13:04:54',22,'Contact centre operations','Contact centres – sometimes known as ‘call centres’ – provide a way for people to get in touch with businesses and organisations. The contact centres industry is one of the fastest growing in the UK, with job opportunities in most urban areas. Contact centre apprentices could work for a number of businesses across a range of sectors – no matter where they end up, they’ll learn all about their employer’s services and products so they can assist customers as helpfully as possible.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you could be working in areas like sales, information retrieval or account management, or for public service advisors, e.g. for the NHS or Local Government. No matter where you end up, the same sets of skills will apply: you’ll work the phones and computer systems; listen and communicate; solve problems; and work with a team in a fast-paced environment.\r\nEmployees of contact centres have to be helpful, friendly and well informed – after all, they’re representing their company or organisation to the public, helping their customers, or even dealing with emergencies for the police, fire and rescue, and ambulance services. Because they spend most of their time making and/or answering calls, or responding to customers via emails or other computer networks, contact centre employees must have an excellent phone manner and be able to communicate in writing (it helps if they enjoy working with and talking to customers too).\r\nUltimately, contact centre work is about providing the best customer service possible, a valuable skill for any apprentice.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles\r\nIntermediate – Trainee agent, Contact centre agent, Help desk operative, Sales advisor, Customer service advisor, Outbound/Inbound sales agent, Outbound/Inbound customer service agent, Telephone banking advisor, Telesales operator\r\nAdvanced – Sales team leader, Customer service team leader, Contact centre team leader, Product specialist, Supervisor, Support analyst, Contact centre manager Higher (Contact Centre Operations Management) – Resource scheduling manager, Senior planner, Team manager, Key account manager, Senior contact centre manager','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): from £12,000 (Intermediate) to £30,000 (Higher)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (62,'Facilities management','<p>Facilities managers are responsible for the systems and people that make\r\na building operate effectively, efficiently and safely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Activities include anything from managing the maintenance of the heating\r\nor air conditioning systems to managing the catering, cleaning, reception and\r\nthe security of a building.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you could work as an assistant to a facilities manager,\r\nsupervising one or more of the facilities or services. You could also be\r\nemployed by a facilities management company in a junior or trainee role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could find yourself working in an office, shopping centre, hospital,\r\nschool, college, university or sports stadium.</p><p>Duties could include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>securing a site</li><li>setting up rooms for events</li><li>assisting with cleaning</li><li>emergency &amp; evacuation procedures</li><li>porterage</li><li>minor maintenance repairs</li><li>reading energy meters. </li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Asset Skills</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p></p>','Assistant facilities manager, Facilities services operative, Caretaker','Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000','2012-11-20 14:13:39','2013-11-26 13:06:30',22,'Facilities management','The Advanced Level Apprenticeship in Facilities Management is a qualification where you will learn about the specifics of facilities management as well as general management topics.\r\nFacilities managers are responsible for the systems and people that make a building operate effectively, efficiently and safely. Activities include anything from managing the maintenance of the heating or air conditioning systems to managing the catering, cleaning, reception and the security of a building. In many cases the facilities manager will be responsible for environmental management, business planning, risk management and will also be likely to be responsible for a large team of staff.\r\nAs an apprentice you could be working as an assistant to a facilities manager, supervising one or more of the facilities or services. You will be involved in resolving issues and making sure the facilities are running smoothly. You could also be employed by a facilities management company in a junior or trainee role.\r\nOn the new Facilities Services pathway your duties could include securing a site, setting up rooms for events, assisting with cleaning, site emergency and evacuation procedures, porterage, carrying out minor maintenance repairs, reading energy meters and using business management systems to control heating and ventilation.\r\nTypes of buildings that you will be working in vary and could include offices, shopping centres, hospitals, schools, colleges, universities and sports stadiums.\r\nFacilities Management apprentices can also apply for associate membership to the British Institute of Facilities Management (BIFM).\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Assistant facilities manager, Facilities manager, Facilities services operative, Caretaker','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org','','26/11/13','','  Starting salary (once qualified): approx. £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (63,'Customer service','<p>Good customer service is key to the success of any business or\r\norganisation. It’s one of those useful skills that’s found all over the place\r\nand covers all the extras that make a customer’s experience better.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most customer service apprentices work in retail, financial services,\r\ncall centres, hospitality, or sport and recreation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your duties will vary, but in most cases you’ll be making sure that\r\ncustomers are dealt with in a positive, reliable and pleasant way – whether\r\nthat’s by offering advice, answering questions or handling complaints.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll need clear and up-to-date knowledge of your organisation’s\r\nproducts and services. You’ll also need to be able to communicate with all\r\nsorts of people.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills CFA</p><p></p>','Customer relationship manager, Customer support officer, Customer relations officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 14:14:51','2013-11-26 13:04:31',22,'Customer service','This Apprenticeship teaches you the skills to provide excellent customer service, and can be applied to hundreds of job roles across many different sectors, from government to telecommunications. However, most customer service apprentices work in retail, financial services, call centres, hospitality, or sport and recreation.\r\nGood customer service is key to the success of any business or organisation. It’s one of those useful skills that’s found all over the place and covers all the extras that make a customer’s experience better.\r\nAs a Customer Service apprentice, you’ll probably work at the front end of an employer’s business activities and regularly assist customers. Duties will vary between sectors, but in most cases you’ll be making sure that customers are dealt with in a positive, reliable and pleasant way – whether that’s by offering advice, answering questions or handling complaints.\r\nTo properly assist customers, you’ll need clear and up-to-date knowledge of your organisation’s products and services. You’ll also need to be able to communicate with all sorts of people.\r\nCompleting this Apprenticeship is a way of providing evidence of skills that will serve you well in virtually any industry – so it’s a very good way to move forward, even if you’re still undecided about your future career.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate – Customer support trainee/assistant/agent/representative\r\nAdvanced – Customer relationship manager, Customer service co-ordinator, Customer service team leader','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): Varies according to job role');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (64,'Funeral operations & services','<p>Good funeral providers help families through difficult times, providing\r\ncare, support and reassurance when it matters most.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you could train for a number of roles:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Funeral service operative</b> – responsible for the day-to-day\r\nactivities that are vital to the smooth running of a funeral</li><li><b>Funeral arranger</b> – work with clients to arrange the funeral of their\r\nchoice.</li><li><b>Funeral director</b> –&nbsp;with overall responsibility for arranging the\r\nfuneral and conducting the ceremony.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>In all roles you will learn to maintain sensitive working relationships\r\nas well as manage and co-ordinate the funeral processes effectively. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skillsmart Retail</p>\r\n','Funeral services operative, Funeral arranger, Funeral director','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-20 14:16:01','2013-11-26 13:08:21',22,'Funeral operations and services','Good funeral providers help families through difficult times, providing care, support and reassurance when it matters most.\r\nAs an apprentice working in the funeral sector you could train for a number of roles: Funeral Service Operatives are responsible for a number of day-to-day activities that are vital to the smooth running of a funeral. Your duties might include driving and caring for the vehicles that are involved in the funeral cortège, preparing and carrying the coffin and being available to clients to ensure that arrangements are being carried out as planned. This is a varied role and no two days will be the same. You will need to have a full driving licence and may be required to participate in an out-of-hours rota.\r\nAs a Funeral Arranger, your primary role is to work with clients to arrange the funeral of their choice. You will liaise with crematoriums, cemeteries or churches to organise the funeral, as well as supporting families that are visiting their loved ones within a funeral home and making sure that they are well looked after. You will need to have a professional attitude, and excellent attention to detail. Clients will need you to be approachable and sensitive to their needs at a very emotional time in their lives.\r\nAt the Advanced level you will work in a more senior role, most likely as a Funeral Director with overall responsibility for arranging the funeral and conducting the ceremony. Since you will be dealing with clients from their very first call, you will need to develop excellent interpersonal skills as well as a good level of self-confidence and knowledge of the options available to the client. You will learn to maintain sensitive working relationships as well as manage and co-ordinate the funeral processes effectively. Good funeral directors become highly respected figures within a local community and are often requested by name.\r\nAll of these roles will require you to have good personal skills and to show empathy for clients. A number of people today use the Internet to research funeral products and services and expect a high level of client service. The ability to think creatively will help you to work sensitively with clients and to adapt to different scenarios as and when necessary.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Funeral services operative, Funeral arranger, Funeral director','Issuing Authority: Skillsmart Retail – www.skillsmartretail.com','','26/11/13','','Starting salary: varies according to employer');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (65,'Retail','<p>Retail covers a host of businesses, from market stalls and independent\r\nshops to national chains and large superstores.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you could be assisting customers on the sales floor of\r\na high street store or handling their purchases. Alternatively, you could be working\r\nin a specialist department and become a product expert, able to help with\r\nspecific queries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>An artistic flair could see you helping to create window and in-store displays. Or you could\r\nwork behind the scenes in stock handling; ensuring products are received in the\r\ncorrect quantities and appropriately stored.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skillsmart Retail</p>\r\n','Sales assistant, Beauty consultant, Customer service assistant, Stockroom assistant','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £11,000 to £15,000','2012-11-20 14:17:04','2013-11-26 13:56:58',22,'Retail','Retail covers a host of businesses, from market stalls and independent shops to national chains and large superstores, and the Retail Apprenticeship covers a range of skills that can be used across this vast sector.\r\nAs an apprentice, your role will depend on your employer – you could be assisting customers on the sales floor of a high street store or handling their purchases. Alternatively, you could be working in a specialist department and become a product expert, able to help with specific queries. An artistic flair could point you in the direction of visual merchandising, helping to create window and in-store displays. Or you could work behind the scenes in stock handling; ensuring products are received in the correct quantities and appropriately stored.\r\nAt Advanced level, your training will focus on gaining specific skills in your preferred speciality. You will handle more responsibility and gain important management skills.\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship has been developed to provide a structured and recognised route into higher level jobs in the retail industry. At this level you may be responsible for managing a small team of individuals, cost control and purchasing, maximising sales and profitability and ensuring that excellent standards of customer service are met.\r\nFrom organising displays to learning the crucial aspects of management, the skills you gain are transferable to all retail companies. With a young workforce, the UK’s retail sector is vibrant and offers many opportunities for early career progression.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Intermediate – Sales assistant, Beauty consultant, Customer service assistant, Stockroom assistant, Visual merchandiser, Fresh food counter assistant (bakery, fish, butchery, fresh produce)\r\nAdvanced – Senior sales assistant, Craft expert (e.g. bakery), Style advisor (Personal shopper, Stylist), Visual merchandiser supervisor, Team leader, Department manager, Store manager of a small outlet\r\nHigher – Director of operations, Regional manager, Area manager, Store manager, Assistant store manager, Floor manager, Department manager, Assistant department manager, Supervisor','Issuing Authority: Skillsmart Retail UK Ltd – www.people1st.co.uk/retail-apprenticeships','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (66,'Property services','<p>Buying a house is the biggest purchase most of us will make in our lives. Estate agents do a serious job, and must understand legal issues as well as\r\ncommercial ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you’re likely to start out in a customer services role\r\nin an estate agent’s office. You might advise people on available properties;\r\narrange appointments and viewings; help market properties; and put customers in\r\ntouch with people who can help during the house-buying process.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could also deal with commercial property, property management,\r\nauctions and selling land.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship has two pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Sale of residential property</b></li><li><b>Residential lettings</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Asset Skills</p>\r\n','Sales administrator, Lettings administrator, Estate agent, Letting agent','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £15,000','2012-11-20 14:18:51','2013-11-26 13:56:11',22,'Property services','This Apprenticeship has two pathways: Sale of Residential Property and Residential Lettings. Buying a house is the biggest purchase most of us will make in our lives – estate agents do a serious job, and must understand legal issues as well as commercial ones.\r\nAs a Property Services apprentice, you’re likely to start out in a customer services role in an estate agent’s office. You might advise people on available properties; arrange appointments and viewings; help market properties; and put customers in touch with people who can help during the house-buying process.\r\nA large part of your work will probably be in residential sales or lettings – however, depending on your agency, you could also deal with commercial property, property management, auctions and selling land.\r\nOn the Advanced Apprenticeship, you’ll get more involved with the different areas of selling properties, from obtaining instructions from clients to invoicing for fees.\r\nWhether you’re finding properties for house-buyers or rental clients, or valuing a property, you’ll need good knowledge of the property market, a professional attitude and people skills. Much of the work will be ‘out and about’ and dealing with people face-to-face, as well as on the telephone.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Sales administrator, Lettings administrator\r\nAdvanced Level – Estate agent, Letting agent','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills www.assetskills.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000 – £15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (67,'Sales & telesales','<p>Selling is the lifeblood of most organisations. If they do not sell\r\ntheir products or services, companies can easily go out of business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good salespeople help customers to buy a product or service to meet\r\ntheir needs. This involves meeting people, building relationships, addressing\r\nchallenges, offering creative solutions and thinking independently. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you could work in a range of sectors, e.g. as a sales\r\nadvisor in a retail store environment, or a membership advisor in a health and\r\nfitness club.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your goal will be to sell as many of your company’s products\r\nand services as possible, while taking into consideration the interests of your\r\nclients. You’ll have to seek out new customers while still looking after the\r\ncurrent ones.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Businesses realise the importance of salespeople and money tends to be\r\ngood. Most salespeople earn commission, and they can even be treated to\r\npresents or other bonuses like free holidays.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills CFA</p><p></p>\r\n','Sales advisor, Telesales operator, Junior sales executive','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £15,000','2012-11-20 14:19:49','2013-11-26 13:58:09',22,'Sales and telesales','Selling is a part of our daily activities. We sell our views, our ideas and ourselves to colleagues, clients, bosses, partners and families. And it doesn’t just stop there. We are often talking with sales people – on the street, in stores and even on the phone.\r\nSelling is a very important process – it is the lifeblood of most organisations. If they do not sell their products or services, companies can easily go out of business. They therefore make sure they recruit promising trainees, give them the best opportunities and hold their good sales people in high esteem.\r\nGood salesmanship involves helping customers to buy a product or service to meet their needs. As a job, this involves meeting people, building relationships, addressing challenges, being creative in offering solutions and thinking independently. As these skills are relevant to many aspects of our daily lives, selling isn’t just a business skill; it’s also a valuable life skill that could help in many circumstances, from ‘selling’ your skills at a job interview to ‘selling’ your ideas during a debate.\r\nAs an Apprentice you could find yourself working in a range of sectors. You may be, for example, a sales advisor in a retail store environment, or a membership advisor in a health and fitness club.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you could take on a supervisory role as team leader and have the ability to earn higher rates of commission. Ultimately, your goal will be to sell as many of your company’s products and services as possible, while taking into consideration the interests of your clients. Customers are important, and you’ll have to seek out new customers while still looking after the current ones.\r\nBusinesses realise the importance of salespeople – money tends to be good, most salespeople earn commission, and they can even be treated to presents or other bonuses like free holidays. In fact, a top-flight senior salesperson could command a salary of up to £100,000, plus commission. But there’s also the other side of things to consider: just because you’re selling something doesn’t mean that people want to buy it. Salespeople have to abide by ethical standards that reflect their professionalism. Their training will focus on the ability to remain calm under pressure and be able to handle rejection gracefully… with the motivation to try again when the opportunity arises.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Trainee sales advisor, Telesales operators, Junior sales executive\r\nAdvanced Level – Sales consultant/supervisor, Sales manager, Telesales professional, Salesperson','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA www.skillscfa.org','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£15,000 plus commission');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (68,'Nuclear working','<p>Nuclear power is an efficient source of energy that\r\nhelps to cut down on carbon emissions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Government has outlined plans to build more\r\nnuclear power stations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once a nuclear power station reaches the end of its\r\nworking life it must be safely shut down and decommissioned.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship, could lead to a variety of roles.</p><ul><li><b>Decommissioning operatives </b>are involved in the safe decommissioning of plant and equipment on a licensed\r\nnuclear site.</li><li><b>Radiation monitors</b> play a\r\nkey role in the safe monitoring of personnel and work environments.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>There are many opportunities to progress to\r\ntechnician, supervisory or management roles. British nuclear industry skills\r\nare also highly valued abroad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The nuclear industry is supported by a wide variety of\r\nsupply chain companies, such as engineering and construction contractors, and\r\nmanufacturers of specialist equipment, which may provide further opportunities\r\nfor employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Cogent</p>\r\n','Decommissioning operative, Radiation monitor','Level 2 (Int)','From £19,000 to £25,000','2012-11-21 09:59:59','2013-11-26 14:15:39',18,'Nuclear working','This Intermediate Level Apprenticeship framework has been designed to meet the requirements for the type of work undertaken in the nuclear industry. The UK’s nuclear industry employs over 50,000 people and provides about 18% of the country’s electricity.\r\nNuclear power is an efficient source of energy that helps to cut down on carbon emissions, and the Government has outlined plans to build more nuclear power stations. Once a nuclear power station reaches the end of its working life it must be safely shut down and decommissioned. With the advent of ‘new build’ for a fleet of modern nuclear power stations, as well as existing operations and decommissioning, there are a number of opportunities across the sector.\r\nThe industry is supported by a wide variety of supply chain companies, such as engineering and construction contractors, fabricators of specialist equipment, manufacturers and specialist service providers, which may provide further opportunities for employment.\r\nAfter undergoing this Intermediate Level Apprenticeship, skilled operatives and technicians could find themselves working in a variety of roles within the nuclear industry. A Decommissioning Operative would be involved in the safe decommissioning of plant and equipment on a licensed nuclear site. A Radiation Monitor would play a key role in the safe monitoring of personnel and work environments.\r\nWithin the industry there are many opportunities to progress to technician, supervisory or management roles. British nuclear industry skills are also highly valued abroad.\r\nThere will be an ongoing need to attract new young people and adults to meet emerging technological challenges, such as the expected expansion due to new build, as well as to replace the ageing workforce within the sector. The Apprenticeship framework will help to ensure that the skills pipeline is robust both in terms of quantity and capability.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Decommissioning operative, Radiation monitor','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £19,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (69,'Gas industry','<p>Gas industry Apprenticeships cover a range of job\r\nroles in the industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could train to work in Gas Utilisation, to cover the installation, service and repair of \r\ndomestic gas appliances, or in Gas Distribution, covering the \r\ninstallation and maintenance of the gas distribution network of gas \r\nmains and service pipes that connect properties to the gas supply.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices work towards registration on the Gas \r\nSafe Register – a legal requirement for anyone carrying out gas work \r\nwithin a property, mobile home or even boats.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Advanced Level apprentices learn to work on more \r\ncomplex systems and have the option to \r\nfollow the emergency services path, learning to respond to a public \r\nreported escape of gas or other emergency.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Energy &amp;\r\nUtility Skills</p>\r\n','Gas service engineer, Gas installation engineer, Gas mainlayer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £28,000','2012-11-21 10:06:06','2013-11-26 14:10:42',18,'Gas industry','The Gas Industry Intermediate and Advanced Level Apprenticeships cover a range of job roles in the industry, which itself consists of two distinct activities: Gas Transmission & Distribution and Gas Utilisation. The Apprenticeships enable you to train to work in Gas Utilisation, to cover the installation, service and repair of domestic gas appliances, or in Gas Distribution, covering the installation and maintenance of the gas distribution network of gas mains and service pipes that connect properties to the gas supply.\r\nIn Gas Utilisation, the types of appliances worked on could include boilers, cookers, central heating systems and fires. Gas installation/service engineers and technicians are trained to connect appliances to gas supplies and ensure that everything’s safe, and deal with faults and gas escapes according to strict safety requirements.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll assist a gas engineer and learn how to install and maintain gas appliances, working towards registration on the Gas Safe Register – a legal requirement for anyone carrying out gas work within a property, mobile home or even boats. The Apprenticeship also covers other aspects of the job, such as systems design, customer service, tools and materials.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn to work on more complex systems. Advanced apprentices will have the option to follow the emergency services path, learning to respond to a public reported escape of gas or other emergency, being able to assess the situation and take the appropriate action, which will include making the installation safe and initiating further repair.\r\nThe Intermediate Apprenticeship also provides opportunities to work on the national transmission and distribution system that transports gas across the country, from ‘beach to burner’. You could learn the skills and knowledge required to lay and maintain gas mains and service pipes.\r\nAs well as technical ability, you need to be good with people, who will want to feel that everything is being done safely. You’ll also need some computer skills, because safety and maintenance records must be kept up-to-date.\r\nApprenticeships are the ideal way into this industry because of their technical content and all the safety requirements of the job – there’s no room for mistakes.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Gas service engineer, Gas heating installer, Gas main layer, Gas service layer, Gas distribution technician, First Call operative','Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000– £28,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (70,'Smart meter installations','<p>Smart meters are gas or electricity meters that\r\nprovide energy companies with detailed information on how much energy a\r\ncustomer is using without needing to visit their homes or business premises to\r\n‘read the meter’.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Customers can manage their energy use more effectively\r\nif they know how much they are spending on energy, and when.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The Government has set a target for smart meters to be\r\ninstalled in all 27 million homes in the UK by 2019.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship focuses on dual fuel (gas and electricity)\r\nsmart meters.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you will learn how to install smart\r\nmeters, how to commission the communications system, pair up the in-home\r\ndisplay device and explain how it works to the customer.</p><p>\r\nYou\r\nwill need to be Gas Safe Registered and so the Apprenticeship covers all the\r\nskills and knowledge you need to achieve that. \r\n<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p>This could be the start of an exciting career in\r\nthe gas or power industry where there are many opportunities for career\r\nprogression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Energy &amp;\r\nUtility Skills</p>\r\n','Smart meter installer (dual fuel)','Level 2 (Int)','From £10,000 to £16,000','2012-11-21 10:08:13','2013-11-26 14:24:59',18,'Smart meter installations (dual fuel)','Smart meters are gas or electricity meters that provide energy companies with detailed information on how much energy a customer is using without needing to visit their homes or business premises to ‘read the meter’. This information also gives customers the power to manage their energy use more effectively once they know how much they are spending on energy and when.\r\nAs part of its energy strategy, and commitment to reducing energy wastage, the Government has set a target for smart meters to be installed in all 27 million homes in the UK by 2019. This will require a large workforce of competent people who have been trained to install and commission smart meters and communication systems.\r\nThis Apprenticeship focuses specifically on dual fuel (gas and electricity) smart meters and will teach you a set of new skills that would traditionally have been taught separately through either the gas or electricity industries. As an apprentice, you will learn how to install smart meters, how to commission the communications system, pair up the in-home display device and explain how it works to the customer. You will need to have good practical skills for handling tools and instruments. This is a very skilled job and some aspects require significant amounts of concentration. Gas and electricity can be dangerous if not handled correctly so you will need to be very safety conscious and have a responsible attitude to your work. You will need to be Gas Safe Registered and so the Apprenticeship covers all the skills and knowledge you need to achieve that. Your role will involve bending and lifting so it’s important that you are fit enough to be able to do the job efficiently and that you are prepared to work outdoors in all kinds of weather.\r\nOn completion of your Apprenticeship, you will continue to work as a competent smart meter installer (dual fuel). This could be just the start of an exciting career in the gas or power industry where there are many opportunities for career progression.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Smart meter installer (dual fuel)','Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £10,000–£16,000 during training, rising to £18,000–£20,000 once qualified');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (71,'Power industry','<p>A massive network of power stations and wind farms\r\nacross the country and the national transmission network (electricity pylons\r\nand utility poles) keep electricity flowing into our houses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers three main areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Generation</b> – power stations and wind farms</li><li><b>Transmission</b> – the national transmission network</li><li><b>Distribution</b> – taking the electricity from the\r\ntransmission network to the customers’ property</li></ul><p>All of the pathways focus on the installation and\r\nmaintenance of plant and equipment associated with electricity distribution,\r\ntransmission and generation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry faces many exciting changes as it must\r\ncome up with new ways to generate electricity – with this Apprenticeship you\r\ncould be part of it.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Energy &amp;\r\nUtility Skills<br></p>\r\n','Jointer, Electrical fitter, Overhead linesperson, Wind turbine apprentice technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Industry average is £20,000','2012-11-21 10:10:10','2013-11-26 14:17:59',18,'Power industry','The massive network of power stations and wind farms across the country and the national transmission network (the electricity pylons and utility poles) keep electricity flowing into our houses.\r\nThis Apprenticeship covers three main areas of the power industry: generation (power stations and wind farms), transmission (the national transmission network), and distribution (taking the electricity from the transmission network to the customers property).\r\nAs an apprentice on the generation pathway of the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’d learn how to operate and maintain the equipment that produces electricity in power stations and wind farms. You could be diagnosing and repairing faults on machinery, testing equipment and handling the materials that the plant uses to generate electricity.\r\nIn the distribution and transmission pathways, you’d be installing and maintaining the network that supplies electricity to homes and businesses. This work can involve many tasks, like joining and repairing cables, maintaining substations, and building or repairing power lines.\r\nAll areas of this Apprenticeship focus on the installation and maintenance of plant and equipment associated with electricity distribution, transmission and generation. Health and safety plays a major role in all areas of training.\r\nThe industry also faces many exciting changes as it must come up with new ways to generate electricity – with this Apprenticeship you could be part of it.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Jointer, Electrical fitter, Overhead linesperson, Wind turbine apprentice technician','Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): the industry average is £20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (72,'Water industry','<p>This Apprenticeship covers a range of occupations\r\nwithin the water industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In the <b>mainlaying</b> pathway, you\r\ncould install and maintain the pipes that make up the network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a <b>servicelayer</b>, you could\r\nlook after the pipes that connect customers to the main.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could be a <b>plant operator</b>,\r\nsupporting the processes at the treatment plant; or a <b>distribution\r\ntechnician</b>, operating the network.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many current managers were once apprentices, so there\r\nis real scope for progression.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Energy &amp;\r\nUtility Skills</p>','Distribution technician, Mainlayer, Servicelayer, Water treatment supervisor, Project engineer, Network manager','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £17,000','2012-11-21 10:11:49','2013-11-26 14:34:46',18,'Water Industry','This Apprenticeship covers a range of occupations within the water industry. Every day, the UK water industry collects, treats and supplies more than 16 billion litres of water to domestic and commercial customers. It’s a large and vital industry that deals with more than just networks of mains and sewers – it plays an important role in the environment too.\r\nThousands of people work to ensure water is drinkable and safe. Rain is collected from rivers, underground and reservoirs, then processed at treatment works and piped to homes and businesses. Once used, it is released into waste systems, with around 10 billion litres per day treated at works. This makes it safe to return to our environment, into rivers and the sea. By-products from the waste water treatment process are a source of renewable energy.\r\nAs an apprentice, you could help to manage the water network from an office or maintain pipes outside. In the mainlaying pathway, you could install and maintain the pipes that make up the network; as a servicelayer, you could look after the pipes that connect customers to the main. You could be a plant operator, supporting the processes at the treatment plant; or a distribution technician, operating the network.\r\nThere is real scope for progression on this Apprenticeship and many managers began their careers as apprentices. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you will probably take on a more supervisory role, and will learn how to work with chemicals, control leaks and diagnose faults. At Higher level your role could be at a managerial level, perhaps taking responsibility for the daily operations of the water or sewerage network or managing leakage control activities on the water distribution network. Alternatively you could work to develop asset management strategies for the water industry or design computer models for the operation of water and sewerage networks.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Intermediate – Distribution technician, Mainlayer, Servicelayer\r\nAdvanced – Water treatment, Mains and services supervisor\r\nHigher – Network manager, Leakage manager, Asset engineer, Network modeller, Design technician, Project engineer','Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (73,'Sustainable resource management','<p>The waste-management industry is developing rapidly as\r\npopulations grow and alternatives to landfill are needed.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The use of technology has become fundamental to the\r\nindustry and there are many exciting changes happening</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentice learn about all different aspects of the\r\nwaste management industry:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>waste collection &amp; transport</li><li>transfer stations</li><li>other household waste recycling centres</li><li>generating energy from waste</li><li>recycling</li><li>processing</li><li>specialist operations</li><li>landfill</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Your Apprenticeship could be with a local authority, a\r\nprivate employer, or a voluntary organisation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Energy &amp;\r\nUtility Skills</p>','Street cleanser, Compost technician, Recycling or refuse technician','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £15,000 to £20,000','2012-11-21 10:13:20','2013-11-26 14:31:20',18,'Sustainable resource management','The waste-management and recycling industry is developing rapidly as populations grow and governments and businesses look for alternatives to landfill sites for political, social, economic and environmental reasons. The use of technology has become fundamental to the industry. There are many exciting changes happening and with this Apprenticeship you could become involved.\r\nWaste management includes the collection, transport, reuse, recycling, treatment and final disposal of waste, the supervision of these operations and the after-care of disposal sites. Core areas within the industry are: waste collection and transport; transfer stations and other Household Waste Recycling Centres; generating energy from waste (including thermal recovery processes and anaerobic digestion); recycling, processing and specialist operations; and landfill.\r\nAs an apprentice you would train ‘on the job’ learning all about different aspects of the waste management industry. You could undertake roles in the collection, transport, treatment and final management of waste and recyclables at both operator and supervisory levels.\r\nAs a Higher apprentice you will probably take on a more managerial role and could find yourself responsible for optimising the outputs from a treatment process, minimising waste within an organisation, site maintenance service contracts, traffic management, logistics, finance, staffing or any other aspects of leadership.\r\nYour Apprenticeship might be with a local authority, a large private employer, a small to medium-sized enterprise (these often offer specialist services), or even within a voluntary organisation. Many jobs require work outdoors, so you should be prepared to work in any kind of weather. You might also need to deal with the general public on a day-to-day basis and for this you should have a polite and courteous manner and be able to provide a good level of customer care.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Intermediate – Manual/Mechanical street cleanser, Compost technician, Recycling or refuse technician (Picker/Sorter/Driver/Loader), Environmental technician\r\nAdvanced – Sustainability officer, Recycling or refuse collection supervisor, Treatment supervisor\r\nHigher – Fleet manager, Refuse manager, Landfill manager, Sustainability manager',' Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship',' Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (74,'Advanced manufacturing engineering','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>Advanced manufacturing engineering apprentices undertake higher-level technical occupations in sectors such as aerospace, nuclear, mechanical, electrical, electronics, automotive and wind turbines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The type of work will depend on your employer and on the pathway you choose to follow, for example:</p>\r\n<ul><li><b>Aerospace</b> – develop, implement and test aircraft systems for use in the cockpit</li><li><b>Nuclear-related technology</b> – design, select, install and verify sensors and related control systems for use on nuclear plants</li><li><b>Mechanical</b> – set up complex production processes and facilities for manufacturing operations</li><li><b>Electrical/electronics</b> – design and develop analogue, digital, small power electronics and microprocessor systems</li><li><b>Automotive</b> – design and configure motorsport engines and other components, both at the factory and trackside</li><li><b>Maintenance</b> – ensure that production equipment operates efficiently and safely</li><li><b>Wind generation </b>– work on the design and operation of gearboxes, hydraulic systems and wind turbine structural components. \r\n</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>This Higher Apprenticeship has been designed to develop high-grade technicians and engineers with practical skills as well as a higher education qualification.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Semta</p>\r\n','Electrical/ electronics technician, Software technician, Systems technician, Manufacturing technician, Quality technician','Level 3 (Adv), Level 4 (Higher)','From £22,000','2012-11-21 11:33:24','2013-11-26 14:38:58',17,'Advanced manufacturing engineering','Advanced Manufacturing Engineering\r\nManufacturing is one of the largest industries – nearly everything we use, eat, drink or travel in has been manufactured to one degree or another.\r\nAs an Advanced Manufacturing/Engineering apprentice you would undertake higher-level technical occupations in sectors such as aerospace, nuclear, mechanical, electrical, electronics, automotive and wind turbines.\r\nThe type of work you will be doing will depend on your employer and on the pathway you choose to follow. On the Aerospace pathway you could work on the manufacturing processes themselves or on the engineering side of the product; for example, developing, implementing and testing of aircraft systems for use in the cockpit. The nuclear-related technology pathway includes the design, selection, installation and verification of sensors and related control systems for use on nuclear plants, ensuring adherence to nuclear-specific quality standards. On the mechanical pathway you could work on setting up complex CNC production processes and facilities for manufacturing operations, ensuring wherever possible that these are as ‘lean’ as can be. On the electrical/electronic pathway you could design and develop analogue, digital, small power electronics and microprocessor systems for real-time and industrial automation projects. The automotive pathway might give you the opportunity to design and configure motorsport engines, transmissions, suspension, steering, brakes, fuel systems and other components, both at the factory and trackside. Whereas on the maintenance pathway you could work towards co-ordinating a team of manufacturing plant maintenance technicians to ensure that the production equipment operates efficiently and safely, by implementing a systematic approach to improving the maintenance activities including condition and performance monitoring. Finally, on the wind generation pathway you could work on the design, operation, control, monitoring and optimisation of gearboxes, hydraulic systems and wind turbine structural components.\r\n\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship for Advanced Manufacturing Engineering at Level 4 has been designed to develop high-grade technicians and engineers who have practical skills, combined with a higher education qualification. This will facilitate progression to Level 5/6 qualifications and enable you to work towards Incorporated Engineer status.\r\nSuccessful candidates will have a variety of qualifications such as A-levels or a Certificate/ Diploma in Engineering, or will have completed an Advanced Apprenticeship in Engineering.','Level: Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles – Electrical/ Electronics senior technician, Software senior technician, Systems senior technician, Manufacturing senior technician, Senior quality technician, Senior design technician, Control and instrumentation senior technician, Computer-aided design (CAD), senior technician, Technical sales specialist, Process senior technician, Safety/performance senior technician, Senior stress technician, Mechanical systems senior technician, Senior environmental test technician, Electronics development senior technician, Electronic engineering software/hardware senior technician, Senior production technician, Motorsport senior technician, Systems maintenance senior technician, Manufacturing plant maintenance senior technician, Engineering services maintenance senior technician, Biomedical equipment maintenance specialist, Senior warranty technician (wind power), Senior blade technician (wind power)','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £22,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (75,'Building energy management systems','<p>Apart from your home, almost every building you enter\r\nis controlled by a building energy management system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The system controls lighting, heating, air\r\nconditioning and water and waste systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn to maintain and\r\noversee the installation, assembly, fitting, testing and decommissioning of\r\ncomplete building services engineering systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your work might include monitoring and adjusting the\r\ncontrol systems to suit changing conditions and building use requirements. You\r\nmay be responsible for the energy efficiency of the building and be expected to\r\nmake recommendations about how to improve this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p>','Building energy management technician','Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:37:19','2013-11-26 14:43:21',17,'Building energy management systems','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship covers a wide range of skills and occupations within the building services engineering sector. Apart from our homes, almost every building we enter will be controlled by a building energy management system. The system controls the lighting, the heating, the air that we breathe and the water and waste systems that make bathrooms work.\r\nYou will learn to maintain and oversee the installation, assembly, fitting, testing and decommissioning of complete building services engineering systems. As a building energy management technician you could find yourself working in many different places, from cellars to gantries and balconies to waste plants. This may include shift work and working unsociable hours.\r\nYour work might include monitoring and adjusting the control systems to suit changing conditions and building use requirements. You may be responsible for the energy efficiency of the building you work in and be expected to make recommendations to the building owner about how to improve this.\r\nThe building services engineering sector takes its responsibility to the environment seriously so you’ll learn to work with this in mind, and health and safety is also of key importance.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Building energy management technician','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (76,'Building services engineering','<p>There are a wide range of skills and occupations\r\nwithin the building services engineering sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lighting, heating, air conditioning and water and\r\nwaste systems must work in harmony with each other.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Technicians take responsibility for the efficiency of\r\nthe building by project managing improvements and updates, as well as reacting\r\nto the changing requirements of the building users.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn to design and oversee the\r\ninstallation and maintenance, assembly, fitting, testing and de-commissioning\r\nof the complete building services engineering systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You might work in an office, interpreting building\r\nplans, or find yourself managing contractors in places like airports, shopping\r\ncentres and football stadiums.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p>\r\n','Building services engineering technician','Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:38:37','2013-11-26 14:45:18',17,'Building services engineering and project management','There are two pathways (technician and design technician) into this Advanced Apprenticeship, which covers a wide range of skills and occupations within the building services engineering sector. The lighting, heating, air that we breathe and the water and waste systems in the buildings we use must work in harmony with each other. The technician will take responsibility for the efficiency of the building by project managing improvements and updates, as well as reacting to the changing requirements of the building users.\r\nYou will learn to design and oversee the installation and maintenance, assembly, fitting, testing and de-commissioning of the complete building services engineering systems. You may be responsible for the energy efficiency of the building you work in and be expected to make recommendations to the building owner about how to improve this.\r\nAs a building services engineering technician you could find yourself working in your own office interpreting building plans or managing contractors and the facilities team in places like airports, shopping centres and football stadiums. This may include shift work and working unsociable hours. While some of this role requires you to work with your hands, you will also need to be able to plan ahead and update official paperwork.\r\nAs a building services engineering design technician you will carry out design work including production of manual and CAD (computer-aided design) drawings, and provide estimates, schedules and data to meet a specification. The role may involve work on new buildings or refurbishment of lighting, heating, ventilation and control systems in a variety of premises.\r\nThe building services engineering sector takes its responsibility to the environment seriously so you’ll learn to work with this in mind, and health and safety is also of key importance.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Building services engineering technician, Building services engineering design technician','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (77,'Domestic heating','<p>The domestic heating industry employs skilled craftspeople and technicians who work with a wide\r\nrange of materials and technologies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Domestic heating engineers must be familiar with\r\neverything from domestic boilers to advanced welding techniques to computerised\r\ncontrol systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They work for\r\ncustomers in their homes, installing heating systems, servicing boilers and laying underground heating pipes.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry includes environmentally\r\nsound technologies like solar water heating and ground source heat pumps.</p><p>As an apprentice you will learn to work under\r\nminimal supervision to install and maintain domestic hot and cold water\r\nsystems, as well as central heating systems. You could find yourself working in\r\nmany different places – from construction sites to residential homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p><p></p>\r\n','Domestic heating engineer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:39:46','2013-11-26 14:57:17',17,'Domestic heating','This Apprenticeship covers training in a range of domestic heating systems and components and their installation. The domestic heating industry is a key part of construction in the UK. It’s a highly competitive field that employs skilled craftspeople and technicians who work with a wide range of materials and technologies. Domestic heating engineers must be familiar with everything from domestic boilers to advanced welding techniques to computerised control systems.\r\nFrom installing heating systems and servicing boilers to laying underground heating pipes, domestic heating engineers work for customers in their homes. In recent years, the industry has also been involved with developing environmentally sound technologies like solar water heating and ground source heat pumps.\r\nAs a domestic heating apprentice, you’ll learn about the installation and maintenance of domestic heating systems and components. You’ll learn how to work under minimal supervision to install and maintain domestic hot and cold water systems, as well as central heating systems.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, your skills base will broaden to include working with oil- and gas-fired domestic heating systems and you’ll be able to enter the profession at a higher level. As a domestic heating engineer, you could find yourself working in many different places – from construction sites to residential homes.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Domestic heating engineer','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (78,'Heating & ventilating','<p>From keeping us warm at the cinema to keeping blood at\r\nthe right temperature for lifesaving operations, heating and ventilation is\r\nfundamental to our lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a broad industry with many occupations\r\navailable to apprentices.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will develop the skills needed to carry out job roles\r\nand responsibilities associated with the installation, maintenance and\r\ncommissioning of heating and ventilating (H&amp;V) systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could find yourself working in many different\r\nplaces, from rooftops or contruction sites to residential and commercial properties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p><p></p>','Heating & ventilating fitter, Service & maintenance engineer, Ductwork installer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:40:43','2013-11-27 10:00:30',17,'Heating and ventilating','This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of skills and occupations within the heating and ventilating industry. From keeping us warm at the cinema to keeping blood at the right temperature for lifesaving operations, heating and ventilation is fundamental to our lives.\r\nThis is a broad industry with many occupations available to apprentices. As an apprentice you will develop the skills needed to carry out job roles and responsibilities associated with the installation, maintenance and commissioning of heating and ventilating (H&V) systems.\r\nIn recent years, the industry has also been involved with developing environmentally sound technologies like air source heat pumps. You could work as a fitter, installing and repairing H&V systems; you could be a welder, using specialist skills to join pipework systems; or you could install the ductwork that either provides clean air to, or extracts air from, parts of buildings.\r\nThe heating and ventilating industry takes its responsibility to the environment seriously so you’ll learn to work with this in mind, and health and safety is also of key importance. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, your skills base will broaden to include designing and installing much larger systems, incorporating other environmental technologies, and you’ll be able to enter the profession at a higher level. As a heating and ventilating engineer you could find yourself working in many different places, from rooftops or construction sites to residential and commercial properties.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Heating and ventilating fitter, Service and maintenance engineer, Ductwork installer','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (79,'Electrotechnical','<p>This Apprenticeship covers the installation,\r\nmaintenance and repair of electrotechnical equipment – from installing\r\nelectrical systems inside a new building to maintaining machinery on a\r\nproduction line.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The electrotechnical industry plays a key role in\r\nother industries – e.g. construction, engineering, manufacturing – and\r\nelectricians use specialist skills to tackle a variety of projects, such as\r\nwiring new shopping centres and sports stadiums or installing CCTV systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices can choose between the following pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Electrical installation</b> – learn to install, inspect,\r\ntest and commission electrical systems, devices, appliances and equipment in\r\ndomestic, industrial, commercial, leisure or agricultural settings.</li><li><b>Electrical maintenance</b> – maintain, service and repair\r\nelectrotechnical systems in office blocks, leisure complexes or shopping\r\ncentres</li><li><b>Highway electrical systems</b> – service and maintain\r\nsystems, from road signs to traffic lights and lampposts, or design and install\r\nthese systems.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</li></ul><p>Electricians can be employed by electrical\r\ncontractors, companies that provide a range of electrical and electronic\r\nservices, specialist operators, and even local authorities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p><p></p>\r\n','Installation electrician, Highway systems electrician, Maintenance electrician','Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:42:25','2013-11-26 14:58:41',17,'Electrotechnical','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship covers the installation, maintenance and repair of electrotechnical equipment – from installing electrical systems inside a new building to maintaining machinery on a production line. The electrotechnical industry plays a key role in other industries – e.g. construction, engineering, manufacturing – and electricians use specialist skills to tackle a variety of projects, such as wiring new shopping centres and sports stadiums or installing CCTV systems.\r\nAs an apprentice on the Electrical Installation pathway, you’ll learn how to complete the installation, inspection, testing and commissioning of electrical systems, devices, appliances and equipment in a wide variety of settings that could include domestic, industrial, commercial, leisure or agricultural buildings, structures or environments.\r\nOn the Electrical Maintenance pathway you will be trained in the maintenance, servicing and repair of electrotechnical systems. You might be working in office blocks, leisure complexes or shopping centres, or on automated production systems.\r\nOn the Highway Electrical Systems and Service and Maintenance pathway, you will be servicing and maintaining existing systems, from road signs to traffic lights and lampposts. On the Highway Electrical Systems Commissioning pathway you will be designing, installing and setting up these systems.\r\nElectricians can be employed by many different organisations: electrical contractors, companies that provide a range of electrical and electronic services, specialist operators, and even local authorities.\r\nBecause this is an Advanced Level Apprenticeship, apprentices will be expected to have strong practical skills and advanced abilities. You’ll need to be able to follow technical drawings and understand health and safety regulations.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Installation electrician, Highway systems electrician, Maintenance electrician','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (80,'Engineering construction','<p>The UK engineering construction industry delivers\r\nsuccessful new build, maintenance, plant upgrade and decommissioning projects\r\nworldwide across the oil, gas, water, power generation, nuclear, chemical,\r\npharmaceutical, water, and food and drink industries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry is fundamental to the economy and the\r\ndemand for engineering construction is set to rise significantly over the next\r\ndecade.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will gain the skills, industry\r\nawareness, practical experience and relevant qualifications to work in a\r\nvariety of roles on engineering construction sites, including offshore\r\ninstallations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>ECITB</p>','Welder, Mechanical fitter, Project control assistant, Electrical technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,500 to £17,000','2012-11-21 11:43:31','2013-11-27 09:52:55',17,'Engineering construction','This Apprenticeship deals with a range of roles in engineering construction.\r\nUK engineering construction is a global force and employs approximately 80,000 people in the UK and 100,000 worldwide. The industry delivers successful new build, maintenance, plant upgrade and decommissioning projects worldwide across the oil, gas, water, power generation, nuclear, chemical, pharmaceutical, water, and food and drink industries. Domestically, the £16 billion industry is fundamental to the economy and the demand for engineering construction is set to rise significantly over the next decade and beyond. The Advanced Level Apprenticeship reflects the many career pathways requiring specialist skills.\r\nIntermediate Level Apprenticeship\r\nThe Engineering Construction Intermediate framework is recognised within the industry as an entry route for new entrants to attain the minimum skills required to support work on engineering construction sites. The occupations within this framework reflect the changing nature of the work and the need to assist with some of the work functions of those trained at a higher level. It can also serve as a progression route for individuals who do not meet the criteria for entry on to the Level 3 framework.\r\nAdvanced Level Apprenticeship\r\nCombining college learning with work experience, this framework is recognised within the industry as the best route for attracting and developing young entrants to the industry and for them to attain the skills, industry awareness, practical experience and relevant qualifications required to work in a variety of roles on engineering construction sites, including offshore installations.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Supporting engineering construction activities (generic activities), Supporting welding activities (includes pipe and plate welding), Supporting mechanical fitting, Metal decking installation, Project control assistant, Steel erecting, Supporting plating, Supporting pipefitting\r\nAdvanced Level – Craft [Pipefitting, Rigging (moving loads), Plating, Mechanical fitting, Steel erecting, Welding (pipe), Welding (plate), Electrical installation], Technician (Electrical maintenance, Instrument pipe fitting, Nondestructive testing, Mechanical maintenance, Instrument and control maintenance, Design and draughting), Project Control (includes options to specialise)','Issuing Authority: ECITB – www.ecitb.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,500–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (81,'Engineering manufacture','<p>Engineers design and build the things that make our\r\nworld go round, from aeroplanes to mobile homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The type of work you do will depend on your employer\r\nand on the pathway you choose to follow.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Generally, you will gain skills and knowledge that\r\nwill enable you to take on a semi-skilled operator role within your chosen area\r\nof engineering.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn about work safety, how to communicate\r\ntechnical information, and how to identify engineering equipment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The following pathways are available:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Aerospace</b></li><li><b>Marine (ship, yacht &amp; boat building, maintenance\r\n&amp;repair)</b></li><li><b>Mechanical manufacturing engineering</b></li><li><b>Engineering maintenance &amp; installation</b></li><li><b>Fabrication &amp; welding</b></li><li><b>Materials processing &amp; finishing</b></li><li><b>Engineering technical support</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The opportunities are endless and diverse.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Semta</p><p></p>\r\n','Sheet metal worker, Electronics maintenance fitter, Military armourer; Pipe fitter, Welder, Process engineer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £16,000','2012-11-21 11:45:00','2013-11-27 09:55:22',17,'Engineering manufacture','Engineers design and build the things that make our world go round. Everything, from aeroplanes to mobile homes, comes back to engineering.\r\nThe Engineering Manufacture Apprenticeship is available at two levels:\r\n• Engineering Manufacture – Operator and semi-skilled\r\n• Engineering Manufacture – Craft and technician\r\n\r\nThe hugely diverse Intermediate Level Apprenticeship is divided into seven pathways: Aerospace; Marine (ship, yacht and boat building, maintenance and repair); Mechanical Manufacturing Engineering; Engineering Maintenance and Installation; Fabrication and Welding; Materials Processing and Finishing; and Engineering Technical Support. As a result, the Apprenticeship offers a broad range of employment opportunities across these sub-sectors.\r\nThe type of work you’ll be doing will depend on your employer and on the pathway you choose to follow. Generally, you will gain the basic skills, knowledge and transferable skills that will enable you to take on a semi-skilled operator role within your chosen area of engineering. You will learn about work safety, how to communicate technical information, and how to identify engineering equipment.\r\nThe opportunities are endless and diverse. For example, on the Aerospace pathway you could train to be a survival equipment maintenance mechanic, ensuring that onboard aircraft survival equipment is maintained and remains fully functional. By contrast, on the Marine pathway you might learn to be a marine carpenter, who fits out ship interiors, or even a sailmaker. The Mechanical Manufacturing Engineering pathway could lead to a future role as a machine operator or semi-skilled sheet metal worker. From electronics maintenance to repair of military weapons, from welding to quality control there really is something for everyone interested in a future career in engineering.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship covers a broad range of areas in the field of engineering, such as Automotive, Aerospace, Electronics and Marine (leading-edge sectors) and Mechanical, Electrical, Metal Goods and Other Transport Equipment (mature sectors). It is designed to provide you with the skills, knowledge and competence to operate as a skilled craftsperson (skilled in practical trades, like fitting or machining) or technician (involved in technical matters and problem-solving) within these areas. Craft roles are generally more common within the mature sub-sectors, whereas technician roles tend to be found within the leading-edge sub-sectors.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship offers a choice of 14 pathways: Aerospace; Marine (ship building, maintenance and repair); Mechanical Manufacturing Engineering; Marine (yacht and boat building, maintenance and repair); Engineering Maintenance; Fabrication and Welding; Materials Processing and Finishing; Engineering Technical Support; Electrical and Electronic Engineering; Installation and Commissioning; Engineering Tool-making; Automotive; Engineering Woodworking, Pattern and Modelmaking; and Engineering Leadership.\r\nThere is a very significant range of job titles, roles and occupations within the scope of the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, including many that require specialist skills. For both Apprenticeships, you will need to demonstrate that you are keen and motivated to work in an engineering environment. You will also require a good head for figures and IT literacy. You’ll need good written and verbal communication skills as well as good spatial awareness and you will be a team player.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Semi-skilled fitter (aircraft assembly), Machine operative, Semi-skilled sheet metal worker, Electronics maintenance fitter, Military armourer, Pipe fitter, Welder, Process engineer, Die-caster\r\nAdvanced level – Specialist welder (submarines), Aero engine fitter/tester, Skilled machinist, Tool-maker, Electrical design engineer, Engineering woodworker','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£16,000 (£18,000 at Level 3)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (82,'Refrigeration & air conditioning','<p>This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of skills and\r\noccupations within the air conditioning and refrigeration industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From keeping us warm at the cinema to keeping blood at\r\nthe right temperature for lifesaving operations, air conditioning and refrigeration\r\nare fundamental to our lives.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a broad industry with many occupations\r\navailable to apprentices. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Refrigeration</b> – learn to install, test and\r\ndecommission refrigeration systems in many different places, from rooftops to\r\nsupermarkets and construction sites</p><p><b>Air conditioning</b> – learn to install, maintain and\r\nrepair air conditioning and heat pump systems. Your job could see you working\r\nat swimming pools, hotels and offices.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p>\r\n','Refrigeration operative, Air conditioning technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:46:22','2013-11-27 10:01:26',17,'Refrigeration and air conditioning','This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of skills and occupations within the air conditioning and refrigeration industry. From keeping us warm at the cinema to keeping blood at the right temperature for lifesaving operations, air conditioning and refrigeration are fundamental to our lives.\r\nThis is a broad industry with many occupations available to apprentices. On the Refrigeration pathway you would learn to complete the installation, assembly, fitting, testing and decommissioning of refrigeration systems. As a refrigeration engineer you could find yourself working in many different places, from rooftops to supermarkets and construction sites. The Air Conditioning pathway on the other hand covers installation, maintenance and repair of air conditioning and heat pump systems. Your job as an air conditioning engineer could see you working at swimming pools, hotels and offices.\r\nYour work might include surveying potential installation sites; planning the layout of pipework, ducts and control panels; and fitting components. Or you could train as a service and maintenance engineers, fixing any problems.\r\nThe refrigeration and air conditioning industry takes its responsibility to the environment seriously so you’ll learn to work with this in mind, and health and safety is also of key importance.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, your skills base will broaden to include working with industrial systems in the refrigeration and air conditioning industries.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate level – Refrigeration operative, air conditioning operative \r\nAdvanced level – refrigeration technician, refrigeration service and maintenance technician, air conditioning technician, air conditioning service and maintenance technician',' Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (83,'Plumbing & heating','<p>The plumbing industry employs skilled craftspeople and\r\ntechnicians who must be familiar with everything from domestic boilers to\r\nadvanced welding techniques to computerised control systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plumbers work for commercial and domestic clients\r\ninstalling sanitation systems, servicing boilers and laying underground\r\ndrainage pipes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you’ll learn to work under minimal\r\nsupervision to install and maintain domestic hot water, cold water, sanitation,\r\ndrainage and rainwater systems as well as central heating systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could find yourself working in many different\r\nplaces – from construction sites to residential homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Summit Skills</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Plumber','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2012-11-21 11:47:26','2013-11-27 09:59:27',17,'Plumbing and heating','This Apprenticeship covers training in a range of plumbing systems and components and their installation. The plumbing industry is a key part of construction in the UK. It’s a highly competitive field that employs skilled craftspeople and technicians who work with a wide range of materials and technologies. Plumbers must be familiar with everything from domestic boilers to advanced welding techniques to computerised control systems.\r\nFrom installing sanitation systems and servicing boilers to laying underground drainage pipes, plumbers work for commercial and domestic clients. In recent years, the industry has also been involved with developing environmentally sound technologies like solar water heating and rainwater harvesting.\r\nAs a plumbing apprentice, you’ll learn about the installation and maintenance of plumbing systems and components. You’ll learn how to work under minimal supervision to install and maintain domestic hot water, cold water, sanitation, drainage and rainwater systems as well as central heating systems.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, your skills base will broaden to include working with oil- and gas-fired commercial and industrial heating systems and you’ll be able to enter the profession at a higher level. As a plumber, you could find yourself working in many different places – from construction sites to residential homes.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Plumber','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (84,'Banking','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>If you have always wanted to be a bank manager, this Apprenticeship is for you.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bank and building society branch managers supervise staff, and ensure that salaries are paid and that leave and other entitlements are provided for.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Branch managers should be committed to the expansion and success of the business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Commercial banking relationship managers work with a financial institution’s corporate clients and provide business advice that will benefit the client.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After completing this Apprenticeship, you could join the IFS School of Finance or the Chartered Banker Institute. You could then complete a professional qualification that offers a fast-track route onto chartered studies. This progression can lead to a specialist role in banking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial Skills Partnership</p>','Branch manager, Commercial relationship manager','Level 4 (Higher)','From £30,000 to £35,000','2012-11-21 12:56:59','2013-11-27 10:05:28',6,'Banking','This Higher Apprenticeship is for anyone who aspires to manage a branch or number of branches for a bank, building society or credit union, or who would like to become a Commercial Relationship Manager.\r\nThe role of the Branch Manager involves supervising staff and includes responsibilities such as ensuring employees’ salaries are paid and that leave and other entitlements are provided for. Ensuring customer satisfaction is also part of the job. The branch manager is often expected to be committed to the expansion and success of the business.\r\nThe Commercial Banking Relationship Manager works with the financial institution’s corporate clients. These clients may be small or medium businesses or large corporations. Depending on the size of the company, the relationship manager may recommend more products and provide business advice that will benefit the business client.\r\nIf you complete this Higher Apprenticeship, you could progress to membership of the IFS School of Finance or the Chartered Banker Institute. You could then complete a professional qualification that offers a fast-track route onto chartered studies through exemptions from certain parts of the syllabus.\r\nThis progression can lead to a specialist role in banking. It’s also possible to enter a higher education course in a subject related to banking, insurance, or other financial services. If you’re interested in a finance career, an Apprenticeship is a great way to get into the market.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Branch manager, Commercial relationship manager','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www. financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £30,000–£35,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (85,'Accounting','<p>Running a business involves a lot of financial\r\nactivities, from expenses and bills to taxes and payroll.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accountants keep track of all these and more to make\r\nsure that businesses manage their money properly.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Job roles in accountancy vary. You could work in\r\nliterally any industry, and apply your skills to any business type – from large\r\npublic sector companies to football clubs and small media firms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Accounting is a highly skilled profession, with staff\r\nworking at many different levels. Apprentices will take the accounting\r\nqualification relevant to their Apprenticeship level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial\r\nSkills Partnership</p>','Accounts clerk, Credit control assistant, Finance assistant, Purchase ledger clerk','Level 2 (Int) Level 3(Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £12,000 to £16,000','2012-11-21 12:58:08','2013-11-27 10:04:13',6,'Accounting','This Apprenticeship could find you working in an accounts department, helping a business or organisation manage its money properly. Running a business involves a lot of financial activities, from expenses and bills to taxes and payroll. Accountants keep track of all these and more to make sure that businesses manage their money properly. Having a business brain, as well as a way with numbers, is a good start if you want to work in accounting.\r\nJob roles in accountancy vary. Depending on whether they’re keeping track of one person’s or a global corporation’s finances, there are several things that accountants can do to help their clients’ businesses. This variety often makes it an attractive profession to pursue. You could work in literally any industry, and apply your skills to any business type – from large public sector companies to football clubs and small media firms. Whatever type of company you want to work for, they will always need the services of an accountant.\r\nAccounting itself is a highly skilled profession, with accounting staff working at many different levels. Apprentices will take the accounting qualification relevant to their Apprenticeship level. Apprentices who qualify as accounting technicians might work as accounts assistants, credit control clerks, accounts clerks, or finance assistants, all helping accountants to keep financial records and prepare accounts. You’ll learn how to balance accounts, process invoices and payments, complete VAT returns, and help prepare financial statements and reports. Depending on whether you work for a large or small company, you could be specialising in one area – like sales – or doing all these tasks as well as handling banking and petty cash.\r\nIf you complete the Higher Apprenticeship, you can progress to full membership of the Association of Accounting Technicians. You could then complete a professional accountancy qualification with a chartered body such as ICAEW, ACCA, CIMA, CIPFA, or ICAS. Successfully completing the Higher Apprenticeship offers a fast track route onto chartered studies and can lead to a specialist role in accounting. It’s also possible to enter a higher education course in a subject related to accounting, banking, insurance, or other financial services.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Accounts clerk, Credit control assistant, Finance assistant, Purchase ledger clerk','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www. financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (86,'Insurance','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>The insurance industry helps individuals and businesses manage risk to protect themselves from catastrophic losses and anticipate potential problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It is a stable yet dynamic industry and work is both financially and personally rewarding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this Higher Apprenticeship you would probably work in the insurance sector in a claims, broking or underwriting technician role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Afterwards, you could join the Chartered Insurance Institute to complete a professional qualification that offers a fast-track route onto chartered studies. This could lead to a specialist role in insurance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial Skills Partnership</p>','Claims technician, Broker technician, Underwriter technician','Level 4 (Higher)','From £20,000 to £25,000','2012-11-21 12:59:31','2013-11-27 10:09:01',6,'Insurance','As the population ages and personal wealth increases, the demand for insurance professionals will increase dramatically. This is great news for anyone wishing to enter this stable yet dynamic industry where work is not only financially rewarding but personally rewarding as well. Your role in the insurance industry will help individuals and businesses manage risk to protect themselves from catastrophic losses and anticipate potential problems.\r\nThis Higher Apprenticeship is about work in the insurance sector in a Claims, Broking or Underwriting Technician or Team Leader/Supervisor role.\r\nTechnicians provide support to all types of insurance work including underwriting, claims or broking, with duties such as reviewing and auditing claims cases, providing advice on technical referrals, contributing to technical audits and liaising with brokers regarding the production of client documentation.\r\nThe role of the Team Leaders and Supervisors is to guide a team of people resolving queries and problems, providing clear goals and developing your team’s professional and technical capabilities.\r\nUpon completion of the Higher Apprenticeship, you could progress to membership of the Chartered Insurance Institute. You could then complete a professional qualification that offers a fast-track route onto chartered studies.\r\nThis progression can lead to a specialist role in insurance. It’s also possible to enter a higher education course in a subject related to insurance, or other financial services. If you’re interested in a career in insurance, an Apprenticeship is a great way to get into the market.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Claims technician, Broker technician, Underwriter technician, Team leader/supervisor','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £20,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (87,'Bookkeeping','<p>Bookkeeping is about understanding how a business\r\nworks and providing accurate figures so that the business knows how well it is\r\ndoing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Bookkeepers record the day-to-day financial\r\ntransactions – sales, purchases, income, and payments – of an organisation and\r\nbring the books to the trial balance stage.</p><p>For men and women of all ages and from all backgrounds,\r\nbookkeeping provides outstanding career opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>(Bookkeeping should not be confused with accounting,\r\nwhere accountants create reports from the financial transactions recorded by\r\nthe bookkeeper and file forms with government agencies.)</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial\r\nSkills Partnership\r\n</p>','Bookkeeping assistant, Bookkeeper','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £18,000','2012-11-21 13:00:48','2013-11-27 10:07:09',6,'Bookkeeping','Bookkeeping is a growing profession – it is demanding, exciting, challenging and, above all, rewarding. It is about understanding how a business works and then providing accurate figures that enable the business to know exactly how well it is doing. For men and women of all ages and from all backgrounds it provides outstanding career opportunities.\r\nBookkeeping is the recording of financial transactions. Transactions include sales, purchases, income, and payments by an individual or organisation. Bookkeeping is usually performed by a bookkeeper. Bookkeeping should not be confused with accounting. The accounting process is usually performed by an accountant. The accountant creates reports from the recorded financial transactions recorded by the bookkeeper and files forms with government agencies. There are some common methods of bookkeeping such as the Single-entry bookkeeping system and the Double-entry bookkeeping system. But while these systems may be seen as ‘real’ bookkeeping, any process that involves the recording of financial transactions is a bookkeeping process.\r\nA bookkeeper, also known as an accounting clerk or accounting technician, is a person who records the day-to-day financial transactions of an organisation. A bookkeeper is usually responsible for writing the ‘daybooks’. The daybooks consist of purchases, sales, receipts and payments. The bookkeeper is responsible for ensuring all transactions are recorded in the correct daybook, suppliers ledger, customer ledger and general ledger. The bookkeeper brings the books to the trial balance stage. An accountant may prepare the income statement and balance sheet using the trial balance and ledgers prepared by the bookkeeper.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Bookkeeping assistant, Bookkeeper','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (88,'Providing financial advice','<pre>&lt;span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"&gt;&lt;span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"&gt;&lt;b&gt; Higher Apprenticeship &lt;/b&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;</pre>\r\n<p>There are hundreds of places to put your money, from savings accounts to ISAs and insurance policies, and with so many options out there people often need help to make an informed choice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are two types of financial advisor:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Independent retail investment advisors</b> research the entire market to give advice and get the best deal for their client.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Restricted retail investment advisors</b> are employed by a bank or building society to advise on the products and services they offer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this Apprenticeship, you will learn to advise on financial matters like investments, pensions and savings. You’ll meet clients, stay up-to-date with financial markets, negotiate prices with providers of financial products and put together financial plans based on your client discussions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial Skills Partnership</p>\r\n','Independent retail investment advisor, Restricted retail investment advisor','Level 4 (Higher)','From £18,000','2012-11-21 13:02:31','2013-11-27 10:23:57',6,'Providing financial advice','This Higher Apprenticeship is about helping people and companies decide how to manage their money by providing financial advice. There are hundreds of places to put your money, from savings accounts to ISAs and insurance policies – and with so many options out there, people need help to make an informed choice.\r\nThere are two types of financial advisor – an Independent Retail Investment Advisor, also known as an Independent Financial Advisor (IFA), who researches the entire market to give advice and get the best deal for their client. A Restricted Retail Investment Advisor, also known as a ‘Tied’ Financial Advisor is employed by a specific bank or building society, and will advise on the products and services offered by their own company.\r\nOn this Higher Apprenticeship, you’ll learn to advise on financial matters like investments, pensions and savings. You’ll be meeting clients, staying up-to-date with financial markets, negotiating prices with providers of financial products and putting together financial plans based on your client discussions.\r\nPeople work hard for their money, and deciding what to do with it can be daunting – so you’ll need a trustworthy manner and the ability to explain complex matters in simple terms. A good head for figures does help, but being a people person is more important.\r\nFinancial advisors often work in business environments – a professional manner and a smart appearance are crucial.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Independent retail investment advisor (also known as an Independent financial advisor [IFA]), Restricted retail investment advisor (also known as a ‘Tied’ financial advisor)','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (89,'Payroll','<p>Large companies employ lots of employees. It’s up to\r\nthe payroll team to make sure that everyone in the company gets the right\r\namount of money, at the right time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It’s not an easy job: payroll clerks are responsible\r\nfor figuring out how much employees should get paid by adding up all their\r\novertime, deducting enough to cover tax and national insurance payments, and\r\ntaking into account things like holiday, sick pay and expenses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn the core skills needed\r\nto work in payroll. Topics include calculating gross and net pay and how to\r\nmaintain accurate employee records. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most payroll departments are lively, office-based\r\nteams. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial\r\nSkills Partnership</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p></p>','Payroll assistant, Payroll clerk, Payroll administrator','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £18,000','2012-11-21 13:03:37','2013-11-27 10:10:25',6,'Payroll','Large companies employ lots of employees. It’s up to the payroll team to make sure that everyone in the company gets the right amount of money, at the right time.\r\nIt’s not an easy job: payroll clerks are responsible for figuring out how much employees should get paid by adding up all their overtime, deducting enough to cover tax and national insurance payments, and taking into account things like holiday, sick pay and expenses.\r\nMost companies pay their employees on the same day, which means that on one day each month, the payroll team has to make sure that perhaps thousands of automatic bank transfers are made accurately. If they’re not, payroll staff are the first people the employees will call.\r\nAn employee’s pay is incredibly important to them, and you’ll be expected to answer queries and solve problems in an efficient, friendly and discreet manner – remember, you’ll have access to a lot of very sensitive financial records and other confidential information.\r\nApprentices will take the payroll qualification relevant to their Apprenticeship level. Level 2 focuses on the core skills needed to work effectively in payroll. Topics covered include calculating gross and net pay and how to maintain accurate employee records. Level 3 builds on what has been learned on Level 2, introducing more complex payroll tasks – including year end procedures. It also helps you develop effective payroll management skills.\r\nMost payroll departments are lively, office-based teams. Organisational skills are important, and while having a good grasp of numbers will help you a great deal, a methodical approach and attention to detail will get you even further.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Payroll assistant, Payroll clerk, Payroll administrator, Trainee payroll administrator\r\nAdvanced Level – Payroll supervisor, Assistant payroll manager, Deputy payroll manager, Payroll team leader','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (90,'Providing mortgage advice','<p>There are many different mortgage products on the\r\nmarket and people often need help to make an informed\r\nchoice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn to advise on mortgages.\r\nYou’ll meet clients, stay up-to-date with financial markets, negotiate prices\r\nwith providers of mortgage products and put together financial plans based on\r\nyour client discussions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>People work hard for their money, and deciding what to\r\ndo with it can be daunting. You’ll need a trustworthy manner and the ability to\r\nexplain complex matters in simple terms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial\r\nSkills Partnership</p>\r\n','Mortgage advisor','Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000','2012-11-21 13:04:38','2013-11-27 10:22:30',6,'Providing mortgage advice','This Advanced Apprenticeship is about helping people and companies decide how to understand the variety of mortgage products by providing mortgage advice. There are a number of mortgage products on the market and, with so many options out there, people need help to make an informed choice.\r\nOn this Advanced Apprenticeship, you’ll learn to advise on mortgages. You’ll be meeting clients, staying up-to-date with financial markets, negotiating prices with providers of mortgage products and putting together financial plans based on your client discussions.\r\nPeople work hard for their money, and deciding what to do with it can be daunting – so you’ll need a trustworthy manner and the ability to explain complex matters in simple terms. A good head for figures does help, but being a people person is more important.\r\nMortgage advisors often work in business environments – a professional manner and a smart appearance are crucial.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Mortgage advisor','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (91,'Providing financial services','<p>There are more than 60 million people in Britain, and\r\nmost of them have at least one bank accoumany nt.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Lots of these people will also have loans, mortgages,\r\ninsurance policies and credit cards, which result in hundreds of transactions\r\nhappening every minute.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a big sector that requires lots of people to keep\r\nthings ticking over. As an apprentice you could work as a cashier, customer\r\nadviser, insurance broker, or insurance and investment administrator.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll learn how to work in a financial services\r\nenvironment and follow important regulations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial\r\nSkills Partnership</p>\r\n','Insurance clerk, Bank/ building society counter clerk, Investment administrator, Pension administrator','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £15,000','2012-11-21 13:06:03','2013-11-27 10:18:46',6,'Providing financial services','This Apprenticeship is about working in the financial services sector and helping customers make transactions.\r\nThere are more than 60 million people in Britain, and most of them have at least one bank account. Lots of these people will also have loans, mortgages, insurance policies and credit cards, which result in hundreds of transactions happening every minute.\r\nThis is a big sector that requires many people to keep things ticking over: cashiers, who perform withdrawals and deposits for customers; customer advisors; insurance brokers, who sell and manage insurance policies; insurance and investment administrators, who keep records and reports up to date, and others.\r\nAs an apprentice, you could be working as an insurance clerk, claims handler, investment administrator, cashier or customer service representative. You’ll learn how to work in a financial services environment and follow important regulations. Every day you’ll encounter customers and numbers, so you’ll need good customer-facing skills and a head for maths.\r\nThe experience and skills you gain will serve you well in many areas of business.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Insurance clerks in a number of areas such as financial services, claims processing, broking and underwriting; customer service staff; bank and building society counter clerks; investment administrators; pension administrators/ advisors','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (92,'Professional services','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>People working in professional services provide specialist advice to their clients.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This includes things like providing tax advice, supporting a company with accounting or providing business advice.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Higher Apprenticeship includes routes into <b>audit</b>, <b>management consultancy</b> and <b>tax</b>.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Auditors</b> help to ensure that firms are run efficiently, public records are kept accurately, and taxes are paid properly and on time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Tax advisors</b> are financial experts specially trained in tax law, i.e. the rules and regulations that govern economic transactions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Consultants</b> are trained to analyse and advise clients to help them make the best possible choices, and to help management solve complex issues that affect their business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Through all three pathways you will develop specialist skills alongside a strong foundation of core business competence valued by all professional services employers. This will give you a great start for a successful career in the professional services sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Financial Skills Partnership</p>','External/Internal audit trainee, Tax trainee, Junior consultant, Account executive','Level 4 (Higher)','From £13,000 to £25,000','2012-11-21 13:07:32','2013-11-27 10:15:58',6,'Professional services','Professional services include a range of different occupations that provide support to businesses of all sizes and in all sectors. People working in professional services provide specialist advice to their clients. This includes things like providing tax advice, supporting a company with accounting or providing business advice. The kinds of services provided mean that the professional services sector helps to improve productivity and growth across the economy.\r\nThe Professional Services Higher Apprenticeship includes routes into audit, management consultancy and tax.\r\n\r\nAudit\r\nAuditors and accountants help to ensure that firms are run efficiently, public records kept accurately, and taxes paid properly and on time. They analyse and communicate financial information for various entities such as companies, individual clients and local governments.\r\nAs an apprentice on this programme you would find yourself working as an external or internal audit trainee, while training for your Certificate in Finance, Accounting and Business through the ICAEW (Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and Wales). This could involve reviewing financial accounts and data; selecting samples of accounts for testing; identifying staff and conducting interviews with them about working practices; updating the client on risks and errors and advising on the action they need to take; and preparing and submitting clear and concise audit reports.\r\n\r\nTax\r\nA tax advisor is a financial expert specially trained in tax law, which is the system of rules and regulations that governs economic transactions. Tax advisors are able to help both companies and individuals interpret issues of a financial nature. Typical work activities might include researching, analysing and interpreting changing tax regulation, liaising and negotiating with HM Revenue & Customs (HMRC), or providing guidance and support on other taxation issues and processes.\r\nIf you choose the tax pathway, you will be working towards the Association of Taxation Technicians (ATT) professional qualification. Your role could include assisting in the preparation of tax returns; assisting in the completion of various tax forms; dealing with client communications in respect of their tax affairs; and preparation of simple accounting statements.\r\nBoth the Audit and Tax pathways are the first step on the ladder towards full chartered status with a chartered body such as the ICAEW or the Chartered Institute of Taxation (CIOT). A consultant is an individual that is trained to analyse and advise a client to help them make the best possible choices, and to help management solve complex issues that affect their business. The day-to-day activities of management consultancy are often varied. Consultancy is essentially entrepreneurial in nature and project-based. Projects can vary in length depending on the type of consultancy, business culture and the demands or industry of the client. They might work as an individual or as part of a large team, and can be based at one site or across several international borders.\r\n\r\nManagement consultancy\r\nThe Consulting pathway could see you taking on two main types of role. As a junior consultant you would assist in the delivery of consulting projects for external or internal clients, working as part of a consulting team supporting the engagement leadership. You might be using your organisational skills to support project management or the consulting sales process, carrying out detailed analysis of the client situation, or helping to make recommendations for clients’ businesses and implement solutions.\r\nAs an account executive or business development assistant, you would support client account teams in relationship management – the tracking and managing of key accounts and relationships – and business development. This would involve tasks such as preparing sales materials and supporting pitch development, or carrying out internal and external communications activities.\r\nIn both roles, a key emphasis would be on developing your own consulting skill-set and core business competence.\r\n\r\nThrough all three pathways you will develop specialist skills alongside a strong foundation of core business competence valued by all professional services employers. The combination of work experience and technical knowledge will give you a great start for a successful career in the professional services sector.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: External/Internal audit trainee, Tax trainee, Junior consultant, Account executive, Business development assistant','Issuing Authority: Financial Skills Partnership – www.financialskillspartnership.org.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (upon completion of Apprenticeship): £13,000– £25,000, depending on company and location within the UK');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (94,'Allied health profession support','<p>This Apprenticeship provides the skills and knowledge\r\nrequired to enable you to support Allied Health Professionals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will work in a supporting role alongside health\r\nprofessionals such as physiotherapists, speech and language therapists,\r\ndieticians and occupational therapists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Patient care is provided in clinics, people’s homes or\r\nhospitals.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills for Health</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Healthcare assistant, Healthcare support worker, Clinical support worker, Therapy assistant','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 11:29:37','2013-11-27 10:25:55',11,'Allied health profession support','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in supporting Allied Health Professionals.\r\nVarious support roles (for example therapy assistant, therapy helper) work alongside Allied Health Professionals – such as physiotherapists, speech and language therapists, dieticians and occupational therapists – to provide patient care in a range of settings including clinics, people’s homes or hospitals.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 3. The duration for completion of this Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Healthcare assistant, Healthcare support worker, Clinical support worker, Therapy assistant, Therapy helper','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £16,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (95,'Cleaning & environmental services','<p>This Apprenticeship has pathways in <b>Cleaning</b>\r\nand <b>Local environmental services</b>.</p>\r\n<p><b>Cleaning – </b>Staff work at\r\ncrime and accident scenes, hospitals, waiting rooms and offices, or even\r\nlarge-scale clean-ups, like on a festival site.</p><p><b>Local environmental services</b> –\r\na mixture of external cleaning and horticulture skills in parks, cemeteries and\r\nother public spaces.\r\n\r\n\r\n</p><p>As an apprentice you will learn a range of cleaning\r\ntechniques and skills as well as how to deal with hazardous chemicals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You might also learn specialised skills such as how to\r\noperate a street cleaner, how to maintain turf or how to use a water-fed pole\r\nsystem to clean windows and building façades.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A huge range of things need cleaning, so you could\r\nfind yourself working in a variety of places.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Asset Skills</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Window cleaner, Street cleansing operative, Specialist cleaner, Caretaker, Neighbourhood services operative','Level 2 (Int)','From £11,000 to £12,000','2012-11-22 11:31:02','2013-12-18 12:23:57',23,'Cleaning and environmental services','This Apprenticeship has two pathways: cleaning, covering many aspects of professional cleaning, and local environmental services, a mixture of external cleaning and horticulture skills.\r\nThere’s more to cleaning than most people realise – cleaning staff can sometimes work at crime and accident scenes, or for the NHS ensuring cleanliness of hospital wards, waiting rooms and offices. They might even take charge of a large-scale clean-up, like on a festival site. As a local environmental services apprentice, you will be working for local authorities and housing associations in settings such as parks, cemeteries and crematoria; public rights of way; countryside recreation sites; and open spaces around people’s homes and council buildings.\r\nTraining is an important part of this career because cleaners deal with hazardous chemicals, and sometimes with large machinery. They also need to have the right customer care skills as cleaners are often in contact with customers. As an apprentice, you’ll learn a range of cleaning techniques and skills including health and safety; working effectively with customers and others; and communication skills. Depending on your employer, you might learn how to clean food areas, confined areas, high-risk areas or the inside of passenger transport vehicles.\r\nThere are even more specialised skills. You might learn how to operate a street cleaner, landscape grounds, how to maintain turf or how to carry out maintenance and minor repairs. You might clean specialised electronic equipment, or use a water-fed pole system to clean windows and building façades. A huge range of things need cleaning, so you could find yourself working in a variety of places.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Hygiene operative, Window cleaner, Street cleansing operative, Specialist cleaner, Caretaker, Neighbourhood services operative','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000 – £12,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (96,'Children & young people’s workforce','<p>This Apprenticeship is for those delivering the Early\r\nYears Foundation Stage within a maintained school setting.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>At Level 2 (Int) you will work under supervision\r\nas a nursery assistant, pre-school assistant, care assistant or assistant youth\r\nsupport worker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At Level 3 (Adv) you could be working on your own or\r\nsupervising others, e.g. nursery nurses, care workers, childminders or foster\r\ncarers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>After completing this Apprenticeship there’s good\r\nscope for career progression and opportunities to undertake further training or\r\nassessment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Care and Development</p>\r\n','Nursery assistant, Pre-school assistant, Care assistant, Nursery nurse, Childminder, Foster carer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £9,000 to £12,000','2012-11-22 11:32:15','2013-11-27 10:33:24',11,'Children and young people’s workforce','This Apprenticeship will help you to develop knowledge and skills relating to the Children & Young People’s Workforce (i.e. those working with children aged 0–19, primarily within Early Learning & Childcare [0–5]; Children’s Social Care; Learning Development & Support Services). This Apprenticeship is suitable if you are looking to join the Children & Young People’s Workforce or if you are already working in the sector.\r\nPlease note: this is not the most appropriate Apprenticeship for those working in/looking to work in playwork or support services (see pages ??? and ???). It is, however, appropriate for those delivering the Early Years Foundation Stage within maintained school settings.\r\nAs an apprentice, the exact nature of your job role will depend on your employer. The Intermediate Level Apprenticeship (Level 2) is for those working under supervision, such as nursery assistants, pre-school assistants, care assistants or assistant youth support workers.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship (Level 3) is for those who may work on their own or who supervise others, for example, nursery nurses, care workers, childminders or foster carers.\r\nAt Advanced level, there are two pathways to enable apprentices to choose the most relevant pathway for the sector they work in, i.e. Early Learning and Childcare for those working with children aged 0–5, or Children and Young People’s Social Care. Please note that the entry requirements for these pathways vary.\r\nAfter successful completion of this Apprenticeship there’s good scope for progression. You may move up through levels of work, e.g. from nursery assistant to nursery manager. There are also opportunities to undertake further training or assessment and possibly to move on to higher level qualifications.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Nursery assistant, Pre-school assistant, Care assistant, Assistant youth support, Community worker\r\nAdvanced Level – Nursery nurse, Pre-school supervisor, Childminder, Nursery teaching assistant, Foster carer, Residential care worker, Short break carer','Issuing Authority: Skills for Care and Development – www. skillsforcareanddevelopment.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £9,000–£12,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (97,'Court, tribunal & prosecution operations','<p>This Apprenticeship will give a broad understanding of\r\nthe Civil and Criminal Justice System and a more detailed knowledge of criminal\r\nprosecution depending on the pathway chosen.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pathways are available in:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Court &amp; tribunal administration</b></li><li><b>Prosecution administration</b></li><li><b>Court &amp; tribunal operations</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices undertake administrative duties including\r\nfiling, data-input, drafting routine letters and photocopying. You might also\r\nmanage casework to ensure that case files are up to date.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills CFA<br></p><p></p>\r\n','Administrative & operational roles within the court/ tribunal/ prosecution services','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000 to £22,000','2012-11-22 11:35:33','2013-12-18 12:22:27',23,'Court, tribunal and prosecution operations','This Apprenticeship will give a broad understanding of the Civil and Criminal Justice System and a more detailed knowledge of criminal prosecution depending on the pathway chosen.\r\nIntermediate level – The Court & Tribunal Administration pathway is for anyone working in an administrative role within a court, tribunal or prosecution service, this pathway gives a more general focus on the Civil and Criminal Justice System. The Prosecution Administration pathway is aimed at administration staff working within a prosecution service. A greater emphasis is placed on knowledge of the criminal prosecution system.\r\nAdvanced level – The Court & Tribunal Operations pathway is for staff who work in an operational role that supports the day-to-day running of the court or tribunal.\r\nAs an apprentice you will undertake a wide variety of administrative duties including extracting files, filing, data-input, drafting routine letters and photocopying documents. You could also have responsibility for managing casework to ensure that case files are up to date and that any missing evidence is gathered from the relevant parties, or for maintaining court records within a system of well-established systems and procedures. Excellent customer service is of paramount importance and you will need to have the confidence to deal with members of the public in a professional and courteous manner. You will also need to have a good eye for detail and be able to work as part of a team as well as under your own initiative.\r\nFor the majority of roles, you will be subject to criminal record checks and some posts may also require you to undergo Criminal Records Bureau or counter-terrorism checks.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: administrative and operational roles within the court/tribunal/prosecution services','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£22,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (98,'Clinical healthcare support','<p>This Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and\r\nknowledge required to support health professionals that provide clinical\r\nhealthcare, such as doctors, nurses, allied health professionals and healthcare\r\nscientists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentice work in various support roles alongside\r\nhealth professionals to provide patient care in a range of settings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>','Clinical healthcare support worker, Healthcare assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 11:36:34','2013-11-27 10:35:30',11,'Clinical healthcare support','This Apprenticeship can be undertaken at Intermediate and Advanced levels and aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in supporting health professionals – such as doctors, nurses, allied health professionals and healthcare scientists – to provide clinical healthcare.\r\nAs an apprentice, you could work in various clinical healthcare support roles (for example as a clinical healthcare support worker or healthcare assistant) alongside health professionals to provide patient care in a range of settings.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 2 and 3. The duration for completion of an Intermediate Level Apprenticeship is 12 months and of an Advanced Level Apprenticeship is 18 months and will depend on age and prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Clinical healthcare support worker, Healthcare assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary: £14,000 – £19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (99,'Dental nursing','<p>A dental nurse provides ‘chair-side support’ for the\r\ndental team, which includes dentists, dental therapists, hygienists and\r\ntechnicians.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship provides quality-assured training\r\nto achieve the qualified standard required by the General Dental Council.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>\r\n','Dental nurse','Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 11:37:29','2013-11-27 10:40:17',11,'Dental Nursing','The Advanced Apprenticeship in Health (Dental Nursing) Advanced Apprenticeship is aimed at individuals who want to work as a dental nurse.\r\nA dental nurse provides ‘chair-side support’ for the dental team, which includes dentists, dental therapists, hygienists and technicians. In England, this Advanced Apprenticeship provides a positive route for attracting staff into the dental sector and quality-assured training to achieve the qualified standard required by the General Dental Council.\r\nThe duration for completion of an Advanced Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Dental nurse','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (100,'Custodial care','<p>Custodial care services play a crucial part in the\r\nday-to-day running of the Justice System.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices support prison officers dealing with\r\nmembers of the public, visitors and prisoners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your duties might include escorting visitors and\r\ncontractors, reception, gate duty, searching visitors and areas and work in the\r\ncontrol room.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The job involves some administration, such as\r\ncompleting forms and writing reports. In high-security prisons, you may be\r\nrequired to escort prisoners in vehicles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may be required to work nights, weekends and bank\r\nholidays and most employers will carry out appropriate security checks. Prison\r\nofficers must be 18 years old and must successfully complete medical and\r\nfitness tests.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nJustice</p>','Prison officer, Prison custody officer, Detention officer, Escort custody officer, Operational support','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £27,000','2012-11-22 11:38:39','2013-12-18 12:30:43',23,'Custodial care','Custodial care services play a crucial part in the day-to-day running of the Justice System.\r\nAt Intermediate Level, apprentices support prison officers on the operational line dealing with members of the public, visitors to the establishment and prisoners. Your main duties will include escorting visitors and contractors, reception, gate duty, searching visitors and areas, providing customer service and work in the control room. The job involves some administration, completing forms and writing reports. In some cases, such as in high-security prisons, you may be required to escort prisoners in vehicles.\r\nFor the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, apprentices work as prison officers or prison custody officers in prisons, as detention officers in an immigration or detention centre, or as escort custody officers looking after the security and welfare of adults, children and young people.\r\nAdvanced apprentices have different roles within different custodial care organisations, according to the type of environment in which they are employed and the level of security required. Your work would involve escorting prisoners/detainees, settling-in prisoners/ detainees when they arrive and supervising their everyday activities such as meals, showers or exercise. You will also carry out searches and security checks and make sure that visitors understand and follow security procedures.\r\nThe job involves some administration, completing forms, writing reports and liaising with colleagues, and management of incidents.\r\nFor all roles you may be required to work nights, weekends and bank holidays and most employers will carry out appropriate security checks. Prison officers must be 18 years old and must successfully complete medical and fitness tests.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Prison officer, Prison custody officer, Detention officer, Escort custody officer, Operational support','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£27,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (101,'Emergency fire service operations','<p>Firefighters mostly work for local authorities, but\r\ncan also be found in airports, chemical works, military bases and power\r\nstations</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you’ll learn about the various ways\r\nto put out a fire using gas, powder, water or foam. You’ll also learn how fires\r\ncan be prevented and advise others on this.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Recruitment into the Fire Service involves mental and\r\nphysical tests, as well as a medical exam and interview.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nJustice</p>','Firefighter','Level 3 (Adv)','From £28,000','2012-11-22 11:39:45','2013-12-18 12:32:23',23,'Emergency fire service operations','Firefighters mostly work for local authorities, but can also be found in airports, chemical works, military bases and power stations – basically, wherever there may be a fire or people needing rescue.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll learn about the various ways to put out a fire using gas, powder, water or foam. More importantly, you’ll know how fires can best be prevented and act as an advisor to others on this important subject.\r\nYou’ll have to be physically fit – the working environment can be very dangerous and will require such feats as climbing ladders, removing obstructions and, occasionally, carrying people to safety. You’ll need to be level-headed, a good communicator and able to take decisive action in emergency situations.\r\nRecruitment into the Fire Service involves mental and physical tests, as well as a medical exam and interview.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Firefighter','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £28,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (102,'Emergency care assistance','<p>Emergency care assistants work within the emergency\r\ncare workforce.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The role involves responding to emergency calls to\r\nprovide care to patients, driving ambulance vehicles, assisting paramedics,\r\nusing medical/life support equipment, providing and collecting information at\r\nthe scene, and completing documentation.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>','Emergency care assistant','Level 2 (Int)','From £14,000 to £17,000','2012-11-22 11:40:41','2013-11-27 10:41:54',11,'Emergency care assistance','This Intermediate Level Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become a competent Emergency Care Assistant within the emergency care workforce.\r\nThe role involves responding to emergency calls to provide care to patients, driving ambulance vehicles, assisting paramedics, using medical/life support equipment, providing and collecting information at the scene, and completing documentation.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 2. The duration for completion of the Apprenticeship is 12 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Emergency care assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (103,'Employment related services','<p>This Apprenticeship supports people working to help\r\nthose seeking employment via welfare to work programmes, recruitment agencies,\r\ncareer guidance, etc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Employment service providers often deliver contracts\r\non behalf of Government departments such as the Ministry of Justice (MOJ) and\r\nDepartment for Education (DfE).</p><p><b>Personal advisors/ job coaches</b>\r\nwork with individuals to identify their strengths and weaknesses, and career\r\naspirations, and develop plans to help them to move into employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Tutors </b>work with\r\ngroups to improve their employability skills, e.g. working on job search and interview\r\ntechniques.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Job brokers</b> liaise with\r\nemployers to generate opportunities to gain and sustain employment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In <b>customer liaison</b> you would be\r\nresponsible for initial screening and developing relationships with customers\r\nand employers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice<br></p>\r\n','Personal advisor, Job coach, Tutor, Job broker, Customer liaison','Level 3 (Adv)','From £18,000 to £25,000','2012-11-22 11:42:12','2013-12-18 12:33:44',23,'Employment related services','Employment related services describes the delivery of contracts or services that help people into employment, or support them to sustain an employed status.\r\nThis Advanced Level Apprenticeship has been developed to support the people who help those seeking employment. It is aimed at those working in the employability and skills sector, which could include welfare to work, recruitment agencies, career guidance and other pre-employment services.\r\nEmployment Service Providers often deliver contracts on behalf of Government departments including the Department for Work & Pensions (DWP), Ministry of Justice (MOJ) and Department for Education (DfE). Examples of contracts where this Apprenticeship would be most appropriate are The Work Programme, Work Choice, National Offender Management Services, Skills Funding Agency, Employability contracting and a number of European Social Fund initiatives that focus on reducing worklessness.\r\nAs an apprentice you could train for a role such as Personal Advisor/Job Coach, working on a one-to-one basis with individuals to identify their strengths and weaknesses, identify their career aspirations and develop plans to help them to move into their desired employment. As a Tutor you would work with groups to improve their employability skills, working on job search and interview techniques, for example. Job Brokers liaise with employers to generate opportunities to gain and sustain employment, whereas if you worked in Customer Liaison you would be responsible for initial screening and developing relationships with customers and employers.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you will develop in a particular role, widen your skills to move into other roles within the sector, and aid your vertical progression into management positions.\r\nAlthough this Apprenticeship has no formal entry conditions, you will need to enjoy assisting others to achieve their potential, be driven by performing well against agreed targets and wish to work with customers and employers to meet their needs. In turn you will gain a high level of job satisfaction from helping others. Some employers may require you to undertake a Criminal Records Bureau (CRB) check depending on the customer group that you would work with.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job role: Personal advisor/ Job coach, Tutor, Job broker/ Employer engagement, Customer liaison','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','','','','Starting salary (once fully competent): £18,000– £25,000 (+ bonus)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (104,'Health & social care','\r\n\r\n<p>Social care is about helping people with a particular\r\nneed, such as the disabled, the elderly or people with learning disabilities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Care can include anything from helping people get\r\ndressed to transporting them to and from a residential home or taking them\r\nshopping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of job roles\r\non two pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Adult social care</b></li><li><b>Health care</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>You could work for the NHS, the private sector, local\r\nauthorities or in the voluntary sector.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nCare and Development </p>\r\n','Care assistant, Support worker, Mental health outreach worker, Community support worker','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £17,000','2012-11-22 11:43:27','2013-11-27 10:45:23',11,'Health and social care','This Apprenticeship covers a wide range of job roles on two pathways: the adult social care pathway and the health care pathway. This could mean working in the NHS, the private sector, local authorities or in the voluntary sectors.\r\nSocial care is about helping people with a particular need, such as the disabled, the elderly or people with learning disabilities. This type of care usually takes place in the home or in care homes or out in the community, and can include anything from helping people get dressed to transporting them to and from a residential home or taking them shopping. As an apprentice in Social Care, you could be a personal care assistant helping someone in their everyday life.\r\nAs an apprentice on the Health Care pathway, you could work in hospitals, the community, hospices or private clinics as a healthcare support worker or a healthcare assistant. You could be supporting doctors or nurses or helping patients in hospital wards or their homes – serving food, making and changing beds and so on.\r\nCompletion of the Advanced Level Apprenticeship will stand you in good stead for progression onto the Care Leadership and Management Higher Apprenticeship (see page ???) as well as the option to progress on to Higher Education in subjects like nursing or midwifery and operating department practitioner roles in the care sector or management roles in care homes. The main difference between the Intermediate Level and Advanced Level Apprenticeships is the level of responsibility you will hold and the role at which you will work.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles:\r\nIntermediate Level – Healthcare support worker, Healthcare assistant, Care assistant, Personal assistant, Relief team worker, Night care assistant, Support worker – supported living, Key workers in residential, domiciliary or day services, Home care support worker, Substance misuse worker, Mental health support or outreach worker, Re-enablement worker\r\nAdvanced Level – Senior healthcare support worker, Senior healthcare assistant, Care officer, Care supervisor, Senior care worker, Supervising care worker, Senior support worker, Relief team leader, Social work assistant, Social services officer, Outreach development worker, Community support worker, Community outreach worker, Community development worker, Family support worker, Personal assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Care and Development – www.skillsforcareanddevelopment.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000 – £17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (105,'Healthcare support services','<p>Support services within the health sector include\r\ncleaning, housekeeping, catering, porterage, administration, record keeping,\r\nsecurity, parking, waste disposal, moving equipment, gardening, looking after\r\nbuildings and machinery.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These roles are central to the smooth running of\r\nhealthcare services.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>','Healthcare support service worker','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 11:44:35','2013-11-27 10:59:43',11,'Healthcare support services','This Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in providing support services within the health sector.\r\nVarious roles exist and duties may include activities like cleaning, housekeeping, catering, porterage, administration, record keeping, security, parking, waste disposal, moving equipment and/or individuals, gardening, looking after buildings and machinery. These roles are central to the smooth running of healthcare services.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 2 and 3. The duration for completion of an Intermediate Apprenticeship is 12 months and of an Advanced Apprenticeship is 12 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Healthcare support service worker','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary: £14,000– £19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (106,'Health informatics','<p>Health informatics is the collection, management, use\r\nand sharing of information to support the delivery of healthcare and to promote\r\nhealth.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will handle and input data as\r\nwell as validating it and producing reports.</p><p></p>You will\r\nbe working with large amounts of information, some of which may be\r\nconfidential, so you will need to be well-organised, conscientious and discreet.<br><br><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>\r\n','Health information assistant','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','£14,000 to £17,000','2012-11-22 11:53:13','2013-11-27 10:57:22',11,'Health informatics','This Apprenticeship can be taken at Intermediate or Advanced level. Health informatics is the collection, management, use and sharing of information to support the delivery of healthcare and to promote health. This Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in health informatics.\r\nAs an apprentice you will work in a health information assistant or assistant practitioner (informatics) role, where you will handle and input data as well as validating it and producing reports. You will be working with large amounts of information, some of which may be confidential, so you will need to be well-organised, conscientious and discreet.\r\nDesigned as a work-based qualification, this Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF level 2 and 3. The duration for completion of this Apprenticeship is 12 months for the Intermediate Apprenticeship and 18 months for the Advanced Apprenticeship, depending on age, prior experience and learning.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Health information assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Salary: £14,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (107,'HM Forces','<p>This Apprenticeship offers a work-based learning route into HM Forces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>To join you must successfully complete the recruitment process for the service you want to join (Royal Navy, Army or RAF), have been accepted to undertake Initial Military training and have been attested as a member of HM Forces.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whichever service you join, you will carry out general or more specialised duties which could be in aggressive, peacekeeping or humanitarian roles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will gain a range of knowledge and skills relating to physical fitness, first aid, navigation, operating weapons systems, ceremonial duties, combat preparation and damage control through the Apprenticeship in conjunction with your military training.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice </p>','Naval warfare rating, Royal Marines general duties rifleman, Army infantryman, RAF regiment gunner','Level 2 (Int)','From £14,000','2012-11-22 11:57:08','2013-12-18 12:38:08',23,'HM Forces','HM Forces continually recruit young people from all walks of life who are interested in securing a career within the Forces and improving their educational standing. This Apprenticeship offers a work-based learning route into HM Forces, adds rigour to the initial military training, and in turn enhances an individual’s career prospects and academic skill set.\r\nTo undertake this Apprenticeship you must first successfully complete the recruitment process for the Service you want to join (Royal Navy, Royal Marines, Army or Royal Air Force), have been accepted to undertake Initial Military training and have been attested as a member of HM Forces.\r\nDue to the nature of the work you will undertake there are a number of entry restrictions relating to age, nationality, residency, gender, medical and physical fitness. Please check the guidance and current entry requirements for each Service on the websites listed below or visit your local Armed Forces Careers Office.\r\nDepending on which Service you join, you will undertake roles such as Naval Warfare Rating, Royal Marines General Duties Rifleman, Army Infantryman or RAF Regiment Gunner. In all roles you will carry out general or more specialised duties which could be in aggressive, peacekeeping or humanitarian roles. Other activities could include preparatory and upgrade training as well as ceremonial duties.\r\nAs an apprentice you will be provided with a structured learning programme that meets the needs of your employer, enabling you to fully understand why you should conduct yourself in a professional and safe manner. You will gain a clear understanding of how your performance is directly related to the success of the Service and help to secure your future career within both the HM Forces and other sectors.\r\nTo be competent as a Sailor/Marine, Soldier or Airman you need a range of knowledge and skills relating to physical fitness, first aid, navigation, operating weapons systems, ceremonial duties, combat preparation and damage control, and you will gain these through the Apprenticeship in conjunction with your military training. Other areas of the Apprenticeship are designed to develop wider skills such as teamwork and effective participation to improve your competence and equip you for future career progression both within the Service and in other sectors (e.g. other uniformed services, security services, management and leadership and teaching and assessment) when your Service career comes to an end.\r\nRoyal Navy (including Royal Marines) – www.royalnavy.mod.uk\r\nArmy – www.armyjobs.mod.uk\r\nRoyal Air Force – www.raf.mod.uk\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job role: Naval warfare rating, Royal Marines general duties rifleman, Army infantryman, RAF regiment gunner','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','','','Starting salary (once fully competent): £14,000, rising to £17,000 on completion of Basic Military Training. Employees of HM Forces can expect their salary to increase with experience and rank. The top end rank earns ~£47,000.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (108,'Legal services','<p>A paralegal is not a qualified lawyer but is qualified\r\nto perform legal work that requires knowledge of the law and procedures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Paralegals or legal assistants work for lawyers or\r\nwithin a legal environment within commerce, industry or the public sector.\r\nTheir duties may take them from office to courtroom, from clients to\r\nconferences, from the law library to the negotiating table.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you would train as a paralegal\r\nassistant or paralegal officer working in criminal prosecution, civil litigation,\r\nemployment practice, family practice, property and private client work. Your\r\nduties could include managing non-complex legal matters to meet timescales and deadlines, and assisting\r\nmore senior colleagues with their tasks. You may be required to attend court\r\nwhere necessary.</p><p>At Higher\r\nLevel there are three pathways: Commercial Litigation, Debt Recovery &amp;\r\nInsolvency and Personal Injury. You will be responsible for\r\nmanaging fairly complex legal matters through to completion and may also supervise more junior staff.\r\n</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nJustice</p>\r\n','Paralegal officer, Paralegal assistant, Claims handler','Level 3 (Adv), Level 4 (Higher)','From £15,000 to £40,000','2012-11-22 11:58:57','2013-11-25 14:41:39',1,'Legal Services','A paralegal is not a qualified lawyer but is qualified to perform legal work that requires knowledge of the law and procedures. Paralegals, or legal assistants as they are also known, may work for lawyers within the legal profession or they may work within a legal environment within commerce, industry or the public sector – in central government or with a local authority for example. This is a rapidly growing profession delivering a wide range of legal services.\r\nParalegals are important members of the legal team and play a key role in the legal process. Working closely with solicitors, barristers and legal executives, their duties may take them from office to courtroom, from clients to conferences, from the law library to the negotiating table.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship offers an opportunity to train in a range of job roles working in the following areas: criminal prosecution, civil litigation, employment practice, family practice, property and private client work. Your duties could include managing non-complex legal matters within your area of responsibility to ensure that they meet timescales and deadlines. Assisting more senior colleagues with pre-defined tasks will also be a regular occurrence for most roles. You will ensure that files are up to date and that any missing evidence is gathered from the relevant parties. You may be required to attend court where necessary.\r\nAt Higher Level there are three pathways: Commercial Litigation, Debt Recovery & Insolvency and Personal Injury. For all pathways you will be responsible for managing fairly complex legal matters through to completion. Your responsibilities may also see you supervising more junior staff.\r\nThe Apprenticeship provides a package of training and qualifications for new and existing staff working in a legal environment involved in the provision and\r\npractice of legal services and legal advice. After completing your Apprenticeship you could go on to take further professional legal services qualifications such\r\nas those offered by CILEx and the National Association of Licensed Paralegals (NALP).\r\nSkills for Justice is in collaboration with law firms and key stakeholders in the legal services sector to develop further pathways for other areas of law and\r\nadditional pathways will be available in the near future.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Advanced Level – Paralegal, Paralegal officer, Paralegal assistant, Claims handler\r\nHigher Level – Senior paralegal, Senior paralegal officer, Personal injury specialist, Senior claims handler, Fee earner, Litigation executive','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','25/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£40,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (109,'Housing','<p>Housing officers supervise the day-to-day management\r\nof rented properties that belong to housing associations and local authorities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They deal with people and property, assess the needs\r\nof people applying for housing, allocate vacant accommodation and deal with\r\nproblems that crop up.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a Housing apprentice, you could be assessing\r\nhousing need of applicants, letting homes, collecting rents, or managing the\r\ndevelopment of new homes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll learn about customer services, housing\r\nmanagement, lettings and allocation, homelessness and advice, supported housing\r\n(which covers shared housing, hostels and sheltered housing), and repairs and\r\nmaintenance.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The work is office-based but there will be some time\r\nspent away visiting tenants, attending meetings, and inspecting buildings.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Asset Skills</p>\r\n<p></p>','Housing officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £20,000','2012-11-22 12:02:58','2013-12-18 12:36:06',23,'Housing','This Apprenticeship deals with work in the housing sector. Housing officers supervise the day-to-day management of rented properties that belong to housing associations and local authorities. They deal with both people and property, assessing the needs of people applying for housing, allocating vacant accommodation and dealing with any problems that crop up, from anti-social behaviour to broken boilers.\r\nAs a Housing apprentice, your duties will depend on your employer and whether they’re part of the public sector, the voluntary sector, or the private rented sector. You could be assessing housing need of applicants, letting homes, collecting rents, or managing the development of new homes.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you’ll learn about customer services, housing management, lettings and allocation, homelessness and advice, supported housing (which covers shared housing, hostels and sheltered housing), and repairs and maintenance.\r\nThe work is office-based but there will be some time spent away visiting tenants, attending meetings, and inspecting buildings. It’s a big, important job – after all, shelter is one of the most basic human needs. You’ll need to deal sensitively with a wide range of people, and come up with real solutions to their problems.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Housing officer','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org ','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000 – £20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (110,'Local taxation & benefits','<p>Schools, the police, and local social services rely on\r\nthe efficient collection of local revenues, and the less well off in society\r\nrely on the efficient administration of housing and council tax benefit.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Local revenues and benefits are generally administered\r\nby local authorities but a growing number of private companies provide benefit\r\nservices to local councils.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you might work for a local housing\r\nassociation or Citizens Advice Bureau offering advice on benefits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Local government revenues officers</b> calculate rents,\r\ncouncil tax and business rates; send bills and issue reminders; collect and\r\nprocess payments; deal with enquiries; and recover arrears of rent or council\r\ntax.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Local government benefits officers</b> assess whether\r\npeople are entitled to housing and council tax benefits, communicate with other\r\ngovernment agencies and deal with enquiries face-to-face.</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Asset Skills</p>','Revenues officer, Benefits officer','Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £21,000','2012-11-22 12:05:17','2013-12-18 12:41:35',23,'Local taxation and benefits','This Apprenticeship will enable you to secure work in revenues and benefits administration, an area that makes a positive contribution to the well-being of communities.\r\nSchools, the police, street cleaning and local social services rely on the efficient collection of local revenues, and the less well off in society rely on the efficient administration of housing and council tax benefit.\r\nLocal revenues and benefits are administered by local authorities in England and Wales, which include district councils and unitary authorities. There are a growing number of private companies contracted to provide benefit services to local councils. As an apprentice, you may also have the possibility of working for local housing associations or Citizens Advice Bureaus offering advice on benefits.\r\nThe duties of a local government revenues officer include calculating rents, council tax and business rates; sending bills and issuing reminders; collecting and processing payments; dealing with enquiries face-to-face, by letter or by phone; and recovering arrears of rent or council tax.\r\nThe duties of a local government benefits officer include assessing whether people are entitled to housing and council tax benefits; communicating with other government agencies; and dealing with enquiries face-to-face, by letter or by phone.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Revenues officer, Benefits officer','Issuing authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org ','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£21,000  Please note that salary information is a guide only.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (111,'Laboratory & science technicians','<p>Laboratory and science technicians carry out routine\r\nand one-off laboratory testing and perform a variety of technical support\r\nfunctions to help scientists, technologists and others with their work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They also help teachers and lecturers in the delivery\r\nof science education.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Careers are available within science, engineering and\r\nmanufacturing industries, from chemicals and pharmaceuticals through to\r\nnuclear, oil, gas, petroleum and polymers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> Semta</p>','Laboratory technician, Medical laboratory assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £16,000','2012-11-22 12:06:24','2013-11-27 11:00:56',11,'Laboratory and science technicians','If you are interested in a career working in a laboratory setting then this Apprenticeship is for you. Laboratory and science technicians carry out both routine and one-off laboratory testing and perform a variety of technical support functions to help scientists, technologists and others with their work. They also help teachers and lecturers in the delivery of science education.\r\nGood laboratory and science technicians make a significant contribution to science companies operating in the UK and have a broad range of practical and theoretical skills. Careers are available within science, engineering and manufacturing industries, from chemicals and pharmaceuticals through to nuclear, oil, gas, petroleum and polymers. There is a significant demand for non-graduate technicians in a variety of support roles.\r\nAs an apprentice, the specific nature of your job will vary according to the needs of your employer, but you could work in the following areas: research and development, scientific analysis and testing or education and industry. Technicians are employed in a wide range of scientific fields that impact almost every aspect of our lives. You could be involved in helping to diagnose disease by supporting medical specialists. You might be called upon to set up equipment and experiments that support teachers and lecturers who teach biology, chemistry, physics and other scientific subjects. \r\nCompletion of the Apprenticeship could lead to further qualifications or Higher Education.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)\r\n','Job roles: Laboratory technician, Medical laboratory assistant','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000 – £16,000 (£18,000 at Level 3)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (112,'Optical retail','<p>This Apprenticeship supports individuals in the\r\noptical retail sector, as part of the wider healthcare team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Optical assistants and practice support staff have a\r\nrange of job titles, for example dispensing assistants, optical assistants,\r\ncontact lens assistants and optical retail receptionists.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All of these support roles assist the optometrist\r\nand/or dispensing optician.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p>\r\n<p></p>','Dispensing assistant, Optical assistant, Contact lens assistant, Receptionist','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000','2012-11-22 12:07:24','2013-11-27 11:08:21',11,'Optical retail','The Health (Optical Retail) Apprenticeship supports individuals in the optical retail sector, as part of the wider healthcare team.\r\nOptical assistants and practice support staff have a range of job titles, for example dispensing assistants, optical assistants, contact lens assistants and optical retail receptionists. All of these support roles assist the optometrist and/or dispensing optician.\r\nThe duration for completion of an Intermediate Apprenticeship is 15 months and for an Advanced Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Dispensing assistant, Optical assistant, Contact lens assistant, Receptionist','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary:£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (113,'Maternity & paediatric support','<p>As an apprentice you will gain the skills and\r\nknowledge required to support maternity and paediatric professionals in a\r\nvariety of roles.\r\n\r\n</p><p>Healthcare support workers, healthcare assistants,\r\nmaternity support workers, paediatric support workers, etc. work alongside\r\ndoctors, midwives, nurses and allied health professionals to provide patient\r\ncare in a range of settings including clinics, people’s homes and hospitals.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nHealth</p><p></p>\r\n','Healthcare support worker, Healthcare assistant, Maternity support worker, Paediatric support worker','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 12:08:19','2013-11-27 11:06:19',11,'Maternity and paediatric support','This Advanced Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in supporting maternity and paediatric professionals. \r\nVarious support roles (for example healthcare support worker, healthcare assistant, maternity support worker, paediatric support worker) work alongside maternity and paediatric professionals – such as doctors, midwives, nurses and allied health professionals – to provide patient care in a range of settings including clinics, people’s homes and hospitals.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Advanced Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 3. The duration for completion of the Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Healthcare support worker, Healthcare assistant, Maternity support worker, Paediatric support worker','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary:£16,000– £19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (114,'Perioperative support','<p>This Apprenticeship will give you the skills and\r\nknowledge you need to support health professionals within the operating theatre\r\ndepartment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Perioperative/theatre support staff work alongside\r\nsurgeons, nurses and operating department practitioners to provide patient care\r\nwithin the hospital operating theatre department.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Health </p>\r\n','Perioperative support worker, Theatre support worker','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 12:09:35','2013-11-27 11:13:11',11,'Perioperative support','This Advanced Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in supporting health professionals within the operating theatre department. Perioperative/theatre support workers work alongside health professionals such as surgeons, nurses and operating department practitioners to provide patient care within the hospital operating theatre department.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Advanced Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 3. The duration for completion of this Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Perioperative support worker, Theatre support worker','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary: £16,000– £19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (115,'Pathology support','<p>As an apprentice you will gain the skills and\r\nknowledge required to become competent in various pathology support roles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pathology support workers, healthcare science assistants\r\nand medical laboratory assistants support health professionals within a\r\npathology laboratory.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for\r\nHealth</p><p></p>\r\n','Pathology support worker, Healthcare science assistant, Medical laboratory assistant','Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 12:10:32','2013-11-27 11:11:09',11,'Pathology support','This Advanced Apprenticeship aims to provide the skills and knowledge required to become competent in various roles – such as pathology support worker, healthcare science assistant, medical laboratory assistant – to support health professionals (for example healthcare scientists) within a pathology laboratory.\r\nDesigned as a work-based programme this Advanced Apprenticeship includes qualifications at QCF Level 3. The duration for completion of this Apprenticeship is 18 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Pathology support worker, Healthcare science assistant, Medical laboratory assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary:£16,000– £19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (116,'Policing','<p>The justice system employs up to a quarter of a million\r\npeople in policing and law enforcement.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On the Defence Policing pathway you would work as a\r\nnon-commissioned officer carrying out investigations into criminal offences\r\nsuch as thefts, assaults and traffic accidents.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your role would include some administrative duties, such as completing forms and writing reports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You can apply for this Apprenticeship via application to the Royal Military Police. You will need to complete the Army’s\r\nPhase 1 Basic Training and be selected for the Royal Military Police.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You must be prepared to be posted anywhere within the\r\nUK or overseas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice</p>\r\n','Non-commissioned officer','Level 3 (Adv)','From £23,000 to £25,000','2012-11-22 12:11:40','2013-12-18 12:43:10',23,'Policing','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship, developed with the support of the Royal Military Police (with involvement from other Defence Police Forces), forms part of the justice system’s plans to develop a clear framework of qualifications for policing and law enforcement across the UK. It is designed to attract new people into the policing services, to increase the skills of the workforce and to provide routes into other roles. The justice system employs up to quarter of a million people in policing and law enforcement.\r\nOn the Defence Policing pathway you would work as a Non Commissioned Officer carrying out investigations into criminal offences such as thefts, assaults and traffic accidents. You would also undertake some administrative duties, including completing forms, writing reports and liaising with colleagues. You need to have a mature, determined and self-confident attitude. Investigating and detecting crime demands an inquisitive but open mind, as well as a genuine interest in police work. You will be able to work unsupervised, and to think and act independently. An honest nature is vital as police officers have a high level of responsibility; applicants should not have any civil convictions.\r\nYou can apply for the Defence Policing pathway via application to the Royal Military Police. You will need to complete the Army’s Phase 1 Basic Training and be selected for the Royal Military Police. The training will give you the basic military skills to undertake the duties required of a soldier and will prepare you for further stages of training. You must be prepared to be posted anywhere within the UK or overseas.\r\nCompleting the Policing Apprenticeship will stand you in good stead for further job roles within the Royal Military Police. You may also be able to progress onto Higher Education courses, such as Criminology, Criminal Law, Forensic Science and Community Justice.\r\nOn average, completion of the Apprenticeship takes approximately 14 months.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job role: Non-commissioned officer','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','','','Starting salary:£23,000– £25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (117,'Pharmacy services','<p>This Apprenticeship supports those working in the\r\npharmacy sector as part of the wider healthcare team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Dispensing and pharmacy assistants and pharmacy\r\ntechnicians are an essential part of the pharmacy team and work under the\r\nsupervision of a registered pharmacist to provide medicines for patients in a\r\nsafe and correct manner.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Health </p>','Dispensing assistant, Pharmacy assistant, Pharmacy technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 12:12:53','2013-11-27 11:14:44',11,'Pharmacy services','The Health (Pharmacy Services) Apprenticeship supports individuals in the Pharmacy sector, as part of the wider healthcare team.\r\nApprentices are employed as Dispensing and Pharmacy Assistants and Pharmacy Technicians.\r\nAs an apprentice you will be an essential part of the pharmacy team and work under the supervision of a registered Pharmacist in order to provide medicines for patients in a safe and correct manner.\r\nThe duration for completion of an Intermediate Apprenticeship is 15 months and for an Advanced Apprenticeship is 24 months depending on age, prior experience and learning.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Dispensing assistant, Pharmacy assistant, Pharmacy technician','Issuing Authority: Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary: £14,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (118,'Security systems','<p>Skilled engineers who can install and maintain\r\nsecurity cameras, intruder and fire alarms and card-access systems are in\r\ndemand in a world of fast-changing technology.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn to install fire\r\nor security systems, test and repair systems and\r\nexplain to customers how to use them.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will probably be working with technologies such as\r\nwire-free system links or infrared and fibre optics as well as learning general\r\nelectrical skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Once qualified, you can progress to planning and\r\nrunning your own jobs, working as a supervisor or manager, or maybe running\r\nyour own business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills for Security</p>\r\n','Security systems engineer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £20,000','2012-11-22 12:14:16','2013-12-18 12:47:36',23,'Security systems','Skilled engineers who can install and maintain security cameras, intruder and fire alarms and card-access systems are in demand in a world of fast-changing technology. The careers available range from installation engineers to system designers but many people start with an Apprenticeship in Security Systems at Intermediate and/or Advanced Level. Once qualified, you can progress to planning and running your own jobs, specifying the best equipment to meet the clients’ needs, working as a supervisor or manager, or maybe running your own business.\r\nEmployers are looking for people who enjoy hands-on working in different environments (indoors and outdoors), investigating and solving problems and who have good customer service skills.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you will learn how to install fire or security systems, rig them to control panels, test and repair systems and explain to customers how to use them. You will probably be working with technologies such as wire-free system links or infrared and fibre optics as well as learning general electrical skills.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Installation and/ or maintenance of security, emergency and alarm systems','Issuing Authority: Skills for Security – www.skillsforsecurity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): around £16,000–£20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (119,'Providing security services','<p>As a security officers you would be responsible for protecting\r\npeople and property from injury, loss or damage caused through theft,\r\nvandalism, fire or flooding.\r\n\r\n</p><p>You could be employed by a private security company or by\r\na large organisation that runs its own in-house security teams.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your duties might include controlling entry to buildings, driving alarm response vehicles, helping the public, dog\r\nhandling, control room operations and patrolling\r\nproperties.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship has three pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Security officer</b></li><li><b>Door supervision</b></li><li><b>CCTV operation</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Security</p>\r\n','Security officer, CCTV operator','Level 2 (Int)','From £16,000','2012-11-22 12:15:27','2013-12-18 12:50:07',23,'Providing security services','Security Officers are generally responsible for protecting people and property from injury, loss or damage caused through theft, vandalism, fire or flooding. They are employed by private security companies or by large organisations, such as NHS Trusts and Universities, which run their own in-house security teams. They are usually uniformed and can work in a wide variety of environments including shops, office buildings and outdoor sites.\r\nSecurity employers are looking for people who are reliable and responsible, have good customer service skills and the confidence to remain calm and take action when necessary. Duties can include controlling entry to buildings; driving alarm response vehicles; providing assistance to the public; dog handling; control room operations; searching people or vehicles; patrolling properties.\r\nThere are also opportunities to progress to supervisory and management levels within the industry.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship in Providing Security Services includes three pathways that cover the following sub-sectors: security officer (static and patrol guarding), door supervision and CCTV operation. It provides the training needed to undertake these roles including how to assess and react to different situations, work as part of a team and keep accurate records of incidents.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Security officer (e.g. in a shopping mall, public building or commercial offices), CCTV operator','Issuing Authority: Skills for Security – www.skillsforsecurity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): around £16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (120,'Witness care','<p>Witnesses are essential to\r\nsuccessful prosecutions but attending court can be very stressful and it is important to make the process as\r\nstraightforward as possible.</p><p>Witness care units provide a contact point\r\nfor victims and witnesses where they can keep up to date with news and receive support that helps reduce the stress of attending court.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice working within a witness care units you will be trained to provide the highest quality of\r\nservice to victims and witnesses so that they are able and willing to attend\r\ncourt, and feel more confident in doing so.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice</p>\r\n','Witness care officer','Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000 to £19,000','2012-11-22 12:16:37','2013-12-18 12:54:28',23,'Witness care','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship framework is aimed at apprentices who work within Witness Care Units. The aim of Witness Care Units is to provide a single point of contact for victims and witnesses, minimising the stress of attending court and keeping victims and witnesses up to date with any news in a way that is convenient to them.\r\nWitnesses are essential to successful prosecutions and it is therefore important to make the process as straightforward as possible. This Apprenticeship framework is designed to ensure that those working within the Witness Care Units are providing the highest quality of service to victims and witnesses.\r\nThe service provided to victims and witnesses by Witness Care Officers is tailored to meet their individual needs, so that they are able and willing to attend court, and feel more confident in doing so. This in turn should reduce the number of trials either abandoned or adjourned, help bring more offenders to justice, improve public confidence in the criminal justice system and help reduce public spending.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Witness care officer','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (121,'Supporting teaching & learning in schools','<p>Learning support staff, such as teaching assistants,\r\nplay a vital role in classrooms by supporting pupils, parents and colleagues to\r\nmake sure pupils get the most out of their lessons.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you’ll work closely with a class teacher. Your duties could include supervising arts and\r\ncrafts activities, helping with outings, or reading to the class.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You might work with pupils who have special\r\neducational needs and/or challenging behaviour, helping them to overcome\r\nbarriers to learning.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice<br></p><p><b>Developer: </b>The Training\r\nand Development Agency for Schools\r\n</p>\r\n','Teaching assistant, Classroom assistant, Learning support assistant, Special needs assistant','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £16,000','2012-11-22 12:17:52','2013-12-18 12:52:53',23,'Supporting teaching and learning in schools','Learning support staff, such as teaching assistants, play a vital role in today’s classrooms by supporting pupils, parents and colleagues to make sure pupils get the most out of their lessons. They work in partnership with teachers, and carry out duties like lesson preparation and work with small groups or individual children. Their work allows the teacher to concentrate on teaching. Some learning support staff have particular specialisms in areas like music or special educational needs.\r\nOn the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship, you’ll work under the close supervision of a class teacher. Your duties will vary depending on how the teachers you work with plan their lessons and handle day-to-day classroom activities – you could find yourself supervising arts and crafts activities, helping with outings, or reading to the class, for example.\r\nThe Advanced Level Apprenticeship incorporates more responsibility into the role. You’ll be working under the direction of the teacher and contributing to the planning, implementation and evaluation of a wide range of learning activities. You’ll be working alongside the teacher to support classroom activities, as well as working alone with individuals or groups of students. You might work with pupils who have special educational needs and/or challenging behaviour, helping them to overcome barriers to learning. Completion of the Advanced Apprenticeship will stand you in good stead to pursue a foundation degree or to train as a Higher Level Teaching Assistant.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Teaching assistant, Classroom assistant, Learning support assistant, Special needs assistant','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','','','','Starting salary: Your salary will depend on your school or Local Education Authority, but most learning support staff salaries start at around £11,000 – £16,000.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (122,'Youth work','<p>Youth workers provide young people with challenges and\r\nnew experiences by allowing them to be creative, active and have fun. It’s all\r\npart of an informal education that helps young people to develop their own\r\nvoice and identity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you might help manage volunteers or\r\npart-time staff, apply for grants, draw up business plans, and network with social workers, teachers and probation officers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>At the end of your Apprenticeship, you’ll be a youth\r\nsupport worker and in a good position to take the next step in your career as a\r\nyouth worker.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Justice<br></p>\r\n','Youth support worker','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £16,000','2012-11-22 12:18:49','2013-11-27 11:15:25',11,'Youth work','This Apprenticeship provides a high-quality, nationally recognised training programme that offers a route into Youth Work. Youth Work is about providing young people with challenges and new experiences by allowing them to be creative, active and have fun – all part of an informal education that helps young people to develop their own voice and identity.\r\nAs an apprentice in the youth work sector you might help manage volunteers or part-time staff, help apply for grants, draw up business plans, and network with other professionals including social workers, teachers and probation officers.\r\nThere’s an administrative side to youth work as well. You might help manage volunteers or part-time staff, help apply for grants, keep records of your work, and network with other professionals including social workers, teachers and probation officers.\r\nAt the end of your Apprenticeship, you’ll be a youth support worker and in a good position to take the next step in your career as a youth worker, with qualifications that most employers will support you in doing on a part-time basis.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Assistant youth support worker\r\nAdvanced Level – Youth support worker','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000 – £16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (123,'Ceramics manufacturing','<p>Ceramic material is found in many items in your home –\r\nhair straighteners, cereal bowls, washbasins and water filters to name a few.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The ceramics industry is constantly evolving to make\r\nmaterial that is stronger and hardier, reduce energy costs and move towards\r\nenvironmental sustainability.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will learn about different\r\nmanufacturing processes and quality assurance. You’ll also gain customer care\r\nskills so you know how to meet customers’ needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some processes are automated and are controlled and\r\nmonitored by sophisticated technology systems, others require very traditional\r\nhand craft skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n','Kiln placer, Hand sponger, Mould maker, Model maker','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,000 to £25,000','2012-11-26 14:33:24','2013-11-27 11:46:26',16,'Ceramics manufacturing','From cereal bowls to hair straighteners, tiles to toilets, washbasins to water filters, ceramic material is found in many items in your home. It is also found in cars, and used in moulds for manufacturing rubber gloves and balloons, and so on. The ceramics industry is a crucial part of the supply chain to construction.\r\nYour coffee mug began its life as clay in the ground. The clay was extracted and processed, moulded into shape, glazed and decorated and heated to high temperatures to change its properties. Ceramic manufacturing is about chemistry as well as creativity. The industry is constantly evolving as a result of advances in technology to make ceramic material that is stronger and hardier, to reduce energy costs and to move towards environmental sustainability.\r\nOn your Apprenticeship your work will vary greatly according to your employer’s business. You will learn about different ceramic manufacturing processes and quality assurance. You’ll also gain valuable customer care skills so you know how to meet a customer’s needs. Some processes are automated and are controlled and monitored by sophisticated technology systems, others require very traditional hand craft skills. Many jobs require manual skills, lifting and handling heavy equipment (although many factories do have lifting devices) and you may need to spend long periods standing, so physical fitness is important. Where hand crafting is used, you will require creativity, an artistic flair, patience and good attention to detail. If you have an interest and skill in art and design you could use this Apprenticeship as a route to becoming skilled in ceramics job roles in product design and decoration. You may be required to work in a factory-based environment and overtime, shift work and weekend working may be required by some employers.\r\nFor more information about careers in Ceramics Manufacturing, please visit mps-academy.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Slip operative, Pressure caster, Kiln placer, Hand sponger, Mould maker, Robot operator, Gloss inspector, Model maker','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (124,'Building products industry','<p>The building products industry supplies essential\r\nproducts to the construction industry, including bricks, blocks, roofing tiles,\r\netc.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship covers operational and technical\r\noccupations in clay and concrete manufacturing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some jobs require very traditional manual skills,\r\nwhereas others are controlled and monitored by sophisticated technology\r\nsystems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could learn to load and operate mixers, crush raw\r\nmaterials, handle equipment like cranes and kilns, and deliver finished goods\r\nto construction sites.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Mobile plant operator, Mould builder, Concrete product setter','Level 2 (Int)','From £14,000 to £18,000','2012-11-26 14:35:06','2013-11-27 11:43:57',16,'Building products industry occupations','The building products industry plays a key role in the supply of essential products to the construction industry, including bricks, blocks, roofing tiles, pipes and much more. The industry covers the manufacture of products that make up our house and public and commercial buildings and is central to society.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship covers operational and technical occupations in both clay and concrete technologies. The work you will carry out as an apprentice will vary greatly according to your employer’s business. Job roles range from those requiring very traditional manual skills to ones which are controlled and monitored by sophisticated technology systems and involve both basic and complex manufacturing processes. You could learn many new skills, including how to load and operate mixers; crush raw materials, handle equipment like cranes and kilns; and deliver finished goods to construction sites.\r\nMany building products roles require manual skills, lifting and handling heavy equipment (although many factories do have lifting devices) and spending long periods standing so physical fitness is important. Some of your work may be outdoors.\r\nYou may be required to work in a factory-based environment. Many roles involve repetitive processes that require both patience and good attention to detail. Overtime, shift work and weekend working may be required by some employers.\r\nFor more information about careers in buildings products please visit mps-academy.co.uk or www.buildingproductsskillsacademy.co.uk\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Mobile plant operator, Stockyard operative, Mould builder, Concrete product setter, Wire tensioner, Extruder operator, Packaging operative, Concrete plant operative, Cage builder','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (125,'Extractives & mineral processing','<p>From toothpaste to bricks, many essential everyday\r\nproducts are made from natural resources that are mined, quarried or dredged\r\nfrom the seabed and processed to meet customer needs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is a diverse industry that includes&nbsp; coalmining, extraction of peat, and mining of iron ore,\r\nuranium and other metal ores.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The&nbsp; opportunities available are endless, from operation of sand and gravel pits to production\r\nof salt or manufacture of cement and concrete.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some jobs require very traditional skills, while\r\nothers are controlled and monitored by sophisticated, cutting-edge technology\r\nsystems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n','Mobile plant operator, Weighbridge operator, Mechanical technician, Blast designer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4&5 (Higher)','From £12,000','2012-11-26 14:36:36','2013-11-27 12:10:56',16,'Extractives and mineral processing','We all depend on the Earth’s mineral resources. From toothpaste to bricks, many essential everyday products are made from natural resources that must be found, mined, quarried or dredged from the ground or sea bed and then processed to meet the needs of customers.\r\nRock, slate and chalk are extracted at quarries; coal, salt and potash from mines; and sand and gravel may be dredged from the sea bed. For example, crushed rock is coated with bitumen at an asphalt plant and used to make or repair roads and runways. Crushed rock, sand and gravel are mixed with cement to produce concrete. Ornamental building stone is cut, shaped and finished. And afterwards, everything needs to be patched up again.\r\nThe extractives and mineral processing industry is diverse and includes deep coal mines and opencast coal working, extraction of peat, and mining of iron ore, uranium and other metal ores. From operation of sand and gravel pits to production of salt or manufacture of cement, plaster, ready-mixed concrete and mortars, the opportunities available are endless.\r\nJob roles range from those requiring very traditional skills to ones which are controlled and monitored by sophisticated, cutting-edge technology systems. The industry requires many specialised jobs to work together under the strictest health and safety guidelines.\r\nThe extractive and mineral processing industry is perfect for anyone who enjoys being outside and working with their hands. You will need to be physically fit as your role may require you to lift and handle heavy equipment (although most factories have lifting devices) and to spend long periods standing.\r\nFor more information visit mps-academy.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Levels 4 & 5)','Job roles: Mobile/Fixed plant operator, Shotfirer, Weighbridge operator, Mines electrical or mechanical technician, Mines rescue worker, Blast designer, Explosives supervisor, Maintenance supervisor, Production manager, HSE advisor','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£80,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (126,'Express logistics','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>Express logistics is the rapid, guaranteed delivery of goods and packages to businesses and consumers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Managing fast-moving logistics processes and keeping a supply chain in motion is complex and demanding.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn to manage the flow of goods effectively and efficiently through a network, and may be responsible for developing business improvements and cost efficiencies to make your company more competitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your roles might include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>managing &amp; motivating staff</li>\r\n	<li>devising strategies</li>\r\n	<li>managing budgets</li>\r\n	<li>ensuring compliance with company policy.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for Logistics</p>','Operational manager','Level 5 (Higher)','From £20,000 to £22,000','2012-11-26 14:38:11','2013-11-27 12:07:38',16,'Express logistics','Express Logistics is the rapid, guaranteed delivery of goods and packages to businesses and consumers. It is one of the UK’s fastest-growing sectors and makes a significant contribution to the UK economy, helping to support at least 72,000 jobs. Managing these fast-moving logistics processes and keeping a supply chain in motion is complex and demanding.\r\nThe Apprenticeship in Express Logistics offers an extensive programme of personal development, mixing on-the-job learning with a Foundation Degree in Express Logistics. You will train for the role of operations manager working within a small or medium-sized logistics company and by the end of your training will be able to contribute fully to the operation and development of an express logistics business. Your roles might include managing and motivating staff, devising strategies, managing budgets, and ensuring compliance with company and legislative policy. You will learn to manage the flow of goods effectively and efficiently through a network, and may be responsible for developing business improvements and cost efficiencies to make your company more competitive.\r\nGood literacy and numeracy skills are a must in this industry and it will help if you enjoy problem-solving, communication and working as a team. Prospective candidates will need to meet the entry requirements of the Express Logistics Foundation Degree and have a keen interest in management and leadership in the logistics sector.\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: Operational manager','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: £20,000–£22,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (127,'Fashion & textiles','<p>This Apprenticeship covers the fashion and textiles\r\nsupply chain, from the processing of raw materials to product manufacture,\r\nthrough wholesale and trading activities, to the after-sales servicing of\r\nproducts.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will specialise in one of the following:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Textiles</li><li>Apparel</li><li>Tailoring</li><li>Leather goods</li><li>Leather production</li><li>Footwear</li><li>Saddlery</li><li>Laundry</li><li>Dry cleaning\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</li><li>Textile care services (laundry &amp; dry cleaning)</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>See also Fashion &amp; textile: technical in the Creative\r\nsection</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Creative\r\nSkillset</p>\r\n','Dressmaker, Pattern cutter, Sample machinist, Leather technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Starting salaries vary','2012-11-26 14:39:52','2013-11-27 12:13:44',16,'Fashion and textiles','The fashion and textiles sector covers the whole supply chain, from the processing of raw materials to product manufacture, through wholesale and trading activities, as well as extending to the after-sales servicing of products. The sector is dominated by small businesses; more than 70 percent are sole traders.\r\nThis Apprenticeship is important to the future success of the fashion and textiles supply chain due to the rapid changes that have occurred within the environment in which fashion and textiles businesses compete.\r\nThe Apprenticeship will prepare you with the technical and practical skills that businesses need. You will specialise in one of the ten main areas – textiles, apparel, tailoring, leathergoods, leather production, footwear, saddlery, laundry, dry cleaning and textile care services. The types of jobs you might be doing as an apprentice will vary according to the area you have specialised in.\r\n\r\nSee also Fashion and Textile: Technical on page ???\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles:\r\n• Textiles – Textile operative, Quality control inspector, Sewing machinist, Knitting operative, Textile technologist, Textile dyeing technician, Team leader/Supervisor\r\n• Apparel – Clothing sewing machinist, Dressmaker, Pattern cutter, Sample machinist, Pattern grader, Cloth cutter, Clothing presser, Garment technologist, Pattern technologist, Quality control inspector, Team leader/Supervisor\r\n• Tailoring – Technical salesperson (Tailoring), Handcraft tailor, Team leader/Supervisor\r\n• Leather goods – Quality control inspector, Leather craftworker, Retail/Service operative, Pattern cutter, Leather goods designer, Sample machinist, Team leader/Supervisor\r\n• Leather production – Leather technician, Leather technologist, Tannery process supervisor, Leather tanner, Trimmer/Finisher, Team leader/Supervisor\r\n• Footwear – Leather craftworker, Pattern cutter, Sample machinist, Product tester, Quality control inspector, Retail/Service operative, Team leader/supervisor, Footwear Designer, Shoe repairer\r\n• Saddlery – Saddler, Harness maker, Pattern cutter, Leather craftworker, Retail/Service operative, Team leader/supervisor\r\n• Laundry – Laundry worker, Clothing packer\r\n• Dry cleaning – Dry cleaning worker, Clothing presser\r\n• Textile care services (laundry and dry cleaning) – Textiles care service worker, Clothing presser, Clothing packer, Clothing alteration hand','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): Varies according to individual roles (see the Creative Skillset website)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (128,'Food and drink','<p>Getting food on the shelves requires a sequence of\r\ndeveloping, testing, sourcing, processing, baking, packaging and distribution.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you could specialise in any of the\r\nmain operations involved in food and drink manufacturing and processing. This\r\ncould include some exciting production areas, such as dairy processing, bakery\r\nproduction, butchery, fishmongering or chocolate manufacturing.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will work as part of a busy team solving problems,\r\nmeeting targets and striving to ensure that food safety requirements are met.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Improve Ltd</p>','Food scientist, Logistics controller, Process worker, Quality controller','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £14,000 to £16,000','2012-11-26 14:41:14','2013-11-27 12:15:45',16,'Food and drink','Getting food on the shelves depends on a range of different people doing various jobs within the food and drink supply chain. For example, in order for a loaf of bread to reach your trolley, it has to go through a sequence of developing, testing, sourcing, processing, baking, packaging and distribution.\r\nAn Apprenticeship in Food and Drink covers a wide range of job roles within the sector, from quality assurance roles and bakers to logistics officers, new product development and butchers. As an apprentice, you could specialise in any of the main operations involved in food and drink manufacturing and processing. This may include some exciting production areas, such as dairy processing; bakery production; butchery, fishmongering; or chocolate manufacturing.\r\nYour work-based learning programme will involve both on-the-job and off-the-job training. Through this combination you will develop technical and practical skills and the knowledge required to do your job.\r\nThis Apprenticeship offers many options, whether you’re someone who likes to be physically on the go, or are interested in how food is made and how the machinery used to make food works. You’ll get to work as part of a busy team, which will involve solving problems, meeting specific targets and striving to ensure that food safety requirements are met.\r\nThe prospects are good and the job is an important one – the demand for food will always be with us.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Baker, Brewer, Butcher, Chocolatier, Fishmonger, Food scientist/technician, Logistics controller, Meat process worker, Process plant machine operative, Production team leader/supervisor, Productivity manager, Quality controller, Soft drinks operative, Technical manager, Grading operative, Storage operative, Packaging operative, Livestock operative','Issuing Authority: Improve Ltd – www.improveltd.co.uk','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (Level 2 entry): £14,000–£16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (129,'Furniture, furnishings & interiors','<p>The furniture, furnishings &amp; interiors industry is\r\ncovered by three main sectors: <b>domestic</b> (home furnishings sold in shops);\r\n<b>office</b> (desks and other items for the office environment); and <b>contract</b>\r\n(furniture for public areas such as hospitals, schools and airports).</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry also includes restoration, upholstery,\r\nsoft furnishings and both kitchen and garden furniture.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The production of furniture has traditionally been a\r\nskilled craft, although it has become increasingly automated in recent years.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A diverse range of careers are available to you as an\r\napprentice, from entry-level framemakers and wood machinists to restorers,\r\nupholsters and cabinet-makers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>','Mattress maker, Cabinet maker, Furniture installer, Upholsterer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £18,000','2012-11-26 14:43:40','2013-11-27 12:16:32',16,'Furniture, furnishings and interiors','Without furniture the world would be an empty and uncomfortable place. There will always be a need for people to design, make and install furniture for our homes, offices and public areas.\r\nThe furniture, furnishings and interiors industry is covered by three main sectors: domestic (home furnishings sold in shops); office (desks and other items for the office environment), and contract (furniture for public areas such as hospitals, schools and airports).\r\nThe industry also includes restoration, upholstery, soft furnishings and both kitchen and garden furniture. The production of furniture has traditionally been a skilled craft, although it has become increasingly automated in recent years. Modern technologies and materials are essential to improve efficiency, productivity and competitiveness. Commercial and domestic consumers have constantly changing demands and preferences and they expect very high standards in the furnishing of their living and workplace environments.\r\nA diverse range of careers are available to you as an apprentice, from entry-level framemakers and wood machinists to restorers, upholsters and cabinet-makers. You will need good hand–eye co-ordination and be able to use tools effectively and work to high levels of accuracy. Making furniture can be physically demanding work. Some roles will take place in a factory environment and you may be required to undertake shift and/or weekend work.\r\nFor more information visit mps-academy.co.uk or www.furnitureskillsacademy.co.uk.','Level: Intermediate (Level\r\n2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Mattress\r\nmaker, Cabinet/Furniture maker, Furniture installer, Soft furnisher, Upholsterer','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (130,'International trade & logistics operations','<p>Importers deal with bringing goods for sale into the\r\nUK from other countries, while exporters handle the procedures for taking goods\r\nout of the UK for sale in other countries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could work for an import/export agency or\r\nfreight-forwarding firm, or be employed by a company that handles its own\r\nexport and import of goods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will work as part of a team arranging the import\r\nand export of goods on behalf of customers, ensuring that insurance and customs\r\ndocumentation meets the legal requirements of each country and organising the\r\nmovement of goods by road, rail, sea or air.</p>\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>','Freight forwarder, Import/export clerk','Level 2 (Int)','From £13,000','2012-11-26 14:45:20','2013-11-27 12:27:19',16,'International trade & logistics operations','This Intermediate Apprenticeship is designed for people who work in the import/export industry. Importers deal with bringing goods for sale into the UK from other countries, while exporters handle the procedures for taking goods out of the UK for sale in other countries.\r\nImporters and exporters work for import/export agencies or freight-forwarding firms, or may be employed by companies that handle their own export and import of goods. Import and export managers buy products and services from other countries or sell to them.\r\nClerks in freight forwarding, import and export are crucial in ensuring that documentation meets the legal requirements of each country. Depending on the size of the company, freight forwarding involves administration/customer service for processing export and insurance documentation, customs clearance and organising the movement of goods by road, rail, sea or air. You will work as part of a team arranging the import and export of goods on behalf of customers. Importers and exporters normally work standard office hours but, if negotiating with suppliers or customers in different time zones, they may need to work outside those hours. There could be a great deal of travel involved for people at more senior levels.\r\nApprentices should have good organisational and IT skills, be able to cope under pressure and, ideally, will have knowledge of other languages. There are no set minimum qualifications to begin this Apprenticeship but many companies ask for at least four GCSEs, including English and maths.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Freight forwarded, Import/export clerk','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): from £13,000 a year');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (131,'Glass industry','<p>Glass takes many more forms than just windows. It can\r\nbe stretched into threads for broadband cables, strengthened to stop bullets or\r\nshaped to magnify objects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry is highly technical but there are roles\r\nfor workers skilled in traditional crafts too.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry also deals with recycling and energy\r\nefficiency and is one of the most environmentally important in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could be based in a large, mass production plant\r\nor in a small, specialised studio designing glass vases.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Additional industries include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>glazing and curtain walling</li><li>manufacture &amp; installation of windows, doors &amp;\r\nconservatories</li><li>automotive glazing</li><li>architectural stained glass</li><li>stained glass conservation</li><li>photovoltaics.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>','Window installer, Bottle maker, Furnace operator, Windscreen fitter, Solar panel installer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £35,000','2012-11-26 14:46:57','2013-11-27 12:18:46',16,'Glass industry occupations','Glass takes many more forms than just windows. It can be stretched into threads for broadband cables, strengthened to stop bullets or shaped to magnify objects. The glass industry is highly technical yet there are many roles where workers skilled in more traditional crafts are required. The industry also deals with recycling and energy efficiency and is one of the most environmentally important in the UK. In the face of increased competition, advancing technology, legislation and environmental issues, employers will require appropriately trained employees to help them to prepare for the future and improve productivity.\r\nThe glass industry covers the manufacture of both flat and hollow glass and of glass fibres. It also involves the shaping and processing of flat glass and other glass, including technical glassware. Additional industries include glazing and curtain walling, manufacture and installation of windows, doors and conservatories, automotive glazing (including mirrors, lights and windscreens), architectural stained glass and stained glass conservation, and photovoltaics.\r\nAs an apprentice you could be based in a large, mass production and fabrication plant or in a small, specialised studio designing glass vases. If you like being outdoors and have the ability to work with tools plus good customer skills and attention to detail, you could work in the construction sector, perhaps as a window, conservatory or solar panelling installer in domestic or commercial properties. Those with an interest and skills in design and artwork might choose to work as craft glass workers and stained glass makers. Some roles (e.g. Furnace operator and Glass blower) will involve working under hot conditions and many jobs are factory based.\r\nIn all roles, on the job training is available and most employers are especially interested in applicants who can demonstrate enthusiasm, good communication skills, a positive ‘can do’ attitude and a willingness to work hard and develop new skills and knowledge.\r\nFor more information about careers in the glass industry, visit mps-aademy.co.uk or www.glassskillsacademy.co.uk.\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Window installer, Curtain walling installer, Bottle maker, Furnace operator, Conservatory installer, Glazier, Windscreen fitter, Glass processor, Stained glass technician, Solar panel installer, Fenestration surveyor, Installation manager','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£35,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (132,'Commercial moving','<p>Removals operatives move office and other furniture\r\nand goods to new premises or into storage.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your work could include European or worldwide\r\nrelocations, as well as local or national moves.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You might also be required to move items into storage\r\nrather than into new premises.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may have to start early, finish\r\nlate or work at weekends to fit in with the customers’ needs. Long-distance\r\nmoves may involve nights away from home.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Moving furniture is hard work and you need to be\r\nphysically fit. Removal van drivers need a large goods vehicle (LGV) licence.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>\r\n','Packer, Driver, Specialist/fine art packer, Estimator','Level 2 (Int)','Around £10,000','2012-11-26 14:48:33','2013-11-27 12:02:18',16,'Commercial moving','Removals operatives move office and other furniture and goods to new premises or into storage. Their work may include European or worldwide relocations, as well as local or national moves. They may also be required to move items into storage rather than into new premises.\r\nAfter receiving instructions at base, removals operatives travel with the removal truck to collect the items. A team leader liaises with the customer and confirms which items are to be moved or stored. Sometimes specialist packers from the removal firm go to the site a day or two before the move to wrap and pack delicate items.\r\nRemovals operatives may have to start early, finish late or work at weekends to fit in with the customers’ needs. Long-distance moves may involve nights away from home. Moving furniture involves a lot of walking, bending and lifting and is hard, physical work.\r\nRemovals operatives need:\r\n• to be physically fit\r\n• good practical skills\r\n• to be able to get on with customers from all backgrounds\r\n• to work well as a member of a team and be able to follow instructions\r\n• an honest and responsible attitude to other people’s property.\r\nPeople wanting to work as removals operatives don’t need any specific qualifications, but GCSEs (A*–C) in English and maths may be useful. Removal van drivers need a large goods vehicle (LGV) licence.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Porter/packer, Specialist/fine art packer, Estimator/surveyor, Driver/ packer and unpacker, Office remover','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): around £10,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (133,'Paper manufacturing','<p>The paper and board manufacturing industry\r\nproduces<span> a diverse range of\r\nproducts that includes books, newspapers, money, roofing felt,\r\npackaging board, wallpaper, disposable nappies and healthcare\r\nproducts.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your work will vary greatly according to your\r\nemployer’s business.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Some paper manufacturing processes are automated while\r\nothers are carried out by hand. Many processes are controlled and monitored by\r\nsophisticated technology systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could train to be a paper maker, operating\r\nequipment involved in the manufacture of paper and paper-derived products. You\r\nmight also learn to transform raw materials, recycled paper and wood pulp into\r\nthe liquid stock needed to make paper.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtD</p>\r\n','Paper maker, Coating operative, Winder operative, Paper technologist','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £35,000','2012-11-26 14:49:36','2013-11-27 11:48:41',16,'Combined manufacturing processes – paper','The paper and board manufacturing industry produces products ranging from books, newspapers, money and tracing paper, through filters, roofing felt, packaging board and wallpaper, to tissue paper, disposable nappies and healthcare products.\r\nYour work in the paper industry will vary greatly according to your employer’s business and there are a myriad of opportunities available in a variety of disciplines. Some paper manufacturing processes are automated while others are carried out by hand. Many processes are now controlled and monitored by sophisticated technology systems and the industry needs a skilled workforce that is able and willing to respond and adapt to changing demands and processes.\r\nAs an apprentice you could train to be a paper maker, operating equipment involved in the manufacture of paper and paper-derived products. In other roles you might learn to transform raw materials, recycled paper and wood pulp into the liquid stock needed to make paper. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you would take a more supervisory role, perhaps leading a team of operators, setting production schedules, planning coordinating and controlling the production process at all stages of papermaking.\r\nFor many jobs within the paper industry you will be required to work in a factory-based environment. Overtime, shift work and weekend working may also be required by some employers.\r\nFor more information about careers in the paper industry please visit mps-academy.co.uk or www.paperskillsacademy.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Paper maker, Coating/chemical additives operative, Winder operative, Paper/product technologist, Production supervisor','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£35,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (134,'Polymer processing operations','<p>Polymer processing is the manufacture and production\r\nof polymer and synthetic substances such as plastic, nylon and PVC.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Plastic is incredibly versatile and can be made from\r\ndifferent ingredients, moulded into any shape, and put to a huge range of uses\r\nacross industry and the rest of society, from carrier bags to electrical cables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will probably work in a factory\r\nor a workshop and learn how to mass-produce plastic or composite items.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will weigh and mix raw materials, learn about the\r\nproduction process, test products, maintain machinery and make sure items are\r\nmade on time and without wasting materials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may be required to manufacture some products or\r\ncomponents using hand-based methods.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Cogent</p>','Process operator, Quality control inspector, Finishing operative','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £25,000','2012-11-27 09:48:48','2013-12-18 11:33:25',16,'Polymer processing operations','This Intermediate Level/Advanced Level Apprenticeship framework has been designed to meet the requirements for the type of work undertaken in the polymer processing industries.\r\nPolymer processing deals with the manufacture and production of polymer and synthetic substances such as plastic, nylon and PVC. Plastic is incredibly versatile and can be made from different ingredients, moulded into any shape, and put to a huge range of uses across industry and the rest of society, from carrier bags to electrical cables. It’s no surprise that the polymer industry is one of the most important areas of manufacturing in the UK. One factory is likely to produce many different kinds of plastic items.\r\nAn apprentice would normally work in either a factory or a workshop and learn how to mass-produce plastic or composite items. They would weigh and mix raw materials, learn about the production process, test products, maintain machinery and make sure items are made on time and without wasting materials.\r\nSuch is the diverse nature of the products manufactured, apprentices may find that they will be required to manufacture some products or components by hand-based methods.\r\nProduction requires practical skills, that will require the apprentice to work quickly on complicated tasks, to use numeracy skills to mix materials and to have an eye for detail.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Process setter/operator, Quality control inspector, Finishing & assembly operative, Process operator/technician','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£25,000 ');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (135,'Mail & package distribution','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the collection,\r\nprocessing and delivery of mail.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Royal Mail is the largest employer but there are many\r\nother mail service providers and some organisations rely on their own internal\r\npostal system.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could find yourself driving a van to\r\ncollect and distribute post, sorting letters in a mail processing centre, or delivering the post, by foot, bicycle, motorcycle or light van.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll learn how to plan routes, handle\r\nand sort post, and process mail using automated systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>\r\n','Mail sorter, Postman/woman','Level 2 (Int)','From £9,500','2012-11-27 09:50:05','2013-12-18 10:52:18',16,'Mail and package distribution','This Apprenticeship deals with the collection, processing and delivery of mail. Mail services accounts for roughly 9% of the total workforce within the Logistics industry. While Royal Mail is the largest employer (with more than 200,000 employees), there are many other specialist mail service providers as well. In fact, some organisations, such as local authorities and health trusts, rely on their own internal postal system.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you could be driving a van to collect and distribute post; sorting letters in a mail-processing centre; or out delivering the post, by foot, bicycle, motorcycle or light van.\r\nYou’ll learn skills like how to plan routes, how to handle and sort post, and how to process mail using automated systems. There are also opportunities to become a manager or supervisor at various stages of the process, whether it’s in the sorting office or keeping tabs on a fleet of vehicles.\r\nYou may need to work anti-social hours in this industry, so you’ll need to be punctual and reliable; but it’s an important service with plenty of job satisfaction.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Mail sorter, Post Office customer service representative, Postman/woman','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £9,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (136,'Print & printed packaging','<p>The printing industry produces a wide spectrum of\r\nproducts, from newspapers, books and magazines to money, passports, signage and printed packaging.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry serves central and local government,\r\nfinancial services, retailing, distribution, travel and tourism and the\r\nmanufacturing industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are a variety of roles available but they are\r\nall split into three main areas:</p><ul><li>Pre-press</li><li>Printing</li><li>Finishing</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Pre-press tends to be mainly computer- and\r\noffice-based, and both printing and finishing are highly practical and skilled\r\nareas of work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In all areas you must have an eye for detail and be\r\nable to complete work to the highest standards.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n','Machine assistant, Trainee bookbinder, Carton manufacturer, Machine printer, Pre-press operator, Graphic designer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £16,000 to £35,000','2012-11-27 09:53:02','2013-12-18 11:35:12',16,'Print & printed packaging','The printing industry produces a wide and varied spectrum of products ranging from the obvious – newspapers, books and magazines – to the less obvious – money, passports, signage and printed packaging. This diverse industry serves central and local government, financial services, retailing, distribution, travel and tourism and the manufacturing industry.\r\nThe industry has a long history of Apprenticeships and these have developed over time to cater for the rapid changes in both products and technology. The industry continues to be very fast moving and increasingly relies on new, cutting-edge technologies. It is essential to have new people entering the industry who have a good understanding of current computer-based technologies and are able and willing to respond and adapt to changing demands and processes.\r\nYour job will vary greatly according to your employer’s business. There are a variety of roles available but they are all split into 3 main areas: pre-press, printing and finishing.\r\nPre-press tends to be mainly computer- and office-based, and both printing and finishing are highly practical and skilled areas of work. Occupations range from entry-level machine assistant, trainee operator, trainee bookbinder, carton manufacturer and design or reprographic assistant to experienced machine printer, pre-press operator or graphic designer.\r\nOther opportunities exist in technical fields such as packaging technologists, web publication designers and desk-top publishing editors.\r\nIn all areas you must have an eye for detail and be able to complete work to the highest standards. Companies of all types and sizes across the country rely on their printed products to ‘sell’ their products and services. Poorly printed products have a direct effect on their business, therefore your role in the printing industry is crucial.\r\nSome printing processes are automated and others are carried out by hand. You may be required to work in a factory-based environment. Overtime, shift work and weekend working may also be required by some employers.\r\nFor more information about careers in the printing industry please visit mps-academy.co.uk or www.printskillsacademy.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Machine assistant, Trainee operator, Trainee bookbinder, Carton manufacturer, Design/reprographic assistant, Machine printer, Pre-press operator, Graphic designer','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £16,000–£35,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (137,'Logistics operations','<p>The ultimate goal of any logistics operation is to\r\nmove a product from supplier to customer. </p>\r\n\r\n<p>This path is called the supply chain, and it needs to\r\nkeep moving in order for goods to arrive at the right place, at the right time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, your duties may involve\r\ntransportation, stock control, warehousing, and/or monitoring the flow of goods\r\nand materials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will be responsible for the day-to-day running of\r\nthings and making sure that quality, cost and efficiency of the supply chain\r\nmeet the standards required.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For this role, you need strong organisation skills and\r\na flair for leadership. You’ll also need to be able to think on your feet and\r\nmake quick decisions.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>','Logistics operative, Distribution manager, Logistics manager, Warehouse manager ','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,500','2012-11-27 09:54:17','2013-12-18 10:49:40',16,'Logistics operations','The ultimate goal of any logistics operation is to move a product from supplier to customer – this path is called the supply chain, and it needs to keep moving in order for goods to arrive at the right place, at the right time. Logistics managers play an important role in all of this, liaising with a range of people including suppliers, manufacturers, retailers and consumers.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship is designed to allow an apprentice the opportunity to work in all areas of a business in order to gain a complete understanding of how the business works. During this time you will have the opportunity to gather evidence towards the Level 2 qualification while working in the various parts of the business and be in a stronger position to decide on which Advanced Apprenticeship would suit you best.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you’ll hold a management role for a logistics company. As an apprentice, your duties may involve transportation, stock control, warehousing, and/or monitoring the flow of goods and materials. You’ll be responsible for the day-to-day running of things and making sure that quality, cost and efficiency of the supply chain meet the standards required. You’ll learn a range of skills, which could include monitoring stock and keeping records; managing the receipt, storage or dispatch of goods; developing relationships with customers and suppliers; and providing leadership for your team.\r\nFor this role, you’ll need strong organisation skills and a flair for leadership. You’ll also need to be able to think on your feet and make quick decisions.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Logistics operative, Distribution manager, Logistics manager, Warehouse manager','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (138,'Locksmithing','<p>Locksmithing is a traditional trade that now includes\r\n21st century access control applications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship programme will provide you with\r\nessential skills such as key cutting, lock fitting and access control.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It will suit you if you enjoy hands-on working in different environments and you like\r\ninvestigating and solving problems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>Skills for\r\nSecurity</p>\r\n','Locksmith','Level 2 (Int)','Not available','2012-11-27 09:55:37','2013-12-18 10:47:28',16,'Locksmithing','Locksmithing is a traditional trade that now includes 21st century access control applications and this new Apprenticeship programme is designed to provide apprentices with the essential skills and knowledge required to start work in the sector, such as key cutting, lock fitting and access control.\r\nWorking alongside an experienced locksmith, you will gain a variety of trade skills and business awareness including customer service, record-keeping and risk assessment.\r\nThe Apprenticeship will suit someone who enjoys hands-on working in different environments (indoors and outdoors), who likes investigating and solving problems and who has good customer service skills. After the Apprenticeship there are opportunities to progress by learning different specialist skills and many locksmiths go on to run their own business.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Locksmith','Issuing Authority: Skills for Security – www.skillsforsecurity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary: Not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (139,'Life sciences & chemical science professionals','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>This Higher Apprenticeship offers laboratory, scientific and technical employees the opportunity to gain qualifications up to graduate level, with the addition of hands-on experience gained through work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>If you want to work in pharmaceuticals or petrochemicals, marine science or mining and quarrying, environmental science or nuclear research, a whole host of opportunities are available in areas such as production, research &amp; development and scientific analysis.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are six pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Life sciences</li>\r\n	<li>Chemical science </li>\r\n	<li>Food science </li>\r\n	<li>Process development </li>\r\n	<li>Packaging development </li>\r\n	<li>Healthcare science</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Cogent</p>','Product analyst, Colorist, Quality control technician, Laboratory technician, Veterinary pathologist','Level 4, 5 (Higher)','From £15,000 to £25,000','2012-11-27 09:57:02','2013-11-27 12:46:15',16,'Life sciences & chemical science professionals','A vast range of industries employ science technicians. For the first time, the Higher Apprenticeship for Life Sciences & Chemical Science Professionals offers laboratory, scientific and technical employees the opportunity to gain qualifications up to graduate level, with the addition of hands-on experience gained through work.\r\nWhether you wish to work in pharmaceuticals or petrochemicals, marine science or mining and quarrying, environmental science or nuclear research, a whole host of opportunities could be available for you to work in areas such as production, research and development and scientific analysis.\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship contains six pathways:\r\n1. Life sciences\r\n2. Chemical science\r\n3. Food science\r\n4. Process development\r\n5. Packaging development\r\n6. Healthcare science.\r\n\r\nEach pathway offers a choice of qualifications and levels including new HND/C Diplomas in Chemical Science for industry, HND/C Diplomas in Bioscience for industry and a variety of foundation degrees, which have been designed to maximise work-based learning. The qualifications are flexible enough to allow you and your employer to select modules that best meet the needs of the job role, while providing the knowledge and skills that are required for jobs at each level.\r\nIn addition, as an apprentice you will develop professionally and gain skills in creative thinking, independent enquiry, team working, self-management, communication and problem solving.\r\n\r\nRecognition of professional development\r\nThis Apprenticeship has been mapped to the requirements of the Science Council Technician Register, allowing higher apprentices to gain professional recognition as a Registered Technician (RSciTech) at Level 3 and, on completion of the programme, as a Registered Scientist (RSci) at Level 5.\r\n\r\nFor further information, visit www.scienceprofessionals.co.uk','Level: Higher (Level 4, Level 5)','Job roles:\r\nThere is no standard title for job roles and the range of activities varies widely depending on the organisation and the nature of its business. Some examples of job roles in different industries are given here:\r\n• Chemical manufacturing – Product analyst\r\n• Polymer manufacturing – Colorist\r\n• Pharmaceuticals – Quality control technician\r\n• Crystallisation engineer\r\n• Process safety scientist\r\n• Laboratory technician\r\n• Tissue culture laboratory technician\r\n• Packaging technician\r\n• Nutrient analyst\r\n• Animal technologist\r\n• Animal breeding technician\r\n• Veterinary pathologist\r\n• Livestock/equine breeding technician\r\n• Plant research technician\r\n• Plant breeder\r\n• Water treatment technician\r\n• Hospital laboratory technician\r\n• Paper manufacture – Quality technician\r\n• Colour match technologist (development/production)','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (140,'Operations & quality improvement','<p>Nearly everything we use, eat, drink or travel in has\r\nbeen manufactured to some degree.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this Apprenticeship you will gain the skills and knowledge needed to help businesses to identify and deliver continuous\r\nand sustainable quality, cost and delivery improvements for their products, processes and/or services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will learn to apply tools and techniques of\r\ncontinuous improvement that help increase performance, add value for the customer, reduce variation and prevent defects.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Semta</p>\r\n','Business improvement coordinator, Production team leader','Level 3 (Adv)','From £20,000','2012-11-27 09:58:23','2013-11-27 12:41:28',16,'Operations and quality improvement','Manufacturing is one of the largest industries – nearly everything we use, eat, drink or travel in has been manufactured to one degree or another. Many companies are introducing lean manufacturing and continuous improvement techniques to improve productivity and competitiveness and to help UK manufacturers to withstand stiff international competition from places such as China and the Pacific rim. The highest performing companies in the UK are those that train their employees in the latest business improvement techniques.\r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship in Operations and Quality Improvement sets out the skills, knowledge and understanding you will require to support businesses to identify and then deliver continuous and sustainable quality, cost and delivery improvements for existing or new products, processes and/or services. You will learn how to apply the proven tools and techniques of continuous improvement that help increase performance by reducing or eliminating anything that does not add value for the customer, reducing variation and preventing defects.\r\nSuitable candidates will have achieved an N/SVQ Level 2 and/or Level 3 or equivalent in a relevant sector/occupation such as engineering, manufacturing or science, or completed an Intermediate Level Apprenticeship in the relevant sector (such as Engineering Manufacture or Improving Operational Performance) or potentially have 5 GCSEs, or equivalents including English, Maths and Science (grade C or above) or A-levels or equivalents in Maths, Science, Business or another vocational subject relevant to the sector.\r\nThis Apprenticeship will appeal to those willing to undertake a course of training both on- and off-the-job and who can apply this learning in the workplace. Successful applicants will have an analytical mind and an aptitude for finding solutions to problems, and will enjoy working as part of a team.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Business improvement coordinator, Lean manufacturing facilitator, Production team leader, Six Sigma quality and reliability coordinator','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (141,'Process manufacturing','<p>The process manufacturing industries produce many of\r\nlife’s necessities, including pharmaceuticals, soap and\r\ntoiletries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The refining industries turn\r\ncrude oil into fuels and lubricants.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>These industries face considerable challenges, such as\r\nglobal competition, the need to be safe, clean and\r\nsustainable, and public demand for new and better products.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Following this Apprenticeship you could find yourself\r\nworking as a skilled operator or technician in a variety of roles that aid\r\nproduction.</p><p><b>Process operators</b> or <b>technicians</b> start up, control, monitor and\r\nshut down the systems and machinery involved in production.</p><p><b>Maintenance technicians</b> keep equipment in good working\r\norder.</p><p><b>Refinery operators</b> or <b>technicians</b> monitor and assist\r\nin the production of refinery products.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Cogent</p>\r\n','Process operator, Maintenance technician, Refinery operator','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £19,000 to £25,000','2012-11-27 10:01:17','2013-12-18 11:38:41',16,'Process manufacturing','This Intermediate/Advanced Level Apprenticeship has been designed to meet the requirements for the type of work undertaken in the process manufacturing industries. The process manufacturing industries produce many of life’s necessities including products like pharmaceuticals, soap and toiletries, while the refining industries (also known as Downstream) are responsible for turning crude oil into fuels and lubricants.\r\nThe process manufacturing industries face many considerable challenges: competition from companies all over the globe; the requirement to be safe, clean and sustainable; and ever-increasing public expectations for new and better products. Technology, science and engineering underpin the success of process manufacturing industries. Research engaging employers and stakeholders has shown that there is an ongoing demand for highly skilled and flexible scientists, engineers, production operatives, managers and leaders. With an ageing workforce and a decline in the number of technically trained people coming through the system, meeting this demand has become an imperative.\r\nThere are insufficient operators and technicians entering these industries to meet forecasted future demand. The framework is designed to meet the needs of the process manufacturing industries by providing the future skilled operators and technicians that will have the vocational skills and knowledge to meet the challenges listed above.\r\nAfter undergoing this Intermediate/Advanced Level Apprenticeship, skilled operators and technicians could find themselves working in a variety of roles that aid production. A process operator or technician would start up, control, monitor and shut down the systems and machinery involved in production. A maintenance technician would keep the equipment in good working order. A refinery operator/technician would monitor and assist in the production of refinery products.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Process operator/technician, Maintenance technician, Refinery operator/technician','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £19,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (142,'Production of coatings','<p>You can’t always see them but coatings are everywhere:\r\non our jackets, walls, cars and computers to name a few.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Different coatings are used for a variety of purposes\r\nsuch as printing, waterproofing and rust-prevention.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Scientific research and testing is a big part of this\r\nfield. Coatings employers are always developing new products, embracing the\r\nlatest technologies  and exploring new markets.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A range of operational and technical jobs are\r\navailable to apprentices within the following categories:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Decorative</li><li>Industrial</li><li>Powder coating</li><li>Printing inks</li><li>Speciality coating</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Job roles are varied and encompass both basic and\r\ncomplex manufacturing processes. Many processes are controlled and monitored by\r\nsophisticated technology systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Production operative, Process technician, Senior production operative, Quality controller','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £25,000','2012-11-27 10:02:30','2013-12-18 11:41:49',16,'Production of coatings','You can’t always see them but coatings are everywhere: on our jackets, walls, cars and computers to name a few. There are many different coatings used for a variety of purposes such as printing, waterproofing and rust-prevention. Since better coatings make better products, scientific research and testing is a big part of this field. Coatings employers are always developing new products, embracing the latest technologies and work practices and exploring and entering new markets.\r\nGenerally, coatings are broken down into five categories: decorative, industrial, powder coating, printing inks and speciality coatings. Depending on which pathway you choose, there are a range of operational and technical jobs available to you as an apprentice within the coatings industry.\r\nJob roles are varied and encompass both basic and complex manufacturing processes. Many processes are controlled and monitored by sophisticated technology systems. For laboratory and quality-based roles you will need a logical and analytical approach and good attention to detail. Good science and mathematical skills are invaluable for laboratory-based roles. For most manufacturing roles, you will work in a factory-based environment.\r\nGood physical fitness is important as some roles will involve working with your hands, handling and operating equipment and spending long periods standing.\r\nFor more information about careers in Production of Coatings, please visit mps-academy.co.uk or www.coatingsskillsacademy.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Production operative, Process technician, Senior production operative, Quality controller, Colour matcher, Product development, Coatings laboratory technician, Senior chemist','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk ','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (143,'Supply chain management','<p>A supply chain is the movement of goods and services\r\nfrom supplier to customer, and is at the heart of every logistics operation. It\r\nis vital that things turn up at the right places, in the correct quantities, at\r\nthe right time.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Supply chains play a crucial role in most industries,\r\nfrom clothing and automotive to pharmaceuticals and construction.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you’ll learn how to help control the\r\nordering and delivery of materials, or how to manage materials, stock and\r\nstorage. </p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>','Supply chain officer/ manager/ controller/ designer/ scheduler','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 5 (Higher)','From £13,500','2012-11-27 10:03:39','2013-12-18 11:47:12',16,'Supply chain management','This Apprenticeship is about supporting the functions of a supply chain. The supply chain is the movement of goods and services from supplier to customer, and it’s at the heart of every logistics operation. Supply chain operators make sure that things turn up at the right places, in the correct quantities, at the right time.\r\nSupply chains play a crucial role in most industries, from clothing and automotive to pharmaceuticals and construction. It’s what moves raw materials to the factory for assembly and then on to distribution centres and shops.\r\nAs a Supply Chain Management apprentice, you’ll learn many new skills, like how to help control the ordering and delivery of materials, or how to manage materials, stock and storage.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll take on a supervisory role and be involved in analysing the supply chain’s performance. There is also a Higher Apprenticeship available, where you might make changes to improve the supply chain’s performance.\r\nIn this role, you’ll have to identify any risks to schedule and performance, and stay on top of the game. And if something does go wrong, you’ll need to be able to fix things quickly and get things moving again.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: Supply chain officer; Supply chain manager, Supply chain controller; Supply chain designer; Supply chain scheduler','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (144,'Signmaking','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the design, production\r\nand installation of all sorts of signs, from those displayed on company\r\nentrances to the advertising hoardings you see around football pitches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The signmaking process involves many diverse skills,\r\nfrom graphic design through to electrical engineering and uses materials such\r\nas perspex, vinyl, plastic, metal and glass.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices learn a range of skills including how to\r\ndesign signs, prepare different types of surfaces, cut out and build plastics\r\ninto letters and logos, use digital technologies and install signs.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Computer-controlled routers are used for cutting out\r\nmoulded glass fibre lettering. Screen-printing may be used to produce posters,\r\nwhile traditional signwriting could involve designing by hand and painting with\r\nspecial brushes and enamel paint.</p>\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Cogent</p>\r\n','Signmaker, Fabricator/fitter, Quality control technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £20,000','2012-11-27 10:07:46','2013-12-18 11:45:30',16,'Signmaking','The Signmaking Apprenticeship Framework has been designed to meet the requirements of the signmaking industry. This Intermediate/Advanced Level Apprenticeship deals with the design, production and installation of all sorts of signs, from those displayed on company entrances to the advertising hoardings you see around football pitches. The signmaking process involves many diverse skills, from graphic design through to electrical engineering and incorporates materials such as perspex, vinyl, plastic, metal and glass.\r\nVarious methods are used to produce lettering for signs, depending on the project, e.g. computer-controlled routers for cutting out moulded glass fibre lettering. Screen-printing may also be used to produce posters, while traditional signwriting could involve designing by hand and painting with special brushes and enamel paint. An apprentice could be employed as a signmaker, sign installer, quality technician or manufacturing technician.\r\nApprentices need to learn a range of skills including how to design signs; prepare different types of surfaces; cut out and build plastics into letters and logos; use digital technologies and install signs. The nature of the work will vary with the employer, but it could involve machining, joining, engraving, etching, hand decorating, spray-painting and screen-printing.\r\nThere will be an ongoing need to attract new employers to provide Signmaking Apprenticeships as at present some employers carry out their own non-regulated training.\r\nAfter undergoing the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship or the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, skilled signmakers and technicians could find themselves working in a variety of roles within the signmaking industry.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Signmaker, Fabricator/Fitter, Quality control technician, Sign installation maintenance engineer, Sign designer','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (145,'Warehousing & storage','<p>This Apprenticeship deals with the movement and\r\nstorage of goods, and is an essential part of logistics operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice you might learn how to get things\r\ndown from high storage spaces or how to keep goods at low temperatures.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will improve your spatial awareness, so that you\r\ncan quickly and efficiently load objects of different shapes and sizes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your duties could include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Stock management</li><li>Inventory audits</li><li>Keeping equipment in good working order</li><li>Processing returned goods</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p><p></p>\r\n','Warehouse operative, Forklift driver, Warehouse supervisor','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,500','2012-11-27 10:09:04','2013-12-18 11:52:33',16,'Warehousing & storage','This Apprenticeship deals with the movement and storage of goods, and is an essential part of logistics operations. However, there’s more to this job than just lifting and moving things around (although it does involve a fair bit of that, so you’ll need to be fit and learn how to lift things properly).\r\nAs a Warehousing and Storage apprentice, you might learn skills in operating specialist machinery to get things onto – and down from – high storage spaces; learn about keeping some goods at low temperatures; and improve your spatial awareness, so that you can quickly and efficiently load objects of different shapes and sizes.\r\nYour duties will depend on your employer, but you could manage stock; audit inventory, keep equipment in good working order; process returned goods; or manage the receipt, storage and dispatch of goods. You might even learn how to maintain the safety of hazardous goods and materials.\r\nGood teamwork is important when you’re working to a tight schedule, such as loading or unloading a lorry that can only wait for a little while before it needs to go on to the next job. You’ll also learn how to maintain health and safety, and work towards a certificate in Logistics and Transport.\r\nThe Warehousing and Storage Advanced Apprenticeship (Level 3) is designed for Warehouse supervisors/Team Leaders. Working as the Senior Member/Team Leader of the team, in addition to normal warehouse operation activities, you will also have delegated responsibility for overseeing the correct selection and packing of customer orders, ensuring the team complete these tasks on time ready for despatch.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Warehouse operative, Forklift driver, Warehouse supervisor, Team leader',' Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (146,'Traffic office','<p>This Apprenticeship concerns planning, scheduling and\r\nrouting goods that are transported overland.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most jobs are in haulage and courier companies\r\n– outfits which have large amounts of material to move across the country and\r\nbeyond.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This is an area that requires serious organisational\r\nskills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice, you’ll learn how systems work by\r\ncarrying out routine tasks within a traffic office, such as managing\r\ntimetables, planning routes, scheduling loads, and assigning drivers to\r\nvehicles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll also be introduced to the commercial aspects of\r\nthe business by learning how to quote for services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Skills for\r\nLogistics</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Traffic officer, Traffic clerk, Transport manager','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,500','2012-11-27 10:10:24','2013-12-18 11:51:03',16,'Traffic Office','This Apprenticeship concerns planning, scheduling and routing goods that are transported overland. Most of the jobs are in haulage and courier companies – outfits which have large amounts of material to move across the country and beyond. It’s an area that requires serious organisational skills.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll gain a broad overview of how systems work by carrying out routine tasks within a traffic office, such as managing timetables, planning routes, scheduling loads, and assigning drivers to vehicles. You’ll also be introduced to the commercial aspects of the business by learning about how to quote for services. At all times, a high standard of customer service must be maintained.\r\nFor this sort of work, you’ll need to be good with people and an able communicator. Punctuality, attention to detail and reliability are essential traits, as well as the ability to react quickly to plan alternative solutions if things go wrong.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Traffic officer, Traffic clerk, Transport manager','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,500');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (147,'Wood & timber processing & merchants industry','<p>The wood and timber industry supplies products for use\r\nin residential and commercial spaces, including veneer, plywood, particle\r\nboard, cork and straw, as well as products made from these materials.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices can follow either a sawmilling or timber\r\nmerchants pathway.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Sawmilling</b> – you will be responsible for machining\r\nwood and wood products, identifying the timber to be used and operating\r\nmachinery.</p><p><b>Timber merchants</b> – you will be based at the customer end of the\r\nbusiness. You could work on a trade counter, advising members of the building\r\ntrade or general public on products and pricing. Other roles could include\r\npricing potential orders, ensuring the safe movement of materials within a\r\ntimber-based workplace, or packaging finished products ready for shipping.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Proskills UK\r\nLtd</p>\r\n','Wood processor, Saw operator, Estimator, Warehouse operative','Level 2 (Int)','Not available','2012-11-27 10:12:01','2013-12-18 11:54:43',16,'Wood and timber processing and merchants industry','The wood and timber industry supplies products for use in residential and commercial spaces, including veneer, plywood, particle board, cork and straw, as well as products made from these materials. With an annual turnover of over £7 billion, the industry makes a valuable contribution to the UK economy.\r\nApprentices can follow either a sawmilling or timber merchants pathway. If you choose sawmilling, you will be responsible for machining wood and wood products, identifying the timber to be used and operating machinery. You will almost certainly be involved in sawing, planing, moulding, boring and sanding of wood and wood products.\r\nIf you follow the timber merchants pathway, you will find yourself based at the customer end of the business. You could work on a trade counter, advising members of the building trade or general public on products and pricing. You will learn to communicate effectively with customers and ensure that their requirements are met. Other roles could include pricing potential orders, ensuring the safe movement of materials within a timber-based workplace, or packaging finished products ready for shipping.\r\nThe production of wood products has traditionally involved skilled crafts and more than a quarter of the people working in the industry are employed in skilled trades. However, the sector is becoming increasingly automated as businesses rise to the challenge of using new technologies to increase efficiency and meet targets for sustainability.\r\nFor more information about the wood industry, please visit www.woodskillsacademy.co.uk. This website shows information on careers available, new emerging jobs, transferability of skills, career paths and opportunities for progression. There is information on pay scales, how to enter the industry and what qualifications are available.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Wood processor, Sawyer, Saw operator/CNC machinist, Wood machinist, Trade counter, Estimator, Yard/warehouse operative, Sales representative','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (148,'Improving operational performance','<p>Nearly everything we use, eat, drink or travel in has\r\nbeen manufactured to one degree or another.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices are trained in the skills needed by a\r\nwide variety of engineering, manufacturing, assembly and process operators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are several different pathways:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Performing engineering operations</b> – a basic\r\ngrounding in engineering operations and techniques.</li><li><b>Performing manufacturing operations</b> – train to operate\r\neffectively in a manufacturing environment.</li><li><b>Business improvement techniques</b> – learn tools and techniques to identify and eliminate waste, create flow and\r\nimprove quality, leading to greater efficiency and increased profitability.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n</li></ul><p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> Semta</p>\r\n','Machine operative, Production inspector, Maintenance operator, Quality control operative','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,000 to £16,000','2012-11-27 10:33:43','2013-11-27 12:34:06',16,'Improving operational performance','Manufacturing is one of the largest industries – nearly everything we use, eat, drink or travel in has been manufactured to one degree or another. Many companies are introducing lean manufacturing and continuous improvement techniques to improve productivity and competitiveness and to help UK manufacturers to withstand stiff international competition from places such as China and the Pacific rim. The highest performing companies in the UK are those that train their employees in the latest business improvement techniques.\r\nThis Intermediate Level Apprenticeship will give you a route to becoming a trained operator within this important sector as it addresses the fundamental skills needs of a wide variety of engineering, manufacturing, assembly and process operators. There are several different pathways available to you as an apprentice.\r\nPerforming Engineering Operations – On this pathway you will gain a basic grounding in engineering operations and techniques to become a semi-skilled operative. Typical job roles include metal working operatives, plant and machine operatives, quality control, routine inspection and testing, and production of parts using computer-controlled equipment. You may then be able to enter an Advanced Level Apprenticeship in Engineering Manufacture or in Operations and Quality Improvement (see below).\r\nPerforming Manufacturing Operations – Apprentices are trained to operate effectively in a manufacturing environment. On this pathway you might work in assembly operations of electrical and electronic products, vehicles, aerospace, marine, metal goods and production of moulded products.\r\nBusiness Improvement Techniques – This pathway provides an industry-standard programme centred on the proven tools and techniques of lean process and quality improvement activities. It is designed to support continuous improvement by promoting effective team working and developing lean skills across the wider workforce. This is a down-to-earth, hands-on programme designed for operators in companies that have lean systems in place but are looking to engage the wider workforce in continuous improvement activities. It will teach you to identify and eliminate waste, create flow and improve quality, leading to greater efficiency and increased profitability.\r\n\r\nThis Apprenticeship will appeal to those willing to undertake a course of training both on- and off-the-job and who can apply this learning in the workplace. Successful applicants will have an analytical mind and an aptitude for finding solutions to problems, and will enjoy working as part of a team.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Machine operative, Production inspector, Maintenance operator, Materials handler, Quality control operative','','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£16,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (149,'Able seafarer/Tug rating','<p>Tugs\r\nassist with the movement of larger ships in and out of port so that they can\r\nsafely dock and undock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most tugs\r\noperate within the immediate area of a port or harbour, but there are\r\nopportunities for sea-going work if a disabled vessel needs to be moved to a\r\nsafe haven or to assist with salvage work.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Tugs and\r\nocean-going ships operate from all larger ports and harbours.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority: </b>Skills\r\nfor Logistics</p>\r\n','Tug deck officer, Engineer officer','Level 2 (Int)','Good – based on responsibility','2012-11-27 11:21:23','2013-12-18 12:02:02',15,'Maritime occupations – Able seafarer/tug rating (deck or engine room)','Tugs assist with the movement of larger ships in and out of port so that they may safely dock and undock. Most tugs operate within the immediate area of a port or harbour, but there are opportunities for sea-going work concerned with moving disabled vessels to a safe haven and assisting with salvage work. This Apprenticeship pathway offers an excellent way into the industry for anybody who wants to work on board a tug or ocean-going ship.\r\nAs an apprentice, you will gain a practical insight into many different areas of vessel operations, maritime technology, navigation, safety, towage operations, leadership and management. This practical experience will be supported with off-the-job learning to provide the theoretical knowledge necessary to work safely and effectively, as well as giving a sound basis for career progression. You will have the opportunity to either work on deck or in the engine room helping to ensure the vessel’s engine and machinery function effectively. Working on an ocean-going ship will involve time spent away from home, possibly for long periods.\r\nCareer opportunities – you can continue your career along the deck route by progressing to Mate and then on to Master once you have achieved the relevant statutory qualifications.\r\nIf you wish you can move into related maritime industries such as the Merchant Navy, Sea Fishing, offshore support or a Boatmaster working on rivers or inland waterways. These industries recognise the expertise you have gained while working in the tugs sector and may provide you with further opportunities to develop your career.\r\nLocation – There are tugs and ocean-going ships operating from all larger ports and harbours. It is likely you would chose somewhere convenient to travel to from where you live.\r\n\r\nYou can get more information on careers at the Careers at Sea and Beyond website: www.casandbeyond.org','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Tug Deck Officer or Engineer Officer, Deck Rating or Engine Rating, Tug Master or Tug Engineer, Merchant Navy Deck Officer, Merchant Navy Engineering Officer, Merchant Navy Rating, Boatmaster, Workboat Deckhand, Mate or Skipper, Royal Navy Rating, Sea Fish Deckhand, Mate or Skipper','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.co.uk','','','','Starting salary: Those working on tugs receive a good salary based on the responsibilities of their job. There are unsocial hours and you will work a shift system with time off in lieu.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (150,'Merchant Navy','<p>The\r\nMerchant Navy’s fleet of ships transports goods and people over the seas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It\r\nincludes ships and oil tankers, cruise ships and car ferries and specialist\r\ncraft that support offshore oilrigs or lay underseas cables.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The\r\nApprenticeship is an excellent progression pathway if you are already working\r\nin the shipping industry as a qualified seafarer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could\r\nproceed to a higher level Apprenticeship or HNC that will lead to a role as a\r\njunior Merchant Navy Officer, working on the bridge or in the engine room.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Or you\r\ncould qualify to undertake able seafarer/crew member roles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For\r\nvacancies contact the Merchant Navy Training Board</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority: </b>Skills\r\nfor Logistics</p>','Trainee Merchant Navy Officer, Junior Merchant Navy Officer','Level 3 (Adv)','Good – based on responsibility','2012-11-27 11:22:40','2013-12-18 11:58:01',15,'Maritime occupations – Merchant Navy (deck or engineering)','This Advanced Level Apprenticeship is an excellent progression pathway if you are already working in the shipping industry as a qualified seafarer. You could proceed to a higher level Apprenticeship or HNC that will lead to a role as a junior Merchant Navy Officer, working either on the bridge or in the engine room; alternatively you will become qualified to undertake able seafarer/crew member roles.\r\nDepending on which pathway you choose, you could be assisting on the bridge with navigation and look-out duties, berthing and mooring operations, crew and vessel safety, or helping in the engine room with routine maintenance, repair and oversight of a vessel’s engines and ancillary mechanical and electrical systems.\r\nCareer opportunities – you can continue your career along the Merchant Navy route by progressing to junior Merchant Navy Officer and other Merchant Navy Officer positions. If you wanted to you could move into related maritime industries such as the ports, sea fishing, offshore support and tug boat work. These industries recognise the expertise you have gained while working in the Merchant Navy and may provide you with further opportunities to develop your career.\r\nLocation – merchant shipping fleets can be found all over the world.\r\nFor current vacancies and wider careers information: contact the Merchant Navy Training Board – www.mntb.org.uk\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Trainee Merchant Navy Officer, Junior Merchant Navy Officer. Those following the Merchant Navy Advanced Apprenticeship pathways will not be employed, but ‘sponsored’ by the company that recruits them.','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary: Those working in the Merchant Navy receive a good salary based on the responsibilities of their job. There could be unsocial hours and many operate a shift system.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (151,'Port operations','<p>Port\r\noperations covers the work that goes on in sea, river and inland waterway\r\nports, harbours, quays, terminals, wharves and jetties, and the\r\nassociated handling and logistics operations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an apprentice your role could include helping with the loading and unloading of\r\ncargo using lifting equipment and vehicles,  berthing and\r\nestablishing vessel access, or working safely\r\nwith hazardous cargo and in potentially dangerous environments. You will learn how to respond to\r\nemergency situations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority: </b>Skills\r\nfor Logistics</p>\r\n','Port operative','Level 2 (Int)','Good – based on responsibility','2012-11-27 11:23:53','2013-12-18 12:15:15',15,'Maritime Occupations – Port Operations','Port operations covers the work that goes on in sea, river and inland waterway ports, harbours, quays, terminals, wharves, jetties, related facilities and the associated handling and logistics operations.\r\nYour roles as an apprentice could include helping with the loading and unloading of cargo by various means including lifting equipment and vehicles; working safely with hazardous cargo and in potentially hazardous environments; responding to emergency situations; storing, receipt and dispatch and berthing and establishing vessel access.\r\nCareer opportunities – if you have enough skill and drive, you can continue your career along the port route by progressing to port operations supervisor, port commercial or port management roles.\r\nAlternatively, you can move into related maritime industries such as the Merchant Navy, sea fishing, offshore support and tug boat work. These industries recognise the expertise you have gained while working in the ports sector and may provide you with further opportunities to develop your career.\r\nLocation\r\nThere are a number of large ports located around the country which could provide job opportunities.\r\nYou can find more information on careers at www.portskillsandsafety.co.uk.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Port operative','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary: Those working in port operations receive a good salary based on the responsibilities of their job. There could be unsocial hours and many operate a shift system.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (152,'Rivers & inland waterways','<p>Vessels\r\noperate on most navigable inland waterways and from coastal ports out a limited\r\ndistance to sea.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice, you will work as a key member of the crew, assisting the Master of\r\nthe vessel with navigation, steering and lookout. You will help manage passengers and\r\ncargo, operate and maintain deck gear and assist with mooring.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nhelp to ensure the vessel is kept clean, tidy and ‘shipshape’ and, if you have an interest in engineering, you may be able to develop this through routine\r\nmaintenance tasks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For\r\ncurrent vacancies contact Watermen’s Company</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority: </b>Skills\r\nfor Logistics</p>\r\n','Mate, Master','Level 2 (Int)','Good – based on responsibility','2012-11-27 11:25:20','2013-12-18 12:17:16',15,'Maritime occupations – rivers, inland waterways & limited distances to sea','For anybody who wants to work on vessels operating on inland waterways and limited distances to sea, this Apprenticeship pathway is an excellent way into the industry. As an apprentice, you will be working as a key member of the crew, assisting the Master of the vessel with navigation, steering and lookout; management of passengers and cargo; operating and maintaining deck gear; and assisting with mooring.\r\nYou will help to ensure the vessel is kept clean, tidy and ‘shipshape’. On some vessels you may be encouraged to develop your interest in engineering through active assistance in undertaking routine maintenance tasks.\r\nCareer opportunities – you can continue your career along the deck route by progressing to Mate and then onto Master once you have achieved the relevant statutory qualifications. You might wish to operate your own small boat and become qualified as Master of a vessel carrying less than 12 passengers, or else pursue the engineering option.\r\nIf you wish you can move into related maritime industries such as the Merchant Navy, Sea Fishing, offshore support and tug boat work. These industries recognise the expertise you have gained while working in the inland waterways sector and may provide you with further opportunities to develop your career.\r\nLocation\r\nThere are vessels operating on most navigable inland waterways and from coastal ports out a limited distance to sea. It is likely you would chose somewhere convenient to travel to from where you live. It is usual once you are nearing completion of the qualification that your employer will offer you a permanent position. But with your qualification you can work anywhere on inland waterways and in some cases elsewhere within the European Community.\r\n\r\nCurrent Vacancies: Contact Watermen’s Company (T: 0207 283 2373)','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Mate, Master, Merchant Navy Deck Officer, Merchant Navy Engineering Officer, Merchant Navy Rating, Inshore tug deckhand, Royal Navy Rating, Sea fishing deckhand, mate or skipper','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary: Those working on inland waterways receive a good salary based on the responsibilities of their job. There are unsocial hours and many operate a shift system.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (153,'Seafishing','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship pathway is an excellent way into the industry for anybody who\r\nwants to work on fishing vessels.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nwork as a key member of the crew responsible for health and safety, preparing\r\nthe deck and equipment for the catch. You will also operate and repair fishing gear and other\r\nequipment, and learn to gut and store fish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You might\r\nalso cook for crew members and will certainly help to ensure the vessel is kept\r\nclean, tidy and ‘shipshape’.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>For\r\nvacancies contact Seafish.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority: </b>Skills\r\nfor Logistics</p>\r\n','Deck hand, First mate, Skipper','Level 2 (Int)','Good – based on responsibility','2012-11-27 11:26:16','2013-12-18 12:20:14',15,'Maritime occupations – sea fishing','This Apprenticeship pathway is an excellent way into the industry for anybody who wants to work on fishing vessels. You will be working as a key member of the crew responsible for health and safety; preparing the deck and equipment for the catch; operating fishing gear and other equipment used for shooting and hauling fishing gear; repairing fishing gear; gutting and storing fish.\r\nYou might also cook for crew members and will certainly help to ensure the vessel is kept clean, tidy and ‘shipshape’. On some vessels you may be encouraged to develop your interest in engineering through active assistance in undertaking routine maintenance tasks.\r\nCareer opportunities – you can continue your career along the deck route by progressing to Mate and then on to Skipper once you have achieved the relevant statutory qualifications. You might wish to operate your own small boat and become qualified as an Inshore Skipper, or else pursue the engineering option.\r\nIf you wish you can move into related maritime industries such as the Merchant Navy, offshore support and harbour tug boat work. These industries recognise the expertise you have gained while working in the fishing sector and may provide you with further opportunities to develop your career.\r\nLocation\r\nOnce trained it is up to you which port you would like to work from depending on the method of fishing you would like to pursue and the size of vessel or company. It is usual that when you are nearing completion of the qualification your training provider will assist you in obtaining a crew position on a vessel.\r\n\r\nCurrent Vacancies: Contact Seafish (T: 01472 252300)','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Deck hand, 1st Mate, <16.5m Skipper (Inshore), Class 2 Skipper, Class 1 Skipper, Merchant Navy Deck Officer, Merchant Navy Engineering Officer, Merchant Navy Rating, Inshore Tug Deckhand, Royal Navy Rating, Fish farmer','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.co.uk','','','','Starting salary: Fishermen are paid under the self-employed share fishermen’s scheme, and receive a share of the catch which will vary from each trip to the next, depending on the time of year, how much fish has been landed and its value at market.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (154,'Aviation operations on the ground','<p>There are 57 commercial airports in the UK that need check-in staff, baggage handlers, customer service agents and\r\nramp side operators to keep things running smoothly on the ground.</p><p>\r\n\r\nAs an apprentice you could be:</p><ul><li>handling baggage</li><li>loading freight</li><li>helping move aircraft for refuelling</li><li>checking-in passengers</li><li>assisting in airfield maintenance</li><li>escorting passengers</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>Ground handling staff are usually employed by an independent\r\ncompany that works across a number of different airlines.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st</p>\r\n<p></p><p></p>\r\n','Check-in staff, Baggage handler, Airfield maintenance','Level 2 (Int)','From £11,500 to £20,000','2012-11-29 11:16:29','2013-12-18 13:09:17',5,'Aviation operations on the ground','This Apprenticeship covers some of the main jobs involved in supporting the ‘taking off and landing’ part of what happens at an airport. This includes everything from maintaining runways to ensuring passengers receive their luggage at their destination.\r\nThere are 57 commercial airports in the UK, and each requires a range of employees – check-in staff, baggage handlers, customer service agents and ramp side operators – to keep things running smoothly on the ground. With so many daily flights, the aviation industry relies on efficient ground operations.\r\nAs an apprentice in Aviation Operations on the Ground, you could be loading and handling baggage and freight; helping to move an aircraft to the right place for refuelling; checking in passengers; assisting in airfield maintenance; or escorting passengers who are due to board a flight.\r\nThe aviation industry is heavily regulated, and safety is crucial. You’ll need to work well in a team, be detail-oriented, and react quickly to situations while remaining professional and efficient. Ground handling staff are usually employed by an independent company that works across a number of different airlines.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Check-in staff, Baggage handlers, Customer service agents, Ramp side operators, Airside operations, Airfield maintenance','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,500–£20,000, depending on skills and experience');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (155,'Automotive management & leadership','<pre><span style=\"color: #ffffff;\"><span style=\"background-color: rgb(88, 154, 171);\"><b> Higher Apprenticeship </b></span></span></pre>\r\n<p>In the automotive retail sector, managers are needed to recruit and retain skilled staff, increase customer loyalty, and help businesses to remain competitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They work in sales, after-sales, vehicle parts, fleet control, and vehicle repair workshops.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will need a good head for numbers as you will be responsible for devising budgets, ensuring sales targets are met and controlling costs and stock levels. Good interpersonal skills are important too – you will be liaising with customers, advising them on technical issues and dealing with customer complaints.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>','Sales manager, Parts manager, Service manager, Body shop manager','Level 5 (Higher)','Not available','2012-11-29 11:18:38','2013-12-18 13:08:03',5,'Automotive management and leadership','Reliable transport keeps people, goods, services and the economy running smoothly. Across the Automotive Retail Sector, managers are needed to recruit and retain skilled staff, increase customer loyalty, and help businesses to remain competitive. Managers and leaders work in sales, after-sales, vehicle parts, fleet control, vehicle body and repair workshops, and vehicle maintenance and repair workshops.\r\nIf you are interested in managing and motivating staff, enjoy devising strategies and are keen to manage budgets as well as being responsible for a team of people, this could be the Apprenticeship for you.\r\nExperience of working in a managerial role will help and you will need to have a good head for numbers as you will be responsible for devising budgets, ensuring sales targets are met and controlling costs and stock levels. Good interpersonal skills are important too – you will be liaising with customers, advising them on technical issues and dealing with customer complaints.','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: Sales manager, Parts manager, Service manager, After-sales manager, Body shop manager, Fleet maintenance manager','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (156,'Driving goods vehicles','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship is for anyone interested in riding bikes as a courier, or\r\ndriving vans or large goods vehicles (LGVs) – vehicles weighing over 3.5\r\ntonnes.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Goods\r\nvehicles drivers transport and deliver goods between suppliers and customers,\r\ntravelling across the roads and motorways of the UK and beyond.</p><p>\r\n\r\nAs an\r\napprentice, you’ll be involved in:\r\n\r\n</p><ul><li>pick-ups\r\n&amp; multidrop deliveries</li><li>planning\r\nschedules &amp; routes</li><li>supervising\r\nloading &amp; unloading of cargo</li><li>completing\r\npaperwork &amp; log books</li><li>lots of\r\ndriving!</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>LGV drivers\r\nneed to know the rules of the road and have good time-keeping and planning\r\nskills. You might have to work antisocial hours, and spend time away from home,\r\nbut you’ll see the world from behind the wheel.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> Skills for Logistics</p>\r\n','LGV driver','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £15,000','2012-11-29 11:19:46','2013-12-18 13:12:31',5,'Driving goods vehicles','This Apprenticeship contains four pathways and is for anyone interested in riding bikes as a courier, or driving vans or driving large goods vehicles (LGVs) – vehicles weighing over 3.5 tonnes. Goods vehicles drivers transport and deliver goods between suppliers and customers, travelling across the roads and motorways of the UK and beyond. LGV driving is a skilled job, and doing it safely takes work and training.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll be involved in transporting goods with pick-ups and multidrop deliveries. Other duties may include planning schedules and routes, supervising the loading and unloading of cargo, completing paperwork and log books – and, of course, lots of driving.\r\nIf you complete an Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll be in a position to gain wider experience within the logistics sector through team leading, management, or by moving into traffic operations. There are also training opportunities for transporting goods like chemicals or hazardous materials that require specialist skills.\r\nLGV drivers need to know the rules of the road and have good time-keeping and planning skills. They can work antisocial hours, often alone, and spend time away from home. But you’ll see the world from behind the wheel.\r\nWhile this Apprenticeship is open to people aged 16, most employers prefer you to be 18 or older.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: LGV driver','Issuing Authority: Skills for Logistics – www.skillsforlogistics.org','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (157,'Bus & coach engineering & maintenance','<p>Modern passenger carrying vehicles\r\nare strong and well designed, but they need to be properly maintained and then\r\nrepaired when they break down.\r\n\r\n</p><p>Bus &amp; coach engineering &amp; maintenance staff perform routine\r\nmaintenance tasks as well as more technically advanced jobs, like working out where an electrical fault has occurred and repairing it.</p><p>\r\n\r\nApprentices can focus on:\r\n\r\n</p><ul><li>bodywork</li><li>mechanics</li><li>electrics </li><li>mechelec\r\n(mechanics &amp; electrics)</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st</p>\r\n','Auto electrician, Bodywork repairer, PCV technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,500 to £17,000','2012-11-29 11:22:02','2013-12-18 13:10:51',5,'Bus & coach engineering and maintenance','This Apprenticeship deals with the maintenance and repair of buses and coaches, or passenger carrying vehicles (PCVs). Public transport is becoming more and more important as we try to reduce carbon emissions and cut the volume of traffic on the roads, and we need skilled personnel to keep things moving.\r\nPCVs that regularly carry large numbers of people get put under a tremendous amount of strain. Modern PCVs are strong and well designed, but they need to be properly maintained and then repaired when they break down. This is where Bus and Coach Engineering and Maintenance (BACEM) staff come in.\r\nBACEM staff can do anything from routine maintenance on buses to more technically advanced jobs, like working out where a particular electrical fault has occurred on a bus and repairing it.\r\nApprentices will have the choice of focusing on bodywork, mechanics, electrics or mechelec (a combination of mechanics and electrics) – the four pathways involve some different training and require different skills, but whatever you end up doing it will be a vital role that will help to keep the transport network up and running.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Auto electrician, Bodywork repairer, PCV technician','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,500–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (158,'PCV driving: bus & coach','<p>Across the country,\r\nfrom the school run to the last bus home, PCVs deliver people from place to\r\nplace.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It takes a\r\nlot of skill to drive an 18-tonne bus around narrow city centre streets, and\r\nsome coach drivers drive long distances on motorways, or abroad.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As a PCV\r\ndriver, you’ll be expected to help passengers safely reach their destinations\r\non time, pay attention to other road users, assist passengers with special\r\nneeds, keep your vehicle in good working order… and know how to keep your cool\r\nif surrounded by difficult passengers, singing school children, or fare\r\ndodgers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st</p>\r\n','PCV driver','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,500 to £16,000','2012-11-29 11:23:01','2013-12-18 13:16:21',5,'Passenger carrying vehicle driving: bus and coach','This Apprenticeship is about driving passenger carrying vehicles (PCVs). Across the country, from the school run to the last bus home, PCVs deliver people from place to place – and it’s the drivers who make sure they get there safely. It takes a lot of skill to drive an 18-tonne bus around narrow city centre streets, and some coach drivers may have to go even further – driving long distances on motorways, or driving abroad.\r\nAs a PCV driver, you’ll be expected to help passengers safely reach their destinations on time, pay attention to other road users, assist passengers with special needs, keep your vehicle in good working order… and know how to keep your cool if surrounded by difficult passengers, singing school children, or fare dodgers.\r\nYou won’t necessarily need a licence to gain entry to this Apprenticeship, but you’ll work towards a PCV provisional licence during your training. Bear in mind that this type of licence requires you to meet certain medical requirements. As an apprentice you’ll also have to achieve a PCV driver certificate of professional competence (CPC) before you can drive for your company.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: PCV driver','  Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,500–£16,000, but overtime available and drivers often earn tips');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (159,'Rail infrastructure engineering (track & maintenance)','<p>There are\r\nover 10,000 miles of railway track in the UK, connecting more than 2,000\r\nstations.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this\r\nApprenticeship you will train as a Skilled track operative and play a key role\r\nin ensuring that the network of track across the UK is in good condition for\r\nthe safe and efficient running of trains.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As part of a\r\nmaintenance team you will be responsible for inspecting track and carrying out\r\ngeneral maintenance tasks using manual and automated tools.</p><p>In bad weather, you\r\nwill clear tracks so that trains can run safely.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st </p>\r\n','Skilled track operative','Level 2 (Int)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-29 11:24:18','2013-12-18 13:50:30',5,'Rail infrastructure engineering – track and electrification maintenance)','There are over 10,000 miles of railway track in the UK, connecting more than 2,000 stations. It’s the oldest railway network in the world and it requires an army of skilled engineers to make sure that the elements that make up the railway are kept in good working order.\r\nCompanies such as Network Rail, and other major contractors and sub-contractors, require skilled staff to undertake the complete range of engineering tasks, including track maintenance and renewal. The industry is always looking for innovative ways of reducing costs while maintaining its outstanding safety record.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you will train to become either a Track Operative and will play a key role in ensuring that the network of track across the UK is in good condition for the safe and efficient running of trains. As part of a maintenance team you will be responsible for inspecting track, and carrying out general maintenance tasks using manual and automated tools. You may have to walk along sections of live track and work in areas where trains are running very close by so it is important that you are always aware of your environment to keep yourself and your colleagues safe.\r\nIf you have a keen interest in working in the rail industry, are willing to work shifts, enjoy physical work and are prepared to work outdoors in all weathers, this could be the Apprenticeship for you. You will need to be good at working with your hands, have a good understanding of health and safety, and be able to follow instructions and diagrams. Due to the safety critical nature of the role, you should be prepared to go through checks for physical health, including hearing and eyesight, and be tested for drugs and alcohol abuse.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Skilled track operative','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (160,'Rail infrastructure engineering','<p>The rail infrastructure\r\nis a complex set of systems including track, signalling and telecoms that have\r\nto work together to ensure the trains operate safely and efficiently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Every system\r\nhas to be designed, installed, commissioned and maintained and a whole host of\r\nengineers and technicians are required to deliver a fit-for-purpose rail\r\nsystem.</p><p>\r\n\r\nThere are 3\r\npathways:</p><ul><li>Track</li><li>Signalling</li><li>Telecoms</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>You are\r\nlikely to work as a technician playing a key role in inspecting, fault finding,\r\nmaintaining and renewing the assets within your discipline.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority</b>: People 1st</p><p></p>\r\n','Signal technician, Track technician, Telecoms technician','Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £18,000','2012-11-29 11:25:53','2013-12-18 13:52:28',5,'Rail infrastructure engineering – Advanced Apprenticeship','The rail infrastructure is a complex set of systems including signaling, track, telecoms and electrification, that have to work together to ensure the trains operate safely and efficiently. Every system has to be designed, installed, commissioned and maintained and a whole host of engineers and technicians are required to apply their engineering skills and knowledge to deliver a fit-for-purpose rail system.\r\nTrain drivers only know where to go, how fast, and whether a station is safe to approach or not because of the signalling system. It’s a vast network of signs, lights and more, telling drivers what to do and when. If it goes wrong, the results could mean delays, diversions and even disasters if the problem isn’t sorted quickly. Add to that the jobs involved in laying the track, keeping communication between stations and trains up and running, and even using the vehicles necessary to get from one point to another on a track to fix it, and you’ve got a lot of opportunities.\r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship in Rail Infrastructure Engineering covers four pathways dealing with track, signaling, telecoms and electrification (overhead power cables and third rail supplies). Whichever pathway you choose you are likely to work as a technician or junior technical engineer. Technicians play a key role in inspecting, fault finding, maintaining and renewing the assets within their discipline. The junior technical engineer is critical in the measurement, analysis and planning of work on the various assets.\r\nAs an apprentice, you might work in an office as well as on site. You’ll need to enjoy solving problems, be willing to work shifts and be prepared to work outdoors in all weathers.\r\n','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Junior signal technical engineer, Signal technician, Junior track technical engineer, Track technician, Junior telecoms technical engineer, Telecoms technician','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (161,'Rail services','<p>Rail\r\nservices involves:</p><ul><li>driving\r\ntrains</li><li>operating\r\nsignals and crossing barriers</li><li>communicating\r\nbetween stations and trains</li><li>assisting\r\npassengers on trains and at stations</li><li>moving\r\ntrains into position at stations.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice, you’ll choose<span> between\r\nshunting (moving trains from place to place), signal operations, control room\r\noperations, or passenger services.</span></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st</p>\r\n','Train driver, Signal operator, Ticket examiner, Guard, Conductor, Steward','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,500 to £17,000. Train drivers can earn £30,000','2012-11-29 11:30:25','2013-12-18 14:28:45',5,'Rail services','This Apprenticeship covers the many occupations that help to deliver rail services to the millions of passengers that use trains every year. Rail Services involves many tasks, like driving the trains, operating signals and crossing barriers, communicating between stations and trains, assisting passengers both on board trains and at stations, and moving trains into position at stations.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll choose your area of specialisation – shunting (moving trains from place to place), signal operations, control room operations, or passenger services. Within each, along with technical skills, you’ll learn how to develop and maintain working relationships, how to effectively communicate information, and how to work safely. You’ll need to be physically fit, have good full-colour eyesight (you need to be able to see red and green lights, after all), and be able to work as part of a team, as well as on your own. You also need to be confident and reliable as the work that you do will affect what passengers think about railway services.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Train driver, Shunter, Signal operator, Control room operator, Train movements, Traction current, Fleet allocation, Maintenance provision, Passenger services, Welcome host, Station services, Customer services, Station announcer, Train dispatcher, Ticket examiner, Guard, Conductor, On-board services, Steward, Travel consultant, Reservations & enquiries, Travel centre, Call centre','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,500–£17,000; starting salaries for train drivers are around £30,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (162,'Vehicle body & paint operations','<p>From a\r\nscratched door to a dented bumper, accidents can affect a car’s bodywork,\r\nmechanical parts and paint job.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice, you can choose to focus on:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Mechanical,\r\nelectrical &amp; trim body fitting</b> – repairing moving parts and electronics</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Body\r\nrepair</b> – fixing the\r\noutside body of the car</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Body\r\nfinishing</b> – adding the\r\nfinal surface touch by applying primers and paint so everything looks as good\r\nas new</p><p><b>Automotive glazing and windcreen repair</b> – replacing and repairing damaged windscreens and other glazing</p><p><b>Vehicle damage assessment </b>– appraising damage and assessing repair costs.<br></p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>\r\n','Mechanical, electrical and trim technician, Body repair technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,500 to £18,000','2012-11-29 11:31:45','2013-12-18 14:31:03',5,'Vehicle body and paint operations','This Apprenticeship is about patching up damaged vehicles. From a scratched door to a dented bumper, accidents can affect a car’s bodywork, mechanical parts and paint job. As an apprentice, you’ll train as a technician, assessing and repairing damage, restoring body and paintwork, and carrying out automotive glazing and windscreen repair on a range of light and heavy vehicles. At Advanced Level you could be responsible for appraising vehicle damage, assessing vehicle repair methods and estimating costs.\r\nApprentices have the choice to focus on either mechanical, electrical and trim; body fitting; body repair; body refinishing; automotive glazing; windscreen repair; and assessing vehicle damage (Advanced Level).\r\nMechanical, electrical and trim technicians repair damaged moving parts and electronics. They assess the damage and then get at the broken parts inside by removing the bodywork (trim), they fix the internal parts, and then replace the bodywork.\r\nBody building technicians on the other hand are responsible for measuring, marking out, cutting and assembling body panels and units from various metals and materials. They might remove standard components and fit new, custom-made parts.\r\nAutoglazing and windscreen repair technicians replace and repair vehicle glazing within a bodyshop environment or off-site. They repair stone chips and damage on units and replace whole screens where necessary.\r\nAll apprentices need a good eye to assess damage. Each bump and scrape will present a new challenge, but you’ll feel an enormous sense of satisfaction when you have helped transform a damaged vehicle into something that works again and looks as good as new.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Mechanical, electrical and trim technicians, Body repair technician, Body finishing technician','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk. See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,500–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (163,'Rail traction & rolling stock engineering','<p>Trains are\r\nmade up of locomotives (also known as traction), carriages (for passengers),\r\nwagons (for cargo) and rolling stock.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All must be\r\nmaintained and repaired so they operate safely and efficiently.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The majority\r\nof work happens at night when carriages and rolling stock are not required to\r\ncarry customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice you will work as a technician, working as part of a team to inspect\r\ntraction and rolling stock, find faults and undertake maintenance and renewal\r\nwork.</p><p>You will learn to use the appropriate tools and equipment for the task\r\nrequired while ensuring that standards have been met and accurate records<b> </b>kept.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> Semta\r\n</p>\r\n','Traction and rolling stock technician','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £14,000 to £19,000','2012-11-29 11:33:28','2013-12-18 14:29:46',5,'Rail traction & rolling stock engineering','The rail industry is a vibrant and growing means of public and freight transport. It provides a service to customers wanting to travel and to the freight and haulage industry. The railways are a complex system and one of the key parts is the train. Trains (rolling stock) are made up of traction and passenger carriages for people and locomotives and wagons (for cargo). All must be maintained and repaired so they operate safely and efficiently and the majority of the work happens at night when rolling stock is not required to carry customers.\r\nAs an Intermediate Level apprentice you would work as a traction and rolling stock operative, carrying out routine and preventative maintenance of traction and rolling stock assets and associated equipment, dealing with breakdowns and restoring components and systems to serviceable condition by repair and replacement using appropriate tools and equipment\r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship includes elements of mechanical, electrical and electronic engineering, providing apprentices with the skills, knowledge and motivation needed to help support a safe, efficient and effective railway. As an apprentice you will work as a technician, working as part of a team to inspect traction and rolling stock, find faults and undertake maintenance and renewal work. You will learn to use the appropriate tools and equipment for the task required while ensuring that standards have been met and accurate records kept.\r\nThis is a perfect role if you are interested in applying engineering principles, like solving problems, enjoy working in a team and are willing to work shifts. The qualifications included within these Apprenticeships are demanding and many employers will look for applicants who have gained four GCSEs at grade D to E for Intermediate level and C or above for the Advanced level Apprenticeship. Good dexterity for using a range of hand tools, an understanding of health and safety, and the ability to follow instructions and diagrams are other useful skills that you should be able to demonstrate. You may be asked to go through checks for physical health.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Traction and rolling stock operative/technician\r\n','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semtaorg.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £14,000–£19,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (164,'Vehicle maintenance & repair','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship deals with the repair and maintenance of all types of vehicle,\r\nfrom mopeds to lorries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice, you could work for a dealership and focus on a particular\r\nmanufacturer, or work for an independent garage that deals with many different\r\nmakes of vehicles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>In both,\r\nyou’ll choose your area of specialisation, whether that’s motorcycles, cars,\r\ncaravans and motorhomes, heavy vehicles or vehicle electrical systems.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll work\r\nin a service technician type role, carrying out routine maintenance and basic\r\nrepairs, as well as identifying and reporting faults.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>\r\n','Vehicle service technician, Lift truck technician, Diagnostic technician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) Level 4 (Higher)','From £13,000 to £15,000','2012-11-29 11:34:33','2013-12-18 14:33:19',5,'Vehicle maintenance and repair','This Apprenticeship deals with the repair and maintenance of all types of vehicles, from mopeds to lorries. There are more than 32 million vehicles on the UK’s roads, which means we need plenty of motor vehicle technicians to keep them roadworthy.\r\nAs an apprentice, you could work for a dealership and focus on a particular manufacturer, or work for an independent garage that deals with many different makes of vehicles. In both, you’ll choose your area of specialisation, whether that’s motorcycles, cars, heavy vehicles or vehicle electrical systems. You’ll be working in a service technician type role, carrying out routine maintenance and basic repairs, as well as identifying and reporting faults.\r\nThe Apprenticeship includes pathways in repair and maintenance of light and heavy vehicles, caravans and motorhomes, motorcycles, heavy vehicle trailers and forklift trucks as well as auto-electrical and mobile electrical installation. \r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn about more complex faults and how to identify and repair them using sophisticated diagnostic equipment, while those on the Higher Apprenticeship will learn how to become a first-time manager in a maintenance and repair workshop, as well as keeping up with technical repair and maintenance skills.\r\nVehicle repair is challenging, hands-on work – every vehicle will present a new problem to solve. You’ll also need good communication skills in order to explain everything to the customer. But you’ll feel satisfied when the job’s done and that vehicle is back on the road.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Vehicle service technician, Lift truck technician, Auto electrician, Diagnostic technician, Master/senior technician, Workshop controller','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (165,'Vehicle fitting','<p>Motor\r\nvehicle fitters, or fast-fit technicians, repair and replace tyres, batteries,\r\nexhausts and other vehicle parts, while the customer waits.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You would\r\nnormally work in a fast-fit centre alongside motor vehicle technicians, but\r\nsome fitters specialise in tractors or other heavy vehicles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Whatever\r\nyour specialisation, you must work fast and be able to communicate with\r\ncustomers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices can\r\nchoose between:</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Fast-fit</b> – identifying, removing and replacing\r\nfaulty components like tyres, batteries &amp; brakes</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Specialist\r\ntyre fitting</b> –\r\nremoving &amp; replacing tyres on anything from cars to tractors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>','Vehicle technician, Auto electrician','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £15,000','2012-11-29 11:36:04','2013-12-18 14:32:14',5,'Vehicle fitting','This Apprenticeship deals with fast-fit operations in the motor vehicle industry.\r\nMotor vehicle fitters, or fast-fit technicians, repair and replace tyres, batteries, exhausts and other vehicle parts, while the customer waits. They normally work in fast-fit centres alongside motor vehicle technicians, but some fitters specialise in tractors or other heavy vehicles. Whatever the specialisation, fitters must work fast and be able to communicate with customers.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll choose to specialise in one of two areas: fast-fit, which involves identifying, removing and replacing faulty components like tyres, batteries, and brakes; or specialist tyre fitting, which deals with removing and replacing tyres on anything from cars to tractors.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship, you’ll learn how to supervise fast-fit operations by managing stock, organising staff and advising customers. Whether you find yourself working in a specialist fast-fit operation or in a dealership, you’ll have to be technically competent and able to work under pressure, taking account of time and cost. It’s challenging work, with job opportunities across the country.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Vehicle technician, Auto electrician','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (166,'Vehicle sales','<p>It takes a\r\nlot to sell a car: extensive knowledge of vehicles, the ability to read a\r\ncustomer, negotiation skills, and the self-confidence to pull it all off and\r\nsecure the deal.</p><p>\r\n\r\nAs an\r\napprentice, you’ll learn to:\r\n\r\n</p><ul><li>identify a\r\ncustomer’s needs</li><li>advise\r\ncustomers</li><li>promote\r\nfeatures &amp; benefits of vehicles</li><li>appraise\r\nvehicles</li><li>negotiate\r\ndifficult sales.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>There’s\r\nplenty to do behind-the-scenes too, like keeping the cars and forecourt clean,\r\nhelping to market the dealership, completing paperwork, managing stock lists\r\nand keeping potential customers up-to-date with new products and offers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>\r\n','Car salesperson','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £10,000 to £15,000 plus commission','2012-11-29 11:37:46','2013-12-18 14:35:08',5,'Vehicle sales','This Apprenticeship prepares you for the many activities that go on in a car sales showroom.\r\nIt takes a lot to sell a car: extensive knowledge of vehicles, the ability to read a customer, negotiation skills, and the self-confidence to pull it all off and secure the deal. As an apprentice, you’ll gain a broad range of skills used in a sales environment. You’ll learn how to identify a customer’s needs and interests; advise customers; promote the features and benefits of vehicles; appraise vehicles; and negotiate difficult sales. You’ll also learn how and when to make a successful compromise.\r\nThere’s plenty to do behind-the-scenes as well, like keeping the cars and forecourt clean, helping to market the dealership, completing paperwork, managing stock lists and keeping potential customers up-to-date with new products and offers. These sales skills will serve you well in many areas of business, and every time you make a sale, you’ll feel satisfaction – and earn extra cash in the way of commission.\r\n(Please note: employers are unlikely to employ salespeople before they are 21 years old, because insurance companies will not insure younger people to do test drives, even if they got their driving licence at 17.)','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Car salesperson','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £10,000–£15,000 plus commission');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (167,'Vehicle parts operations','<p>Vehicle\r\nparts operatives order, sell and manage stock control on a wide range of parts\r\nand accessories for all kinds of vehicles – from cars and motorcycles, to\r\nlorries, buses and coaches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices\r\nare likely to be working in a retail outlet selling vehicle parts.</p><p>\r\n\r\nYou’ll learn\r\nhow to:</p><ul><li>receive, move &amp; store stock</li><li>keep records</li><li>write up orders</li><li>manage\r\nreturns</li><li>process payments</li><li>organise displays.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p>The work is\r\ndiverse and you’ll working behind the scenes receiving deliveries and at the\r\nfront desk, serving customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> The Institute of the Motor Industry</p>\r\n','Vehicle parts operative, Parts advisor','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £9,000 to £14,000','2012-11-29 11:39:59','2013-12-18 14:34:17',5,'Vehicle parts operations','This Apprenticeship covers the sale of motor parts for all kinds of vehicles. Vehicle parts operatives (or parts advisers) order, sell and manage stock control on a wide range of parts and accessories for all kinds of vehicles – from cars and motorcycles, to lorries, buses and coaches.\r\nApprentices are likely to be working in a retail outlet selling vehicle parts. You’ll learn skills including how to receive, move and store stock; keep records; write up orders; manage returns; process payments; and organise displays to promote vehicle parts.\r\nDuring this time, you’ll develop knowledge of motor vehicles in order to understand the purpose of vehicle parts and how they function. The work is diverse and you’ll be working both behind the scenes receiving deliveries and at the front desk, serving customers.\r\nA large part of this job is customer service-based. Vehicle parts operatives serve a range of customers, from dealerships to regular members of the public. They also advise customers on how to solve problems with their vehicle by suggesting the right parts to buy. There’s a lot of administrative skill required for this role. IT skills will also come in handy, as stock lists are often managed with the aid of computer programs.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Vehicle parts operative, Parts advisor','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk See also www.autocity.org.uk','','','',' Starting salary (once qualified): £9,000 – £14,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (169,'Activity leadership','<p>Activity leaders work with all types of people, from\r\nholiday-makers looking to enjoy their leisure time to disadvantaged young\r\npeople in need of positive experiences.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are four pathways to choose from:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Outdoors</b> – work in\r\noutdoor recreation, adventure tourism, or education and training. Prepare and lead outdoor activity sessions in a safe, engaging manner.</li><li><b>Exercise and fitness</b>\r\n– fitness instructors and activity leaders prepare and\r\ndeliver exercise sessions.</li><li><b>Coaching</b> – prepare\r\nfor a career coaching community sports such as judo, gymnastics, tennis or\r\nrugby.</li><li><b>Leadership</b> – prepare and\r\ndelivering activity sessions in a community or school setting.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Whichever pathway you choose, you’ll need a\r\nconfident, outgoing personality, a good level of fitness, a clear voice to\r\nissue instructions and the maturity to take charge of people’s health and\r\nsafety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing Authority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p>\r\n','Activity leader, Outdoor instructor, Fitness instructor, Community sports coach','Level 2 (Int) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:22:39','2013-12-18 12:57:25',14,'Activity leadership/Outdoor programmes','The UK outdoors sector is vibrant, exciting and growing. It is particularly suited to those with a passion and enthusiasm for working with people and in the outdoors. Although gusto for adventurous activities is a must, you should remember that ‘activity leadership’ is actually about leading people in various activities. Activity leaders work with all types of people, from holiday-makers looking to enjoy their leisure time to disadvantaged young people in need of positive experiences.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship in Activity Leadership has three pathways.\r\nOn the Outdoors pathway you could work in outdoor recreation, adventure tourism, or education and training. Your job may involve preparing and leading all manner of outdoor activity sessions in a safe, engaging and inclusive manner to suit a range of participants. You may be responsible for maintenance and care of equipment, explaining safety procedures and instructing in specialist areas such as canoeing, sailing or abseiling.\r\nOn the Exercise and fitness pathway you are most likely to work as a fitness instructor or activity leader, preparing, planning and delivering exercise/activity sessions for a range of clients.\r\nCoaches play a major part in helping develop elite performance in sports and fitness across a wide range of settings such as schools, youth clubs, leisure centres and sports clubs. The Coaching pathway would prepare you for a career coaching community sports such as judo, gymnastics, tennis, rugby, and many more.\r\nOn the Leadership pathway you are most likely to work as an activity leader in community or school settings, preparing, planning and delivering activity sessions.\r\nWhichever pathway you choose to follow, you’ll need to have a confident, outgoing personality, a good level of fitness, a clear voice to issue instructions and the maturity to take charge of people’s health and safety. You might need to undergo police checks if your job involves working with vulnerable adults and children.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Apprenticeship in Outdoor Programmes you will work in a more senior capacity, in roles where you will be required to take the lead on a specific activity or supervising a specific team, including taking responsibility for people, financial resources and logistical implications. You may work with more demanding groups – such as corporate teams or the socially disengaged – in more hazardous activities and more remote environments.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Activity leader, Outdoor instructor, Fitness instructor, Community sports coach, Group leader, Senior instructor, Project leader','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (170,'Outdoor programmes','<p>The UK\r\noutdoors sector is exciting and suitable for anyone who has a passion to work with people and in the outdoors.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this\r\nAdvanced Level Apprenticeship you will take the lead on a\r\nspecific activity or supervise a specific team.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will be responsible for people, financial resources and logistical\r\nimplications.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may work\r\nwith demanding groups – such as corporate teams or the socially disengaged – in\r\nhazardous activities in remote environments.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll need\r\na confident, outgoing personality, a good level of fitness, a clear voice to\r\nissue instructions and the maturity to take charge of people’s health and\r\nsafety.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> SkillsActive</p>\r\n<p></p>\r\n','Group leader, Senior instructor, Project leader','Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:25:20','2012-12-03 11:39:49',14,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (171,'Exercise & fitness/Personal training','<p>Fitness\r\ninstructors work with all kinds of people – from athletes who want to improve\r\ntheir marathon times to elderly people who would like to become more mobile.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They put\r\ntogether personal health plans, lead exercise classes and induct new members\r\ninto the gym.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your\r\nresponsibilities could include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>reception\r\nduties</li><li>planning\r\n&amp; delivering sessions</li><li>membership\r\nsales</li><li>delivering\r\nexercise classes</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nneed to have excellent fitness levels and a positive, motivating, ‘can do’\r\nattitude.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p>','Fitness/gym instructor, Personal trainer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:27:05','2013-12-18 12:58:23',14,'Exercise and fitness/Personal training','The health and fitness industry is made up of private health clubs and gyms that are publicly run through local authority leisure facilities. Over 7 million people are members of gyms and fitness centres in Britain, so there’s a need for plenty of fitness instructors to teach people how to safely and sensibly improve their fitness and reach their health goals. Fitness instructors work with all kinds of people – from athletes who want to better their marathon times to elderly people who would like to become more mobile – to put together personal health plans, lead exercise classes and induct new members into the gym.\r\nAs a fitness/gym instructor your responsibilities could include reception duties, planning and delivering sessions for members and membership sales. As an exercise instructor, you might prepare, deliver and evaluate classes in aerobics, step aerobics, circuit training or aqua aerobics. Depending on your employer, you might also have to help out with other more general tasks such as working on reception, keeping the pool clean, advertising the gym and performing maintenance checks.\r\nOn completion of the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship you could progress onto a specialist role such as teaching exercise to children.\r\nOn the Advanced Level Advanced Fitness Apprenticeship (Personal Training) you could train for a more specialist role requiring greater technical knowledge and skill, as a personal trainer.\r\nYou will need to have excellent fitness levels as well as a positive, motivating, ‘can do’ attitude. You should be willing to work as part of a team or on your own and prepared to work shifts and sometimes unsociable hours. You might be required to undergo police checks if you are working with vulnerable adults and children.\r\nThe qualifications and training you gain through this Apprenticeship will enable you to join the Register of Exercise Professionals (REPS) which has been established to allow employers to know that instructors, coaches, trainers and teachers are operating at the highest standards.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Fitness/gym instructor, Exercise instructor, Studio coordinator, Personal trainer','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (172,'Leisure operations & management','<p>Places with\r\nleisure and recreation facilities range from leisure and recreation centres to\r\ncaravan and holiday parks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>From\r\nswimming pools to sports halls, ice rinks to dry ski runs, this is a great area\r\nto work in if you are interested in both sport and business.</p><p>Your\r\nresponsibilities could include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>operating\r\n&amp; maintaining equipment and facilities</li><li>undertaking\r\nsafety checks</li><li>maintaining\r\ngrounds &amp; outdoor spaces</li><li>reception\r\nduties</li><li>planning\r\nstaff timetables</li><li>organising\r\nevents</li><li>recruiting\r\nstaff</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p>\r\n','Receptionist, Groundsman, Recreation assistant, Duty manager','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:28:21','2013-12-18 13:00:02',14,'Leisure operations and management','Places with leisure and recreation facilities range from leisure and recreation centres to caravan and holiday parks. From swimming pools to sports halls, ice rinks to dry ski runs, this is a great area to work in if you are interested in both sport and business.\r\nOn the Intermediate Level Apprenticeship you might work in a role where you are responsible for operating and maintaining equipment and facilities – for example, ensuring the cleanliness of the building, undertaking regular checks to ensure that standards of safety, environmental control and hygiene are being maintained, or maintaining grounds and outdoor spaces. Alternatively you might work in a more customer-facing role, for example as a receptionist. You will need to have a positive, ‘can do’ attitude and be willing to work as part of a team and on your own. You might need to work shifts, and sometimes unsociable hours. In holiday and caravan parks the work might be seasonal.\r\nAs a Leisure Centre Manager you would be responsible for the day-to-day running of the leisure facility, managing staff, facilities and/or services. Your job could involve planning staff timetables, organising events and marketing material, recruiting staff, keeping up with health and safety regulations and promoting the centre in the local community. Good managers have excellent organisational skills and are able to keep calm under pressure. You will need strong leadership skills to run a healthy business.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Park operative, Maintenance operative, Park receptionist, Groundsperson, Recreation/Leisure assistant, Club/Duty manager','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (173,'Coaching','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship is for anyone who wants to work in the active\r\nleisure sector as a swimming or tennis coach.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices\r\nare often employed in community settings as sport coaches or club coaches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Coaches play\r\na valuable role in improving and increasing participation in sports in schools, youth\r\nclubs, leisure centres and other settings.</p><p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p><p><br></p>\r\n','Community sports coach, Swimming coach, Tennis coach','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','Not available','2012-12-03 11:29:38','2013-12-18 12:56:40',14,'Coaching – swimming and tennis','The Apprenticeship in Coaching is designed for those individuals who wish to gain a broad but solid foundation to allow them to follow a career in the active leisure sector as a coach.\r\nThe roles covered by this Apprenticeship tend to have more of a community and/or club focus, and apprentices are often employed in community settings as community sport coaches or club coaches.\r\nAs a coach you will play a valuable role in improving and increasing participation in a wide range of settings such as schools, youth clubs, leisure centres and other sport settings.\r\nThe Apprenticeship currently caters for two sports: swimming and tennis. The Advanced Level Apprenticeship is currently only available for tennis coaching.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Community sports coach, Club coach/instructor, Swimming coach, Swimming teacher, Tennis coach','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (174,'Spectator safety','<p>Event\r\nstewards, marshals and ground safety officers ensure the safety and security of\r\nspectators at sporting events, festivals, outdoor public\r\nevents and football matches.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They usher\r\npeople in and out of venues, make sure that health and safety regulations are\r\nbeing followed and deal with incidents and queries.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this\r\nApprenticeship you’ll learn how to prepare for spectator events; control the\r\nentry, exit and movement of people; and deal with accidents and emergencies.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p>\r\n','Event steward, Marshal, Ground safety officer','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:30:36','2013-12-18 13:01:43',14,'Spectator safety','Event stewards, marshals and ground safety officers are responsible for ensuring the health, safety and security of spectators attending large-scale sporting events, festivals, outdoor public events and local football matches. They usher people in and out of venues, make sure that health and safety regulations are being followed and deal with incidents and queries – whether that’s helping someone to find the toilet, dealing with a lost child, caring for someone who has fainted, resolving conflicts or any of the thousand other things that could happen at a major public event.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship you’ll learn how to prepare for spectator events; control the entry, exit and movement of people; and deal with accidents and emergencies. In general the public are an unpredictable lot and you’ll need to have the confidence to manage a crowd, as well as good people skills and the ability to think on your feet.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Event steward, Marshal, Assistant ground safety officer, Senior steward, Ground safety officer','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (175,'Playwork','<p>Playworkers\r\nplan, organise and take part in play and leisure activities for young people\r\naged between four and 16.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>They work in\r\nafter-school clubs, youth groups and holiday playschemes as well as in more\r\nspecialised settings such as hospitals, refuges or family services.</p><p>There’s a lot of organisation involved – from planning cooking lessons to outdoor games, while making sure that everyone stays\r\nsafe and feels involved.</p><p><br>You will learn about:</p><ul><li>playwork values and principles</li><li>team working</li><li>communication</li><li>child\r\nprotection</li><li>health and safety</li><li>paediatric first aid</li><li>customer services</li></ul>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive</p>\r\n','Assistant playworker; Play centre assistant; Playworker; Senior playworker','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:31:35','2013-09-05 11:24:23',14,'Playwork','Play is important in every child’s life, helping to develop valuable social skills that form the foundation of a healthy lifestyle. Providing play opportunities in communities across the UK is a way to make sure that all children are able to learn these skills, regardless of their background and circumstances. Playworkers plan, organise and take part in play and leisure activities for young people aged between four and 16. They work in after-school clubs, youth groups, holiday playschemes and play centres. In some cases playworkers work in more specialised settings such as hospitals, refuges or family services.\r\nPlayworkers have two main roles: to plan activities and to keep young people busy, safe and active. There’s a lot of organisation involved – from planning cooking lessons one day to outdoor games the next, all the while making sure everyone stays safe and feels involved.\r\nThe Apprenticeship in Playwork is for you if you want to start a career as a playworker or if you are already working in the sector and want to gain additional qualifications and skills. You will gain knowledge of playwork values and principles, team working, communication, child protection, health and safety, paediatric first aid and customer services. On the Advanced Level Apprenticeship you will work in a more senior capacity, taking responsibility for supervising a team of playworkers and ensuring that policies and procedures are followed.\r\nPart of your job might involve listening to young people who confide in you and offering a sympathetic ear and advice. If you think someone’s welfare is at stake, you’ll need to have the maturity to talk to parents, carers or even social workers. You will need to have a positive, ‘can do’ attitude and the ability to work in a team or on your own. You should be willing to work shifts and you may need to undergo a police check. Most employment opportunities within playwork are part-time and some are seasonal, e.g. in the school holidays.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Assistant playworker, Play centre assistant, Playworker, Senior playworker','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (176,'Sports development','<p>Sports\r\ndevelopment aims to improve access to sport and physical activity for people of\r\nall ages and abilities and to develop communities through the use of sport and\r\nphysical activity.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>On this Apprenticeship\r\nyou are most likely to work as a sports development officer working with local\r\ncommunities to identify the need and demand for new activities, improving\r\naccess to sport for young people with disabilities or from disadvantaged\r\ncommunities, or supporting initiatives to reduce crime and rehabilitate\r\noffenders.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your tasks\r\ncould include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>ensuring\r\nthat resources are used and all available funding is accessed</li><li>organising,\r\npromoting and running projects</li><li>finding and\r\ntraining staff, coaches and volunteers</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b>\r\nSkillsActive </p>','Sports development officer','Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:32:32','2013-12-18 13:04:41',14,'Sports development','Sports development aims to improve access to sport and physical activity for people of all ages and abilities, to develop communities through the use of sport and physical activity and to address wider social inclusion agendas. The work is challenging and varied and may include the development of performance sport, community sport and physical activity and/or participation for particular target groups.\r\nSports development involves organising projects, programmes, information and training to encourage people to increase their activity levels and have a healthier lifestyle or participate in their community. You won’t just be a coach doing a bit of organising, you will have a real opportunity to decide and influence strategy and policy.\r\nSports development is used to promote justice, sustain communities, reduce crime and promote health. Success in sport can help people in rehabilitation and self-help programmes.\r\nOn this Advanced Level Apprenticeship you are most likely to work as a Sports Development Officer, perhaps responsible for working with local communities to identify the need and demand for new activities, improving access to sport for young people with disabilities or from disadvantaged communities, or supporting initiatives to reduce crime and rehabilitate offenders. Your tasks could include ensuring that resources are used and all available funding is accessed; organising, promoting and running projects; finding and training suitable staff, coaches and volunteers; and much much more.\r\nSports Development Officers sometimes promote sport in general, working for a County Sports Partnership or local authority, or concentrate on a specific sport, working for a national governing body as a Sports-Specific Development Officer.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Community sports development officer, Sports-specific development officer','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (177,'Sporting excellence','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship has been designed to develop athletes with a better\r\nunderstanding of what it takes to perform at the highest level.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As an\r\napprentice you will gain access to high-quality facilities, expertise and\r\nequipment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nalso learn about nutrition, physiology and goal setting as well as how to\r\nimprove your life skills and progress your career to work in alternative sports\r\nemployment areas.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could be\r\na full-time contracted apprentice at a professional club, a full-time athlete\r\nidentified as a potential high performer or a talented young person in the\r\n‘academy environment’ who has not yet been offered full-time terms.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> SkillsActive\r\n</p>','Athlete (funded), Sports coach, Support officer','Level 3 (Adv) ','Not available','2012-12-03 11:34:14','2013-12-18 13:02:38',14,'Sporting excellence','This dedicated Advanced Level Apprenticeship has been designed to meet the needs of young and talented athletes ‘who have the realistic potential to achieve excellence in their sport and are seeking to perform at the highest level in that sport as their main career goal’.\r\nThe Apprenticeship will develop athletes with a better understanding of what it takes to perform at the highest level, including gaining access to high-quality facilities, expertise, equipment, etc. Apprentices will also gain expertise in nutrition, physiology and goal setting as well as ways to improve their life skills and how to progress their career to work in alternative sports employment areas.\r\nApprentices could be full-time contracted apprentices at professional clubs; full-time athletes identified as potential high performers; or talented young people in the ‘academy environment’ who have not yet been offered full-time terms.\r\nIt is recommended that apprentices should have gained a minimum of 5 GCSEs A* to C, however not meeting this criterion does not exclude talented athletes from the programme.\r\nOn completion of this Advanced Level programme, you could become a professional or semi-professional athlete, sports coach or a support officer in a high-performance environment. Alternatively you might choose to enter Further or Higher Education courses studying for a sports coaching or sports science foundation degree, or for an undergraduate programme such as a BSc in Sport and Exercise Science/Sport Management.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Full-time athlete (funded), Sports coach, Support officer, Professional/semiprofessional athlete','Issuing Authority: SkillsActive – www.skillsactive.com','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (178,'Drinks dispense systems','<p>The drinks\r\ndispense industry is associated in particular with beer but also includes soft\r\ndrinks, wine and cider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The industry\r\naims to ensure that equipment and systems are safely installed, and that drinks\r\nare served at the highest standard and to the specification set by the drinks\r\nbrand owners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentice\r\nlearn to install and remove drinks dispense systems and provide an on-going\r\nmaintenance service including cleaning, repairs and upgrading.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nlearn skills relating to electrical, plumbing, gas and refrigeration services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People\r\n1st</p>','Drinks dispense technician, Maintenance technician','Level 2 (Int)','From £20,000 to £25,000','2012-12-03 12:24:09','2013-07-31 13:17:51',4,'Drinks Dispense Systems','<p>\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>The\r\ndrinks dispense industry is associated in particular with beer but also\r\nincludes soft drinks, wine and cider. The aim of the industry is to ensure that\r\nthe equipment and systems are safely installed, and that drinks can be served\r\nat the highest standard by the retailer and received by the customer at the\r\nright specification set by the drinks brand owners.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Although\r\nthe drinks dispense industry is a relatively small niche market in terms of numbers\r\nemployed, it supports a much larger industry – pubs, bars and clubs – which\r\ncould not operate without the services of drinks dispense technicians.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cellar\r\nbar equipment and services have traditionally been provided by the brewer/brand\r\nowner; however, more and more pub operators are now taking responsibility for\r\ncellar and bar equipment. In recent years there has been a significant increase\r\nin the use of sub-contracted local or national cellar service installation\r\ncompanies, therefore a number of drinks dispense technicians are now either\r\nself-employed or employed by a service provider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>As\r\na Drinks Dispense Systems apprentice you would learn to install and remove\r\ndrinks dispense systems and provide an on-going maintenance service including\r\ncleaning, repairs and upgrading. You will gain a wide range of skills including\r\nthose relating to electrical, plumbing, gas and refrigeration services.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Good\r\npractical and problem-solving skills as well as an interest in plumbing or\r\nelectrical roles are essential. You will also need to be 18 years old or over\r\nbefore starting the competence-based element of the Apprenticeship as you will\r\nhave to sample products to ensure they are being dispensed correctly. You\r\nshould be willing to work in enclosed spaces as the job requires this as well\r\nas a certain amount of lifting. A full driving licence is not essential for\r\nentry to the industry but will eventually be required to enable you to conduct\r\nsite visits.</p></p>','<p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Level:\r\n</b>Intermediate (Level\r\n2)</p></p>','<p><b>Job\r\nroles: </b>Drinks\r\ndispense technician, Maintenance team technician</p>','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £20,000–£25,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (179,'Cabin crew','<p>Air cabin\r\ncrew make sure that passengers are safe and comfortable during a flight.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This\r\ninvolves more than just handing out refreshments with a smile, providing\r\ncustomer service in the narrow spaces of an aeroplane takes finesse and skill.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Cabin crew\r\nmembers are trained to deal with a wide range of security and emergency\r\nsituations.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your role\r\ncould involve:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>preparing\r\nthe inside of the aircraft for a flight</li><li>checking\r\nsupplies</li><li>ensuring\r\nsafety equipment is in place</li><li>greeting\r\ncustomers onboard</li><li>safety\r\nprocedures</li><li>serving\r\nmeals</li><li>helping\r\npeople fill out customs forms</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>You will\r\nalso learn about immigration regulations, cultural awareness and how to\r\ncomplete flight reports and other paperwork.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People\r\n1st</p>\r\n<p></p>','Air cabin crew member, Flight attendant','Level 2 (Int)','From £12,000 to £18,000','2012-12-03 12:25:41','2013-11-27 11:23:02',4,'Cabin crew','This Apprenticeship is for anyone interested in becoming an air cabin crew member. Air cabin crew are the people who make sure passengers are safe and comfortable for the duration of their flight. This involves a lot more than just handing out refreshments with a smile – providing customer service in the narrow spaces of an aeroplane takes finesse and skill. Importantly, air cabin crew members must also be trained to deal with a wide range of security and emergency situations.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you’ll learn how to prepare the inside of the aircraft for a flight by checking supplies and making sure the right safety equipment is in place. You’ll greet customers onboard, help passengers find their seat and run through safety procedures.\r\nCustomer service is a big part of the job, whether you’re serving meals or helping people fill out their customs forms. You might also learn about specific things like immigration regulations, cultural awareness and how to complete flight reports and other paperwork.\r\nAs an apprentice, you’ll always be on the go – don’t expect a 9 to 5 schedule. Depending on your flight route, you could work long shifts and unsocial hours. However, you’ll have the opportunity to see parts of the world.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Air cabin crew member, Flight attendant','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (180,'Hospitality','<p>Hospitality covers work in hotels and other holiday\r\naccommodation, restaurants, cafés, pubs, bars and nightclubs.</p><p>It includes\r\nwell-known chains and smaller, independent operators.</p><p>As\r\nan apprentice you could work in a hotel reception area greeting\r\ncustomers and creating a good first impression.</p><p>Or you might learn to run a\r\nB&amp;B or youth hostel, or pride yourself on keeping a hotel crisp and clean.<br></p><p>Successful\r\ncompletion of an Advanced level Apprenticeship could lead to a management or\r\nsupervisory role.<br></p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People 1st\r\n','Waiter, Chamber maid, Housekeeper, Front of house manager','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £17,000','2012-12-03 12:26:53','2013-11-27 11:27:47',4,'Hospitality','This Apprenticeship covers a range of occupations within one of the largest industries in the country. Hospitality covers work in hotels and other holiday accommodation, restaurants, cafés, pubs, bars and nightclubs. It includes well-known chains and smaller, independent operators and all sizes of business in between.\r\nAs an apprentice in hospitality you could work in a hotel reception area greeting customers and creating a good first impression. Or you might learn to run a B&B or youth hostel, or pride yourself on keeping a hotel crisp and clean.\r\nTo reflect the many career options on offer, there are several pathways. At Intermediate level you might find yourself working in hospitality services where your duties could include serving customers, preparing and serving food and drinks or cleaning and preparing rooms. If you’re interested in working ‘front of house’, there are roles for waiters and silver-service waiters, bar staff, housekeepers, chamber maids and receptionists.\r\nSuccessful completion of an Advanced level Apprenticeship could lead to a management or supervisory role where you might be required to control a budget, provide leadership for your team, maintain the health, hygiene, safety and security of your working environment and lead a team to improve customer service.\r\nWhatever pathway you choose, employers will be looking to see that you are keen to work as part of a team, have a \'can do attitude\' and have high standards of personal hygiene. You will need to have good basic communication skills and be willing to work shifts, which will often be outside traditional 9–5 working hours.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Team leader, Waiter/silver service waiter, Barperson, Housekeeper, Receptionist\r\nAdvanced Level – Head housekeeper, Head of reception, Front of house manager, Unit manager in a hotel chain or contract catering company, Regional supervisor/manager in a restaurant or pub chain with multiple outlets','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (181,'Travel services','<p>While many\r\npeople book their own travel arrangements online, plenty more prefer to arrange\r\nholidays through travel agencies and tour operators.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This\r\nApprenticeship is perfect for anyone with a keen interest in travel but it’s\r\nnot a paid holiday.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Working in\r\nthis sector requires hard work, excellent customer service skills, and a firm\r\ngrasp on product knowledge.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>There are\r\nthree pathways to choose from:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Leisure\r\n&amp; business</b> – for customer-facing roles like travel agents or business\r\ntravel consultants.</li><li><b>Tour\r\noperator (head office)</b> – work for an organisation like Thomas Cook helping\r\ncustomers to make travel plans</li><li><b>Tour operator\r\n(field staff)</b> – provide support to customers on their holiday as a resort\r\nrepresentative or tour guide.</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People\r\n1st</p>\r\n','Travel consultant, Travel advisor, Resort representative','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £18,000','2012-12-03 12:28:45','2013-11-27 11:34:56',4,'Travel services','The British are taking more and more holidays each year. While many book their own travel arrangements online, plenty of people prefer arranging holidays through bonded travel agents, travel agencies and tour operators. These services make up the travel services industry.\r\nThis Apprenticeship is perfect for those with a keen interest in travel – but it’s not a paid holiday. Working in this sector requires hard work, excellent customer service skills, and a firm grasp on product knowledge.\r\nThe Apprenticeship has three pathways. The Leisure & Business route focuses on customer-facing roles like travel agent or business travel consultant. In the Tour Operator (Head Office) pathway, you could be working for an organisation like Thomas Cook and helping customers make travel plans by checking availability and costs, making bookings and processing payments. Many of these roles take place in call centres. Finally, on the specialist Tour Operator (Field Staff) pathway, you could provide support to customers on their holiday as a resort representative or tour guide.\r\nAfter an Apprenticeship, there are opportunities to progress to managerial roles within your organisation. If you work for a larger organisation, you might even get the chance to work further afield as resort staff or cabin crew.\r\n\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – Leisure travel consultant, Business travel consultant, Travel advisor, Customer service advisor, Resort representative\r\nAdvanced Level – Senior leisure travel consultant, Senior business travel consultant, Senior travel advisor, Senior customer service advisor, Senior resort representative, Team leader','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£18,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (182,'Licensed hospitality','<p>As an\r\napprentice working in licensed hospitality you are likely to work in a pub, bar\r\nor nightclub serving food and drink, taking payment, working in the cellar and\r\nstock-taking.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Completion\r\nof this Apprenticeship will give you the skills, knowledge and confidence you\r\nneed to make the most of the exciting job opportunities available within\r\nlicensed hospitality and to develop your career further into management roles.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You must be\r\naged 16 or over as mandatory units are based around the sale, service and\r\ndelivery of alcohol.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority:</b> People\r\n1st</p>\r\n<p></p>','Barperson, Waiter, Waitress','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £9,000 to £13,000','2012-12-03 12:29:51','2013-11-27 11:31:00',4,'Licensed hospitality','The pub, bar and nightclub industry is the second largest within the hospitality sector. To ensure that standards of service and quality of products are maintained, the industry needs well-trained, responsible licensed hospitality staff of the highest quality; and with upcoming high-profile events such as the Rugby World Cup in 2015, this need has never been greater.\r\nOver one million people work in licensed hospitality, and pubs, bars and nightclubs have the youngest workforce of all UK industries. However, staff turnover is high, particularly in leased and tenanted premises, often due to lack of training and the perception that there is limited opportunity for career progression.\r\nThe Intermediate Level Apprenticeship is for those working behind a bar or in any customer-facing roles in licensed hospitality premises, such as pubs, hotels, restaurants and nightclubs. The Advanced Level Apprenticeship is for those working in a supervisory role within such premises.\r\nAs an apprentice working in licensed hospitality you are likely to be responsible for a range of activities including serving food and drink, taking payment, working in the cellar and stock-taking. Completion of these Apprenticeships will give you the skills, knowledge and confidence you need to make the most of the exciting job opportunities available within licensed hospitality and to develop your career further into management roles.\r\nTo become a licensed hospitality apprentice you must be aged 16 or over as mandatory units are based around the sale, service and delivery of alcohol. In addition, as most roles are customer facing, you will need a positive attitude, good communication skills, a desire to provide an excellent level of customer service and a willingness to work as part of a team. You should also be prepared to work unsociable hours, often in busy and noisy premises.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Barperson, Assistant bar manager, Waiter, Waitress','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £9,000–£13,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (183,'Nuclear power plant operations','<p>The nuclear industry employs over 44,000 people in the UK.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>This Apprenticeship provides an entry route into the\r\ncommercial nuclear power industry to develop the skills needed for nuclear\r\npower plant operations technicians.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You would undertake skills and knowledge training in one of\r\nthe following areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>the generation pathway</li><li>nuclear fuel operations</li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Nuclear power plant technicians are responsible for the safe\r\nand reliable operation of a nuclear power plant in the areas of power\r\ngeneration and providing and/or removing fuel from the reactor.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your working conditions will be varied and may include\r\nshift work. You may have to operate specialist safety equipment and work within\r\na radiological environment.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing authority:</b>\r\nCogent</p>\r\n<p></p>','Nuclear power plant technician, Production technician','Level 3 (Adv)','Not available','2012-12-10 12:24:44','2012-12-10 12:24:44',18,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL);
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (185,'Catering & professional chefs','<p>The catering industry covers hotels, restaurants, pubs, bars\r\nand nightclubs, contract catering, holiday centres and school catering.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It operates across well-known chains and in small\r\nbusinesses.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Pathways are available in:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li><b>Food production &amp; cooking</b></li><li><b>Professional cookery</b></li><li><b>Craft cookery</b></li><li><b>Patisserie &amp; confectionery</b></li></ul>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>On all pathways you will learn to prepare, cook and serve\r\nmeals in a hygienic environment, minimise waste and maintain stocks.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You may learn to use specialist ingredients and methods.</p>\r\n<p><b>Issuing authority:</b>\r\nPeople 1st</p>\r\n\r\n\r\n','Kitchen assistant, Chef, Sous chef, Commis chef, School cook, Pastry chef, Craft chef','Level 2 (Int) Level 3 (Adv)','From £11,000 to £17,000','2012-12-10 12:27:37','2013-11-27 11:25:36',4,'Catering and professional chefs','This Apprenticeship covers a range of occupations within one of the largest industries in the country. The catering industry covers work in restaurants, hotels and holiday accommodation, cafés and pubs. It also supplies other industries with food and drink. Schools, colleges, hospitals and large businesses nearly always have canteens and catering staff too.\r\nChef skills are in short supply, with customers increasingly demanding meals that are cooked from scratch using fresh ingredients in mainstream restaurants and pubs. If you are interested in cookery, you could either train as a chef in a restaurant, or learn how to cook on a large scale for institutions such as the NHS or armed forces. You could work in all sorts of kitchens, from fine-dining to chain restaurants through to gastro-pubs.\r\nAt Intermediate level you could work as a kitchen assistant helping with food preparation and keeping the working area clean and tidy, or as a school cook, preparing, cooking and serving nutritious meals in large volumes. Alternatively you might work in a role that requires you to specialise in Asian, Oriental or other cuisines.\r\nSuccessful completion of an Advanced Level Apprenticeship could lead to more senior roles as a sous chef or senior chef, preparing and finishing food from scratch for a wide variety of dishes and ingredients. Or you might choose to specialise in patisserie and confectionery and become a pastry chef.\r\nWhatever pathway you choose you will need to have a positive, hard-working attitude and excellent standards of personal hygiene. Most roles in catering will require you to work shifts, which could include evening and weekend work.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Intermediate Level – School cook, cook, team member or chef, Kitchen assistant\r\nAdvanced Level – Sous chef or senior, Chef/cook, Pastry chef','Issuing Authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','NEW','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £11,000–£17,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (190,'Composite engineering','<p>Composites are made from two or\r\nmore materials with different properties that, when combined,\r\nproduce a material with different structural characteristics from the original\r\ncomponents – stronger and more rigid perhaps.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Carbon\r\nfibre composites, resins and glass fibre-based materials are used for buildings\r\nand bridges, to make boat hulls, swimming pool panels and racing car parts, and\r\nin imitation granite work surfaces.</p><p>The most advanced\r\ncomposites are used in structures such as wind turbine blades and in spacecraft,\r\nand have to be able to withstand incredibly demanding environments.</p>As an\r\napprentice, you\r\ncould learn how to produce any one of a range of different composite materials,\r\nusing a variety of resins, fibres and other core materials.<p></p><p>As well as having good numeracy and literacy skills, you\r\nneed to be practically minded and willing to work with your hands.<br></p>\r\n','Composite assembly operator, Quality assurance operator, Composite technician, Pattern maker','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £25,000','2013-07-17 11:32:42','2013-11-26 14:52:18',17,'Composite engineering','Composite materials (or composites as they are more commonly known) are made from two or more constituent materials with different properties that, when combined, produce a material with different structural characteristics from the original components –stronger and more rigid perhaps.\r\nCarbon fibre composites, resins and glass fibre-based materials are used for buildings and bridges, to make boat hulls, swimming pool panels and racing car parts, and in imitation granite work surfaces. The most advanced composites are used in structures such as wind turbine blades and in spacecraft, and have to be able to withstand incredibly demanding environments.\r\nThere are around 1,500 companies involved in the UK composites industry and it is estimated that the sector will grow by 4–6% over the next five years, with the biggest growth likely to be in aerospace and wind energy.\r\nAs the use of composites in industry continues to rise, more skilled workers will be needed to help introduce this new technology, reduce production costs and increase the use of renewables to make the industry more sustainable.\r\nAs an apprentice, you are most likely to be employed as a semi-skilled operator. You could learn how to produce any one of a range of different composite materials, using a variety of resins, fibres and other core materials. You will need to show that you are keen and motivated to work in an engineering/manufacturing environment. As well as having good numeracy and literacy skills, you will also need to be practically minded and willing to work with your hands.\r\nCompletion of your Apprenticeship could lead to a role as a team leader or supervisor within your company. For Advanced apprentices, there may be the opportunity to progress to a Higher Apprenticeship in Engineering at Level 4 or to opt for a Foundation degree or HNC/HND.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2); Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Operator (semi-skilled), Composite assembly operator, Quality assurance operator, Composite technician, Pattern maker','Issuing Authority: SEMTA – www.semta.org.uk','NEW','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£25,000 depending on region and employer');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (191,'Metal processing & allied operations','<p></p><p>The\r\nmetal processing industry covers a variety of ways of working with different metals\r\nto produce materials that are suitable for the next stage in their\r\nmanufacturing process.</p><p>From large-scale\r\nstructures, such as bridges or the hulls of ocean-going ships, to smaller metal\r\ncomponents, this diverse industry covers a range of different production\r\ntechniques to create the properties in metals that make them suitable for a\r\nwide range of products.</p><p>Apprentices work in a variety of semi-skilled\r\noperative roles, in foundries, forges, workshops and machine rooms for example.</p>For\r\nall roles you will need to be practically minded and\r\nenjoy working with your hands.<p></p>\r\n','Casting operator, Metals production operative, Casting technician, Team leader','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £12,000 to £25,000','2013-07-17 11:48:23','2013-12-18 11:02:15',16,'Metal processing and allied operations','The metal processing industry covers a variety of ways of working with different metals to produce materials that are suitable for the next stage in their manufacturing process.\r\nFrom large-scale structures, such as bridges or the hulls of ocean-going ships, to smaller metal components, this diverse industry covers a range of different production techniques to create the properties in metals that make them suitable for a wide range of products.\r\nAs an apprentice you could find yourself working in any one of a number of different semi-skilled operative roles. In a foundry, for example, you might work on processes to heat and pour metals, prepare moulds and to remove and clean casts, while working in a forge might see you heating and shaping stock to achieve the right shape and properties for later machining and other mechanical operations. Alternatively, as an inspection and testing operative you might gather and prepare samples of metal materials and products to ensure they comply with quality control requirements.\r\nYou could find yourself working in a more technical role – perhaps as a casting technician, or maybe as a scheduler, working on the shop floor to ensure that materials are in the right place at the right time and that they meet the quality requirements of the manufacturing process. Metal products technicians plan and carry out operations to change the shape of hot and cold metals by applying physical pressures such as rolling and forging, and roles also exist for team leaders who organise the efficient working of production teams using their knowledge of the techniques and procedures required.\r\nFor all roles you will need to show your enthusiasm for working in a manufacturing or engineering environment. You will also need to be practically minded and enjoy working with your hands.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Casting operator, Metals production operative, Foundry processing operative, Forging operative, Metal forming operative, Metals process inspection and testing operative, Casting technician, Materials scheduler, Metal products technician, Process technician, Forgemaster technician, Heat treatment technician, Team leader','Issuing Authority: SEMTA – www.semta.org.uk','NEW','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £12,000–£25,000 depending on region and employer');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (192,'Engineering environmental technologies','<p><p>Industrial\r\nactivity in the past 50 years has created serious ecological problems, such\r\nas global warming, loss of biodiversity, pollution and toxic\r\nwaste.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>The\r\nengineering manufacturing, building services engineering, and construction\r\nsectors need a skilled workforce to help improve\r\nenvironmental performance, increase productivity and remain competitive.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentice learn how\r\nengineering and environmental awareness can be used across different sectors\r\nfor the benefit of all.</p>There\r\nare three pathways:</p><ul><li>Construction\r\nand the Built Environment<span></span><br></li><li>Manufacturing\r\nEngineering</li><li>Building\r\nServices Engineering</li></ul>','Construction technical supervisor, Supply chain co-ordinator, Environmental supervisor','Level 4 (Higher)','£33,000 (once qualified)','2013-07-17 12:08:42','2013-11-27 09:58:07',17,'Engineering environmental technologies','Industrial activity in the past half century has created serious ecological problems, such as global warming, loss of biodiversity, air pollution, acid rain and toxic waste.\r\nThe engineering manufacturing, building services engineering, and construction sectors need a skilled workforce of technicians and engineers to help improve environmental performance, increase productivity and remain competitive.\r\nAs an apprentice in Engineering Environmental Technologies, you will learn how engineering and environmental awareness can combine across different sectors for the benefit of all. For example, manufacturing engineers use environmentally friendly processes to produce sustainable materials for the construction and maintenance of new energy-efficient homes and buildings.\r\nThrough a combination of practical skills combined with a higher education qualification, you will learn how to respond to environmental issues and how new technologies can be used to implement sustainable practices.\r\nThere are three pathways on the Higher Apprenticeship in Engineering Environmental Technologies:\r\n•	Construction and the Built Environment\r\n•	Manufacturing Engineering\r\n•	Building Services Engineering\r\n\r\nDepending on the pathway you choose, you could find yourself managing the quality, cost and sustainability of construction projects, or identifying potentially hazardous engineering and manufacturing environmental risks and working to reduce the environmental impact of site operations. Or you might work alongside planning engineers to ensure that new manufacturing equipment is selected, installed and commissioned in line with environmental standards and requirements to minimise power consumption, air and water pollution, and environmental hazards.','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Construction technical supervisor, Built environment sustainability manager, Supply chain co-ordinator, Retrofit technical site supervisor, Environmental supervisor, Health, safety and environmental supervisor, Manufacturing shop operations supervisor, Facilities controls engineer, Environmental manufacturing planning engineer, Technical facilities/contract manager, Technical business development manager','Issuing Authority: Semta – www.semta.org.uk','NEW','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £33,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (193,'Mineral products technology','<p>The mineral products industry extract minerals from the ground for use in their natural form or to process them into products such as bricks, \r\nconcrete and asphalt.\r\n\r\n</p><p>These products are basic, but essential. They help to build houses, hospitals and schools and roads, railways and airports.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>It’s an exciting and stimulating environment in which to work, and offers excellent pay and job opportunities.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You could choose to work in one of the following areas:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>Coal mining</li><li>Peat extraction</li><li>Manufacture of solid fuel</li><li>Mining of iron ore, uranium, thorium, etc. </li><li>Quarrying</li><li>Operation of sand &amp; gravel pits</li><li>Production of salt</li><li>Manufacture of cement &amp; concrete</li><li>Cutting, shaping and finishing stone</li></ul>\r\n<p>You will most likely work in a trainee supervisor role, gaining \r\nexperience and qualifications in the operational and supervisory aspects\r\n of the industry.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Issuing authority:</b> Proskills</p><p></p>\r\n','Engineering technician, Draftsperson, Laboratory technician','Level 4 (Higher)','Around £12,000','2013-07-17 12:43:42','2013-12-18 11:07:10',16,'Mineral products technology','Mineral products are extracted from the ground and used in their natural form or can be processed into bricks, concrete and asphalt. These are basic but essential products that help to build our houses, hospitals and schools, and our roads, railways and airports.\r\nThis is an exciting and stimulating environment to work in and offers excellent pay, opportunities to travel, plus the chance to work with cutting-edge technology in a variety of disciplines.\r\nThis diverse industry includes coal mining; peat extraction; mining of iron ore, uranium, thorium and other metal ores; quarrying of architectural stone, building stone and aggregates for construction, chalk and slate; operation of sand and gravel pits; mining of clays, kaolin and fertilizer minerals; salt production; and manufacture of cement, plaster and ready-mixed concrete.\r\nThe world’s population is predicted to increase from 6.5 billion to 9 billion by 2050 and the demand for minerals is likely to rise. The Mineral Products Technology industry will need to satisfy this growing demand in a sustainable way, which will require high-quality science, engineering, technical and management skills at a variety of levels. Higher-level apprentices who successfully complete their programme will be very much in demand.\r\nAs an apprentice you will probably start off as a trainee technical supervisor gaining experience and relevant qualifications in operational and supervisory aspects of the industry. This could lead on to more diverse supervisory or managerial roles in technical or production areas, or you might move into the commercial side of the business, in a sales role for example.\r\nYou will need to be able and willing to work outside, in all weather conditions and in remote locations. You could also be asked to work safely at heights or in enclosed spaces, perhaps below ground. Many of the larger companies operate sites across the world and you might get an opportunity to travel and gain international experience.\r\n\r\nTo find out more visit any of the following:\r\nInstitute of Quarrying – www.quarrying.org\r\nInstitute of Asphalt Technology – www.instituteofasphalt.org\r\nThe Concrete Society – www.concrete.org.uk\r\nUK Coal – www.ukcoal.com\r\nInstitute of Materials, Minerals and Mining – www.iom3.org\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Trainee technical supervisor, Engineering technician, Draftsperson, Laboratory technician, Quality assurance technician','Issuing Authority: Proskills UK Ltd – www.proskills.co.uk','NEW','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): in the region of £21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (194,'Care leadership & management','<p></p>Adult\r\nsocial care provides personal and practical support to help people maintain their\r\nindependence and dignity, and to make sure they have choice and control.<p></p><p>This Apprenticeship will give you a range of\r\nskills to enable you to identify ways to provide high-quality\r\ncare and is designed for anyone aspiring to a more senior role</p><p>People are supported in a variety of settings including their own \r\nhomes, supported accommodation, day care centres or residential \r\naccommodation.</p><p></p><p>As an\r\napprentice you could manage day-to-day provision in a residential service,\r\nor you may specialise in an area such as dementia.</p><p>There are two pathways:</p><ul><li>General adult social care</li><li>Specialist adult\r\nsocial care</li></ul><b>Issuing authority:</b> Skills for Care and Development<br><p></p>\r\n','Adults\' residential manager, Adults\' manager, Adults\' advanced practitioner','Level 5 (Higher)','From £16,000 to £30,000 ','2013-07-29 13:03:49','2013-11-27 10:31:03',11,'Care leadership and management','This Higher Apprenticeship has two pathways: General adult social care and Specialist adult social care. It is ideal for taking the next step in a career in adult social care and is designed for anyone aspiring to a more senior role, perhaps as a manager or specialist practitioner.\r\nAdult social care is about providing personal and practical support to help people live their lives. It’s about supporting individuals to maintain their independence and dignity, and to make sure they have choice and control. An Apprenticeship in Care Leadership and Management will give you a range of transferrable skills to enable you to identify ways to innovate and provide high-quality care. The framework can be tailored to fit to your specific job role and the needs of your organisation.\r\nAs an apprentice you could be managing day-to-day provision in a residential service, you might manage day care provision or you may have a specific specialism in an area such as dementia or assistive technology. This is a great opportunity to build on and develop your skills and knowledge at a high level. \r\nCompletion of an Apprenticeship in Care Leadership and Management will stand you in good stead to progress your career in adult social care. The Specialist adult social care pathway includes a Level 5 Higher Education Diploma, and allows further progression at a Higher Education level.\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles:\r\nAdults’ residential manager – management of day-to-day provision in a residential service which could be as an assistant manager, deputy, unit or service manager. May include responsibility as registered manager of the service.\r\nAdults’ management – management of day-to-day provision in a service that is not residential (e.g. domiciliary care, day service). This could be as assistant manager, deputy, unit or service manager. May include responsibility as registered manager of the service.\r\nAdults’ advanced practitioner – roles within adult social care services that need a high level of knowledge of care provision activities or a specific specialism. Not involved in direct management of staff but has some responsibility for assessment of individuals’ needs and ensures positive outcomes. Specialisms could include dementia, diabetes, infection prevention and control, physical disability, acquired brain injury, sensory loss, learning disability, substance misuse, reablement','Issuing Authority: Skills for Care and Development – www.skillsforcareanddevelopment.org.uk','NEW','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £16,000–£30,000 ');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (195,'Interactive design & development','<p>\r\n\r\n</p><p>This Higher\r\nApprenticeship in creative and digital media provides a specialised pathway for those involved with the\r\ndesign and development of interactive media products.</p><p>It includes the\r\nmanagement of online communities, user experience and creative industry\r\nbusiness techniques.</p>Employers will expect you to be prepared for, and possibly have previous\r\nexperience in a working environment.<p></p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Creative Skillset<br></p>\r\n','Online community manager, User experience co-ordinator, Junior interactive product designer, Junior interactive product developer','Level 4 (Higher)','From £18,000 to 20,000','2013-07-30 10:29:36','2013-11-26 12:26:38',20,'Interactive design and development','The creative and digital media industries are constantly changing and evolving. Digital technology is re-shaping the landscape, demanding new, highly specialised skills.\r\nThis Higher Apprenticeship provides a more specialised pathway for those involved with the design and development of interactive media products and includes the management of online communities, user experience and creative industry business techniques.\r\nDepending on the role you take on you could find yourself involved in managing online communities and social media sites, monitoring and managing data usage, designing interactive product content or developing user interfaces, using code, software, advanced programming languages and testing systems.\r\nThe Apprenticeship provides an alternative entry route into what has historically been a graduate industry and it is hoped that this will increase the diversity of the workforce. The creative industries have customarily relied on graduates to meet higher level skills needs, yet traditional entry routes do not address all employers’ needs and employers are seeking a supply of new entrants with the right technical skills.\r\nAt Higher Apprenticeship level, employers will expect you to be prepared for, and possibly have previous experience in a working environment. The Apprenticeship provides an entry route from previous learning and employment, as well as a route to progress from the Advanced Apprenticeship in Creative and Digital Media and related subjects.','Leve: Higher Apprenticeship (Level 4)','Job roles: Online community manager, User experience co-ordinator, Junior interactive product designer, Junior interactive product developer','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','NEW','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £18,000–20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (196,'Journalism','<p><p>Journalists\r\nbring the news from your street, community, town or city, and from around\r\nthe world. <br></p><p>They bring you the news on television, on\r\nthe radio, in print, on websites and on mobile devices.</p>As an apprentice journalist you will find out how the industry\r\nworks and gain core journalism skills, such as reporting and editing, in the\r\nworkplace.</p><p>As well as learning how to find and tell a story you will gain\r\nknowledge on public affairs, media law, court reporting, news reporting and\r\nshorthand.<b><br></b></p><p><b>Issuing authority</b>: Creative Skillset<br></p>','Junior journalist','Level 3 (Adv)','Not available','2013-07-30 11:45:03','2013-11-26 12:52:13',20,'Journalism','Journalists bring you the news from your street, community, town or city, and from around the world. They keep you informed and up to date, about where you live and work or what you do or are interested in. They bring you the news on television, on the radio, in print, on websites and on mobile devices.\r\nJournalism is fast changing and full of opportunity. New technology and publishing platforms mean more people read news reports than ever before, and those reports are sourced faster than ever before.\r\nAs an apprentice journalist you will find out how the industry works and gain core journalism skills, such as reporting and editing, in the workplace. Your training will be supported by gaining a qualification designed and developed in conjunction with industry leaders by the National Council for the Training of Journalists.\r\nAs well as learning how to find and tell a story you will gain knowledge on public affairs, media law, court reporting, news reporting and shorthand.\r\nYou will probably begin your training as a junior journalist finding, researching and reporting news stories on various platforms. You will gain experience of interview techniques and learn how to write an accurate and engaging story. You will also develop and be assessed on shorthand and listening skills.\r\nAn ability to write accurately is a must. You will also need to have an enquiring mind, a hard-working attitude and a lively interest in current affairs. Persistence will help you to get the most out of a story and you should be prepared to work unsocial hours.\r\nAs well as having good literacy and numeracy skills, you will need to show your commitment to a career in journalism. Any work you have published in a school or college magazine or your own blog will help demonstrate that you have the necessary drive to succeed in this creative and fast-moving industry.\r\nFor further information visit the National Council for the Training of Journalists website – www.nctj.com.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Junior journalist','Issuing authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','NEW','26/11/13','','Starting salary: Not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (197,'Broadcast technology','<p>Broadcast engineers work in teams to design, build, fix and maintain studios,\r\nnetworks and other media equipment.</p><p>Their duties are wide and may include assessing and advising on the technical\r\nquality of pictures, sound and data broadcast to meet business requirements,\r\ndiagnosing faults and responding to broadcast-critical failures as well as\r\nplanned maintenance.</p><p>As an\r\napprentice, you will be employed by the BBC and undertake modular learning in a\r\nuniversity setting, at both the University of Salford and Birmingham City\r\nUniversity. Upon successful completion of your Apprenticeship programme, you\r\nwill gain a Bachelors degree: a BEng in Broadcast Engineering (Hons) jointly\r\nawarded by both institutions</p><p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority</b>: Creative Skillset<br></p>','Apprentice broadcast engineer','Level 6 (Higher)','£11,500 p.a. for 3 years','2013-07-30 11:51:42','2013-11-26 14:41:16',17,'Broadcast Technology','The fusion of creative intervention and technological innovation has created a world-class creative industry in the UK, particularly in terms of digital media. The BBC, ITV, Channel 4 and independent production companies lead the field in delivering technically complex television programming that is consumed across the globe. A recent example of this was the London 2012 Olympics opening ceremony and subsequent sporting coverage.\r\nPlaying a vital role in this industry, broadcast engineers work in teams using their technical engineering expertise to design, build, fix and maintain studios, networks and other media equipment essential to production and post-production. Their duties are wide and may include assessing and advising on the technical quality of pictures, sound and data broadcast to meet business requirements, diagnosing faults and responding to broadcast-critical failures as well as planned maintenance.\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship in broadcast technology has been developed to enable apprentices to gain the technical knowledge and real practical experience required for their immediate job and future career. These will be acquired through a mix of learning in the workplace, formal off-the-job learning and the opportunity to practise and embed new skills in a real work context.\r\nThe Apprenticeship has been tailored to fit the specific role of broadcast engineer through a carefully selected blend of electronics, engineering and computer science modules that have been added to the experience of learning on the job.\r\nAs an apprentice, you will be employed by the BBC and undertake modular learning in a university setting, at both the University of Salford and Birmingham City University. Upon successful completion of your Apprenticeship programme, you will gain a Bachelors degree: a BEng in Broadcast Engineering (Hons) jointly awarded by both institutions.\r\nThe employer training and work-based elements of the programme are managed by BBC Technology and the BBC Academy, and apprentices are given placements at various BBC sites as well as with selected industry partners to provide experience of the private sector.\r\nSuccessful applicants will need to complete the BBC selection process. You will also need to demonstrate that you have the necessary technical aptitude to become a broadcast engineer and the academic ability to successfully complete the Honours degree. You should be passionate about how things work and problem-solving, and be able to interact with people at all levels. You should also be prepared to work unsocial hours away from home.\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 6)','Job roles: Apprentice broadcast engineer','Issuing Authority: Creative Skillset – www.creativeskillset.org','New','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: apprentices will be paid £11,500 p.a. for the 3 years of their Apprenticeship');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (198,'Sound engineering & studio recording facilities','<p>Sound\r\nengineers work to ensure that the sound during a live performance is of the\r\nhighest possible quality.</p><p>Roles vary from planning the\r\nsound before an event and setting-up equipment to working from a mixing desk during a performance to control and\r\nbalance sound levels (and solve any problems that may arise).</p><p>The\r\nskills you will acquire could be transferred to a range of occupations within\r\nbroadcasting, theatre, television and film.</p><p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority</b>: Creative &amp; Cultural Skills<br></p>','Recording engineer, Mixing engineer, Broadcast engineer, Sound engineer','Level 2 (int), Level 3 (Adv)','Freelance rate: ~£150 per day','2013-07-30 12:03:20','2013-11-26 12:56:19',20,'Sound engineering and studio recording facilities','Sound engineers work to ensure that the sound during a live performance is of the highest possible quality. The roles are many and varied, from planning the sound before an event, setting-up equipment, attending rehearsals and arranging soundchecks, to working from a mixing desk during a performance to control and balance sound levels (and solve any problems that may arise).\r\nAn increase in the use of digital platforms and a rise in relatively inexpensive recording equipment mean that sound engineering and music audio technology has become more accessible in recent years. You will mainly work within music but the skills you will acquire could be transferred to a range of occupations within broadcasting, theatre, television and film.\r\nSound engineering is a hands-on process, and working closely within a business as an apprentice is one of the fastest ways to gain the essential skills required.\r\nAs an Intermediate Level apprentice you will train as a recording engineer, learning to manipulate digital sound and edit sound sources. You could find yourself assisting at a recording session, or taking on general duties within a professional recording environment. You might also assist with outside broadcasting and recording at a variety of venues.\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices train as recording engineers, mixing engineers, broadcast or live sound engineers. Your role could see you mixing sound in real-time, as it is performed for an audience, or working to improve the mix following a performance.\r\nSound engineers need a good musical ear and a keen interest in working with the latest technology. You don’t need to be able to play an instrument, but it could be an advantage, and any experience you can get with music technology, either at home or school, will help you – why not volunteer your services for school musical or theatrical productions, or get involved in live events within your community?\r\nFinally, you should be prepared to travel extensively, both in the UK and abroad and it is normal to work irregular hours, including evening and weekend work.\r\n\r\nFor further information about careers in the creative and cultural industries visit www.creative-choices.co.uk or www.getintomusic.org\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Recording engineer, Mixing engineer, Broadcast engineer, Sound engineer','Issuing Authority: Creative & Cultural Skills – www.ccskills.org.uk','NEW','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): Sound engineers are often freelance. Pay starts from around £150 per day.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (199,'Energy assessor & advisor','<p>Domestic\r\nenergy advisors analyse the energy efficiency of residential buildings to\r\nprovide an Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) and make suggestions for\r\nimprovements so homeowners can improve the energy efficiency of their\r\nproperty</p><p>Typical duties include conducting inspections, data entry and reporting back to the customer,\r\nproviding advice to ensure improvement of the energy efficiency rating.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Asset Skills<br></p>','Energy advisor','Level 3 (Adv)','From £20,000 to £30,000','2013-07-30 12:27:02','2013-11-26 14:05:10',18,'Energy assessor and advisor','This Apprenticeship is for new entrants to the energy sector and existing staff moving to a new role.\r\nA domestic energy advisor analyses the energy efficiency of residential buildings to provide an Energy Performance Certificate (EPC) and makes suggestions for improvements so the homeowner can improve the energy efficiency of their property, sell or rent their property. They will also advise customers on the new Green Deal initiative, set up by the Government, which helps to finance the installation of energy improvements.\r\nAs an energy advisor, typical duties will include: conducting inspections – collecting information about a property including its age, building type, room measurement and type of heating; data entry – input of all of the information gained into computer software for analysis to produce an EPC; and reporting back to the customer, providing advice to ensure improvement of the energy efficiency rating.\r\nOn this Apprenticeship, you’ll learn all aspects of conducting energy assessments in a safe, effective and professional manner.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job role: Energy advisor','Issuing Authority: Asset Skills – www.assetskills.org','NEW','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £20,000–£30,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (200,'Nuclear power plant operations','<p>Nuclear power stations are well distributed around\r\nthe coast of Great Britain</p><p>The Government\'s view is that nuclear power should be part of the\r\nUK’s low-carbon energy mix and aims to build new nuclear power stations that\r\nwill be generating electricity from around 2018.</p><p>This new\r\nApprenticeship will provide an entry route into the commercial nuclear power industry\r\nto develop the skills needed to become a nuclear power plant operations\r\ntechnician.</p><p>As a\r\ngeneration technician, you would help to ensure the safe and reliable operation\r\nof a nuclear power plant in accordance with all licences and regulating bodies.</p><p>As a fuel\r\ntechnician you would take responsibility for safely and reliably removing fuel\r\nfrom or providing fuel to the reactor.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Cogent\r\n<br></p>','Nuclear power plant production technician (generation or fuel)','Level 3 (Adv)','Not available','2013-07-30 13:03:05','2013-11-26 14:13:12',18,'Nuclear power plant operations','A well-trained and highly skilled workforce of over 24,000 people is employed in the operation and decommissioning of the UK’s nuclear power stations. The stations, which compete with other fuel types in the electricity market, are well distributed around the coast of Great Britain.\r\nTo combat the effects of climate change and ensure a secure energy supply for the future, the Government has set out its view that nuclear power should be part of the UK’s low-carbon energy mix. The aim is to build new nuclear power stations that will be generating electricity from around 2018, and research shows that this new build programme will require about 1000 people to be recruited each year, many at apprentice and graduate level.\r\nThis new Apprenticeship will provide an entry route into the commercial nuclear power industry to develop the skills needed to become a nuclear power plant operations technician.\r\nAs an apprentice, you would undertake skills and knowledge training in either the generation pathway or nuclear fuel operations.\r\nAs a generation technician, you would help to ensure the safe and reliable operation of a nuclear power plant in accordance with all licences and regulating bodies, and in line with company business strategies and industry practice in the area of power generation.\r\nAs a fuel technician you would take responsibility for safely and reliably removing fuel from or providing fuel to the reactor. In both positions you would hold one or more emergency scheme roles.\r\nThe Advanced Apprenticeship in Nuclear Power Plant Operations will take a minimum of 36 months to complete. All apprentices must be prepared to work in a variety of conditions that may include working at heights, shiftwork (including nights and weekends), working outdoors, wearing specialist safety equipment and working within a radiological environment.\r\nThe Apprenticeship is open to anyone aged 16 or over. However, it is important to note that, under the Nuclear Installations Act, entry into radiation controlled areas is normally restricted to those over the age of 18.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Nuclear power plant production technician (generation or fuel)','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent.ssc.com','NEW','26/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (201,'Professional aviation pilot','<p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b></p><p>Professional\r\naviation pilots combine skills and knowledge, good judgement and common\r\nsense, to safely operate aircraft for commercial purposes.</p><p>On\r\ncompletion of this Apprenticeship you will be awarded with an Honours degree that\r\nincorporates all the regulatory requirements for the issue of a commercial\r\npilot licence and employment as a professional aviation pilot.</p><p>The\r\nApprenticeship will take a minimum of 24 months (and up to 36 months to\r\ncomplete) and may encompass either the Multi-crew Pilot Licence (MPL) or the\r\nAirline Transport Pilot Licence (ATPL) training schemes.</p><p>Note: Training\r\nto become a commercial airline pilot requires personal investment of between\r\n£70,000 and £100,000. Trainees may have the\r\npotential to access loans and grants to cover their fees in line with\r\nother higher education learners.</p><p><b>Issuing authority</b>: People 1st – <i><a href=\"http://www.people1st.co.uk\"><span>www.people1st.co.uk</span></a></i><br></p>','Professional aviation pilot','Level 6 (Higher)','From £30,000 (budget airline)','2013-08-01 11:09:44','2013-11-27 11:33:06',4,'Professional aviation pilot practice','The Higher Apprenticeship for Professional Aviation Pilots has been designed to provide the aviation sector with a new route into commercial pilot training.\r\nProfessional aviation pilots combine their skills and knowledge, good judgement and common sense, to safely and efficiently operate aircraft for commercial purposes.\r\nAs an apprentice you will follow a structured training programme to gain higher-level technical and practical skills. You will develop leadership, managerial and command experience, together with analytical and problem-solving abilities, and the communication and team skills that are essential for a role as a professional aviation pilot.\r\nOn completion of your Apprenticeship you will be awarded with an Honours degree that incorporates all the regulatory requirements for the issue of a commercial pilot licence and employment as a professional aviation pilot.\r\nThe Apprenticeship will take a minimum of 24 months (and up to 36 months to complete) and may encompass either the Multi-crew Pilot Licence (MPL) or the Airline Transport Pilot Licence (ATPL) training schemes.\r\n\r\nFunding\r\nTraining to become a commercial airline pilot requires personal investment of between £70,000 and £100,000. There is no public support for training, and the regulated elements of the training are delivered by private training providers. In general airlines do not recruit pilots until basic training has been completed.\r\nIt is impossible to know how many aspiring pilots are excluded from applying to enter the profession due to a lack of access to funding.\r\nThe Higher Apprenticeship for Professional Aviation Pilots provides a nationally recognised, qualification-based route into training. As a trainee apprentice you might be able to access loans and grants to cover your fees in line with other higher education learners.\r\nOnce you have qualified as a pilot, you may not gain immediate full-time employment; you must, however, maintain minimum levels of flying/experience to ensure that your licence remains valid and you should be aware of the additional cost of this before undertaking an Apprenticeship.\r\n\r\nFor more information on careers in aviation, visit the following websites:\r\nAviation Skills Partnership – www.aviationskillspartnership.com\r\nRoyal Aeronautical Society – www.aerosociety.com\r\nGuild of Air Pilots and Air Navigators –www.gapan.org\r\nCareers in Aerospace – www.careersinaerospace.com\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 6)','Job roles: Professional aviation pilot','Issuing authority: People 1st – www.people1st.co.uk','NEW','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: Around £30,000 for pilots working for a budget airline');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (202,'Assistant practitioner','<p>Assistant practitioners competently deliver healthcare with a level of knowledge and skill beyond that of traditional\r\nhealthcare assistants or support workers.</p>\r\n<p>As an apprentice you will provide patient care in clinics, people’s homes or hospitals.</p>\r\n<p>You might work in a single health profession (e.g. nursing, physiotherapy or speech and language therapy) or across a number of different disciplines.</p>\r\n<p>This programme includes foundation degrees and qualifications at QCF level 5. You will need to show that you can meet the academic requirements for the programme of study.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for Health</p>','Assistant practitioner','Higher (Level 5)','From £18,000 to £22,000','2013-08-01 12:03:48','2013-11-27 10:28:00',11,'Assistant practitioner','This Higher Apprenticeship provides the skills and knowledge required to become an assistant practitioner in a health setting.\r\nAssistant practitioners competently deliver healthcare to and for people. They have a level of knowledge and skill beyond that of traditional healthcare assistants or support workers. Some of the functions undertaken by assistant practitioners were previously only carried out by health professionals such as nurses, physiotherapists, radiographers, podiatrists, speech and language therapists, occupational therapists. While these functions are now carried out by assistant practitioners they are still delegated by the health professionals.\r\nAssistant practitioners can work in a single health profession (e.g. nursing, physiotherapy or speech and language therapy) or work across a number of different disciplines. Roles exist in a wide range of areas, including long-term conditions, staying healthy, end of life care, maternity and newborn, acute care, planned care, mental health, and children and families.\r\nAs an apprentice you will work alongside health professionals providing patient care in a range of settings that could include clinics, people’s homes or hospitals. You will gain the new skills and learning you need to carry out your job and to prepare you for future employment as an assistant practitioner and your career progression within the health sector. The precise activities you carry out will be outlined in your Apprenticeship agreement and job description.\r\nThis work-based programme was designed and developed with employers and includes foundation degrees and qualifications at QCF level 5. You will need to show that you can meet the academic requirements for the programme of study. Employers will also expect you to have had experience of working within a healthcare setting. The duration of this Apprenticeship is 2 years.\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job role: Assistant practitioner','Issuing Authority:Skills for Health – www.skillsforhealth.org.uk','NEW','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Salary once qualified: £18,000–£22,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (203,'Legal advice','<p>Legal\r\nadvisors provide members of the public with advice and information about their\r\nrights, entitlements and responsibilities under the law.</p><p>This framework is for those providing\r\ninitial legal advice to clients.</p><p>There are two levels:<span><span></span></span></p><ul><li><span><span></span></span>Intermediate\r\nApprenticeship – Supporting Legal Advice Provision</li><li>Advanced\r\nApprenticeship – Providing Legal Advice</li></ul><b>Issuing authority</b>: Skills for Justice\r\n<br>\r\n','Legal signposting advisor, Caseworker, Generalist legal advisor','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £24,000 to £28,000','2013-08-01 13:36:03','2013-11-25 14:25:19',1,'Legal advice','Legal advisors provide members of the public with advice and information about their rights, entitlements and responsibilities under the law. The provision of advice should be independent, that is it should be in the best interests of the client and not influenced in any way by the interests or views of anyone other than the client.\r\nAs an apprentice you are most likely to be working for a not-for-profit organisation whose primary focus is to provide legal advice to the public.\r\nThis framework is for those providing initial legal advice to clients. There are two levels:\r\n\r\nIntermediate Apprenticeship – Supporting Legal Advice Provision\r\nAt Intermediate level apprentices work as legal signposting advisors. They will act as the first point of contact for clients, assess their needs and refer them to appropriate colleagues or external organisations. Apprentices develop their skills, knowledge and understanding about where to find legal information materials and learn how to give basic advice.\r\n\r\nAdvanced Apprenticeship – Providing Legal Advice\r\nAs an Advanced Level apprentice, you might work as a generalist legal advisor or caseworker. You would manage client interviews and would also be required to research further detail electronically, using the Internet or perhaps through your client’s organisation’s intranet. You would provide general legal advice to clients, which would include supporting the client to plan, implement and review action.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Legal signposting advisor, Caseworker, Generalist legal advisor','Issuing authority: Skills for Justice – www.skillsforjustice.com','NEW','25/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £24,000 (Level 2), £25,000–£28,000 (Level 3)');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (204,'Intelligence analysis','<p>Intelligence\r\nanalysis is an important area of work, for HM Forces and also for a wide range of organisations involved in defence, security, transnational\r\ncrime, cybercrime and immigration.</p><p>Intelligence analysis is a key area in\r\nmaintaining the defence and security of the nation.</p><p>As an apprentice, you will play a vital role in the gathering, classification, interpretation and\r\ndissemination of information, which is critical to the safe and successful\r\ndelivery of defence and security operations.</p><b></b><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for Justice<i></i>','Intelligence analyst','Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000','2013-08-01 13:57:40','2013-12-18 12:39:46',23,'Intelligence Analysis','Intelligence analysis is an increasingly important area of work, not just for HM Forces, but for a wide range of organisations involved in defence, security, transnational crime, cybercrime and immigration. Intelligence analysis is a key area in maintaining the defence and security of the nation.\r\nOnce recruited into intelligence analysis as an apprentice, you will develop a wide range of skills and knowledge to carry out your role. You will be involved in gathering and collating data from a wide range of sources, both human and electronic. Your task will be to evaluate this data and the sources in order to provide an analysis to those involved in strategic and tactical decision-making. You might be asked to make presentations of your analyses to superiors and maintain files of historical data gathered.\r\nOverall you will play a vital role in the gathering, classification, interpretation and dissemination of information, which is critical to the safe and successful delivery of defence and security operations. These range from intelligence-related to domestic threats of disorder and terrorism handled by the police and law-enforcement agencies, to active areas of conflict around the world in which HM Forces may be involved.\r\nIntelligence analysts work patterns depend on the service or organisation they are employed in but this often involves shifts and weekend working. There are also minimum requirements for fitness, and for HM Forces there are nationality criteria to be met.\r\n','Level: Advanced Apprenticeship (Level 3)','Job role: Intelligence analyst','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','NEW','','','Salary after training: £17,000 and rising dependent on rank');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (205,'Community safety','<p>This\r\nApprenticeship is designed to train people to advise communities on safety\r\nissues.</p><p>The main focus is on minimising the risk of fire within communities,\r\nbut you will also learn about road safety.</p><p>Your core responsibility will be to work with communities to\r\nhelp to reduce safety risks.</p><p>The role will\r\ninvolve travel within the community including to community centres, homes,\r\nschools and places of work.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for Justice<i></i>\r\n<br></p>','Community safety advisor, Community safety advocate','Level 2 (Int)','From £15,000','2013-08-01 14:02:15','2013-12-18 12:26:56',23,'Community safety','This Apprenticeship is designed to train people to advise communities on safety issues. The main focus is on minimising the risk of fire within communities, but you will also learn about road safety and may be required to provide interventions with drivers and pedestrians. You will help to gather information and data which will inform community safety strategies.\r\nAs a community safety advisor, your core responsibility will be to work with communities to help to reduce safety risks. You will perform Home Safety Checks, deliver group presentations and work with partner agencies to ensure that resources are targeted where they will make the greatest impact.\r\nThe role will involve travel within the community including to community centres, homes, schools and places of work.\r\n','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Community safety advisor, Community safety advocate','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','NEW','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £15,000 plus');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (206,'Criminal investigation','<p><b>Higher\r\nApprenticeship</b><p>To\r\naccess this Higher Apprenticeship you will need to be a serving police officer.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices will\r\nwork as detective investigators within the police service, in roles such as Reactive\r\nCID investigator, Family crime investigator or Serious and acquisitive\r\ninvestigator.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You will devise and evaluate investigative strategies and gather information\r\nand evidence relating to the investigation.</p><p>You will also be required to interview victims,\r\nwitnesses and suspects effectively, in accordance with current legislation,\r\npolicies and procedures, and ensure that information is recorded accurately and\r\nethically.</p>For all roles\r\nyou will be required to work nights, weekends and bank holidays.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for Justice<i><a href=\"http://www.sfjuk.com\"></a></i>\r\n\r\n</p>','Reactive CID investigator, Family crime unit, serious and acquisitive investigator, Major crime investigator, Violent crime investigator, Hate crime investigator, High-tech crime investigator, Financial crime investigator, Covert policing, Counter terrori','Level: Higher (Level 5)','From £23,000','2013-08-01 14:08:44','2013-12-18 12:29:19',23,'Criminal investigation','Criminal investigation plays a crucial part of a police officer’s role within the justice sector. To access this Higher Apprenticeship you will need to be a serving police officer.\r\nApprentices will work as detective investigators within the police service, in roles such as Reactive CID investigator, Family crime investigator or Serious and acquisitive investigator. This Apprenticeship enhances the detective investigator role.\r\nYour work in conducting an investigation will incorporate decision-making and recording of rationale. You will devise and evaluate investigative strategies and gather information and evidence relating to the investigation. The role will require you to communicate effectively with internal and external specialist support to maximise the opportunities for evidence gathering. You will also be required to interview victims, witnesses and suspects effectively, in accordance with current legislation, policies and procedures.\r\nThe job involves responsibility for ensuring that the recording of information is accurate and ethical; that information and other material is retained in accordance with current legislation, policies and procedures; and that files of evidence are prepared to an appropriate standard for court proceedings.\r\nFor all roles you will be required to work nights, weekends and bank holidays.\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 5)','Job roles: Reactive CID investigator, Family crime unit, serious and acquisitive investigator, Major crime investigator, Violent crime investigator, Hate crime investigator, High-tech crime investigator, Financial crime investigator, Covert policing, Counter terrorism, Professional standards','  Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','NEW','','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £23,000 plus');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (207,'Consumer electrical & electronic products ','<p>As an apprentice you will learn to deliver and install, or service and maintain, electrical and electronic products such as washing machines, dishwashers, fridges, visual and audio entertainment systems.</p><p>These products could be installed in domestic, industrial and commercial premises.</p><p>You will need technical skills to replace, for example, a whole part such as a dishwasher element or a resistor on a control circuit board, as well as good levels of customer service and communication skills.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Summit Skills<br></p>','Installer, Faults repairer','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £17,000 to £21,000','2013-08-05 11:51:05','2013-11-26 14:55:00',17,'Consumer electrical and electronic products ','As an apprentice in Consumer Electrical and Electronic Products you will be involved in the delivery and installation, or service and maintenance, of electrical and electronic products such as washing machines, dishwashers, fridges, visual and audio entertainment systems.\r\nThese products could be installed in domestic, industrial and commercial premises where you will need technical skills to replace, for example, a whole part such as a dishwasher element or a resistor on a control circuit board, as well as good levels of customer service and communication skills. You may be required to visit a customer’s premises to diagnose a fault and then carry out any necessary repair work on site.\r\nAs an Advanced apprentice you might work to repair faults in electronic components. For this work you are likely to be workshop-based, repairing products at a component level (e.g. replacing electronic resistors and micro-chips), but you may be required to collect products from customers’ premises and return them to the workshop for further investigation.\r\nWhatever role you work in, it will help if you are practically minded and are interested in technology. You will need to have good numeracy and literacy skills, as a significant amount of paperwork will be involved. Apprentices must also have good colour vision to be able to recognise colour-coded wires and components.\r\nYou should be willing to learn to drive if you don’t already have a driving licence and some roles may require you to work outside and carry out manual lifting of heavy electrical products.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Installer, Faults repairer','Issuing Authority: Summit Skills – www.summitskills.org.uk','NEW','26.11.13','','Starting salary (once qualified): £17,000–£21,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (208,'Recruitment','<p>Effective recruitment ensures that organisations have the right people, in the right place, at the right time, and is crucial to the performance of every company in the UK.</p><p>Every year, up to 1.5 million individuals are placed in jobs.</p><p>The role of a recruiter is very sales-orientated, but also involves elements of human resources. Apprentices will be expected to have a ‘can do’ attitude, as well as good numeracy, literacy and communication skills.<br></p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills CFA<br></p>','Junior recruitment consultant, In-house resource, Account representative, Recruitment consultant','Level 3 (Adv), Level 4 (Higher)','From £26,000','2013-08-05 14:46:06','2013-11-26 11:00:45',1,'Recruitment','Effective recruitment ensures that organisations have the right people, in the right place, at the right time, and is crucial to the performance of every company in the UK. Recruitment is one of the fastest growing industries in the UK, with over 90,000 people currently employed. Each year it is responsible for placing up to 1.5 million individuals in jobs, emphasising its importance to the success of the overall economy.\r\nThe role of a recruiter is very sales-orientated, but also involves elements of human resources. Anyone involved in recruitment activities needs to have the appropriate knowledge and skills to do the job properly and as a Recruitment apprentice, you will be expected to have a ‘can do’ attitude, as well as good numeracy, literacy and communication skills which your Apprenticeship will build on.\r\nAdvanced Level apprentices may be involved in identifying client recruitment requirements, pre-selecting and assessing candidates, matching and presenting candidates to employers and attracting, briefing and supporting candidates, as well as administering the recruitment processes.\r\nAt Higher Level your responsibilities could include advising clients on strategic recruitment planning, identifying their recruitment requirements, planning the recruitment process, pre-selecting and assessing candidates, building relationships with clients, and attracting, coaching and supporting candidates.','Level: Advanced (Level 3), Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Advanced Level – Trainee/Junior recruitment consultant, In-house resource, Account representative\r\nHigher Level – Recruitment consultant, Senior/Principal/Lead consultant, Account manager','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org ','NEW','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary: Salaries vary across sectors and locations. However, average salaries are around £26,000, with senior consultants earning an average of £32,000. Those with lengthy experience can earn £40,000+. Bonuses and commission are also commonplace ');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (209,'Explosives','<p>Explosives apprentices will undertake a variety of functions, including the storage, quality maintenance and inspection, safe handling, transport, movement and hand over of explosives to others.</p><p>The key target group for this Apprenticeship is the Army’s ammunition technicians, but it is open to anyone seeking a career in ammunition management and related areas.</p><p>Successful completion of this Apprenticeship will arm you with the skills you need to work with explosives within a military environment, in MoD civilian establishments and in the private sector.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Cogent<br></p>\r\n','Ammunition technician','Level 2 (Int)','From £275 a week','2013-09-04 10:54:19','2013-11-27 12:04:37',16,'Explosives','The Apprenticeship in Explosives provides a structured programme of learning and practical experience with an emphasis on explosives safety. Apprentices will have the opportunity to undertake a variety of functions, including the storage, quality maintenance and inspection, safe handling, transport, movement and hand over of explosives to others.\r\nAlthough the key target group for this Apprenticeship is the Army’s ammunition technicians, it is open to anyone seeking a career in ammunition management and related areas. This includes the other Armed Forces, MoD civilians and those employed in or seeking to be employed in the private sector.\r\nSafety is critical in this industry and apprentices need to be aware that failure can carry a high cost at a strategic, tactical and financial level as well as potentially leading to loss of life. You will need to be prepared to operate in conditions that could be both hazardous and hostile, as well as to accept the demands of antisocial working hours both at home and abroad.\r\nIn return, successful completion of this Apprenticeship will arm you with the skills, knowledge and occupational competence that you need to work with explosives within a military environment, in MoD civilian establishments and in the private sector, for example in de-mining companies and defence manufacturers.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job roles: Ammunition technician','Issuing Authority: Cogent – www.cogent-ssc.com','NEW','27/11/13','','Starting salary (once qualified): Regular soldiers receive over £275 a week in Phase 1 training, which rises to at least £17,767 a year depending on which Army job you do. Some roles get specialist pay, which can be worth at least an extra £19 per day.');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (210,'Learning support','<p>Learning\r\nSupport practitioners provide opportunities to\r\nhelp people to learn, achieve and make progress within their workplace or in\r\neducational settings and other environments.</p><p>Learning\r\nsupport can mean general help with education or skills, or more specialised support\r\nfor disabled or deaf learners, or anyone who needs help with literacy, language\r\nand numeracy.</p><p>You might train as a general learning support practitioner, or opt to work in a more specialised role\r\noffering support to those who need specific help with literacy, language and\r\nnumeracy learning, or helping deaf or disabled learners with their\r\ncommunication or learning needs. <br></p><p><b>Issuing\r\nAuthority</b>: Skills for Justice<br>\r\n<br></p>\r\n','Learning support practitioner','Level 3 (Adv)','Not available','2013-09-05 10:21:29','2013-11-27 11:04:18',11,' Learning support','Learning Support practitioners work in a variety of roles providing opportunities to help people to learn, achieve and make progress within their workplace or in educational settings and other environments.\r\nLearning support can mean general help with education or skills, or more specialised support for disabled or deaf learners, or anyone who needs help with literacy, language and numeracy.\r\nThe difference that this level of support makes to learner achievement is increasingly recognised by employers, enabling them to play a key role in the development of individuals and to tailor their learning programmes to meet the specific needs of an organisation.\r\nThis Apprenticeship offers an entry route into learning support occupations. It will also enable career progression to more senior roles, and to higher-level training and qualifications.\r\nAs an apprentice you will work under guidance to provide learning opportunities that promote achievement and progression. You will provide learning support for both individuals and groups, helping them to reach their goals whatever their needs or settings.\r\nYou might choose to train as a general learning support practitioner, or opt to work in a more specialised role offering support to those who need specific help with literacy, language and numeracy learning, or helping deaf or disabled learners with their communication or learning needs.\r\nAfter completing your Apprenticeship you might have the opportunity to move into a role as an educational interpreter or senior learning support practitioner, or to take further qualifications in, for example, learning and development, advice and guidance or coaching and mentoring.','Level: Advanced (Level 3)','Job roles: Learning support practitioner (general or more specialized roles)','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','NEW','27/11/13','','Starting salary: Not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (211,'Work-based learning practitioners','<p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b><br></p><p>The\r\nwork-based learning industry employs 30,000 people in England, as staff in\r\npersonnel and training departments, and as tutors, assessors, independent\r\ntrainers and training managers.</p><p>Work-based learning\r\npractitioners motivate, inspire and encourage\r\nnew ways of learning that will lead to performance excellence.</p><p>Apprentices gain a wide range of transferable skills\r\nthat will enable you to design, develop and deliver learning that centres\r\naround activities carried out at work.</p><p>Trainers or tutors plan and deliver all aspects of learning and\r\nassessment, including learning on and off the job, while career guidance counsellors\r\nprovide support and pastoral care to learners.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Skills for Justice<br></p>\r\n','Trainer, Tutor, Teacher, Instructor, Learning advisor, Assessor, Quality assurance controller, Skills tutor, Career guidance counsellor, Supervisor','Level 4,5 (Higher)','Not available','2013-09-05 10:27:45','2013-12-18 12:51:39',23,'Professional development for work-based learning practitioners','The work-based learning industry employs 30,000 people in England, as staff in personnel and training departments, and as tutors, assessors, independent trainers and training managers.\r\nMany of these roles combine occupational responsibilities with support for workplace training and development.\r\nThis Higher Apprenticeship aims to bring together aspects of work-based learning, education and teaching, and information, advice and guidance, each of which is essential to provide work-based learning practitioners with the skills they require to motivate, inspire and encourage new ways of learning that will lead to performance excellence.\r\nAs an apprentice you will gain a wide range of transferable skills that will enable you to design, develop and deliver learning that centres around activities carried out at work. You will learn to recognise and overcome some of the problems associated with practical work-based learning and to support the practical application of learning in a work context. You may even support career planning and progression for apprentices and other work-based learners.\r\nWorking as a trainer or tutor you will plan and deliver all aspects of learning and assessment, including learning on and off the job. Alternatively, as head of quality assurance you will be responsible for ensuring the quality and standardisation of learning delivery and assessment practice. Career guidance counsellors provide support and pastoral care to learners, while mentors, coaches and managers support learning and development, with or without line management responsibility.\r\nYou will need to have a strong interest in a career in work-based learning and be able to demonstrate a ‘can do’ attitude. As well as having basic numeracy, literacy and communication skills, you will be expected to have experience of your occupational sector to ensure you have the suitable foundations on which to build your knowledge and skills. You should also be willing to undergo a Criminal Records Bureau (CRB) check.\r\nAfter completing this foundation degree programme you might have the opportunity to progress onto the BA (Hons) degree in professional development that is being developed as a Higher Apprenticeship at Level 6.','Level: Higher (Level 4, Level 5)','Job roles: Trainer, Tutor, Teacher, Instructor, Learning advisor, Assessor, Quality assurance controller, Skills tutor, Career guidance counsellor, Supervisor, Coach, Mentor, Manager','Issuing Authority: Skills for Justice – www.sfjuk.com','NEW','','Higher Apprenticeship','Salary: Not available');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (212,'Power engineering','<p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b></p><p>The power sector covers activities associated with the generation, national transmission and local distribution of electricity, up to, and including, the customer\'s meter.<br><br>Higher apprentices undertake one of a number of engineering roles:</p><p><b>Asset management or strategy engineers</b> produce long-term plans for the industry, taking account of new technology, regulatory requirements, and other factors.</p><p><b>Design and/or planning engineers</b> produce designs to meet statutory and industry standards, while also considering client requirements, network strategy and budget constraints.</p><p><b>Programme planning engineers</b> ensure that work programmes are delivered on time and meet quality, cost and safety requirements.</p><p><b>Operations engineers plan</b>, undertake and manage a range of engineering operations to meet safety, time, cost and quality requirements.</p><p>This Higher Apprenticeship can provide a springboard to an exciting career in the power sector. You could also move on to a suitable Foundation Degree course such as the Foundation Degree in Power Engineering offered by Aston University.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority</b>: Energy &amp; Utility Skills<br></p>\r\n','Asset management engineer, Design/Planning engineer, Programme planning engineer, Operations engineer','Level 4 (Higher)','£27,000 (industry average)','2013-09-09 09:21:05','2013-11-26 14:21:16',18,'Power engineering','The power sector covers activities associated with the generation, national transmission and local distribution of electricity, up to, and including, the customer\'s meter.\r\nOver the coming years, some of the key challenges facing the industry include the need to: improve the efficiency of transmission and distribution systems to minimise power loss; replace infrastructure; invest in new technologies to support low-carbon networks; and change the fuel mix and increase the use of renewable energy sources to meet Government targets.\r\nHigher apprentices undertake one of a number of engineering roles. As an asset management or strategy engineer, you would produce long-term plans for the industry, taking account of new technology, regulatory requirements, and other factors. You might be required to analyse electrical networks, seek methods of improving performance or study historic data.\r\nDesign and/or planning engineers produce designs to meet statutory and industry standards, while also considering client requirements, network strategy and budget constraints, whereas it is the task of the programme planning engineer to ensure that work programmes are delivered on time and meet quality, cost and safety requirements.\r\nFinally, operations engineers plan, undertake and manage a range of engineering operations to meet safety, time, cost and quality requirements.\r\nWhatever route you choose to follow, this Higher Apprenticeship can provide a springboard to an exciting career in the power sector. On completion of your Apprenticeship there will be great opportunities to progress to more senior positions if you are well motivated. You could also move on to a suitable Foundation Degree course such as the Foundation Degree in Power Engineering offered by Aston University.\r\nFor further information on careers in Power visit www.thinkpowersector.co.uk.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Asset management engineer, Design/Planning engineer, Programme planning engineer, Operations engineer','Issuing Authority: Energy & Utility Skills – www.euskills.co.uk','NEW','26/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship',' Starting salary (once qualified): the industry average is £27,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (213,'Hospitality management','<p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b></p><p><p></p>This Higher Apprenticeship has been developed to provide a career route \r\ninto management, for those working within the hospitality sector.</p><p>Staff \r\nwho have the opportunity to move into higher level jobs are likely to be\r\n more motivated and to remain within a business, which, in turn, can \r\nhelp the business to increase its productivity and remain profitable.<p></p>\r\n\r\n<p>Apprentices train in a range of hospitality management job roles that support the day-to-day running of the business, \r\nsuch as deputy general manager, front office manager, operations or unit\r\n manager.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Your duties could include:</p>\r\n\r\n<ul><li>improving food service</li><li>monitoring day-to-day management</li><li>assessing departments</li><li>welcoming guests</li><li>registering arrivals,</li><li>taking bookings</li><li>preparing bills and taking payments.</li><li>liaising with the housekeeping department.</li></ul>\r\n<p><b>Issuing authority:</b> Skills CFA</p></p>','Deputy general manager, Front office manager, Operations manager, Unit manager','Level 4 (Higher)','from £20,000','2013-09-10 08:51:21','2013-11-27 11:28:47',4,'Hospitality management','The Higher Level Apprenticeship in Hospitality Management has been developed to provide a career route into management, for those working within the hospitality sector. Staff who have the opportunity to move into higher level jobs are likely to be more motivated and to remain within a business, which, in turn, can help the business to increase its productivity and remain profitable.\r\nAs a Higher Level apprentice you might work in any one of a number of roles across many different establishments, from hotels and restaurants to backpacker hostels or self-catering accommodation. You could find yourself working for a large chain or a small, independent business.\r\nDeputy general managers support the general manager in running the business. Their responsibilities include developing plans for improved service and financial performance, influencing and improving food service, monitoring day-to-day management and assessing departments.\r\nFront office managers have regular contact with the guests, welcoming and registering arrivals, answering queries, taking bookings, preparing bills and taking payments. They liaise closely with the housekeeping department and encourage guests to use the facilities available to them.\r\nOperations managers ensure the effective day-to-day management of all operational aspects of the business, ensuring that effective customer service is provided, maximising profits and improving customer satisfaction. They are also responsible for the management of on-site maintenance.\r\nFinally, unit managers lead, manage and develop staff to achieve their set objectives. They lead the relationship with the client and continually review the service standards and food offered at the unit.\r\nAll roles require some level of experience of working at a supervisory level. You will also need to have excellent customer service skills to help provide a welcoming and pleasant experience for customers.\r\n','Level: Higher (Level 4)','Job roles: Deputy general manager, Front office manager, Operations manager, Unit manager','Issuing Authority: Skills CFA – www.skillscfa.org','NEW','27/11/13','Higher Apprenticeship','Starting salary (once qualified): £20,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (214,'Multi-skilled vehicle collision repair','<p>Multi-skilled vehicle collision repair apprentices train as auto repair technicians in the collision\r\nrepair industry, repairing and restoring a range of passenger and light commercial\r\nvehicles to their pre-accident condition.</p><p>As an apprentice, you will learn how to identify and remove mechanical, electrical &amp; trim\r\ncomponents; assess the level of damage and repair/replace panels as appropriate;\r\nand prepare and paint the required areas of the vehicle to the manufacturers’\r\nspecification</p><p>After further training and development you may have the\r\nopportunity to progress into a range of jobs, such as workshop controller,\r\nbodyshop manager or service manager.</p><p><b>Issuing Authority: </b>The Institute of the Motor Industry<br></p>','Multi-skilled auto repair technician','Level 2 (Int), Level 3 (Adv)','From £13,000 to £15,000','2013-09-10 09:17:07','2013-12-18 13:14:44',5,'Multi-skilled vehicle collision repair','Vehicle body and paint businesses have traditionally employed individuals in narrow roles, where each employee would specialise in a particular area, for example mechanical, electrical & trim (MET), body repair (panel) and body paint. For some businesses this restricts the flexibility that they require and limits the effective use of their resources, and these businesses are now looking to train individuals into ‘multi-skilled’ roles, meaning that they will have employees who are able to work across a number of areas instead of just one.\r\nAs a Multi-skilled Vehicle Collision Repair apprentice you will train as an auto repair technician in the collision repair industry, repairing and restoring a range of passenger and light commercial vehicles to their pre-accident condition. You will learn how to identify and remove mechanical, electrical & trim components; assess the level of damage and repair/replace panels as appropriate; and prepare and paint the required areas of the vehicle to the manufacturers’ specification.\r\nAdvanced apprentices will work at a more senior level. After further training and development you may have the opportunity to progress into a range of jobs, such as workshop controller, bodyshop manager or service manager.\r\nFor vacancies in the retail motor industry visit www.autocity.org.uk','Level: Intermediate (Level 2), Advanced (Level 3) ','Job roles: Multi-skilled auto repair technician','Issuing Authority: The Institute of the Motor Industry – www.motor.org.uk','NEW','','','Starting salary (once qualified): £13,000–£15,000');
INSERT INTO `apprenticeship_types` (`id`,`apprenticeship_type`,`description`,`job_role`,`qualification`,`salary`,`created_at`,`updated_at`,`sector_id`,`print_title`,`print_description`,`print_qualification`,`print_job_role`,`issuing_authority`,`new`,`revised`,`higher_apprenticeship`,`print_salary`) VALUES (215,'Animal technology','<p>Want to work with animals and their welfare? Do you have an interest in scientific and bio-medical research? An Apprenticeship in Animal Technology could be for you.</p><p>Research using animals provides vital information in the development of new drugs and treatments for both humans and animals. Each year in Britain three million animals are used in authorised scientific procedures in over 200 approved research establishments that include pharmaceutical companies, teaching hospitals, universities, veterinary colleges, specialist research organisations and animal breeding companies.</p><p>Apprentices work as animal technicians in areas such as the husbandry and care of animals, hygiene and bio-security, and animal welfare.<br></p>','Animal technician','Level 2 (Int)','Around £12,000','2013-11-25 11:50:32','2013-11-25 11:50:32',12,'Animal technology','If you have a genuine interest in working with animals and their welfare, as well as an interest in scientific and bio-medical research, an Apprenticeship in Animal Technology could be for you.\r\nResearch using animals provides vital information in the development of new drugs and treatments for both humans and animals. Each year in Britain three million animals are used in authorised scientific procedures in over 200 approved research establishments that include pharmaceutical companies, teaching hospitals, universities, veterinary colleges, specialist research organisations and animal breeding companies.\r\nYour roles as an apprentice will vary according to the needs of your employer, but you will probably find yourself working as an animal technician in areas such as the husbandry and care of animals, hygiene and bio-security, and animal welfare.\r\nAfter completing your Apprenticeship, you might have the opportunity to progress onto a level 3 Diploma in Laboratory Animal Science and Technology and become eligible to apply to becoming a licence holder.\r\nTo carry out research using animals, organisations have to be licensed by the Home Office and the industry works closely with various animal welfare organisations to promote good practice in the care of all laboratory species. Everyone in the industry works hard to ensure that the guiding principles of reduction, replacement and refinement are met so that the number of animals used in research is minimised, non-animal alternatives are used whenever possible and that all animals are looked after properly and any pain or distress is kept to a minimum.','Level: Intermediate (Level 2)','Job role: Animal technician',' Issuing authority: Lantra – www.lantra.co.uk','','25/11/13','','Starting salary: £12,000');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (1,1,'Welcome to the Apprenticeship Guide online','Taking an Apprenticeship could change your life. This site is here to help you. It\'s full of information on what Apprenticeships you can study, how you apply, who offers the Apprenticeships schemes, and much, much more.\r\n\r\nTo get started explore one of the notes opposite.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:29:30','2012-07-20 01:29:58');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (2,1,'What is an Apprenticeship?','Earn while you learn!\r\n\r\nFor many, the later years at school can be frustrating when all you want to do is get out into the world, start working and earn a living. Likewise, if you\'re already working, you may be looking to try something new altogether or to improve your skills and knowledge to help you progress up the career ladder. You may also want to improve your prospects of finding a job in your chosen industry.\r\n\r\nWhether you\'re looking for your first role or are already in employment, Apprenticeships give you the chance to do just that. They enable you to enter or stay in the world of work, earn a decent wage and learn new skills.  An Apprenticeship will offer you amazing opportunities to shine in a job you enjoy.\r\n\r\nApprenticeships mix on-the-job training with classroom learning.  They provide you with the skills you need for your chosen career that will also lead to nationally-recognised qualifications. As an Apprentice you earn while you learn and receive other benefits as well.  Apprenticeships are real jobs for real people.\r\n\r\n','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:31:53','2012-07-20 01:31:53');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (3,1,'Types of Apprenticeship available','Over 150 types of Apprenticeship!\r\n\r\nThere are more than 150 Apprenticeships available in approximately 80 sectors of industry and commerce. These range from nail services to nuclear engineering, seafishing to scaffolding, carpentry to ceramics manufacturing. You can find details of almost all of these in Section Two of the printed Guide.\r\n\r\nTherange is vast and the opportunities are excellent. Whatever industry you decide to pursue a career in, you should be able to find an Apprenticeship that suits you.\r\n\r\nApprenticeship frameworks can be divided into a number of sub-sections:\r\n\r\n• Beauty and wellbeing\r\n• Business and IT\r\n• Charity and volunteering\r\n• Construction\r\n• Creative\r\n• Customer Service\r\n• Energy\r\n• Engineering and electrical\r\n• Finance\r\n• Land-based industries\r\n• Manufacturing and logistics\r\n• Marine\r\n• Public services\r\n• Sport and fitness\r\n• Travel and hospitality\r\n• Vehicles and Transport','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:32:52','2012-07-20 01:32:52');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (4,1,'Levels','There are three levels of Apprenticeship:\r\n\r\nIntermediate Level Apprenticeship\r\nWorking towards work-based qualifications such as an NVQ Level 2, Key Skills and perhaps a learning-based qualification such as a BTEC. The qualifications you receive are equivalent to five GCSEs at grades A–C.\r\n\r\nAdvanced Level Apprenticeship\r\nYou can expect to gain a work-based qualification such as an NVQ Level 3 as well as Key Skills. In most cases you’ll work towards a learning-based qualification such as a BTEC. These qualifications are equivalent to two A-levels.\r\n\r\nHigher Apprenticeship\r\nYou’ll work towards work-based qualifications such as an NVQ Level 4 and perhaps ','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:34:24','2012-07-20 01:34:24');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (5,1,'Why should I do one?','Why should I do one?\r\n\r\nThere are lots of great reasons to do an Apprenticeship, but here are the big ones:\r\n\r\n• Money\r\n• Qualifications\r\n• Training\r\n\r\n\r\nMoney\r\n\r\nYou’ll be working for an employer and earning a salary while you learn. Salaries vary, but apprentices earn an average of £170 per week.\r\n\r\nFunding\r\nWhile you’re on an Apprenticeship, your employer pays you a salary and supports you in your training – most of your learning will happen at work, but some might take place with a training provider.\r\n\r\nFinancial help is available and you won’t have to pay any fees. If you’re between 16 and 18, the Government will pay the full cost of your training (if you’re over 19, your employer may be expected to contribute to your training costs). The funding you’re eligible to receive depends entirely on your circumstances, your employer and the type of Apprenticeship. Don’t worry – your employer will work with you to try and support your individual requirements.\r\n\r\nSalary\r\nThe National Minimum Wage is £2.60 per hour for apprentices under 19, or those who are aged 19 or over but are in the first year of their Apprenticeship. Many employers will pay you more as you develop your skills – the average apprentice takes home around £170 per week.\r\n\r\nIt’s important to remember that completing an Apprenticeship will mean you earn more in the long run – research shows that apprentices earn, on average, around £73,000 more over their lifetime than other employees, and this figure rises to £100,000 for those who have completed an Advanced Level Apprenticeship – you’ll also be more employable than those who leave education without these qualifications.\r\n\r\nOther benefits\r\nAs an apprentices you will receive the same benefits as other employees in the company – this may include pension contributions and subsidised canteen and leisure facilities. You may also be entitled to additional money for essential books, clothing or equipment, or to help you with a disability. You’ll get paid holidays too.\r\n\r\nIn special circumstances there are Learner Support Funds available, depending on your situation, the type of Apprenticeship you are doing, and your age. These vary depending on your employer and learning provider and need to be discussed with them individually.\r\n\r\n\r\nQualifications\r\n\r\nYou’ll gain nationally recognised qualifications that will be valid for any employer. That means you can change jobs and take your skills and qualifications with you.\r\n\r\nAll Apprenticeships include the following elements:\r\n\r\n• A competencies qualification which you’ll need to achieve to qualify for your Apprenticeship certificate. This qualification shows that you are competent in performing the skill,\r\n\r\ntrade or occupation your Apprenticeship requires.\r\n• A technical knowledge qualification to show you have the necessary technical skills, knowledge and understanding of theoretical concepts as well as knowledge and understanding of the relevant industry and its market.\r\n• Either Key Skills (e.g. team-working, problem-solving, communication and using new technology) or Functional Skills to help you achieve a good standard of literacy and numeracy.\r\n\r\nThere are three levels of Apprenticeship:\r\n• Intermediate Level Apprenticeship\r\n• Advanced Level Apprenticeship\r\n• Higher Level Apprenticeship\r\n\r\n\r\nTraining\r\n\r\nWith an Apprenticeship under your belt, employers will know that you’ve got the skills and training needed to do the job and they’ll be more likely to hire you. Taking an Apprenticeship doesn’t restrict you to one specific job role. During your training you’ll pick up a number of skills that will make you more attractive to other employers, from basic skills like teamwork and health and safety awareness, to more specialised capabilities that will help you progress through the industry.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:35:29','2012-07-20 01:35:29');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (6,1,'What are they like?','Doing an Apprenticeship is just like having a real job. Basically, you’ll work alongside experienced members of staff to learn the exact skills needed for your chosen career, whether that’s hairdressing, cooking or engineering. As well as learning on the job, you’ll go to a college or training provider, usually on a day-release basis, to study towards a nationally recognised qualification, such as an NVQ. This gives you the perfect mix of theory and practical learning.\r\n\r\nAll Apprenticeships include the following elements:\r\n\r\nA competencies qualification which you’ll need to achieve to qualify for your Apprenticeship certificate. This qualification shows that you are competent in performing the skill, trade or occupation your Apprenticeship requires.\r\n\r\nA technical knowledge qualification to show you have the necessary technical skills, knowledge and understanding of theoretical concepts as well as knowledge and understanding of the relevant industry and its market.\r\n\r\nEither Key Skills (e.g. team-working, problem-solving, communication and using new technology) or Functional Skills to help you achieve a good standard of literacy and numeracy.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:36:46','2012-07-20 01:36:46');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (7,1,'How long does it take?','There\'s no set time to complete an Apprenticeship as they vary widely in content and size. The length of time taken will depend on the sector choosen, the ability of the individual apprentice and the employer\'s requirements. Apprenticeships typically take between one and four years to complete, depending on the type of framework, so it\'s important that you\'re committed enough to see it through.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:38:07','2012-07-20 01:38:07');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (8,1,'What\'s in it for me?','Give yourself a headstart\r\n\r\nApprenticeships offer high-quality, work-based training programmes and are a fantastic way to launch yourself into a career when you have finished school. They are also a great route for those already in employment to develop or change their future prospects and career.\r\n\r\nApprenticeships are becoming more and more popular. Last year, there were more than 250,000 Apprentices in England alone, training in over 180 different types of Apprenticeship. As you get paid throughout your Apprenticeship you have no worries about paying course fees or student loans.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:38:43','2012-07-20 01:38:43');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (9,1,'Training that\'s useful','Employers all over the country recognise and value Apprenticeships. This is because they demonstrate that you\'ve achieved the skills you need to produce great work. This means that you can develop excellent career prospects, depending on your progress, and go on to be offered a full time role by your employer at the end of your training.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:39:30','2012-07-20 01:39:30');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (10,1,'What can I do next?','When you complete an Apprenticeship, you’ll be able to prove to any employer that you have the required skills, qualifications and dedication to do the job. There’s also the opportunity to progress on to higher education, either part-time or full-time, with your employer’s help and support. An Apprenticeship will also provide you with an edge in the job market, as well as giving you a great sense of personal satisfaction.\r\n\r\nAn Apprenticeship will also increase your chances of gaining a good rate of pay and being promoted. In the long term, you could also proceed to further education – there are many Apprentices who go on to complete degrees.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:40:10','2012-07-20 01:40:10');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (11,1,'What can I expect?','Earn a good wage while you continue to learn\r\n\r\nIf you\'re entering the world of work for the first time, you\'ll start earning a wage from day one of your Apprenticeship. There is no set salary for Apprentices. However, a recent survey showed that the average wage per week for an Apprentice is now around £170, and in some job roles, around £210 per week. This is dependent on your employer and the type of work you do. As your skills develop and you begin to progress, your pay will increase accordingly. Research shows that Apprentices earn, on average, over £100,000 more throughout their lifetime than other employees.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nQualifications\r\n\r\nOn completion of your Apprenticeship, you\'ll have a package of nationally recognised qualifications. That means they will be valid for any employer so you can change jobs and take your skills and qualifications with you.\r\n\r\nYour performance and knowledge is assessed on the job as you reach different levels. These assessments count towards your final work-based qualification, such as a National Vocational Qualification (NVQ), which will be at either  Level 2 or Level 3/4. Examining bodies award these qualifications to make sure there\'s a consistently high level of quality across the nation.\r\n\r\nDepending on the Apprenticeship you choose, you may also study for a technical certificate which will give you further knowledge and understanding of your job. This might be a BTEC Diploma or City & Guilds Award.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll also learn communications, information technology, problem solving, application of numbers and personal skills. These important skills will help you do any job and make you more employable in whatever career path you choose to follow.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nPaid holidays\r\n\r\nLike most employees, you will be given paid holiday and bank holidays.\r\n\r\nYour individual entitlement will be detailed in your terms of employment or training agreement: 20 days is an average holiday entitlement.\r\n\r\nJust like any other job, your employer will have rules about how far in advance holidays need to be booked, and the times that holiday can\'t be taken.\r\nYou may also be able to take some time off for study leave, in addition to your usual paid leave.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nOther opportunities\r\n\r\nMany employers also offer opportunities to get involved in out of work activities including social events, community projects or volunteer programmes.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nSupport during training\r\n\r\nYour employer or training provider will ensure that you have a mentor. Their job is make sure that your training fits your personal requirements, offers the skills needed for the job and meets national standards. They\'ll also be there to help you through any difficult times and answer any questions you may have.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nProspects\r\n\r\nBecause Apprenticeships train you in the skills that employers want, they give you choices in your career.\r\n\r\nWhen you\'ve completed your Apprenticeship you can carry on working, maybe get promoted, or even go on to higher education in a college or university.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:40:46','2012-07-20 01:40:46');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (12,1,'How do I apply?','Visit the \'Find an Employer\' section\r\n\r\nYou\'ll find lots of companies on this website who are looking for apprentices. It\'s a great place to start…\r\n\r\nNational Apprenticeship Service\r\n\r\nThe National Apprenticeship Service (NAS) (www.apprenticeships.org.uk) look after Apprenticeships in England and are good people to contact. You can search for, view and apply for Apprenticeship vacancies across the country through their website, register your details to find out more information, or use their helpline for support and general advice.\r\n \r\nSearch for vacancies online\r\nYou can search for Apprenticeship vacancies by postcode, keyword, occupation type, job role, or learning provider. Click on the ‘Search for vacancies’ link to see what’s available.\r\n\r\nNAS helpline\r\nCall the NAS helpline (T: 08000 150 600) for support using the online vacancy matching service. An advisor will also be able to give you general advice on applications and how to put yourself forward in the best light. The call is free and could lead to your future career.\r\n\r\nEmployer contact\r\n\r\nIf you\'ve found an Apprenticeship within a company that particularly interests you then you can approach the employer directly. Before you contact them, it\'s a good idea to check the company\'s website as answers to the most common questions might be there. Remember that you\'ll be contacting the company as a potential employee so act professional - first impressions are important.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n Finding an employer\r\n\r\nTo find companies offering Apprenticeships, check your local job listings and Jobcentre plus. Local recruitment agencies might also be a good source of advice.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAlready working?\r\n\r\nIf you\'ve got a job, why not ask your employer if they\'d consider taking you on as an apprentice? Point them to the employers\' section of the NAS website - www.apprenticeships.org.uk - for more information.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:41:38','2012-07-20 01:41:38');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (13,1,'Am I eligible?','How to get onto a scheme\r\n\r\nThere are no set entry requirements for Apprenticeships. Apprenticeships are open to anyone over 16 living in England, not currently in full-time education or holding a university degree. Entry requirements are flexible because Apprenticeships are not just based on academic achievement. Employers value your enthusiasm for work and desire to learn, so your practical skills and interest in your chosen area are very important.\r\n\r\nIn order to apply you need to be:\r\n\r\n    • Committed\r\n    • Able to show that you’ve fully researched the area of work you want to do, and you’re the right person for the job\r\n    • Aware of your responsibilities to both yourself and the company who would employ you\r\n    • Prepared for further study\r\n    • Realistic about the amount of work you may have to do\r\n    • Happy to work both as part of a team and an individual\r\n    • Able to use your own initiative\r\n\r\nApprenticeships can be demanding, but very rewarding. It’s not just a question of seeing what’s out there and then selecting your career path. It helps if you’re focused enough to know what you want to do before you apply.\r\n\r\nAccess to Apprenticeships\r\n\r\nIf you are aged between 16 and 24 but not eligible to take on a full Apprenticeship you might be able to join the Access to Apprenticeships programme.\r\n\r\nAs a participant on this programme you would work towards the elements of a full Apprenticeship for up to 6 months before moving to a full paid Apprenticeship – with a contract of employment – once you have demonstrated your commitment to work and study to the required standards. Talk to your careers advisor to find out if you might be eligible.\r\n\r\nEquality and diversity\r\n\r\nApprenticeship programmes are inclusive and must comply with the principles of equality and diversity. They must show that they take an active approach to identifying and removing barriers to entry and progression. Apprenticeships must ensure equality of access for those with a learning difficulty. If there are any legal restrictions that limit entry to an Apprenticeship these must be stated.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:42:34','2012-07-20 01:42:34');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (14,1,'Useful links','Your best friend for this one is of course Google, but there are some other really useful resources out there.\r\n\r\nThe most comprehensive is the National Apprenticeship Service, which has loads of information.\r\n\r\nIf you\'re 19 or under, www.connexions-direct.com is well worth a visit, and can put you in touch with dedicated advisers.\r\n\r\nYou can search for a job at the JobCentre Plus site.\r\n\r\n\r\nDirectgov website\r\nwww.direct.gov.uk\r\n\r\nThe official UK Government website offers loads of useful careers information for young people. On this site you can:\r\n• apply for a Jobseeker’s Allowance\r\n• plan your career using the Next Step service\r\n• build your CV\r\n• search and apply for jobs via Jobcentre Plus\r\n• contact a careers advisor\r\n• and lots, lots more.\r\nThere’s a whole host of advice that might be useful to you, about careers and many other aspects of your everyday life.\r\n\r\nThe Apprenticeship Guide 2012 - printed guide\r\n\r\nThe printed guide is now available to purchase at the price of £29.99 including postage and packing.  Generous discounts are available for multiple copy orders.  To order your copy now contact Jonathan Crawley on tel: 01423 851150 or by email: jonathan@barkerbrooks.co.uk .\r\n\r\nThe Guide is over 300 pages and includes over 50 updated frameworks and a wealth of information on Apprenticeships including case studies and inspiring true stories, together with hints and tips on making an application, CV preparation and contact details of companies offering Apprenticeships.','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 01:43:27','2012-07-20 01:43:27');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (15,2,'Beauty & Wellbeing Apprenticeships','If you are looking for a rewarding and diverse career that can bring you not just glamour and excitement, but the real rewards of hard work and dedication as well, then a job in the Beauty and wellbeing industry may be for you.\r\n\r\nView beauty and wellbeing apprenticeships\r\n\r\nHair, beauty, nails and spa therapy are really diverse professions that can take you virtually anywhere and you could find yourself working in some unusual locations besides a high street salon.\r\n\r\nMany hairdressers and beauty therapists operate as self-employed freelancers, running their own business and visiting clients in their own homes; others find themselves working in spas, health farms, holiday resorts, film and TV sets and even the theatre. Some airlines offer in-flight hair and beauty treatments and most cruise liners will have a hair and beauty salon on board.\r\n\r\nHairdressing services are also required in prisons and on military bases, and both hairdressers and beauty therapists are required in hospitals and care homes to work with people who may be very ill, especially those who are losing their hair through cancer treatment or who need make-up to cover scars, burns and other injuries.\r\n\r\nMany people go on to work in sales, marketing, public relations and photography, while others choose to concentrate on the business aspects of running a salon rather than performing treatments.\r\n\r\nFinally, if you have enough experience, you can choose to go into education, working as a tutor or lecturer in a training centre to pass on your knowledge and skills.\r\n\r\nThe Industry has an annual turnover in excess of £5 billion and employs approximately quarter of a million people across the country.* You will almost certainly have to start at the bottom rung of the ladder and work your way upwards but with hard work, passion and a determination to succeed you will quickly begin to make real progress in your career.\r\n\r\n *Figures supplied by Habia (www.habia.org)\r\n What do I need for a Beauty Apprenticeship?\r\n\r\nHave lots of stamina – you will spend a lot of time on your feet!\r\n\r\n    Be presentable and take care of your own appearance\r\n    Be a good listener and be sensitive to what people want\r\n    Enjoy working with your hands\r\n    Be motivated by doing a job for love not just for money\r\n    Have good time management skills\r\n    Enjoy new ideas and have plenty of your own\r\n','',NULL,1,'2012-07-20 01:52:10','2012-07-20 01:52:22');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (16,2,'Business & IT Apprenticeships','This sector covers the many different occupations that keep businesses running efficiently and profitably, and keep staff and customers happy. Millions of people work in this sector, and your Apprenticeship could lead to a role in a number of different areas within a business.\r\n\r\nBusiness Administration is a popular one, with many jobs at entry level. Administrators do a bit of everything: deal with internal and external correspondence; type up letters, agendas and reports; send emails and faxes; answer phone calls... It\'s no wonder that many upper level staff members rely on the assistance of administrators to do their jobs.\r\n\r\nBusiness Management staff - from team leaders and supervisors up to company directors - make decisions about how to do things effectively and provide leadership. Equally important are human resources (HR), who look after the people who work for the organisation and also help with recruiting and training staff.\r\n\r\nMarketing and public relations (PR) is a method of telling people about your company or product - whether through advertising or sponsorship, publicity stunts or viral videos on the internet. It\'s about attracting customers and keeping them - the foundation of business activity.\r\n\r\nAll of these roles use computers in some way. The IT sector can be divided into two categories: the companies that provide IT solutions - such as web developers - and those that use IT in some form with their business (which is pretty much everyone else).\r\n\r\nMost jobs in this industry are office-based with a typical 9 to 5, Monday to Friday working week. It\'s important to be punctual and presentable, and you\'ll need to be a good team player.','',NULL,2,'2012-07-20 01:53:20','2012-07-20 01:53:20');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (17,2,'Construction Apprenticeships','View Construction Apprenticeships\r\n\r\nConstruction is a multi-billion pound industry that deals with developing the underlying structure of anything from a housing estate to the groundbreaking Eden Project. One in 14 of the UK\'s workforce is employed in construction (that\'s nearly two million people), and the task of building everything needed for the London 2012 Olympics will create approximately 33,500 additional jobs over the next few years.\r\n\r\nApprenticeships are a recognised and valued route of entry into construction. There are 38 different Apprenticeships covering a range of occupations, from groundworks and plant maintenance to civil engineering and joinery. No matter where you start your career, if you have the determination and are ready to work hard, there\'ll be plenty of scope to move up the career ladder. It\'s also worth noting that in the construction industry, more than 35% of people are their own boss and run their own company.\r\n\r\nThere\'s lots to choose from: if you\'re the sort who enjoys physical work, you could help lay the foundations of a 20-storey building; build scaffolding around a famous landmark due for restoration; plaster the interior of an office building; or maintain heavy plant. Those with a flair for organisation could help make sure projects run on time and within budget; liaise with suppliers; or assist a civil engineer with design plans - there are many places to put your creative skills to the test.\r\n\r\nWith a construction Apprenticeship, you could be working on various sites in your region and beyond - there are also plenty of opportunities to work abroad, as many of the largest construction companies operate around the world. Whatever profession you decide to pursue, you can count on the fact that your work will be used and admired by people for years to come. And there\'s always going to be a need for people to build and develop.\r\n\r\n','',NULL,3,'2012-07-20 01:55:40','2012-07-20 01:55:40');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (18,2,'Charities & Volunteering Apprenticeships','View Charities and Volunteering Apprenticeships\r\n\r\nDo you want to make a difference to your community? Does your passion lie with campaigning to make a difference to the society that we live in, not only today but also for the future? Do you want to work for an organisation that helps disadvantaged people? Then an Apprenticeship in the Charity and Volunteering sector could be the perfect opportunity for you. This sector, also known as the voluntary sector, consists of a range of charities and organisations that exist to help the local, national and, in some cases, the international community. Examples of such organisations include, Macmillan Cancer Support, Children in Need, Comic Relief, Unicef and Oxfam. As well as the large charities, over 50% of the sector consists of small organisations that help the local community. For example there may be a small organisation in your area that is helping to regenerate the community, or providing services for disadvantaged people.\r\n\r\nThere is a huge variety of paid employment available and there is currently a demand for Apprenticeships within this sector. New apprenticeships have been specifically developed and tailored for three professional roles within the voluntary sector: Fundraising, Campaigning and Volunteer Management.\r\n\r\nBy undertaking an Apprenticeship within one of these areas you will develop the necessary skills to provide you with a great start in a career within this sector. The skills you learn will also give you the opportunity to work in the voluntary sector permanently, meaning you can play a big part in achieving real changes in society.\r\n\r\nIf you are already employed by a voluntary sector organisation, completing an Apprenticeship will further enhance your CV by recognising your learning and development through nationally accredited qualifications. It also offers you the opportunity to professionalise your job roles through recognised learning.\r\n\r\nThe ability to complete Functional Skills in English, Maths and ICT along with an interest in the work of work of charities, social enterprises or voluntary and community organisations is the only entry requirement for these apprenticeships.\r\n\r\nA career in this sector can be very challenging but at the same time extremely rewarding.','',NULL,4,'2012-07-20 01:56:50','2012-07-20 01:56:50');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (19,2,'Creative, Media & Arts Apprenticeships','The arts world covers everything from film to fashion, music to computer gaming. While it\'s the artists and actors, musicians and models who take centre stage, they wouldn\'t be there without armies of assistants and teams of technicians - just take a look at the number of crew members listed in the credits next time you watch a film.\r\n\r\nThe creative industries are very popular, with lots of competition for job roles. It\'s not easy to walk into your dream job in TV or the fashion industry, so an Apprenticeship can be a great way to get a foot in the door.\r\n\r\nCreativity takes on many forms, and likewise, the creative industry encompasses a broad array of jobs requiring different practices, talents and skills. The Apprenticeships in this section sample a good portion of that range. If you\'re technically creative, then you could be a games tester searching for glitches in new computer games or help rig the lighting for a playhouse. Like working with your hands? Then you could learn how to build sets and stages for film productions, or how to work the machines that manufacture clothing.\r\n\r\nThere\'s also a strong administrative side to this industry, so you could find yourself contributing to the office of a busy record label, helping to promote a live event, or organising member information for a theatre. You could even take on a more socially-engaged role by working for a community arts programme.\r\n\r\nYou\'ll find most opportunities in London and larger cities, but there are openings for creative types in most places. Imagination and a flair for English, art, music or a similar creative subject can help you succeed in the creative industries. But this is also a sector where passion and hard work will get you far.\r\n\r\nDon\'t expect the red carpet treatment right away - long, antisocial hours are not unusual, and the pay is often not great for junior staff. But the work is fun and fulfilling, and you\'ll be working with interesting and creative people.\r\n\r\n','',NULL,5,'2012-07-20 01:57:41','2012-07-20 01:57:41');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (20,2,'Customer Service Apprenticeships','View Customer Service & Retail Apprenticeships\r\n\r\nA well-known rule of business is that it\'s easier to sell to your existing customers than to find new ones. A satisfied customer is not only a good advert for your business, but they\'re likely to buy from you again. An unhappy customer, on the other hand, is not just a customer you\'ve lost - they can also do untold damage to your reputation.\r\n\r\nNo wonder, then, that a whole field has grown up devoted to keeping customers happy. In a small shop, customer service can be as simple - and important - as the person behind the counter giving a friendly greeting and helping shoppers find what they\'re looking for. Larger businesses and other organisations might employ a dedicated customer service team, whose job it is to answer questions, give advice and offer refunds on faulty products or services. They\'re also the ones who have to sort out problems and deal with complaints.\r\n\r\nCustomer service often involves dealing with the public face-to-face, but as many companies now have clients all round the world, telephone call centres and computer helpdesks are becoming increasingly important.\r\n\r\nAs well as serving their existing customers, businesses need to find new ones - and to persuade them to buy things. This is where sales comes in - salespeople persuade customers to buy products or services, and the business they bring in keeps the customer services team busy.\r\n\r\nCustomer service is at the heart of most business activity, so the skills gained from the Apprenticeships in this section will prove valuable across a range of industries and roles.','',NULL,6,'2012-07-20 01:58:46','2012-07-20 01:58:46');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (21,2,'Energy & Power Apprenticeships','View Energy Apprenticeships\r\n\r\nThe essential energy and utilities sector covers the generation, transmission, distribution and supply of electricity; the transportation, distribution and supply of gas; the collection, purification and distribution of water; waste management and the collection and treatment of sewerage; and nuclear fuel processing. The Apprenticeships in this section provide entry routes into all of these areas.\r\n\r\nKeeping gas, electricity and water supply in check isn\'t easy. By nature, gas hates being in an enclosed space and is always looking for a place to escape. A gas leak could potentially cause an explosion, so anyone working with this substance needs to be highly skilled - any mistake could have serious consequences.\r\n\r\nThis section also features two Apprenticeships in the growing nuclear industry, which produces roughly 20% of the electricity in the UK. The provision of nuclear power and the safe decommissioning (or closing down) of the UK\'s older nuclear power plants both rate highly on the government agenda. This sort of work involves skills that are transferable to other sectors within this industry, as well as engineering.\r\n\r\nThe many roles in this sector require people with all sorts of skills. Practical roles like pipe fitting, line repair and cable jointing are in high demand, as are plant operatives. There\'s also a large administrative and commercial side to the industry.\r\n\r\nEvery household and company in the country has an electricity bill to pay - that\'s a lot of customers to look after, and a lot of administrative work. All the major supply companies have large contact centres to deal with areas like customer service and sales.\r\n\r\nApprenticeships are a popular method of entry into this sector, and many of today\'s managers and supervisors were once apprentices. Also, much of the skilled workforce is now approaching retirement age, which means excellent career prospects when you qualify.','',NULL,7,'2012-07-20 01:59:38','2012-07-20 01:59:38');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (22,2,'Engineering & Electrical Apprenticeships ','View engineering and electrical apprenticeships\r\n\r\nWe live in a world constantly in motion: electricity fizzing around at the speed of light along power lines, through cables into billions of light bulbs and motors, industrial machines and household appliances. Voices babbling down telephone lines and over the radio waves. Gas pumping through pipes into ovens and heaters. Water gushing from taps and cisterns, down drains and into sewers. Computers spinning webs of data while moving pictures bounce off satellites onto TV screens.\r\n\r\nIt\'s a wonder it doesn\'t descend into absolute chaos. That it doesn\'t is thanks to a legion of skilled people making sure their part of the system functions as it should - the plumber mending a broken pipe to the team of electricians wiring up an office block to an engineer servicing a broken escalator.\r\n\r\nThe engineering and electrical sector is all about making things work. It\'s a huge field, so you\'ll specialise in a particular area. For example, few Apprenticeships offer as many diverse pathways as the engineering Apprenticeship - you could be demolishing buildings, servicing escalators, checking RAF aircraft or activating phone lines for BT - and that\'s just the start of a long list of opportunities.\r\n\r\nOne thing is certain: you\'ll need to be good with machines, whether your specialism is fixing faulty DVD players in a local electrical store, or maintaining the machinery in a factory. You\'ll often need to be good with people, too - you might be going into somebody\'s home to fix their fridge or to stem the flood in their bathroom.\r\n\r\nManual and technical skills are important in this sector, and maths, IT and science are often relevant. You need to be good at following instructions and working as part of a team, but engineers in particular often need to use their own initiative to solve problems.\r\n\r\nProspects are good in this sector. And while there are many large firms on the lookout for skilled employees, a lot of electricians and plumbers are self-employed and run their own companies. If you think you can combine your manual and mechanical skills with a head for business, there\'s a healthy living to be made.','',NULL,8,'2012-07-20 02:00:33','2012-07-20 02:00:53');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (23,2,'Finance & Accounting Apprenticeships ','View finance apprenticeships\r\n\r\nThey say that money makes the world go round, and in many ways they\'re right. Almost every business is set up in order to make money, and making money is not something that happens automatically - it requires careful planning and constant attention.\r\n\r\nCompanies big and small need teams of people to look after their finances: monitoring who they need to pay, who owes them money and so on. They need people to help them sort out their tax bills and make sure all their employees get paid on time, while making them as profitable as possible. Those finance experts are, generally speaking, people with good organisational skills and a good head for numbers.\r\n\r\nAnd, of course, it\'s not just businesses that need help with their money. From the student taking out a loan to cover tuition fees, to the entrepreneur putting on a festival, to the retired person claiming their pension, everyone needs financial help and advice at some stage. And it\'s employees in banks, accountants and insurance companies who offer that help. Again, people working in these roles are organised, and good with numbers. But it\'s equally important to be good with people and enjoy the challenge of helping others achieve their financial goals.\r\n\r\nBy choosing to do an Apprenticeship in this area, you\'ll have made a shrewd financial decision. You\'ll be working towards a qualification that should see you earn a higher salary in the future. And instead of running into debt - as you\'d be likely to do if you stayed in full time education - you\'ll be earning while you learn.\r\n\r\nNot only will you be qualified to help other people manage their money, you\'ll also find it easier to manage your own. And as a great many jobs in the finance sector come with a higher-than-average salary, you could find yourself, quite literally, in the money.','',NULL,9,'2012-07-20 02:01:48','2012-07-20 02:01:48');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (24,2,'Agricultural & Land-based Industries Apprenticeships','View Agricultural and Land-based Industries\r\n\r\nThe land-based and environmental industries play a key role in both the national and global economies. In the UK alone, the sector is worth more than £8.9 billion per year, and employs over a million employees and 500,000 volunteers. It\'s a profitable sector, but that\'s only part of it - this industry improves quality of life here in the UK by supplying us with food, producing crops, enriching the rural and urban environment, and protecting our natural heritage.\r\n\r\nLand-based and environmental industries can be broken down into three major categories: land management and production, animal health and welfare, and environmental industries. There are a wide variety of jobs in the sector, and most of them are practical, requiring physical effort and work outdoors.\r\n\r\nPeople you will find in the field include general farm workers, gardeners, fencing contractors, tree surgeons and gamekeepers. There are also creative occupations available, such as floristry; as well as caring jobs that include working for animal welfare charities, as a veterinary nurse, or at a kennels or cattery. In addition, there are more technical roles on offer, such as land-based engineering, and many management opportunities.\r\n\r\nThe Apprenticeships in this section cover 17 different disciplines, from land-based engineering to veterinary nursing. Each of these industries offers the chance to develop skills in practical, technical and specialised areas with opportunities for career progression. And if you\'ve always wanted to run your own business, then this could be a good place to start - today, more than half the people in the workforce run their own business.','',NULL,10,'2012-07-20 02:02:42','2012-07-20 02:02:42');
INSERT INTO `articles` (`id`,`type_id`,`title`,`small_content`,`full_content`,`article_type`,`discipline_id`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (25,1,'Find an Apprenticeship','You can find out more about the different industry sectors by clicking the links on the left., or go directly to the employers by clicking on the following links. Remember, anyone featured on this site wants to hear from you!\r\n\r\n    Agricultural and Land Based Industries\r\n    Beauty and Well Being\r\n    Business and IT\r\n    Construction\r\n    Charities and Volunteering\r\n    Creative, Media and Arts\r\n    Customer Service and Retail\r\n    Energy\r\n    Engineering and Electrical\r\n    Finance\r\n    Health, Care and Public Services\r\n    Manufacturing, Processing and Logistics\r\n    Marine\r\n    Sport & Fitness\r\n    Travel and Hospitality\r\n    Vehicles & Transport\r\n\r\nContact the Sector Skills Councils if you want more information on working in their field - they\'re responsible for raising the profiles of the industries they represent:\r\n\r\n    http://www.sscalliance.org/Home-Public/SectorSkillsCouncils/SSC_Contacts.aspx\r\n','',NULL,0,'2012-07-20 02:04:30','2012-07-20 02:04:30');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (1,'Lantra','12','Lantra','Set up for a career in agriculture','Arable Apprentice Leon Ayres started working on a small farm near his home after leaving school','“I enjoyed it so much that I decided agriculture was what I wanted to do,” says Leon, who went on to secure a job on a farm he saw advertised in Farmers Weekly magazine. As the farm was based in Bedfordshire, relocation was involved, but this didn’t deter Leon.\r\nThe farm specialised in producing onions and was much bigger than the one he had worked on after leaving school.\r\nLeon gained several qualifications while working on the farm, including Pesticides, Rough Terrain Telescopic Lift Truck, Emergency First Aid at Work and Manual Handling. “Most of these were achieved at work through my employer and some of them through college. Training and certification was viewed as very important by my employer,” he explains.\r\nIn 2011 Leon met the owner of a Lincolnshire-based arable farm that specialises in potatoes. “The owner was interested in taking me on as an arable apprentice and I decided that this would be a good opportunity to continue my education and work on a highly mechanised farm,” he says. He decided to enrol at Bishop Burton College in order to undertake the Apprenticeship, which he saw as an ideal way of enhancing his skills, employability and knowledge.\r\nLeon is responsible for maintaining equipment and operating it according to soil conditions. He also acts as relief potato planter operator when the primary operator takes a break.\r\nThere is a variety of key skills required for the role accordingly to Leon. “Listening is especially important, because much of our work is complex and undertaken alone so it is important to know and remember all the tasks that need doing,” he says. “Good timekeeping is also vital. I have to use my own initiative and I must be able to solve minor problems on my own, such as repairing machinery. Communicating with other employees is important too.”\r\nLeon has some useful advice for anyone wishing to pursue a similar career path: “Do not be put off by moving to get the job that you want. Moving 150 miles for me was a challenge but it set me up for my career in agriculture,” he concludes.\r\n','www.lantra.co.uk/careers','','','','Lantra_logo_web.png','Lantra CS photo_Leon Ayres','2013-11-19 14:11:01','2013-12-12 11:22:42');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (2,'Bishop Burton College','12','Bishop Burton College','Transferable experience and qualifications','Matthew Harling, 18, is working towards a Level 3 Advanced Apprenticeship in Land-based engineering operations','Matthew went straight into employment after school, but his Apprenticeship has enabled him to gain qualifications at the same time. He is employed by Windsor Materials Handling and is the winner of a City & Guilds’ Medal for Excellence.\r\n\r\nWhy did you choose Bishop Burton College?\r\nThe course relevance was the main reason as I wanted to gain land-based knowledge, not just engineering. The College also has excellent learning facilities where you can get experience with a variety of machines. My brother recommended it after studying here and it’s in a nice location in the countryside.\r\n\r\nWhat are your plans for the future?\r\nMy father was a Royal Marine and I’ve always been inspired to follow him. I am partway through the application process and want to work on the helicopters as part of the aviation team. My engineering qualifications and experience with machinery will be transferable and I’m looking forward to learning even more on the job.\r\n\r\nHow would you describe your Bishop Burton College experience?\r\nIt’s been great, I’ve enjoyed coming to College. The facilities are constantly being improved and updated and my tutor has been knowledgeable and very supportive. I’ve also had flexible support with my maths from other departments. I’ll keep in touch with my tutor and the lads from my course in the future.\r\n','www.bishopburton.ac.uk','','','','Bishop_Burton_College_web.png','Bishop Burton College CS photo_Matthew Harling','2013-11-19 14:15:47','2013-12-12 11:24:45');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (3,'Riseholme College','12','Riseholme College','Hands-on training in horticulture','Rebecca Gillatt, 18, took on a Level 2 Intermediate Apprenticeship in Horticulture','After successfully gaining qualifications in history, media and psychology at sixth form in Retford, Rebecca decided she would like to focus on a more practical form of training and decided to pursue a career in horticulture. She secured an Apprenticeship position with the Gelder group based in Sturton-by-Stow near Lincoln.\r\n\r\nWhy did you choose Riseholme?\r\n“Gardening has always been a hobby of mine, but I wanted to apply my skills practically and on a larger scale. The mixture of theoretical and practical learning appealed to me, as well as the opportunity to qualify on the job.”\r\n\r\nWhat are your plans for the future?\r\n“I love my new vocation and the variety of challenges it brings. One day I’d like to be a head gardener and be able to pass on my knowledge to another apprentice.  My next step will be to progress onto an Advanced Apprenticeship at Riseholme to develop my management skills and theoretical knowledge.\r\n\r\nHow would you describe your Riseholme experience?\r\nThe Apprenticeship was rewarding from the start as I started gaining qualifications in the first few months, such as first aid and Plasma training. Then I went on to get others, including chainsaw and spraying qualifications. I enjoy the hands-on, practical learning. I am interested in learning more about conservation and ecological developments that can benefit the company and surrounding countryside.\r\n','www.bishopburton.ac.uk/riseholmecollege','','','','Riseholme_college_web.png','Riseholme College CS photo_Rebecca Gillatt','2013-11-19 14:18:17','2013-12-12 11:26:06');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (4,'Leeds City College','12','Leeds City College','Great learning programme down on the farm','Emma Stanworth is working towards a Level 2 Animal Care Apprenticeship','An Apprenticeship has enabled Emma Stanworth to pursue her passion for animals while getting valuable on-the-job experience.\r\nEmma, 18, is completing an Animal Care Apprenticeship with Leeds City College at Howden Clough Farm, an on-site facility at Batley Girls’ High School where she was a student.\r\nThe college works with the school as part of its school careers programme, and felt an Apprenticeship would be the perfect opportunity for Emma to develop her skills, improve her maths and literacy, and help her progress.\r\nThe farm, which has school and community links, houses chickens, ducks, quails and two milking goats as well as having horticultural elements including allotments and flower beds.\r\nEmma, who is following an animal care programme, has helped to build the provision up with a practical focus on animal husbandry while working with students to encourage their interest and involvement.\r\nEmma says she likes the fact that she can learn at a pace which suits her and has help from a college representative if and when she needs it.\r\n“An apprenticeship means that I’ll have a national qualification and practical work experience to help me gain employment in the future,” she adds. “I would recommend this course to anyone who thinks they would like a career in this sort of work.”\r\nFarm Manager Malcolm Firth says: “The Apprenticeship is a valuable resource and has helped Emma develop her animal husbandry skills while improving academically through working on her key skills”.\r\n“The college has worked well with the school to provide a fantastic learning programme at the right pace and level for Emma,” he adds.','www.leedscitycollege.ac.uk','','','','LeedsCityCollege_LOGO.png','Leeds City College CS text_Emma Stanworth','2013-11-19 14:22:35','2013-12-12 11:32:03');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (5,'Paragon','13','Paragon','Michelle is a cut above the rest','23-year-old Michelle O’Connor has traded working with race horses to follow her dream career in hairdressing & barbering, a passion she has nurtured since leaving school','Michelle decided that hairdressing was the route she wanted to take after training with Paragon to become a hairdresser after she completed her GCSEs.\r\nIn October 2012, she felt that having gained the practical skills she required she was now ready to start her own business and opened Dapper Chaps, a retro traditional barbers shop in Weymouth. She is now training another member of her staff as she recognises the benefits to her business as well as to her employee.\r\nMichelle says: “I began training with Paragon when I was 16. The programme has been incredibly flexible and has allowed me to work at my own pace. I cannot praise the hairdressing Apprenticeship enough, it has taught me so much and the experience I have gained is so different and more in-depth than anything I would have learnt at college.\r\n “My business is really taking off and I am still continuing my training with Paragon as I am now doing my Level 3 in Hairdressing.” \r\nGordon McCaul, Hairdressing Assessor for Paragon, adds: “Throughout her training, Michelle has proved to be enthusiastic, motivated and a team player. She is doing exceptionally well and I am proud of what she has achieved in starting up her own business which is no mean feat.”\r\n','www.paragonskills.co.uk','','','','ParagonLogo.png','Paragon_Beauty & wellbeing CS photo_Michelle','2013-11-19 14:27:24','2013-12-12 12:43:08');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (6,'Northumberland College','13','Northumberland College','A golden future for Calum','Top hairdressing apprentice Calum Hall has proven he is a cut above his fellow students by winning gold at a national hairdressing competition at Blackpool for the second year running','Calum, who has just completed an Advanced Apprenticeship in Hairdressing at Northumberland College, won the Level 3 Skills heat, after winning the Level 2 ladies commercial cut and blow dry round last year.\r\nThe 19-year-old had to keep calm under pressure to colour, cut and blow dry a daytime style, before curling and backcombing to create an evening style within the allocated time. \r\nCalum says: “The competitions have given me the opportunity to practise my skills and come up with new and unique styles, and they motivate me to work to the best of my ability.\r\n“Apprenticeships are a great way to learn as you get hands-on experience in a salon while learning the theory at college; it’s the best of both worlds.”\r\nThe competition, which was organised by the Association of Hairdressers and Therapists and held at Blackpool Winter Garden’s Hair Festival, saw entries from professionals and students from across the country.\r\nCalum is now a fully qualified hairdresser and is working full-time as stylist, building up his own client base.\r\nAnyone interested in hairdressing or Apprenticeship courses should visit the Northumberland College website.','www.northumberland.ac.uk','','','','Northumberland_logo.png','Northumberland College CS text_Calum Hall','2013-11-19 14:30:13','2013-12-12 12:42:12');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (7,'Intraining','13','Intraining','Turning heads','18-year-old Tayla Murdy, is currently training as an Apprentice Hairdresser at The Venue Salon in Ashington, Northumberland\r\n\r\n','Having completed her NVQ Level 2, Tayla is now studying towards a Level 3 qualification with national training provider Intraining.\r\nNot only is Tayla doing well in her Apprenticeship but she recently won the Matrix Destination Fame Competition (College Category) which is open to any hairdresser in the UK and Ireland.\r\nTayla’s winning entry was voted for exclusively online, enabling her to fast-track straight to first prize with a style that was born from a desire to create a fashionable, head-turning look.\r\nShe will now get to experience a Year of Fame with Matrix, ensuring her career is set firmly in the direction of her dreams. This includes mentoring by some of hairdressing’s most innovative and iconic names and assisting on a big-budget photo shoot.\r\nTayla says: “I was overwhelmed when I found out that I had won the competition. The experience and mentoring I will gain as a result will really help me in my hairdressing career. Ultimately I would like to be the best I can be, recognised nationally for my hairdressing skills.”\r\n','www.intraining.co.uk','','','','Intraining_logo_web.png','Intraining CS photo_Tayla Murdy','2013-11-19 14:32:49','2013-12-12 12:41:06');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (8,'Wigan & Leigh College','13','Wigan & Leigh College','Best of both worlds','Nicole Davies is a Level 2 Beauty Therapy apprentice at Wigan & Leigh College','Fresh out of high school, 16 year old Nicole didn’t waste any time in securing her first job as a beauty therapist apprentice in a very busy salon.\r\nNicole has always had a keen interest in beauty, hair and make-up and has known for a long time that this is what she wanted to do for a career.\r\nHaving the best of both worlds with an Apprenticeship is the ideal situation for Nicole. Nicole says: “I love being in the beauty salon and dealing with real clients. Being in a working environment every day is the best possible experience I could have. I am really enjoying learning new techniques at Wigan & Leigh College and really look forward to going each week.”\r\nNew techniques and treatments are regularly introduced, so continual learning is a given in the beauty sector to keep up with the changes in demand. The Level 2 in Beauty Therapy will provide Nicole with a great start to her career and ambitious Nicole plans to continue learning and hopes to progress onto the Level 3 course next year.\r\nNicole hopes to secure a full-time role when she completes her Apprenticeship and really hopes to have her own salon one day.\r\n','www.wigan-leigh.ac.uk','','','','Wigan_and_Leigh_web.png','Wigan & Leigh College CS photo_Nicole Davies','2013-11-19 14:35:49','2013-12-12 12:44:17');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (9,'Baltic Training Services','1','Baltic Training Services','IT’s a promising area to work in','Anthony Quinn, 19, from Capgemini, has successfully completed a Level 3 IT Professional Apprenticeship with Baltic Training Services','“I started off in college doing electrical engineering as I originally wanted to become an electrical engineer,” says Anthony. “I spent two years at college and felt at the end of my course that I had not really learnt much. I decided the only way to get a decent job was to do an Apprenticeship. While waiting for the right Apprenticeship opportunity to come along I spent some time temping in an office and worked in a bar for a few months. Finally I found what I was looking for in the Capgemini IT Apprenticeship Scheme.\r\n“I have grown up with electronics and computers, and my best friend’s dad built computers and worked at Capgemini so I knew a fair bit about the company. This Apprenticeship looked like one of the best schemes around, and I felt it would give me a good start towards a career in IT.\r\n“I can now write batch files, network and have the ability to understand what people are talking about in computing to an advanced level. I have also learnt how to troubleshoot problems with computers and repair them.\r\n“I gained a permanent job with Capgemini following my Apprenticeship with Baltic Training Services. I am currently employed in the software packaging side of the organisation. This is a promising area to work in and there are plenty of opportunities to expand my capabilities and progress my career. This is exactly what I hope to do.\r\n“I felt fully supported by Baltic Training Services in my Apprenticeship role. When I needed any help it was there for me, or when I had any questions or support requirements, they would find me the answer and support me in gaining more knowledge.\r\n“I would definitely recommend an Apprenticeship to others.”\r\n','www.balticapprenticeships.com/apprentice-experiences','','','','Baltic_Training_Services_web.png','Shutterstock image','2013-11-19 14:40:18','2013-12-12 11:40:25');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (10,'Birmingham City University','1','Birmingham City University','Apprenticeship has paved way for higher education programme','David Cowling is taking an Apprenticeship in Leadership and Management with Birmingham City Business School','David Cowling joined Coventry & Solihull Waste Disposal Company (CSWDC) in 2008 with little experience in the waste industry. He quickly got into his stride and developed a real flare for innovative ways of looking at the waste industry. This led David to reconsider his career goals and make changes in his job direction. There was, however, one obstacle in David’s plan and that was his lack of real management know-how and gaps in his depth of knowledge. It was at this point that he decided to take up a Level 3 Advanced Apprenticeship programme in Leadership & Management followed by an ILM Level 5.\r\nDavid has never looked back and has progressed his job role with promotion to a project manager position. David has great ambitions to go all the way to the top and realises that without further qualifications to go with his growing experience then his advancement may well be blocked or hindered. After completing the ILM Level 5 he plans to move onto a higher education programme with Birmingham City Business School leading to a work-based degree in Leadership & Management Practice.\r\nDavid is Lead Project Engineer for a ground-breaking project to convert waste into a heat source to benefit Coventry Cathedral, Coventry Library and local Council buildings. “This is an exciting and challenging time at CSWDC and I’m confident that completing the Higher Apprenticeship degree will stand me in excellent stead to play a key role as part of our project team.”\r\nBirmingham City Business School offers a progression route for learners onto a Higher Apprentice degree.\r\n','www.bcu.ac.uk/balmp','','','','BCU_web_1.png','Birmingham City University CS photo_David Cowling','2013-11-19 14:43:46','2013-12-12 11:42:06');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (11,'Birmingham Metropolitan College','1','Birmingham Metropolitan College','Working his way up with Weslyan','Steven Jones took a Business Administration Apprenticeship at Birmingham Metropolitan College','Not everyone that studies A-levels wants to go to university. Steven Jones decided he wanted to achieve his ambition of working in finance and insurance in a different way.\r\nAfter searching the National Apprenticeship Service website, Steven, who is now aged 20, discovered that Weslyan Assurance Society, a financial services organisation, had vacancies available.\r\n“I felt that taking an Apprenticeship would allow me to learn just as much as if I was going to university – and I would be earning as well,” explains Steven who had studied A-level accounts, computer science and maths.\r\nTwo-and-a-half years on, he has gained an NVQ Level 2 in Business Administration from Birmingham Metropolitan College, and was named as one of Wesylan Assurance Society’s Elite Performers at their 2013 staff conference.\r\nDuring his time as an apprentice, Steven worked in an administration role in the Private Clients team in Wesleyan’s General Insurance business. After qualifying, he was taken on as a full-time permanent member of staff, with his role developing to include reporting and programming.\r\nSteven was the youngest person ever to become a Wesleyan Elite winner. He is now doing a Chartered Insurance Institute course and is considering doing a part-time university degree in maths or computer science.\r\nHe adds: “There are members of the Wesleyan Executive team who have worked their way up through the business, so that shows there are definitely a lot of opportunities to build a successful career here.”\r\n','www.bmetc.ac.uk','','','','BirminghamMet_logo.png','Birmingham Metropolitan College CS photo_Steven Jones','2013-11-19 14:48:26','2013-12-12 11:43:28');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (12,'Blackburn College','1','Blackburn College','Range of study options','Jennifer Smith, from Longridge in Preston, works as a Service Desk manager at MITIE PFI Ltd and has completed a Level 3 NVQ in Business and Administration with Blackburn College','Jennifer’s involvement with Blackburn College’s Apprenticeship scheme has given her the opportunity to further her skills and knowledge for a career in business management. She works as a Service Desk manager at MITIE PFI Ltd, part of MITIE Group PLC, who specialise in strategic outsourcing and energy services. Having already completed a Level 3 NVQ in Business and Admininstration, Jennifer will be on the college’s Apprenticeship scheme for a year, further developing her management skills.\r\nJennifer comments: “I manage our PFI Service Desk team, which is responsible for providing world-class customer service to clients at over a hundred schools/health centres nationwide. We log, update and co-ordinate all aspects of our self-delivered facilities management package. The team consist of 13 people and the Apprenticeship scheme is a great way to further develop the skills I need to use every day”.\r\nJennifer was supported every step of the way by the assessing team at Blackburn College who offer a range of study options to fit in with the apprentices’ working schedules.\r\nSandra Martland, business development manager at the college, says: “It’s really satisfying to see our apprentices develop and watch them progress in their new careers.”\r\nJennifer chose just one of the many Apprenticeship frameworks available at Blackburn College – with over 40 to choose from, there is something for everyone!\r\n','www.blackburn.ac.uk/apprenticeship','','','','Blackburn_College.png','Blackburn College CS photo_Jennifer Smith','2013-11-19 14:57:09','2013-12-12 11:45:00');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (13,'Cambridge Regional College','1','Cambridge Regional College','Hospital visit led to dream opportunity','Sophie Burdass lost her voice but found an Apprenticeship when she visited hospital – starting her on the path to her dream job in nursing','The 18-year-old sixth former became Cambridge Regional College’s record 3500th apprentice currently in training when she spotted an Apprenticeship stall during a hospital visit.\r\n“I didn’t know much about Apprenticeships until then,” says Sophie. “I was at sixth-form college, studying sociology, psychology and health and social care, but the traditional way of learning wasn’t really suiting me so I thought a more hands-on approach would be better.”\r\nThe college, one of the region’s major providers of Apprenticeships, introduced Sophie to some current apprentices to find out more – and shortly afterwards she joined Cambridge University Hospitals as an administration apprentice.\r\nSophie, whose ambition is to be a nurse, says: “I love being an apprentice – it’s a great way to start work and I’m getting loads of experience.”\r\nEventually, she hopes to work in the NHS as a nurse and plans to start an Access to Nursing course in her own time – using the experiences gained during her Apprenticeship to help her to reach her goals.\r\nCambridge Regional College runs Apprenticeship programmes in a wide range of sectors including Science, Engineering, Management, Business Administration, Construction and Health Care.\r\n','www.camre.ac.uk','','','','cambridge-regional-college.png','Cambridge Regional College CS photo_Sophie Burdass','2013-11-20 10:43:18','2013-12-12 11:46:23');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (14,'Capgemini','1','Capgemini','Exhilarating career progression','Jack Eker, 20, is working towards a Capgemini Higher Apprenticeship and recently won a regional 2013 Apprentice of the Year title at the National Apprenticeship Awards','“While considering university courses and job opportunities I came across the Higher Apprenticeship scheme,” says Jack. “The combination of a university course while undertaking a full-time job seemed like the perfect path for me! The reason I applied to Capgemini was my passion for IT and computing, plus I found the idea of working for a global company exciting.\r\n“I love the way everybody on the project teams is so helpful and supportive; superiority and rank never hinder progress. And if there is something someone more senior than you can help with, they will always step in to support if required. Whatever project you are working on is always a challenge but it gives you an avenue to demonstrate your skills. Within Capgemini you are never short of opportunities to develop and to learn cutting-edge technologies making career progression simple, interesting and exhilarating.  \r\n“My role is to help deliver bespoke software solutions for large clients and I’ve thoroughly enjoyed working as part of a large team to get a job successfully completed on time. Based on my rapid development I have now been promoted and am trusted with a position working as a software engineer on a technology at the forefront of the UK Government ICT strategy.\r\n“I am passionate about my Apprenticeship and being an apprentice has helped me a lot: I have the learnt the skills to do my job, I am gaining work experience, I have a great salary and in addition Capgemini is sponsoring my degree, so I’m definitely all set for the future.\r\n“Winning the South Central Higher Apprentice of the Year Award feels fantastic. I am not only immensely proud of myself but also Capgemini for helping me to get this far by providing such a leading edge higher apprenticeship scheme. I hope to take what I have achieved and use it to encourage young people to take the apprenticeship route.”\r\n','www.uk.capgemini.com/apprenticeships','','','','Capgemini_Logo.png','Capgemini CS photo_Jack Eker','2013-11-20 10:48:16','2013-12-12 11:48:29');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (15,'Holts Academy of Jewellery','1','Holts Academy of Jewellery','Real skills that employers need','Connor Clark, 18, is a Level 3 Business Administration apprentice','“After studying IT and Business at another college, I saw the opportunity for a Business Administration Apprenticeship at Holts Academy (now the Academy for Creative Enterprise) and I saw it as an excellent opportunity to start my career.\r\n“I didn’t want to go to university, and Apprenticeships give you real work experience so you earn while you learn, rather than taking on a big loan. For me it is a good way of getting to practise what I have learned already and also learn the real skills that employers need, especially skills such as learning how to deal with people and working to deadlines.\r\n“I enjoy the responsibility I am given and this is all helping me to decide what I would like to do in my future career. As the business administration apprentice at the Academy for Creative Enterprise I am responsible for reception and answering the phone – meeting and greeting lots of different people, from students to business leaders. I am also practising my database skills, research skills and general administration skills.\r\n“I am enjoying the variety of the work and learning in a working environment, these are the real day-to-day abilities that employers want. I hope to eventually go into the hotel trade, I would like to be a concierge or front of house manager and I think that the skills I am learning at the Academy will make me much more employable.”\r\n','www.holtsacademy.com','','','','Holts_Academy_of_Jewellery_logo_web.png','Holts Academy CS photo_Connor Clark','2013-11-20 10:52:27','2013-12-12 11:51:56');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (16,'Just IT','1','Just IT','Hands-on experience and up-to-date technical training','Zubar Sarwar works as an IT Apprentice for OPM through IT Apprenticeship provider Just IT','Zubar started his Apprenticeship at the age of 18 after completing A-levels in IT, maths and graphics at college.\r\nZubar has always been passionate about information technology: “IT has been part of my life for as long as I can remember,” he says. “I enjoy building PCs and learning about the latest hardware and software packages. After researching the best ways of entering the IT industry I decided on an IT Apprenticeship rather than university because I could gain real hands-on experience while taking the technical training. I decided that I didn’t want to take on the debt of university and I was worried that by the time I graduated the technologies I had learned would be out of date.”\r\nZubar works as an IT apprentice on the IT Helpdesk and his responsibilities include supporting employees with their IT issues, either over the phone or at their desks.\r\n“I enjoy my job,” adds Zubar. “As it’s a small company, I get the opportunity to try a range of technologies and work on advanced projects.”\r\nAs part of Zubar’s Apprenticeship he has passed his CompTIA A+ certification and completed Microsoft training in Windows 7 & Server 2008, as well as working towards a City &Guilds level 3 qualification.\r\nZubar’s career ambition is to set up his own IT support company and give opportunities to other apprentices.\r\n','www.justIT.co.uk','','','','Just_IT_logo_web.png','Just IT CS photo_Zubar Sarwar','2013-11-20 10:56:58','2013-12-12 11:55:58');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (17,'Newcastle City Learning','1','Newcastle City Learning','Valued member of the team','Carl Gibson, 19 is a Business Administration Apprentice with Fenham Hall Medical Practice, Newcastle','Like many young people today, Carl Gibson was looking for a route into employment. Many employers are looking for people with relevant work experience which cuts out a lot of young people looking for their first job. \r\nCarl says: “I was told about Apprenticeships when I was at school. An advisor was talking to us about different career paths and Apprenticeships were suggested as an alternative to the higher education route. When I left school I contacted Newcastle City Learning and I did some assessments with them so they could get an idea of my skills and abilities, which they used to help me find suitable Apprenticeships to apply for. When I saw the position for Fenham Hall Medical Group, Newcastle City Learning helped me prepare me for the interview.”\r\nCarl started off with tasks such as photocopying and filing, which he soon mastered, and went on to train as a receptionist. In addition to this he has used his IT knowledge to help improve the practice’s website.\r\nCarl is now six months into his role and Helen Gunn, Practice Manager for Fenham Hall Medical Group, has seen considerable growth of confidence in their apprentice: “Carl is almost unrecognisable from the timid young man who joined us six months ago, and through his hard work, enthusiasm and willingness to learn he has become a valued member of our team.”\r\nCarl’s hard work was rewarded when he won Newcastle City Learning’s Apprentice of the Year 2013 award.\r\n','www.newcastlecitylearning.co.uk','','','','NewcastleCityLearning_web.png','Newcastle City Learning CS_Carl Gibson','2013-11-20 11:12:24','2013-12-12 11:57:43');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (18,'Paragon','1','Paragon','Taking control of her finances','Abigail Taylor, 18, has always enjoyed dealing with money and has always been very organised – an Apprenticeship in Business Administration while working as a trainee financial administrator was her dream job','Abigail is working towards a Level 2 Apprenticeship with a company called Involve Visual in Warrington. After leaving Sixth Form College where she completed her A-levels, she was keen to research the Apprenticeship scheme and what it could offer her.\r\n“I found Paragon through the website of the National Apprenticeship Service. It had a lot of great information on what programmes were available and how to apply,” says Abigail.\r\n“I loved the fact that I could earn a salary at the same time as working towards a recognised qualification. I really enjoy working in finance. I sit in an office of 70 and my day-to-day responsibilities include dealing with invoices and any relevant enquiries.”\r\nAbigail’s line manager comments: “Abigail has been a breath of fresh air at Involve Visual. The company is dynamic and forward thinking, offering visual collaboration solutions to a wide variety of industries, so we need energetic and sparky team members like Abigail to reflect this. In my experience Apprenticeships ultimately lead to increased employee engagement and greater productivity. I can’t recommend Apprenticeships enough.”\r\nAbigail concludes: “I have definitely made the right decision to get on the career ladder with an Apprenticeship and I am excited about the future and where this qualification can take me.”\r\nFor further information please visit the Paragon website or call 0800 783 2545.','www.paragonskills.co.uk','','','08007832545','ParagonLogo.png','Paragon CS photo_Abigail Taylor','2013-11-20 11:18:36','2013-12-12 12:01:18');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (19,'Positive Outcomes','1','Positive Outcomes','The power of positive thinking','Kirsty Mead is working towards an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Business Administration','Kirsty, 19, landed an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Business and Administration, and thanks to Positive Outcomes she is relishing her role within the estate agency industry.\r\n“My local Connexions pointed me towards Positive Outcomes and that is how I found my current role; I knew I wanted an office-based job and this one suited my interests.\r\n“Positive Outcomes arranged an interview for me and gave me advice and coaching for the interview process.\r\n“The role appealed to me because I’m a practical learner, so I find it a lot easier to learn while doing my work and I also think it makes it easier to fit in with my day-to-day jobs, as Positive Outcomes adopted the best learning approach that was most suited to me.\r\n“I’m really enjoying it and I’ve noticed improvements in my work throughout my time here. I would really recommend this method of learning to anyone who finds it easier to learn new skills through practical work.”\r\n','www.positiveoutcomes.org.uk','','','','positive_outcomes_web.png','Positive Outcomes CS photo_Kirsty Mead','2013-11-20 11:21:03','2013-12-12 12:06:09');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (20,'Remit Ltd','1','Remit Ltd','All systems go','Sam Hopwell, 20, is an apprentice IT Technician','“I have worked with Plumtree Group in Keyworth since I started my Apprenticeship,” says Sam. “We provide IT systems, software and support to a variety of industries, particularly the healthcare sector.\r\n“I work on the company’s support desk and help to resolve clients’ IT issues, which puts my IT skills to the test daily and helps me to continually increase my knowledge and experience. In addition I look after the company’s internal network, making sure all our own systems are running smoothly.\r\n“Ever since starting with Plumtree Group I have been encouraged to get involved and learn as much as I can from my boss and colleagues. In fact my employers have held extra training sessions with me, on top of my training with Remit’s IT Academy, to help integrate me into the specifics of the business from the start.\r\n“I used the knowledge and experience I picked up while at work, as well as the technical training I received from Remit, to make my own mark on the company from an early stage.\r\n“Since starting I have been working with the support desk team, which means I am continually supporting our clients with their day-to-day IT problems, but have also set up a brand new network management system, which has made a huge difference to the way we work.\r\n“I believe I have been of great help to my boss, Richard Morris, who was originally covering the support desk on his own, which didn’t give him a lot of time to do much else. Now that we are both covering support I feel that between us we have been able to manage our internal network better and it has allowed us to spend more time with customers so we can resolve any issues in a much more efficient manner.”\r\n','www.remit.co.uk','','','','Remit_IT_Academy_logo_web.png','Remit CS photo_Sam Hopwell','2013-11-20 11:24:04','2013-12-12 12:07:42');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (21,'Shipley College','1','Shipley College','Time management skills essential','Louis Gornall, 18, from Tong, is working for Bradford District Care Trust in the HR department\r\n','Having completed his Intermediate Apprenticeship in Business & Administration, Louis has recently progressed to the Advanced Apprenticeship.\r\n“I enjoy going to work to learn instead of being sat in a classroom five days a week,” says Louis. “But it is hard meeting deadlines for college and I have had to learn to juggle my time efficiently. However the college do also offer a great level of support and advice whenever I need it.\r\n “I have really enjoyed the Apprenticeship and, once finished, plan on working full time either at BDCT or in another administration role.\r\n“I would definitely recommend others to consider an Apprenticeship as an option to gain crucial experience while learning.”\r\nAnd who better to vouch for Louis than his mentor at Bradford District Care Trust? Irene Angelosanto is the Workforce Establishment Co-ordinator and liaises between the college, the apprentices and their managers.\r\n“Louis is gaining valuable skills to take forward into his chosen career. The Apprenticeship offers a solid grounding for future employment.”\r\n','www.shipley.ac.uk','','','','shipley_college_web.png','Shipley College CS photo_Louis Gornall','2013-11-20 11:26:43','2013-12-12 12:09:32');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (22,'Sussex Coast College Hastings','1','Sussex Coast College Hastings','Let’s Do an Apprenticeship','Jay Hancock, 20, started her Apprenticeship qualification in Advanced Business and Administration in November 2011, and is due to complete in November 2013','Jay has secured a role as Training Administrator at the Let’s Do Business group while studying for the qualification through the Apprenticeship scheme at Sussex Coast College Hastings. \r\nJay was an Advanced Apprentice with Hastings Trust on a training programme funded by the college. The training gave Jay a detailed understanding of the Apprenticeship process and the confidence to take on the new challenge.\r\nStephen King, Training and Skills Manager at Let’s Do Business comments: “We are very proud to be able to offer Jay a full-time role as the business and opportunities continue to grow.”\r\nTim Scott, Head of Business Development congratulated Jay on her success to date, adding: “Our partnership with local employers is essential to help improve employability of our young people. We are focused on working with local partners to give other students, like Jay, the opportunity to develop in line with the needs of the business and community around Hastings.”\r\nJay says: “It is great to use the skills I have developed on my training programme to good effect. I am able to talk confidently to potential apprentices and explain in detail what an Apprenticeship really means. To me there was no better way to learn by doing, and getting paid to learn was a real bonus.”\r\n','www.sussexcoast.ac.uk','','','','Sussex_Coast_College.png','Sussex Coast College Hastings CS photo_Jay Hancock','2013-11-20 11:31:11','2013-12-12 12:11:19');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (23,'Training 2000','1','Training 2000','Icing on the cake','A 26-year-old former apprentice from Blackpool has launched her own cake shop after completing an Apprenticeship in Business Administration with Training 2000','Sarah Mitchell and her mum, Karen, a trained cake decorator, launched Karah’s Kakes after undertaking an Apprenticeship to help her develop her administration skills.\r\nNow Sarah has completed the qualification and has the skills and confidence to follow her ambition to run her own business.\r\n“My mum has been decorating cakes from our home for the last eleven years and she’s been so busy lately, we felt that now is the time to take the plunge,” says Sarah.\r\n“I had never been very good at planning my workload and my organisation skills left a lot to be desired, but that’s all changed thanks to my Apprenticeship, and the course has really opened up my eyes to the opportunities out there.\r\n“I’m much more confident now and I wouldn’t have been able to write the business plan for Karah’s Kakes had it not been for the things I have learnt in my Apprenticeship.\r\n“We’re both really excited and can’t wait to get cracking. We’ve had a lot of forward orders and, although I am nervous, I’m really looking forward to it. It’s a great feeling to be getting this business off the ground.”\r\nSarah has plans to recruit her own apprentice in the coming months which illustrates how worthwhile investing in training can be.\r\n','www.training2000.co.uk','','','','t2000_web.png','Training 2000 CS photo_Sarah Mitchell','2013-11-20 11:39:00','2013-12-12 12:15:48');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (24,'Truro and Penwith College','1','Truro and Penwith College','Fast forward to a career in marketing','Andrew Pidgeon, aged 18, is a Marketing apprentice with Truro and Penwith College','Andrew started the Level 3 Marketing Apprenticeship in January 2013, working for Truro and Penwith College Business.\r\nAfter completing college, Andrew took time out to decide what to do as he felt that university wasn’t the right route for him. While searching for jobs he stumbled upon Apprenticeships and decided this was the best option for him because of the progression opportunities that an Apprenticeship can offer. \r\n“Before starting the Apprenticeship I thought that it would take me much longer than it has to adjust to a business environment,” says Andrew. “However, everybody helped me settle in, making me feel comfortable to come forward with ideas and have the confidence to participate in meetings and discussions”.\r\nAndrew organises events, creates flyers, updates the website and creates case studies and is a highly valued member of the team. Remarkably, he has received national praise for a report written just three weeks into his Apprenticeship.\r\nAndrew intends to progress his career in Marketing by completing his Apprenticeship. “When I finished college it felt like my development had ground to a halt, but I now feel that my career is really moving forward. The appeal of an Apprenticeship is that it allows you to find a career that you want, whilst gaining the all important work experience and portfolio that employers will be looking for as they recruit.”\r\nFor more information on Apprenticeships contact Laura Dennis on 01872 242718 or email businesscentre@truro-penwith.ac.uk\r\n','www.truro-penwith.ac.uk','','businesscentre@truro-penwith.ac.uk','01872242718','TPCBusiness_colour_logo.png','Truro & Penwith College CS photo_Andrew Pidgeon','2013-11-20 11:48:50','2013-12-12 12:17:29');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (25,'Virgin Media','1','Virgin Media','Ready for the next challenge','Aranjeet Nirwan, 22, joined Virgin Media as an intermediate apprentice training as an installation and service technician','“I spent my first couple of weeks understanding what Virgin Media did by visiting different departments,” says Aranjeet. “At first there seemed to be a lot to take in but as I progressed through my Apprenticeship the time spent with other departments helped me to know who to call for support when I came across something new.”\r\nAfter graduating, Aranjeet was keen to continue in his career and was soon learning again when he was successful in joining the Advanced Apprenticeship in civil engineering and compliance.\r\n“I loved what I was doing and I was ready for another challenge. As a technician I gained a good understanding of our network and relating architecture. In my new role I am responsible for inspecting faults and damages and ensuring all work is carried out to the highest level including any reinstatement.\r\n“I love the variety of work I am involved in; one day I can be on a building site, the next day I can be in a meeting with council officials. The experience I have gained through both of my Apprenticeships with Virgin Media has helped me gain the knowledge I need and confidence to deliver my best at all times.”\r\n','careers.virginmedia.com/apprentices','','','','Logo_Virgin_Media_web.png','Virgin Media CS photo_Aranjeet Nirwan','2013-11-20 11:51:36','2013-12-12 12:19:06');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (26,'Vision Apprentices','1','Vision Apprentices','Insight into the working world','Olivia Harbor, 19, took an Advanced Business Administration Apprenticeship with Vision Apprentices','Having studied her A-levels at West Nottinghamshire College, Olivia enrolled on an Advanced Business Administration Apprenticeship. The scheme is designed to build the next generation of administrators at the college and is studied over two years.\r\nOlivia went straight to the second year in September 2012 and was offered a position at the college as HE and International Advisor and completed the NVQ in Advanced Business Administration.\r\nShe says: “I was involved with co-ordinating events and voiced my ideas to the team on social media. I also created an HE blog along with innovative marketing strategies to get students interested.\r\n“I then got a placement in the marketing team which involved going out to schools to give presentations and developing a Facebook page from new applicants. I also created promotional material for the Apprenticeship scheme.\r\n“I’m so glad I chose the Apprenticeship route because it’s helped develop me and I’ve had an insight into the working world. An obvious benefit is being paid and getting a qualification while you’re working but I think my Apprenticeship was more than that; it helped justify that I could do anything I put my mind to.\r\n“The Apprenticeship has helped enhance my IT and communication skills and introduced me to a lot of people whom I can learn from. Most importantly, I feel comfortable with my decision and have no regrets about taking this route.\r\n“I’m now looking into studying the CIM marketing qualification, an NVQ in Social Media and graphic design or interactive media.”\r\n','www.visionapprentices.co.uk','','','','Vision_Apprentices_Logos_web.png','Vision Apprentices CS text_Olivia Harbor','2013-11-20 11:55:27','2013-12-12 12:20:44');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (27,'YH Training','1','YH Training','Progression is the key to success','Kayleigh Jones is currently undertaking an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Business Administration and is employed at a local driving school, Around the Bend','“I didn’t want to go onto College after leaving school as I knew it wasn’t for me, says Kayleigh. “I got some good grades but not in English, which I knew would let me down when applying for jobs. I contacted YH Training Services and joined their Traineeship. They were really supportive, helped me plan what I needed to do, not just to get a job, but a job with training which means I get paid to learn and develop. I initially started with my Level 2 functional skills in English together with employability skills, this included the best way to create a CV, and how to search and apply for jobs, and gave me the knowledge, skills and confidence to prepare and attend interviews. I felt really motivated and enthusiastic about the whole process, YH have got a way about them that make you feel supported and they instil confidence.\r\n“I applied for a position with a regional driving school who were looking for an apprentice administrator. I was nervous at the interview but was really pleased when they offered me the job. I speak with customers, liaise with the driving instructors on a daily basis, send out letters and emails, use the database to input and update information and book driving tests. The job has got a lot of variety and I’m really enjoying it.\r\n“My trainer says I’m doing really well and making great progress on my qualification. My employer is really happy with my work, my increased confidence and that the training through YH Training Services is geared around what our office does, not just any generic office. I’ve progressed from a YH Traineeship to an Intermediate Apprenticeship and there’s no stopping me, I’m looking to take higher qualifications with YH and see how far they can take me.”\r\nTo find out more about Apprenticeships and vacancies, call Debbie on 0800 542 2848 or email her at debbi@yh-group.co.uk.\r\n','www.yh-group.co.uk','','debbi@yh-group.co.uk','0800 542 2848','YH_Training_logo_web.png','YH Training CS photo_Kayleigh Jones','2013-11-20 11:58:57','2013-12-12 12:22:34');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (28,'Fairtrain 1','3','Fairtrain','Hailing Heyder’s pioneering year','Heyder Rashid has been able to kick start his career in Fundraising thanks to an Apprenticeship offered by Fair Train with Rathbone UK','Heyder Rashid has certainly made his mark in the world of fundraising. During his Apprenticeship, he has been researching and helping to write bids, and organise local cash-raising events for disadvantaged young people. This inspirational apprentice has also played a huge part in piloting the new arts and drama project, Intermix, which is being rolled out nationwide.\r\n “My job advisor said I had the right personality to work with people,” says Heyder.\r\nAnd how right they were! Heyder is now on the organisation’s Equality and Diversity Steering Group, and involved in a new National Apprenticeship Forum. Never one to shy away from an opportunity, he has become a skilled and well-respected member of the Rathbone team.\r\nHeyder is looking forward to a career in either e-fundraising or consultancy for charities. He has this advice for all aspiring Apprentices: “If you see a post advertised that you like – go for it. I looked at the Rathbone job 10 times before I even applied, because I just didn’t think I’d get it. You just never know what will happen. I’m here now and really enjoying it.”\r\n','www.fairtrain.org','','','','Fairtrain_logo_web.png','Fairtrain 1 CS photo_Hailing Heyder','2013-11-20 12:15:58','2013-12-12 12:46:33');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (29,'Fairtrain 2','3','Fairtrain','Kelle’s rewarding Apprenticeship with a Yorkshire children’s centre','Kelle has been able to combine her job as a volunteer co-ordinator with her desire to learn skills and gain qualifications through an Apprenticeship offered by Fair Train and Rathbone UK','Kelle Myers works as the volunteer co-ordinator for the Yorkshire Children’s Centre based in Huddersfield, West Yorkshire. They provide a wide range of services for children, young people and families, most of which require volunteer support. They also operate a number of charity retail outlets, which also utilise volunteers.\r\nKelle was made aware of the opportunity to undertake an Apprenticeship in Volunteer Management by Fair Train, the Group Training Association for the voluntary sector, and Rathbone UK, a national charity that helps young people to transform their lives through learning.\r\n“I was very keen to undertake the qualification as I could see how it could directly relate to my job role,” says Kelle. “I’ve found it very beneficial, particularly in developing my skills around formalising policies and procedures in relation to volunteers, and generally helping me develop my managerial skills”.\r\nKelle was one of the first in the country to complete this new framework, which was developed in conjunction with the Skills Third Sector, after a comprehensive consultation period that established the specific training needs within the charity sector.\r\n“I would recommend anybody in a similar role to undertake an Apprenticeship,” says Kelle.\r\n','www.fairtrain.org','','','','Fairtrain_logo_web.png','Fairtrain 2 CS photo_Kelle Myers','2013-11-20 12:18:57','2013-12-12 12:47:33');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (30,'Bexley College','2','Bexley College','Building up experience and qualifications','David Fry is working towards a Level 3 NVQ in Brickwork at Bexley College','Bexley College offers a full range of construction Apprenticeship courses that are taught at the purpose-built Holly Hill campus, dedicated solely to the construction trades.\r\nCurrent student David Fry first enrolled on an NVQ Level 2 Brickwork Apprenticeship in 2010 with the full support of his employer, Lee Marley Brickwork Ltd, based in Uxbridge, Middlesex. Even though David was already employed, he wanted to further his qualifications and develop new skills relevant to his current trade. Both David and his employers saw Bexley College as the place to make this happen.\r\nAfter completing his Level 2 qualification David moved onto the NVQ Level 3 to further enhance his skill set and enable him to work at a supervisory level and gain an industry-recognised qualification. The course allows David to study one day a week at the college and be assessed in his workplace.\r\n“I was already employed at Lee Marley and wanted to get more qualifications, so they suggested Bexley College as the place to do that,” explains David. “The course is very good and definitely worth doing.”\r\nThe course has opened up many doors for David and allowed him to participate in industry competitions; he came second in both the regional heats of the ‘Guild of Bricklayers’ and in the senior stream of the regional ‘Skillbuild’ competition.\r\nBrickwork lecturer Steve Jenkins comments: “David achieved a well-deserved second place in the Skillbuild competition. Keeping up with tradition, Brickwork have gained a place in the competition every time we enter!”\r\nOn completion of his course, David plans to stay at Bexley College and complete an HNC Level 4 qualification in Built Environment in order to study Surveying.\r\n\r\n\r\n','www.bexley.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'Bexley College – David Fry 1, 2 or 3','2013-12-12 12:56:16','2013-12-12 12:56:16');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (31,'Burton and South Derbyshire College\r\n','2','Burton and South Derbyshire College','Another trophy for bricklaying apprentice','Michael Wood, 19, is undertaking an Intermediate Construction Building – Trowel Occupations Apprenticeship at Burton and South Derbyshire College','Michael recently added to his growing collection of achievements, when he walked away with the winner’s trophy, a set of tools, plus a cash prize at the Guild of Bricklayers East Midlands Regional Competition in Nottingham. The competition is organised and judged by members of the Guild of Bricklayers, who also donate the prizes.\r\nMichael had won a previous heat of the competition, which was hosted at the Burton and South Derbyshire College (BSDC) South Derbyshire Campus earlier in the year. The Swadlincote site was chosen by the Guild of Bricklayers, owing to the state-of-the art construction facilities which provided an ideal competition environment.\r\nAfter winning the regional competition, Michael narrowly missed out on a title at the national finals in Cardiff. He was competing in the Level 3 competitions, which is a massive achievement for a Level 2 apprentice!\r\nMichael says: “It has been a great experience and one that I shall remember all of my life. I would like to thank BSDC for all the support they have given me, with a big thank you for my tutor Ricky Banks, who nurtured both my practical skills and the belief in myself to do well. It has been great.”\r\nRicky Banks, BSDC Construction Course Leader, adds: “Michael performed excellently and I’m extremely proud of what he has achieved this year. He has been a credit to himself and to the College. Well done Michael!”\r\nVisit the Burton and South Derbyshire College website to view the range of Apprenticeships on offer.','www.bsdc.ac.uk/apprenticeships','','','',NULL,'Burton & South Derbyshire College CS text_Michael Wood','2013-12-12 12:58:59','2013-12-12 12:58:59');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (32,'Leeds College of Building','2','Leeds College of Building\r\n','Sparking off a great career\r\n','Josh Derry has completed an Advanced Apprenticeship in Electrical Installation','Josh joined Leeds College of Building in 2010 when he started an Apprenticeship with Shepherds Engineering Services (SES). He always knew when he left school that he wanted to do something hands on and after a lot of research he decided that an Apprenticeship was the best option for him, as he could earn money while learning.\r\nHis role as an electrical installation apprentice involves installing new electricity equipment to the correct specification and location shown on the plans. It can include wiring, terminating and installing cable containment. Josh has worked on big projects including Drax Power Station and Archbishop Sentamu Academy.\r\nJosh has taken part in various skills competitions and recently won the northern regional final of the SkillELECTRIC competition. He came out on top after 12 competitors went head-to-head in a task to install conduit and trunking with three electrical circuits. Judges awarded Josh with the most points against tough criteria including accuracy, quality of work and health and safety.\r\nHe was also selected as the Electrical Installation Apprentice of the Year at the College Award Ceremony due to his hard work and commitment with his studies.\r\nJosh says: “My Apprenticeship with SES has benefited me massively as I have been lucky enough to progress through my exams at college while working, enabling me to put the theory into practice. I want to continue working for SES as there are great opportunities available to progress my career including supervisory and engineering roles.”\r\nTo find out more about the Apprenticeships available at Leeds College of Building call 0845 129 7857 or email info@lcb.ac.uk.','www.lcb.ac.uk/apprenticeships','','','','Leeds_College_of_Building_logo_100x100.png','Leeds College of Building CS photo_Josh Derry','2013-12-12 13:02:40','2013-12-12 13:02:40');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (33,'Lovell\r\n\r\n','2','Lovell','Apprenticeship gave Mark the confidence to become a management trainee','Mark Rimmer, 27, Quantity Surveyor joined Lovell in 2002 as an apprentice joiner, following in the footsteps of his father, uncle and brother who all work in the construction industry','Mark applied for an Apprenticeship with Lovell while they were undertaking refurbishments locally to where he lived in Liverpool.\r\nDuring his time as an apprentice Mark worked on new build and refurbishment projects in Liverpool and across the North West. This included working on a landmark project, The Way in Beswick, East Manchester where he was part of an award-winning site team, building 550 new homes constructed using a structural insulated panel system, the largest scheme of its kind at the time.\r\nFollowing attainment of an NVQ Level 2 and NVQ Level 3 in Carpentry and Joinery, Mark was selected for Lovell’s Management Trainee Programme.\r\n“My experience as a Lovell apprentice was fantastic,” says Mark. “It was a great introduction to carpentry and the industry. In my case it really prepared me and gave me confidence to make the jump to being a management trainee.”\r\nMark’s success has continued with his further promotion to Assistant Quantity Surveyor and to Quantity Surveyor in 2012, the year he celebrated 10 years of service with Lovell. He has most recently achieved his membership to the Royal Institute of Chartered Surveyors.\r\nMany Lovell Apprentices go on to complete an Advanced Apprenticeship and to HNCs and degrees.','www.lovell.co.uk/careers','','','','Lovell_Colour_Logo_100x100.png','Lovell CS photo_Mark Rimmer','2013-12-12 13:07:19','2013-12-12 13:07:19');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (34,'South Gloucestershire and Stroud College','2','South Gloucestershire and Stroud College','Shaun gains confidence through bricklaying Apprenticeship','Bricklaying may be very different to graphic design but Shaun Hatcher is getting stuck in and is increasing in confidence; the 23-year-old is currently training as a Trowel Occupations apprentice','Shaun grew up in Spain. He lived there with his family for 11 years and spent five years working as a graphic designer.\r\nWhen he returned to England two years ago, he quickly started a job as a labourer with a local building company, S&C Bennett Construction.\r\nEager to help his development and keep him as an employee, the construction firm from Gloucestershire allowed Shaun to undertake an Apprenticeship so he could develop his skills in a working environment while studying for recognised qualifications at South Gloucestershire and Stroud College.\r\nShaun comments: “Bricklaying is very different to graphic design but I really enjoy it. I like the company I work for, the people I work with and the hands-on nature of the job.\r\n“Having the opportunity to develop in the trade and get recognised qualifications has helped my confidence and made me more determined to succeed. The support I am receiving from both my employer and college tutor is helping me to become more competent. I would recommend Apprenticeships to anyone looking to gain work-based experience with qualifications and the opportunity to earn a salary.”\r\nGlyn Hillier, lecturer at SGS College, says: “It is great to see employers identifying the skills needs of their workforce and supporting them through Apprenticeship schemes just as S&C Bennett Construction have done with Shaun.”\r\n','www.sgscol.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'South Gloucestershire and Stroud College CS photo_Shaun Hatcher','2013-12-12 13:20:18','2013-12-12 13:20:18');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (35,'Vision Apprentices','2','Vision Apprentices','Apprenticeship builds foundation skills','Hayley Waterhouse, 18, is a construction apprentice with Vision Apprentices','Hayley Waterhouse left school with five GCSEs and a burning desire to become an interior designer or architect.\r\nThe chance to apply for a place on a unique scheme run by Vision Apprentices provided the opportunity she had been looking for.\r\nHayley says: “I found I really enjoyed being creative; I just wasn’t sure how I’d get into the world of design or architecture. Somebody from Vision Apprentices told me about a programme called the ‘Summer Job Shop’ and I thought I had nothing to lose in applying and trying something different over the school holidays.”\r\nThe three-week scheme prepares young people for employment through workshops and provides the chance to meet employers who are looking to recruit new talent.\r\n “I was really pleased to be selected and over the three weeks took part in interview-preparation workshops, and learnt how to put together a good CV,” adds Hayley. “The council then offered me the chance to try painting and decorating at their housing depot.\r\n“I really enjoyed the tasks they gave me and it made me think of my long-term plan to become an interior designer. I realised I needed the foundation skills in decorating before pursuing that any further.”\r\nHayley’s commitment and conscientious attitude paid off when she became one of five participants to secure an Apprenticeship at the council, which she started in September 2011.\r\n “I’m glad I discovered more about Apprenticeships,” she says. “It’s turned out to be one of the best moves I ever made.”\r\n','www.visionapprentices.ac.uk','','','','Vision_Apprentices_Logos_100x100.png','Vision Apprentices CS photo_Hayley Waterhouse','2013-12-12 13:23:09','2013-12-12 13:23:09');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (36,'City of Bristol College','20','City of Bristol College','Marketing apprentice shows potential to go far','Oliver Paton, aged 18, is a Marketing Apprentice (Level 2) at City of Bristol College','Oliver Paton found that the school environment did not really encourage his learning potential. After doing some research, he discovered that a career in marketing was something that sparked his interest and he successfully applied to become City of Bristol College’s first Marketing apprentice.\r\nThrough hard work and determination, Oliver quickly showed his talent and passion, demonstrating a fantastic level of confidence in dealing with new tasks and people at all levels. His day-to-day role sees him involved in college and school events, social media updates, analysis of digital marketing campaigns and the production of posters and flyers.\r\nDuring National Apprenticeship Week Oliver swapped jobs with the college principal, which involved him in tasks such as chairing a senior meeting and meeting VIPs. He was also selected to work with the human resources team to help with the interview/assessment days for senior management recruitment. Shortly after beginning his placement at the College, Oliver’s manager spotted his potential and decided to put him forward for ‘Outstanding Apprentice of the Year’ at The Bristol Post’s prestigious Apprenticeship Awards.\r\nOliver says: “I have learnt so much from this Apprenticeship and it’s been a great experience. I’ve learnt a lot about building relationships with people in a professional working environment. My favourite part of the Apprenticeship, by far, is being treated as an adult and an equal to my colleagues. I’ve developed a passion for Marketing and I can’t wait to start the Level 3 Apprenticeship.”\r\n','www.cityofbristol.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'City of Bristol CS photo_Oliver Paton','2013-12-12 13:30:53','2013-12-12 13:30:53');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (37,'Creative Alliance','20','Creative Alliance','Each project gives more encouragement to work on the next one','Charlie Barrington-Osbourn, 23, took a Level 3 Advanced Apprenticeship in Design with Creative Alliance','“Having completed nearly two years at university I was in limbo between applying for jobs and Apprenticeships,” says Charlie. “I knew people who were doing Apprenticeships, but not in the creative industry. I thought there must be some creative Apprenticeships out there so I searched the Internet and found the www.apprenticeship.gov website, where I applied for the design Apprenticeship position at Trilby.\r\n“During my Apprenticeship I worked on all of the design for Trilby’s internal and client projects, within a small software development team. In the past I’ve worked on small web design jobs but certainly in the last six to eight months my primary focus has been designing and developing user interfaces for some rather large software development projects.\r\n“My Apprenticeship has allowed me to study the theory, learn the practical skills and gain real project experience. Seeing your work being used in the actual environment it was designed for is really rewarding, instead of it sitting in a project folder on your lecturer’s desk.\r\n“I think the best thing has been working on real life client projects and seeing the results from that, because each project gives you more encouragement to work on the next one, and you see an improvement in every project. There’s constant room for improvement and that’s the best thing about apprenticeships.\r\n“I now know exactly what its like in the industry, which has been one of the biggest learning curves I’ve had. I’ve also learned practical skills, how to work within a team, business skills and working alongside real designers and programmers.”\r\n','www.creativealliance.org.uk','','','','Creative_Alliance_logo_100x100.png','Creative Alliance CS photo_Charlie Barrington-Osbourn','2013-12-12 13:34:46','2013-12-12 13:34:46');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (38,'Holts Academy','20','Holts Academy','Dream job in jewellery','Dave Grant, age 24 from Birmingham, attended a Jewellery Manufacturing Apprenticeship at Holts Academy','“I wanted to get into the jewellery industry,” says Dave. “I have always respected the time and effort that goes into each and every piece of jewellery.\r\n“I chose Holts Academy because not only did they give me a chance to find out more about pursuing a career in jewellery but they also helped me brush up on basic skills and knowledge that helped me when going for interviews for companies within the jewellery quarter.\r\n“Currently on the Apprenticeship I have found the whole package very helpful and it has given me the motivation to push myself harder to learn more about each technique within each area of the trade, as well as improving on my own skills that have only appeared since starting the Apprenticeship.\r\n“Being able to work in this industry is amazing but being able to attend the school of jewellery while holding down a full-time job truly is a dream come true.\r\n“I am happy to say I have found my dream job and a job that I am happy with every day no matter what the weather or what time I have to be up because it is worth it. After completing my two-year apprenticeship I plan to aim for higher qualifications so that even more doors will open for me. I want to push myself harder to learn and improve my own skills so that someday I might be able to give someone else the chance that could change their life as much as this has changed mine.”\r\n','www.Holtsacademy.com','','','','Holts_Academy_of_Jewellery_logo_100x100.png','Holts Academy CS text_David Grant','2013-12-12 13:37:27','2013-12-12 13:37:27');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (39,'Vision Apprentices','20','Vision Apprentices','Working towards ideal career plan','Francesca Foster, 20, took a Diploma in Creative and Digital Media with Vision Apprentices','“After applying for interviews with Apprenticeship agencies, my interview with De Agostini was my first one and I got the job straight away. I started my Apprenticeship in May 2012.\r\n“My role at DeAgostini as an apprentice was a marketing assistant and I was also doing graphic design work: designing advertising and promotion images and banners to build their websites to promote their products. I’ve designed backgrounds and promotion images for all the social networking pages such as Facebook and Twitter.\r\n“My Apprenticeship lasted a year and I was assessed both at work and in my training centre. During that time I’ve developed as a person and my skills and knowledge have grown in graphic designing and how to market products. My confidence has increased as I’ve learnt to adapt to how media companies work. \r\n“I love the idea of being an apprentice working and learning at the same time as it’s allowed me to adapt to the working environment I’d love to be in, to enhance and develop new skills while at the same time learning and qualifying for my ideal career plan. Now I have the experience, skills and qualifications all achieved at the same time, which is exactly what employers are looking for. \r\n“I’m delighted to say that after finishing my Apprenticeship, De Agostini have now given me the job as a marketing assistant and I’m looking forward to moving my career onwards and become a highly-skilled graphic designer.”\r\n','www.visionapprentices.co.uk','','','','Vision_Apprentices_Logos_100x100.png','Vision Apprentices CS text_Francesca Foster','2013-12-12 13:40:38','2013-12-12 13:40:38');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (40,'East Riding College','22','East Riding College','Confidence booster','Jessica Young, 22 is a Level 2 Retail apprentice','Jessica Young was one of two employees from her workplace who enrolled on the Level 2 Intermediate Apprenticeship in Retail.\r\nA shop assistant at a supermarket, Jessica was put on the course by her line manager with a view to formalising and improving her skills. She immediately found that the Apprenticeship style of learning was to her liking and she was comfortable going through the competency checks with her assessor.\r\nJessica quickly progressed towards her NVQ in Retail Skills and enjoyed being taught the basics of retail knowledge through her technical certificate, along with her basic skills in maths and English.\r\nShe completed a wide variety of units, including retail legislation, manual handling, customer service, handling stock and processing payments.\r\nShe completed the Apprenticeship to a very high standard and her line manager gave positive feedback, saying she had increased in confidence and her standard of working had improved as a result of the qualification.\r\nJessica says: “I found this Apprenticeship really suited me and helped me to develop my skills, as well as giving me a formal qualification.\r\n“I have earned a lot about rules and regulations that are relevant to retail and feel a lot more confident now I’ve completed it, and I would recommend Apprenticeships as a way of earning qualifications in your work.”\r\n','www.eastridingcollege.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'East Riding CS photo_Jessica Young','2013-12-12 13:49:58','2013-12-12 13:49:58');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (41,'First 4 Skills','22','First 4 Skills','Be the best and reach for the stars','Jemma Oliver is celebrating after being named Apprentice of the Year at the 2013 STF Awards','During Jemma’s placement at Argos one of the managers spotted her potential and advised her of a permanent position that was coming up. Jemma applied and was successful in securing a part-time sales advisor role; soon after she enrolled onto a Retail Level 2 Apprenticeship programme at Argos.\r\n“Doing my Apprenticeship with First4Skills definitely really pushed me and helped me build up my confidence,” says Jemma. “I have gained a wide variety of skills through my Apprenticeship, including generic retail skills and a great overall knowledge of the business I work in, and my manager has seen my confidence, ability and skills increase.”\r\nThrough hard work and determination, Jemma has shown how in these tough times, by pushing herself forward, she has been able to achieve a fantastic career path. She has now progressed onto a Level 3 Retail Sales professional role and is on her way to a successful management career pathway.\r\nWhether you are already employed, currently unemployed and between the ages of 16 and 18, or if you are fresh out of school and feel unprepared to enter the world of work, First4Skills can help you on the right path towards achieving a fantastic career!\r\nIf you would like to be like Jemma and gain a nationally recognised qualification while working, why not get in touch.\r\n','www.first4skills.com','','','',NULL,'First 4 Skills CS photo - Jemma Oliver','2013-12-12 13:52:16','2013-12-12 13:52:16');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (42,'Holts Academy','22','Holts Academy','Shine bright like a diamond','Paige Balman, 20, is taking a Level 2 Jewellery Retail Apprentice with The Beverly Hills Group','“Before I joined Holts Academy of Jewellery as an apprentice I studied for a Level 2 in horse management and gained a national certificate.\r\n“The reason for applying to Holts Academy was because I had an interest in fashion and jewellery and there are not many opportunities to study within the jewellery industry. It was interesting to read what the Apprenticeship had to offer on the website as I had no previous experience in the jewellery industry. I wanted a career which I could learn correctly and from the best companies in the best locations.\r\n“The most unusual and interesting things I have learnt while working at my placement at The Beverly Hills Group, is how everything is worked by hand, computer free. The most difficult thing for me to learn so far is how the wedding rings are priced by working out the weight, metal and if diamonds are set.\r\n“The thing I really love and enjoy most about working in my placement is when a customer has no idea of what they want nor any knowledge about diamonds and settings, and they leave either loving a ring or at least with some knowledge of diamonds and what is best for them and their budget.\r\n“At the moment I would definitely want to continue to study on the Level 3 course. I would be happy to continue to work for Beverly Hills company and gain more knowledge through them as I have learnt a lot in a short amount of time.”\r\nFor more information call Holts Academy of Jewellery on 0207 405 0197.','www.holtsacademy.com','','','','Holts_Academy_of_Jewellery_logo_100x100.png','Holts Academy CS text_Paige Balman','2013-12-12 13:56:52','2013-12-12 13:56:52');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (43,'Intraining','22','Intraining','Teenager Helen has designs on success as tattoo artist','19-year-old Helen Beal is realising her dreams of becoming a tattoo artist after starting her Apprenticeship at Absolute Art Tattoo','Helen is now studying NVQ level 1 in both English and maths, while completing her Apprenticeship in Customer Service.\r\nAt work, she is learning about health and safety, dealing with customers and the traits of the business, while also designing tattoos for customers.\r\nHelen says: “This is my first job since leaving school, but it is the job I have always wanted and I now feel as though I have a future and a purpose. Drawing and designing is my talent, so it’s great that I can put it to use.”\r\nRakesh Kachhela, Employer Engagement Consultant at Intraining adds: “This is a wonderful outcome for both Helen and Absolute Art Tattoo. She has got the job she has always wanted and, through ongoing training and qualifications, can develop it into a great career, while the company has a great apprentice and financial assistance coming their way.”\r\nNeill Forty, owner of Absolute Art Tattoo, recommends that other businesses go to Intraining for advice and support on recruiting and training staff. He says: “Helen is doing fine, so it is working out nicely for both her and us. She is designing tattoos and developing her drawing skills, but we will teach her the art of tattooing later on.”\r\n','www.intraining.co.uk','','','','Intraining_logo_100x100.png','Intraining CS photo_Helen Beal','2013-12-12 14:08:09','2013-12-12 14:08:09');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (44,'Learn Direct','22','Learn Direct','Good prospects for promotion','Mary Thomson is 20 years old and is taking a Retail Apprenticeship with Primark','When Mary Thomson, from Motherwell prepared to leave school she saw others around her struggling to find work.\r\n“When I was due to leave school I went to see the careers advisor. She told me about an Apprenticeship, which would allow me to learn while I earn. I’d seen lots of people leave school and have no jobs to go to so I was very interested. They put me in touch with Primark at Motherwell.\r\n“As I learned new skills I gathered more evidence for my Apprenticeship and started to take on more responsibility – so much so that I now have my own department. I enjoy the responsibility as it builds on my skills and gives me something to look forward to. I feel more independent and confident to make decisions.\r\n“I’ve been amazed by how much support I have received. My colleagues have been great and the learning centre couldn’t have been better. While I was concentrating on my work they were working on my career path to see how I could develop further. They rang me to say that another Primark nearby had jobs available and that I should apply. When I enquired with my line manager, she said they wanted to keep me here, and gave me a permanent position.\r\n“Life is good now. I have a good job and I’m happy. I feel so fortunate to have stepped out of school, into a learndirect centre and into Primark. The support I have received and the qualifications I have gained have positioned me well for any future promotion opportunities.\r\n“To anyone else considering an Apprenticeship with learndirect, I\'d say go for it!”\r\n','www.learndirect.com','','','','learn-direct-new_100x100.png','Learn Direct CS photo_Mary Thompson','2013-12-12 14:12:00','2013-12-12 14:12:00');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (45,'Next','22','Next','Preparation for first management position','Ryan Topping has learnt about team-building and decision-making through the Next Retail Apprenticeship programme','“I joined the Next Apprenticeship programme because it seemed the perfect opportunity to earn some money while training,” says Ryan. “With 30 hours work experience per week, it helped me improve my qualifications and work with lots of different people as part of a great team.\r\n“The programme taught me superb customer service skills and, eventually, I was ready to take on additional responsibilities such as store layouts and supporting new starters with their training.\r\n“Next provide their apprentices with lots of opportunities to develop new skills. I volunteered to support recruitment fairs as an ambassador for Next Apprenticeships and took part in a project to develop new ideas to improve store recycling. Another highlight was the Outward Bounds experience – I learnt about team work and decision-making, from raft racing and climbing ropes, to say nothing of making some amazing new friends!\r\n“My confidence has grown so much over the last year and I’m delighted to have recently progressed onto the Advanced Next Apprenticeship Programme. I’m now learning how to supervise a team, organise rotas, control sales floors and use commercial reports to make business decisions. This will help me prepare for my first management position.\r\n“Next like to recognise achievement and I’ve also been lucky enough to have won a prestigious learning and development prize for the best team coach in the company. This had led to me being nominated in the National Apprenticeship Service Apprentice of the Year Awards 2013.\r\n“If you’re thinking of an Apprenticeship... I’d recommend Next!”','careers.next.co.uk','','','',NULL,'Next CS photo_Ryan Topping','2013-12-12 14:14:03','2013-12-12 14:14:03');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (46,'Positive Outcomes','22','Positive Outcomes','Apprenticeship offers broader experience than college','Hailey Marks-Burton is working towards an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Customer Service','Hailey Marks-Burton, 19, is working as a sales negotiator for a local estate agency while training for an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Customer Service with Positive Outcomes.\r\nHailey, who found the role through Positive Outcomes via their dedicated Apprenticeship website www.paidtolearn.co.uk, is already seeing the benefits of the work-based training. And she has scooped the Sales Negotiator of the Month award for the Norfolk West region.\r\nHailey comments: “It’s been absolutely fantastic. I think Apprenticeships are such a great idea and I believe that what you get out of them is much more valuable than a college course, especially for this type of job.\r\n“I work through a set number of tasks each week and usually complete them while I am at work, as my manager and colleagues are here to offer me advice or answer any questions I might have.”\r\nHailey was keen to try her hand at estate agency having completed two weeks of work experience in the industry when she was at school.\r\nShe adds: “I love meeting and speaking to people and that’s a big part of the job, so it’s perfect for me, and I also enjoy being able to set my own agenda.\r\n“I would definitely recommend an Apprenticeship to other people my age because the experience is much broader than the one you can get at college, and I think the combination of work experience and qualifications can really set you apart.”\r\n','www.positiveoutcomes.org.uk\r\nwww.paidtolearn.co.uk','','','','Positive_Outcomes_logo_100x100.png','Positive Outcomes CS photo_Hailey Marks','2013-12-12 14:17:11','2013-12-12 14:17:11');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (47,'Superdrug','22','Superdrug','A super start in retail','Danielle Blaydon is a Retail apprentice with Superdrug','Danielle started her Apprenticeship with Superdrug in December 2012. She had left school the previous year with no qualifications and had been diagnosed as severely dyslexic. Her manager put her forward for the Apprenticeship as she could see that with a little patience and guidance she had the potential to do well.\r\nDanielle was given extra support from her assessor through one-to-one coaching for her maths and english skills and extra visits. Her manager provided encouragement and support, and helped by making sure she put into practice at work what she was learning from her qualification.\r\nDanielle was very nervous when it came to sitting the tests for her BTEC but she worked hard revising and learning in the store and passed each one first time with flying colours. A methodical and logical approach to her work which really helped her with the multiple choice questions in her key skills tests and she passed them too with very good scores.\r\nHer confidence has grown an incredible amount and even the simplest things like holding a conversation with a customer have become much easier for her; she no longer gets flustered and has really started to excel at what she does.\r\nDanielle completed her Apprenticeship two months ahead of her target end date. Her manager says: “She has improved beyond recognition and she is so much more confident now in everything she does.” When Danielle was asked what she had gained from doing her Apprenticeship she said: “definitely confidence when talking to customers and also my reading and writing have improved, especially my spelling! I really enjoyed it and would like to go on to do more qualifications in future.”\r\n','www.superdrug.com','','','','Superdrug_100x100.png','Superdrug CS text_Danielle Blaydon','2013-12-12 14:20:01','2013-12-12 14:20:01');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (48,'National Grid','18','National Grid','Make employers weak at the knees','James Murphy is working on an Engineer Training Programme with National Grid','“When I finished my AS-levels, lots of my classmates were applying for university. I liked the idea myself, but the thought of being in full-time education for another three years didn’t appeal to me.\r\n“In a lecture one day my tutor showed me a leaflet from a recent careers fair and I saw that National Grid was advertising the opportunity to study for a university qualification in a permanent role earning a good salary.\r\n“In the eight months that I have been with National Grid, I have worked with some truly amazing people, using some incredibly interesting equipment. I’ve worked on some of National Grid’s most vital assets, such as high-voltage 400kV equipment. I have also had experience on operating the Great Britain Transmission Network and met the people who ‘keep the lights on’ in our homes and places of work; observing how truly amazing advanced technology can be when at its best.\r\n“I can honestly say that I am still living a dream, as the reality of the long and prosperous career ahead of me still hasn’t quite sunk in. I have gained valuable and unique skills which will stay with me for life.\r\n“For anyone who is thinking of going to university but is put off by the large fees and loans, I would highly recommend searching for ‘earn whilst you learn’ type employment. You will have an advantage over any graduate searching for a job as you will already have the skills, qualifications and most importantly experience that will make any employer weak at the knees.','www.nationalgridcareers.com/Development-Opportunities/','','','',NULL,'National Grid CS photo_James Murphy','2013-12-12 14:24:09','2013-12-12 14:24:09');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (49,'UK Power Networks','18','UK Power Networks','Powering ahead with her career ','Francesca Higgs completed a two and a half year Apprenticeship with UK Power Networks','As an electrical jointer, Francesca arranges new and altered electricity connections in Sussex. While on standby she is also sent out at night in her van to help fix power cuts.\r\nNow 22, she started her Apprenticeship in 2010 and has gained a Qualification and Credit Framework (QCF) Diploma in Electrical Power Engineering.\r\n“I find the job a challenge and I like being outdoors in a different place every day, so I never get bored. Everyone here is really friendly – in fact it feels like a big family,” says Francesca.\r\n“For me learning and earning was ideal. After the recession hit I didn’t want to come out of university with debt and no graduate job. You still have to study, but it’s more practical.\r\n“The training is excellent and we are sent on loads of different courses. Some things you can’t learn in a workshop and there were always people to guide us.\r\n“I plan to stay in the company for my full career if I can and I would like to climb the career ladder. There are opportunities that interest me in design and engineering. I hope to continue my education as my career develops.\r\n“As a woman in electrical engineering, there are some things I have difficulty with, strength-wise, but I can always work round it. Everyone is so supportive and most people really respect me for doing this job.”\r\n','www.ukpowernetworks.co.uk','','','','UK_Power_Networks_Logo_100x100.png','UK Power Networks CS text_Francesca Higgs','2013-12-12 14:26:40','2013-12-12 14:26:40');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (50,'British Sugar','17','British Sugar','Sweet smell of success','Edward Haylock is a multi-skilled engineer at British Sugar’s Wissington factory','“I am part of the maintenance team at the Wissington factory and am involved in maintaining the plant and keeping it running in breakdown situations. I am mainly based in the electrical engineering department but I am also qualified to do mechanical engineering work. I enjoy the fact that I never know what job I’m going to be doing: the wide range and size of equipment at our site means that one minute I can be working on a small control/instrumentation device and the next I can be working on high-voltage equipment or large motors.\r\n “British Sugar is a well-known employer in my area. I saw that they were offering an Apprenticeship scheme and decided to go for it. I had previous experience of working with British Sugar through their involvement with my local college.\r\n“I started my Apprenticeship in September 2007 and was taken on permanently in September 2011. Through my Apprenticeship I have completed NVQs in engineering at Levels 2 and 3 as well as a Btec National Certificate in Engineering and a further HNC.\r\n“By choosing an Apprenticeship instead of the more traditional degree route, I have been able to earn while I learn and still have the opportunity to gain a degree through further education if I want to. I have a job that is well paid for the area and will give me good experience in my trade. And I don’t have the large sums of debt that I could have if I had done a degree from college.\r\n“With an Apprenticeship, you learn a skill that will stay with you for life and is transferable to almost any industry because plants will always need maintenance or improvement. There are many opportunities in engineering to work abroad and earn a lot of money.”','www.britishsugar.co.uk','','','',NULL,'British Sugar CS photo_Ed Haylock','2013-12-12 14:50:51','2013-12-12 14:50:51');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (51,'Derby College','17','Derby College','Engineers scaling dizzy heights','Three young people are the latest in a long line of apprentices at Atlas Composites, the Ilkeston-based manufacturer of composite components','Historically the majority of apprentices have been school leavers, as Atlas Composites work very closely with local education including a close relationship with Derby College.\r\nNew recruit, 17-year-old Nathan Gregory, however has a slight edge, as he already has a year of college under his belt.\r\nNathan joins Atlas Composites this month by starting his first year Apprenticeship at Level 1 in Mechanical Engineering, even though he has already completed Level 1 in Motor Vehicle Engineering at Derby College.\r\nHe joins Luke Beardsley (pictured), aged 17, who is progressing onto an Advanced Apprenticeship having joined the company from leaving school, and Adam Smith, 22, who has completed a Foundation Degree in engineering and is now considering his next step in higher education.\r\nAdam says: “It is great that the company supports us all in progressing our qualifications and invests in our future.”','www.derby-college.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'Derby College CS photo_Luke Beardsley','2013-12-12 14:52:46','2013-12-12 14:52:46');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (52,'Leicester College','17','Leicester College','Engineering a great future','Mihir Patel enrolled on an Advanced Apprenticeship at Leicester College as he wanted to pursue a career in Engineering','Mihir Patel says the course at Leicester College was exactly what he was looking for: “I knew I wanted to do something in engineering so I looked around for the right course. I chose Leicester College as it is local to me and the course offered everything I was looking for.\r\n“The facilities in engineering at Leicester College are really good. They have good machinery, such as a manual milling lathe and a CNC milling lathe which you can use to learn on.\r\n“I love the variety of projects available on this course. It’s given me a great insight into mechanical engineering which will be useful to me in the future.\r\n“Being on an Apprenticeship course is a fantastic way to learn. My employer supplies landing gear, aero engines and industrial gas turbines, and are a reputable company to work for. The added bonus is I get to work, learn and earn all at the same time. \r\n“It’s a great opportunity for me. I’m working as an apprentice for a company that is renowned world-wide, so I couldn’t ask for anything better. I would recommend an Apprenticeship to anyone. For me, it’s the best way to learn.”\r\n','www.leicestercollege.ac.uk','','','','Leicester_College_logo_100x100.png','Leicester College CS text_Mihir Patel','2013-12-12 14:54:43','2013-12-12 14:54:43');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (53,'National Grid','17','National Grid','Job for life','Michael Jones is working on an Engineer Training Programme with National Grid','“Having completed a degree at university, and feeling that nothing could top the experience and fun, I joined the world of unemployment. I struggled with part-time jobs while looking for a dream role, got my hopes up at interview only to be told I lacked experience. It’s different to what you are led to believe – that a degree guarantees you a better paid job – I was struggling to find one.\r\n“I stumbled upon National Grid’s Engineer Training Programme. Offering a great salary and excellent benefits, and a fully paid degree, this job had it all – as well as a guaranteed job with National Grid.\r\n“Two years on, I’ve nearly completed a second degree at one of the most highly regarded engineering universities in the UK. This time round I have had no student debts or worries about the cost of food or accommodation and I have completed it with a bunch of colleagues who will be friends for life.\r\n“The other half of my time is spent on site gaining valuable experience as a Substation Engineer. My mentor helps to put all the theory into practice and that’s when things start to fall into place. The training facilities are great with fully qualified staff that make learning a breeze.\r\n“I consider myself blessed to have had this opportunity. I don’t regret going to University but the Engineer Training Programme is a great alternative and offers much more than just a qualification. It’s a job for life.”\r\n','www.nationalgridcareers.com/Development-\r\nOpportunities/','','','',NULL,'National Grid CS photo_Michael Jones','2013-12-12 14:57:03','2013-12-12 14:57:03');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (54,'Northbrook College','17','Northbrook College','A mature approach to studies','Shane Willard took a Mechanical Engineering Apprenticeship with GlaxoSmithKline','“I have always had a passion for mechanical engineering, so gaining an Apprenticeship at GlaxoSmithKline and undertaking the course of training at Northbrook College has enabled me to get into the career I have always dreamed of.\r\n“Being a mature student I initially found it a bit of a challenge to return to education but it is amazing how quickly you can pick things up if you are determined to learn. I was grateful for the help of my mentor at GlaxoSmithKline, my tutor at College as well as my framework training co-ordinator at Northbrook.\r\n“Having a mature approach to my studies has actually been an advantage rather than a hindrance as I am focused on what I need to do and I am fully committed to achieving it. When I first started my Apprenticeship I was renovating a house, which took a long time. I had to work long hours to fit everything in.\r\n“Achieving my City and Guilds qualifications has really opened doors for me in the workplace. I am considered a bit of a specialist on autoclaves now and often have more experienced engineers coming to me for advice, which really gives me a sense of achievement. I have also been asked to become a mentor for other apprentices who work for Glaxo SmithKline, which I really enjoy.\r\n“Engineering is not only interesting but also fun and anyone can learn if they have the determination.”','www.northbrook.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'Northbrook College CS text_Shane Willard','2013-12-12 14:58:40','2013-12-12 14:58:40');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (55,'South Thames College','17','South Thames College','Engineering student named Crossrail’s Apprentice of the Year','Regina Tumblepot, 27, is a Civil Engineering apprentice with BBMV and South Thames College','Regina took home the Apprentice of the Year and Trade Apprentice Award at a ceremony at the Houses of Parliament. She was nominated for her work on the building platform tunnels at the new Whitechapel Crossrail station with contractor BBMV. Her co-workers dubbed her “a phenomenal find”, “a stand-out individual” and “an inspiration to all the apprentices.”\r\nThe awards recognise the achievement and contribution made by apprentices on the Crossrail Project and more than 130 nominations for apprentices, individuals and companies working on the project were received for the awards.\r\nRegina says: “I’m really proud to have won this award, especially when I see the quality of the work that the other apprentices have done. It’s really great to celebrate the success of apprentices and recognise our hard work. Being an apprentice has worked for me and I’m really glad that BBMV has helped me grow and learn on the job.”\r\nSarah Horrell, Vice Principal at South Thames College, adds: “Regina has achieved so much; it’s great that her hard work has been recognised. BBMV and the other companies with which we work do a fantastic job in helping our apprentices contribute and learn on the job. I hope Regina’s success will convince others to find out how South Thames Apprenticeships can help them succeed too.”\r\n','www.south-thames.ac.uk/apprenticeships','','','',NULL,'South Thames College CS photo_Regina Tumblepot','2013-12-16 10:55:20','2013-12-16 10:55:20');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (56,'Swindon College','17','Swindon College','A passion for engineering','Anna Kulling, 18, is an Advanced Level Engineering apprentice','Anna Kulling always had a passion for engineering so after completion of her GCSEs at school she knew she wanted to go down the Apprenticeship route.\r\nAnna joined the Engineering Apprenticeship programme at Swindon College after guaranteeing a job with an employer as an Advanced Apprentice.\r\nAnna says: “I’ve always been interested in the way things work and the idea of fixing things so I knew this course would be perfect for me.\r\n“The programme is great; it’s really practical and hands on which I love and it fits in so well with work. I get a better understanding of everything and then I am able to use the skills I have developed in the future and utilise them in my workplace.\r\n“This has definitely been the best option for me; working, learning and earning at the same time. I have made so many friends on the course and it’s a really nice environment to work in. The tutors are brilliant and so helpful with everything.\r\n“Once I complete my Apprenticeship I will continue to work with my current employer. I would definitely recommend an Apprenticeship at Swindon College.”','www.swindon-college.ac.uk','','','','Swindon_College_logo_web.png','Swindon College CS photo_Anna Kulling','2013-12-16 10:59:10','2013-12-16 11:02:29');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (57,'UK Power Networks','17','UK Power Networks','Powering ahead with her career','Francesca Higgs completed a two and a half year Apprenticeship with UK Power Networks','As an electrical jointer, Francesca arranges new and altered electricity connections in Sussex. While on standby she is also sent out at night in her van to help fix power cuts.\r\nNow 22, she started her Apprenticeship in 2010 and has gained a Qualification and Credit Framework (QCF) Diploma in Electrical Power Engineering.\r\n“I find the job a challenge and I like being outdoors in a different place every day, so I never get bored. Everyone here is really friendly – in fact it feels like a big family,” says Francesca.\r\n“For me learning and earning was ideal. After the recession hit I didn’t want to come out of university with debt and no graduate job. You still have to study, but it’s more practical.\r\n“The training is excellent and we are sent on loads of different courses. Some things you can’t learn in a workshop and there were always people to guide us.\r\n“I plan to stay in the company for my full career if I can and I would like to climb the career ladder. There are opportunities that interest me in design and engineering. I hope to continue my education as my career develops.\r\n“As a woman in electrical engineering, there are some things I have difficulty with, strength-wise, but I can always work round it. Everyone is so supportive and most people really respect me for doing this job.”\r\n','www.ukpowernetworks.co.uk','','','','UK_Power_Networks_web.png','UK Power Networks CS text_Francesca Higgs','2013-12-16 11:01:35','2013-12-16 11:01:35');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (58,'Vision Apprentices','17','Vision Apprentices','Improving employability potential','Perry Minett, 19, is an Advanced Level Engineering Manufacture Craft and Technician apprentice','Perry discovered the vacancy on the Vision Apprentices website and was offered the position following a successful interview. He also attends The Engine one day a week and in January 2011 secured a full-time contract with Advanex.\r\nPerry says: “I left school in 2010 with 15 GCSEs and a diploma in engineering. I’ve always wanted to be an engineer and have always been intrigued by engineering practices and using machines.\r\n“I’d had some experience on various bits of machinery but I’ve come into contact with much more high-tech and new machinery at Advanex. I’m really benefiting from working with people with great experience in engineering and I’m learning lots from their experience.”\r\nPerry, who enjoys learning and earning at the same time, is looking to study on the HNC programme in the future to improve his employability potential.\r\nHe is keen to carry on working at Advanex and would be happy to work overseas for the company if given the opportunity.\r\n','www.visionapprentices.co.uk','','','','Vision_Apprentices_Logos_web.png','Vision Apprentices CS photo_Perry Minett','2013-12-16 11:11:14','2013-12-16 11:11:14');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (59,'West Nottinghamshire College','17','West Nottinghamshire College','Holiday job led to great opportunity','Lloyd Kemp, 21, took a diploma in Installing Electrotechnical Systems and Equipment at West Nottinghamshire College','\"I never planned on becoming an apprentice electrician – I kind of fell lucky and was offered the job because I had worked with Wilkinson Electrical during the summer for extra money.\r\n\"After I had done the job for a year I then decided to go to college to become an electrician and I began my Apprenticeship in 2010.\r\n\"I searched for the nearest colleges to where I live and visited West Notts. It was easy to apply and after taking an initial test I began my course. I attended college one day a week at the Station Park campus.\r\n\"The study facilities at West Notts College were brilliant, especially the practical working bays. Everything is very up-to-date and I gained so much from the sessions.\r\n\"Within my role at Wilkinson Electrical I undertake lots of different jobs depending on what type of contracts we’re working on. This varies from domestic, commercial and industrial work.\r\n\"An Apprenticeship is good because you are earning money as well as learning a trade to progress to a better future. It’s helped me a lot because as well as learning a trade I’ve been able to study other subjects such as maths and ICT.\r\n\"In the future I would like to get into property development and buy some properties of my own to improve.\"\r\n','www.wnc.ac.uk','','','','West_Notts_College_Logo_web.png','West Notts College CS photo_Lloyd Kemp','2013-12-16 11:14:32','2013-12-16 11:14:32');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (60,'ACCA','6','ACCA','A passion for numbers','Roddy Bannerman Aning decided that he wanted the ACCA qualification which is recognised worldwide, so he always had the security of future employment','“If you are looking to be always in employment, then ACCA is the way for you,” says Roddy. “Although it is a tough qualification which requires a lot of hard work, there are so many rewards, which you’ll continue to enjoy for your whole career.”\r\nRoddy is a Trustee at the Community Childcare Service, a voluntary organisation, and likes to make a difference providing financial information and development of services to those in his local community.\r\n“I enjoy working with numbers which is why I chose a career in accountancy. Being self-employed is definitely an attractive attribute of this career, and I don’t want to work for an employer all my life, so accountancy is my perfect choice.\r\n“Apart from the fact that it is a worldwide recognised qualification, ACCA, unlike other bodies, provides a 2-in-1 package, which consists of the ACCA Qualification and a BSc in Applied Accounting at Oxford Brookes University. You can determine how long it takes you to qualify, and the degree which comes with it is almost free of charge!”\r\nRoddy would advise anyone thinking about a career as an accountant to take the ACCA qualification: “If you are a person who likes a challenge and does not easily give up, then I’d recommend giving it a shot. Do a lot of homework prior to beginning the course and do not give up. It is a tough qualification, but it is recognised worldwide. Even as I looked through jobs in the accountancy industry, many employers make it a requirement for the applicant to hold an accountancy qualification, usually ACCA”.\r\n','www.accaglobal.com/uk/join','','','',NULL,'ACCA CS photo_Roddy Aning','2013-12-16 11:31:25','2013-12-16 11:31:25');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (61,'BPP','6','BPP','Higher and higher','A Grade A maths student chose the Higher Apprenticeship route to pursue her career as a Chartered Tax Advisor','Nineteen-year-old Rebecca Hulse gained three As in her A-levels, including maths, and was accepted into her top five university choices. However, she decided to take the Apprenticeship route to fast-forward her career.\r\n“I’m employed as an apprentice and tax assistant at McEwan Wallace Chartered Accountants, studying towards becoming a Chartered Tax Advisor,” says Rebeecca.\r\n“By beginning training straight from leaving sixth form, I already have a minimum of a three-year head start over my graduate competitors. In addition to this, the professional services aspect to my Apprenticeship means that I have a multi-dimensional qualification. I not only possess the knowledge of a tax technician, but I am also able to translate this in many different ways to maximise my career potential.\r\n“For me, BPP couldn’t be a better provider for my Higher Apprenticeship. I can structure my revision around my own commitments and workload to ensure that everything is completed to the highest standard. My tutors are only ever an email or phone call away to help me with any queries, and my work-based assessor provides continued support and guidance at our frequent meetings.\r\n“All in all I feel incredibly lucky to be able to train in such a fantastic environment, and I would recommend Apprenticeships to anyone with the commitment and drive to succeed in a top professional career.”\r\n','bpp.com/apprenticeships','','','',NULL,'BPP CS photo_Rebecca Hulse','2013-12-16 11:43:10','2013-12-16 11:44:06');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (62,'Chartered Insurance Institute','6','Chartered Insurance Institute','A brighter future','Matthew Weeks joined Bluefin Insurance’s Apprenticeship programme','“Before I started the Bluefin scheme I believed, like many school leavers, that going to University was my only route to success,” says Matthew. “Consequently, I moved to London and began a degree in Engineering. After a difficult year I realised that pushing myself to succeed in a course I wasn’t enjoying, was not the best way forward, and I dropped out. At that point the future looked fairly bleak; I felt like just another statistic to be brandished around the country. This was until I realised there were alternatives to a degree and was offered the opportunity to join the Apprenticeship scheme at Bluefin.\r\n“For me the Apprenticeship scheme combines two key elements of career advancement – knowledge and experience. I believe that the experience you gain from working in the industry while studying gives you a basis from which you can launch your career. The framework enabled me to channel my ambition while also balancing my work life with my personal life. It is not an easy scheme and has required hard graft on my part but the rewards are worth every second spent revising.\r\n“For me the Apprenticeship is coming to an end; however, it will have a lasting effect and will always be the basis for my achievements. I cannot praise the Bluefin Apprenticeship scheme enough and I would recommend it to anyone. If, for whatever reason, you don’t attend university, the Apprenticeship scheme that I have undertaken is a fantastic alternative to obtain your qualifications.”\r\n','www.discoverrisk.co.uk','','','',NULL,'Chartered Institute CS photo_Matthew Weeks','2013-12-16 11:47:10','2013-12-16 11:47:10');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (63,'Craven College','6','Craven College','Start professional accountancy training at age 16','Sophie Rayner began training as an Accountancy apprentice at the Shepherd Partnership in Skipton after finishing her GCSEs','Sophie knew that after finishing her GCSEs she wanted to be an accountant and an Apprenticeship gave her the opportunity to start her professional training straight away at 16 rather than go into sixth form.\r\n“For me, doing A-levels and going to university would have been a waste of my time and money as I didn’t need to take that route to achieve the qualifications I wanted,” she says. “I knew employers wanted people who have the skills to deal with confidential data and most employers don’t offer work experience due to this. I was delighted when Shepherd Partnership offered to take me on as an apprentice. Working and studying at the same time can be very hard but I have good support from Craven College and from my work colleagues.”\r\nSophie has progressed from an Intermediate to an Advanced Apprenticeship and is now close to completing her Level 4 Higher Apprenticeship in Accounting at The Shepherd Partnership.\r\n“Some of my friends have finished A-levels now and are at university with no guarantee of a job at the end of their training, but I am earning a decent wage and I hope to continue to increase my earnings. I now have the work experience and qualifications employers want so I can really recommend Apprenticeships to get your career off to a great start.”\r\nAdam Dutton, director at the Shepherd Partnership, adds: “Sophie has worked hard in the company and at Craven College and is now a great asset to us.”\r\n','www.craven-college.ac.uk','','','','craven_college_web.png','Craven College CS photo_Sophie Rayner','2013-12-16 11:56:23','2013-12-16 11:56:23');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (64,'ICAEW','6','ICAEW','Fast-Track to a successful career in business and finance','Thomas, 23, is an Audit Principal at the National Audit Office, London','“The percentage of FTSE 100 boards that have ACA qualified chartered accountants was a huge attraction for me when looking into potential professional qualifications.\r\n“Another attraction of the ACA was that I was able to complete it through the AAT-ACA Fast Track. This scheme allowed me to leave school after my A-levels and work towards a prestigious qualification, all while getting practical experience as an accountant with the National Audit Office.\r\n“I am now an Audit Principal for the National Audit Office, which plays an important part in helping to ensure that the Government is held accountable to Parliament for the way it uses public money. A typical day doesn’t exist and I can be anywhere from the office in London, to visiting clients in other parts of the country or indeed Europe. My work is heavily client focused and as a result I have the pleasure of spending significant amounts of time out at my clients, understanding the risks facing the organisation and their processes and controls.\r\n“The most difficult aspect of training via the AAT-ACA Fast Track has been balancing work commitments and study. However I don’t have any regrets about not going to university and I feel perhaps even at a slight advantage to my peers, as I have already had four years’ experience working for the National Audit Office.\r\n“My advice to anyone considering a career as a chartered accountant is that they should do their research. You should take care to ensure that where you choose to train will give you the support you need. The remuneration is important but not as important as the quality of training and support you will receive.”','icaew.com/careers','','','',NULL,'ICAEW CS photo_Thomas','2013-12-16 11:59:16','2013-12-16 11:59:16');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (65,'Learn Direct','6','Learn Direct','Career path clearly mapped','Isaac Jones, 21, is taking an Apprenticeship in Providing Financial Services with learndirect','When Isaac Jones heard about at an Apprenticeship at Lloyds Banking Group, he knew he was on the wrong career path and decided to make the change. Lloyds seemed to offer everything he was looking for.\r\n“I found the offer of an Apprenticeship very reassuring as it meant they didn’t expect the applicant to know it all already, so I thought I might be in with a shot,” says Isaac.\r\n“I applied online for the job of assistant relationship manager and was offered an interview. They told me all about the Apprenticeship and I felt pretty comfortable with it as I’m fine with learning new things.\r\n“As soon as I started I was sent to a training centre for three days and was very impressed by everything Lloyds had to offer. There was a big emphasis on training and developing within Lloyds, on a mapped out career path.\r\n“I’m well on with my Apprenticeship now and it works well with my role. The first three months were a bit difficult as I tried to balance a new job with my Apprenticeship but I’ve learnt so much about the business that my role within it makes more sense.\r\n“My assessor comes once a month to assess my work and help me with the next stage, most of this is done through discussion so I don’t have to write things up.\r\n“Banking is a complex industry but my Apprenticeship has helped my learning and my career.”\r\n','www.learndirect.co.uk','','','','learn-direct-new_web.png','Learn Direct CS text_Isaac Jones','2013-12-16 12:02:37','2013-12-16 12:02:37');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (66,'PwC','6','PwC','Stress of exams has paid off','Lucy Johnson is now a fully qualified Auditor thanks to her Apprenticeship with PwC','Rather than heading to university like her schoolmates, Lucy decided to take a chance and apply to PwC. She’d heard about the company through friends, and after doing some research, quickly realised the number of opportunities open to her. Five years later, Lucy has completed her exams and is a fully qualified Auditor looking after some big clients.\r\nLucy says: “I wanted to be an astronaut but that was never going to happen! So I applied to PwC to see what it was like. The main focus for the first two years was passing my exams. My third, fourth and fifth years were when the responsibility started. I began making my own decisions and really started to grasp what auditing was all about. Now I’m going for a Manager promotion.”\r\nWould Lucy have done anything differently? “I’ve no regrets whatsoever. From my point of view, I’m 23 years old and I’ve been able to do some fantastic things. Yes the exams are stressful and the work can be challenging, but it’s worth it and has certainly paid off.”\r\n','www.pwc.com/uk/careers','','','','PwC_logo_web.png','PwC photo - Lucy Johnston','2013-12-16 12:06:31','2013-12-16 12:06:31');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (67,'Training 2000','6','Training 2000','Martin leads the way for Apprenticeships','Martin Brennan broke new ground when he signed up for an Apprenticeship; he was the first apprentice to be taken on by his employer, Nixon Williams Ltd in Blackpool','Martin, 26, has a secure job that he loves and qualifications that will stand him in good stead in his career in future. He has always focused on finding work in accountancy. “I wanted to do something I was good at, and I was good at maths,” he says. “I chose an Apprenticeship because I thought it would provide a platform for obtaining the qualifications needed in order to make a start in my chosen career.”\r\nNow a fully qualified chartered accountant, Martin got his foot on the first rung of the career ladder thanks to Training 2000, where he was able to take exams leading towards the Association of Accounting Technicians’ (AAT) qualifications.\r\nSince then he has completed the ACCA, studying at home and in the classroom, and is now taking a distance learning course, which will lead to membership of the Chartered Institute of Taxation.\r\n“It’s a great way to kick-start your chosen career,” says Martin. “I’d certainly recommend it to others. The skills I’ve learned through taking the qualifications have helped me to learn quickly and achieve progression.\r\n“There are many benefits to the AAT and ACCA qualifications, but I would say the main one is learning the basic accounting principles. This enables you to prosper in your job.”\r\nNixon Williams Ltd have now employed a total of 30 apprentices since 2008.\r\n','www.training2000.co.uk','','','','t2000_web.png','Training 2000 CS photo_Martin Brennan','2013-12-16 12:08:38','2013-12-16 12:08:38');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (68,'Connect 2 Care','11','Connect 2 Care','Apprentice a big hit with the residents','Night care assistant Lenka Burikova is working on an Advanced Apprenticeship in Health and Social Care with Connect 2 Care','Apart from the formal qualification she will gain on completion, Lenka says her Apprenticeship has had a beneficial effect on many other aspects of her life.\r\n“I’ve improved my knowledge and understanding of the care sector, I feel better able to fulfil my role as a carer, I’m much more confident and, as an extra bonus, it’s helped me improve my English!” says 27-year-old Lenka, who started her Apprenticeship in 2012 after leaving her home in Slovakia to work in the UK.\r\n“My employers have been great, they encourage all the staff to undertake proper training,” she adds. “As well as supporting me in my progress, it means they benefit from having a properly qualified employee and I feel able do a much better job, even though I still have lots to learn!”\r\nHer main duties at Maidment Court, a residential home with 41 residents of mixed abilities in Poole, Dorset, include all aspects of personal care and medication. Lenka has also recently progressed to becoming a keyholder which, says her trainer-assessor Jane Crawford, demonstrates that she is well on her way to becoming a senior carer.\r\n“Lenka is a fantastic learner and has worked really hard since starting her Apprenticeship,” says Jane. “She’s really wonderful with the residents and has a real flair for working with elderly people.”\r\n','www.connect2care.org','','','','Connect2Care_web.png','Connect 2 Care CS photo_Lenka Burisova','2013-12-16 12:23:41','2013-12-16 12:23:41');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (69,'Learn Direct','11','Learn Direct','Apprenticeship has opened many doors','Beckie Watson, 19, is a Dental apprentice with learndirect','After completing sixth form, Beckie was struggling to decide whether to go to university to become a nurse. But when her mum gave her a leaflet about a Level 3 Apprenticeship she could do with learndirect while working as a dental nurse her mind was made up.\r\nBeckie says: “I’ve always been interested in being a nurse but mostly because I wanted to care for patients. To become a nurse I would have to study at university for four years. I wasn’t sure it was the right option for me. I had no experience as a nurse and didn’t know if I would like it; four years seemed like a big commitment. \r\n“Then my mum brought home a leaflet about becoming a dental nurse. I would have to do a Level 3 Apprenticeship to qualify but I was keen to do a job that gave me something more. Being able to earn good money while developing my career caring for patients ticked all of my boxes.\r\n“The course was great, I really enjoyed it and although it was hard in places, I had a lot of support available to me. The girls at work helped me to gain experience and my trainer offered lots of support. \r\n“Doing my Level 3 Apprenticeship has opened so many doors for me. I can work my way up to become a hygienist, move into private practice or even become a dentist.\r\n“The best thing about my Apprenticeship is that it gave me an insight to the industry and helped me to decide whether it’s the right one for me.”\r\n','www.learndirect.co.uk','','','','learn-direct-new_web.png','Learn Direct CS photo_Becky Watson','2013-12-16 12:26:47','2013-12-16 12:26:47');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (70,'Paragon','11','Paragon','Achieve personal and professional goals with an Apprenticeship','Charlotte Leech, 18, is a shining example of how an apprenticeship route has been a worthwhile stepping stone to her future career','Charlotte has been a Childcare Apprentice with Croft Day Nursery since August 2012. She originally attended college but decided that gaining work experience was more suited to her, and opted for a work-based learning programme as an alternative.\r\nCroft Day Nursery contacted Paragon seeking the perfect individual and Charlotte was the right person for the job. She was able to continue her studies but gain important work experience at the same time with the addition of getting a wage too.\r\nCharlotte says: “My Apprenticeship has been invaluable to me. I have learnt so much, including how to deal with behavioural issues and safeguarding. My long-term mission is to become a teaching assistant in a school. Completing my Level 3 will stand me in good stead along with all the experience I have gained along the way.”\r\nCharlotte’s assessor Stephanie Biocs continues: “Charlotte is a very good apprentice and always produces work to a high standard. She shows brilliant communication skills and is continuing to develop her knowledge with every visit we have. I feel the Apprenticeship has been of great benefit to Charlotte and hope that in time she will achieve her personal and professional goals”.\r\nThe Croft Day Nurseries are private day nurseries, offering day care and education for children aged from 6 weeks to school age.\r\nFor further information on Apprenticeships at Paragon, call 0800 783 2545 or visit the Paragon website.\r\n','paragonskills.co.uk','','','',NULL,'Paragon CS photo_Health & care_Charlotte Leech','2013-12-16 12:29:13','2013-12-16 12:29:13');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (71,'Shipley College','11','Shipley College','Apprentices are much more than an extra pair of hands','Shannen Coldwell, 17, started her Apprenticeship at Allerton Children’s Centre and was given the chance to complete an Apprenticeship in Children’s Care, Learning and Development','Shannen works four days a week as a crèche worker, and is given the same responsibilities as other members of staff, she then spends one day a week at Shipley College for class-based study. As well as working with the children at the centre, Shannen also helps with displays and talks to parents, which has improved her communications skills.\r\nShannen says: “I have really enjoyed my Apprenticeship so far and I feel like I am learning so much on a daily basis. The skills I am learning will improve my career options, whether I want to become a social worker, a health visitor or a family support worker.\r\n“Shipley College has supported me throughout my Apprenticeship and I would recommend them to anyone who wants to work in childcare. I have gained so many skills and my confidence has grown, and I also have experience of working as a trusted member of staff in an organisation, which many young people don’t have.”\r\nAnne Milner, Deputy Head of Allerton Children’s Centre, adds: “Shannen is the first apprentice we have had at the centre and she has become a valued member of staff. Apprentices are much more than an extra pair of hands, they become part of the team and everyone here thinks Shannen is great.\r\n“Apprenticeships are extremely important for young people, particularly in childcare, and I would highly recommend them to other employers. Shannen has been able to see many different aspects of childcare and can use her time here as a stepping stone to full-time employment.”','www.shipley.ac.uk','','','','shipley_college_web.png','Shipley College CS photo_Shannon Coldwell','2013-12-16 12:31:44','2013-12-16 12:31:44');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (72,'Skills for Care','11','Skills for Care','Caring for her community','After completing an Apprenticeship in Health and Social Care, Hannah, 24, became a community care worker with Hertfordshire County Council','Hannah knew she wanted to pursue a career in care and went on to study a care-related course at college. It was here that her tutor suggested she went to the Hertfordshire County Council’s Apprenticeship programme open day.\r\nDuring the open day, Hannah realised she liked the idea of a more practical programme and was accepted on a health and social care Apprenticeship.\r\nDuring her Apprenticeship, with the support of a mentor, Hannah worked at a residential home and two day centres which provide support for adults with a variety of needs.\r\nOnce her 18-month programme was complete, she continued to work at the Stevenage Resource Centre, and was later offered the job of day service support worker.\r\nHannah’s long-term goal is to be a social worker, and she is taking her first step towards this dream through her new role as a community care worker within the council. She has really benefited from the mixture of study and practical work experience, and has found it really useful to be able to put the theory she was learning into the context of the service users she was dealing with every day. Hannah has built up a vast amount of practical experience that she will take forward into her new role.\r\nMost importantly, if she hadn’t completed her Apprenticeship, Hannah believes she would have found it impossible to even think of becoming a social worker, which now seems to be a very real possibility for the future.\r\nCommenting on her Apprenticeship, Hannah says: “It’s such a great programme, a real door-opener. It has set me up for following my career goal, and I would never have got there otherwise.”\r\n','www.skillsforcare.org.uk','','','',NULL,'Skills for Care CS text_Hannah','2013-12-16 12:33:48','2013-12-16 12:33:48');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (73,'Somerset Skills & Learning','11','Somerset Skills & Learning','Great tutorial support','Sarah Jones is a Health & Social Care apprentice','“I love my Apprenticeship because I have always wanted to work in care,” says Sarah. “I began by starting at sixth form to complete A-levels to enable me to go into nursing. I then found out that I could complete an Apprenticeship which would give me a qualification while I was actually doing the job. I knew nothing about the job role before I started, but have found the classroom sessions really helpful in helping me to understand why I complete the tasks I do at work.\r\n“The class was not too big, and I found the support given by the tutor and the others in the classroom was really good. I like hearing about how other people work in their care settings, and the tutorial support was great: she explained what we have to do, how to get the evidence and how to present it.  The course is not as difficult as I thought it would be, and I am studying while doing a job I enjoy! I have also been nominated for a Newcomer of the Year award, which I am really pleased about.”\r\nSarah is now working in care.','www.learnsomerset.co.uk/i-am-16-to-18-years-old/apprenticeships','','','','Somerset_Skills___Learning_logo_web.png','Somerset Skills & Learning CS photo_Sarah Jones','2013-12-16 12:36:17','2013-12-16 12:36:17');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (74,'The Sheffield College','11','The Sheffield College','Swapping jobs with the Deputy Prime Minister','Deputy Prime Minister Nick Clegg swapped jobs with Genna Hibberson, 18, a Sheffield College apprentice pharmacy technician at Woodhouse Pharmacy Direct','The Sheffield Hallam MP visited Genna’s workplace to take up her role, and in return Genna will visit Westminster to learn more about Nick Clegg’s position in Government.\r\nThe job swap initiative is part of Nick Clegg’s One Million jobs campaign which aims to double the number of businesses offering Apprenticeships.\r\nGenna says: “I have always wanted to work in a pharmacy and this position has allowed me to get my foot on the ladder.”\r\nNick Clegg adds: “It was great to step into Genna’s shoes and learn more about her role. I’m extremely grateful to her and all the staff welcoming me into the team. I’m already looking forward to seeing Genna in Westminster when the roles will be reversed.\r\n“Not only do Apprenticeships create new opportunities for young people, but companies get the highly skilled staff they need to compete and expand; and communities get a boost to make their local economy stronger.”\r\nBrigitte Waring, Manager of Woodhouse Pharmacy Direct, would recommend Apprenticeships to any business looking at taking on new staff: “There are a lot of talented young people out there and working with the Sheffield College couldn’t be easier as they support you every step of the way.”\r\nThe Sheffield College offers Apprenticeships in 26 different vocational areas and is continuing to expand its programme. For more information call 0114 260 2600 or email businessgateway@sheffcol.ac.uk.\r\n','www.sheffcol.ac.uk/apprentices','','','','The_Sheffield_College_Logo_web.png','Sheffield College CS photo_Genna Hibberson','2013-12-16 12:38:43','2013-12-16 12:38:43');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (75,'YH Training','11','YH Training','Every day is enjoyable','Adam Wright is currently undertaking an Intermediate Apprenticeship in Healthcare Support Services and working for the Yorkshire Ambulance NHS Trust (YAS)','“I chose to undertake an Apprenticeship with the Yorkshire Ambulance Service (YAS) as I have always wanted to be a part of the NHS,” says Adam. “I really enjoy caring for others and have a keen interest in becoming a paramedic in the future. I felt the Apprenticeship through YH Training was the best career route for me to take as it gave me the opportunity to earn, learn and hopefully progress my career at the same time.\r\n“So far I am 9 months through my Intermediate Apprenticeship in Healthcare Support Services and really feel that I have learned a lot. It’s a really rewarding role; I attend workshops, have one-to-one mentoring with my trainer and receive training and support from the staff at YAS on a daily basis. The great thing is being able to put in practice what you learn immediately.\r\n“Since commencing the Apprenticeship, every day has been different. The development days with the Air Ambulance and the Hazardous Area Response Team were thoroughly enjoyable. Before this, I would never have thought that learning could be so enjoyable and would recommend the Apprenticeship route, and YH of course, to anyone looking for a career in the NHS. For me it’s been a life changing experience and ticks all the boxes; being employed, learning new skills together, gaining a respected qualification and having the support to help me move on to achieve my ultimate goal… to eventually become a paramedic.”\r\nTo find out more about Apprenticeships and vacancies, call Debbie on 0800 542 2848 or email her at debbi@yh-group.co.uk.\r\n','www.yh-group.co.uk','','','','YH_Training_logo_web.png','YH Training CS photo_Adam Wright','2013-12-16 12:44:22','2013-12-16 12:44:22');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (76,'Babcock International','4','Babcock International','Apprenticeship gives solid grounding for success','Sam Ward, 23, took a Hospitality Apprenticeship as part of his barista training with Caffè Nero','Sam has always wanted to run his own business and had a passion for hospitality while still at school, but he knew that to achieve his goal he needed solid experience and the qualifications to match. Sam started work at Caffè Nero in Belfast four years ago with a barista course, having learned about the opportunity to study an Apprenticeship with Babcock as part of working at Caffè Nero.\r\n“The world of coffee shops is an unbelievably lucrative one,” says Sam. “It’s also a great place to work that’s social, fast moving and dynamic. An Apprenticeship is an excellent way to get the qualifications that you need and to help you step up the career ladder. Running a coffee shop is multi-layered and complex and you need to be on top of the detail if you’re going to make a success of it.”\r\nIn 2011, Sam was named Area Caffè Nero Barista of the Year in the company’s international Barista of the Year competition, and undertook the MIT Manager in Training programme within Caffè Nero, an extensive skills package to manage a Caffè Nero outlet. Sam has now gone onto an Advanced Apprenticeship, which includes NVQ Level 3 in Hospitality Supervision, and he was a finalist in the Northern Ireland Apprentice of the Year Awards in 2012. A solid grounding for running his own business. \r\nIf you’d like to follow in Sam’s footsteps or want to know more about the wide range of career opportunities in the hospitality sector, please visit the Babcock website\r\n','www.babcockinternational.com/training','','','','Babcock_web.png','Babcock CS photo_Sam Ward – use man in centre only','2013-12-16 13:01:01','2013-12-16 13:01:01');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (77,'British Institute of Innkeeping','4','British Institute of Innkeeping','Not just about serving beer','Donna Holt, 17, is taking a BII Intermediate Apprenticeship in Licensed Hospitality','Donna Holt currently works at the Rose and Crown Hotel in Clitheroe, Lancashire, for licensee Nigel Riley and his partner Michelle Harboard. She is working towards her Intermediate Apprenticeship in Licensed Hospitality.\r\nDonna says: “I was surprised how much I enjoy working at the Rose and Crown Hotel and to be offered an Apprenticeship here is great. The range of duties I carry out are varied, it’s not just about serving beer!\r\n“The support and training I get from Nigel and Michelle is really helping me apply the theory I am learning to the practical parts of my job. I am really enjoying my course and I hope to complete my Intermediate Apprenticeship soon and progress onto an Advanced Apprenticeship. In the future I would like to run my own pub.”\r\nWhen Donna turns 18, she will get a chance to have a go at running a pub – and will manage the Rose and Crown when Nigel and Michelle go on holiday.\r\nNigel initially became interested in Apprenticeships after Thwaites brewery, in conjunction with Blackburn College, started promoting the scheme within its pubs. He was keen to be a part of the training initiative and offered to employ Donna as an Intermediate Apprentice.\r\n','www.bii.org','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-16 13:03:11','2013-12-16 13:03:11');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (78,'Brooksby Melton College','4','Brooksby Melton College','Apprentice serves royal family at Jubilee celebration','Lynsey Bell has been a Hospitality and Catering apprentice with Brooksby Melton College at the Belmont Hotel for over a year','Lynsey has grown into a dedicated young worker for the hotel and her new-found confidence and skills saw her being selected to serve the Queen, the Duke of Edinburgh and the Duchess of Cambridge at a silver service luncheon as part of the Queen’s Diamond Jubilee visit to Leicester.\r\nLynsey says: “I was so excited, it was a once in a lifetime opportunity. When I found out I was serving royalty, I was speechless.\r\n“I really appreciate all the training I get from staff at the hotel and from Brooksby Melton College, it has allowed me to see how far I can go in this industry.”\r\nLead Training Officer, June Norris, who has worked with Lynsey adds: “Lynsey is a real credit to both Brooksby Melton College and the Belmont Hotel. Though she was nervous about the event, I knew that she would be fine on the day. She is a lovely girl and will go far in the industry.”\r\nTo find out more about our Hospitality and Catering\r\ncourses and Apprenticeships, call us on 01664 855 372.\r\n','www.brooksbymelton.ac.uk/apprenticeships','','','','Brooksby_Melton_College_logo_web.png','Brooksby Melton CS text_Lynsey Bell','2013-12-16 13:04:58','2013-12-16 13:04:58');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (79,'HIT Training','4','HIT Training','A job he loves and no loans','Rising chef Ronald Dzepasi changed course midway through university and became an apprentice to carve out a career in the hospitality industry','Ronald, 24, decided he needed to ‘earn as he learned’ instead of amassing huge student loans – so he ditched his studies at Kingston University and embarked on an Apprenticeship at the four star Lancaster London hotel in Hyde Park – and has never looked back.\r\n“It just made so much sense,” said Ronald. “Why rake up mounting loans when I could learn to do something I’d love and earn money to support myself at the same time?”\r\nIt was Ronald’s part-time job as a kitchen porter that gave him a taste for the chef’s life.\r\n“I used to watch the chefs and they inspired me,” he said.\r\nRonald is now nearing completion of his Advanced Apprenticeship in Professional Cookery with specialist hospitality apprenticeship provider HIT Training. He’s learnt much about the hospitality industry in general, and specifically about all sections of the Lancaster’s Island Grill restaurant. He’s also worked large banqueting events of more than 1000 guests, and is currently learning about room service and the pastry kitchen.\r\n“Apprenticeships really give you a feel for the job,” he said. “The hands-on approach was the way forward for me and I’d recommend it to any young person.\r\n“Why struggle and strive for a career that may never happen in this economic climate when you can ‘earn as you learn’ and enjoy a satisfying and fulfilling working life?”\r\n','www.hittraining.co.uk','','','',NULL,'HIT Training CS text_Ronald Dzipasi','2013-12-16 13:07:15','2013-12-16 13:07:15');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (80,'HIT Training','4','HIT Training','Learn while you earn the perfect solution for Tom','An Apprenticeship was ideal for catering assistant Tom Langman, 18, who finds it difficult to study in a classroom but thrives on learning at work','Learning as you earn is the perfect solution for Tom and he’s keen to recruit many of his friends who are in a similar situation.\r\n“An HIT assessor came into my school and told me about Apprenticeships. I knew instantly that was the way forward for me,” says Tom. “HIT is an amazing company. I recommend it to all my friends because they are like me and can’t really learn in a classroom.\r\n“This is the perfect job for me. Hospitality is the industry I want to be in and I’m working and learning about it at the same time. It’s the full package.”\r\nHIT first helped Tom get a job at a café in Birmingham city centre but it ran into financial difficulty and closed after he had worked there for about a year.\r\nLuckily, HIT was there to offer Tom another lifeline. He sailed through the interview and landed a job as catering assistant at Corporate Catering Solutions in Birmingham. Tom and the team at Corporate Catering Solutions prepare and serve hot meals and snacks for hundreds of office workers at their Holiday Street base, and also offer an outside catering service.\r\nTom has already earned his Customer Services (level 2) NVQ and is now working towards his Food and Beverage Apprenticeship (Level 2).','www.hittraining.co.uk','','','',NULL,'HIT Training CS2 photo_Tom Langman','2013-12-16 13:11:36','2013-12-16 13:11:36');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (81,'Learn Direct','4','Learn Direct','Confidence builder','21-year-old Emma McKinlay is a Hospitality apprentice with learndirect','When Emma landed the role of assistant manager at an Edinburgh hotel her manager encouraged her to do a Level 3 Hospitality apprenticeship with learndirect. Emma hadn’t considered it before but the offer of free education and an opportunity to prove her skills was all the encouragement she needed.\r\n“I’m told I completed my Apprenticeship very quickly as I did it in just six months but I found it so interesting I wanted to get on with it,” says Emma.\r\n“During my Apprenticeship my manager left and I had to step into his role for a month. I was taking on all sorts of new tasks and the Apprenticeship gave me the confidence to do this. It confirmed to me that I had the skills I needed.\r\n“It also helped me to make the transition from being one of the team to the assistant manager. I found it hard to see myself as a manager, but the Apprenticeship showed me that I did have the skills and, because it linked to my job, I very quickly got the experience too.\r\n“Thanks to learndirect I’ve learnt to be more managerial. I have the knowledge and skills I need to do my job and now I have the experience to draw upon too.\r\n“I’d tell anyone considering an apprenticeship with learndirect to do it. It’s free education that gives you a qualification for the work that you do. Why wouldn’t you?”\r\n','www.learndirect.co.uk','','','','learn-direct-new_web.png','Learn Direct CS text_Emma McKinlay','2013-12-16 13:42:50','2013-12-16 13:42:50');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (82,'Peterborough Regional College','4','Peterborough Regional College','True grit','Karolina Morkunaite, 25, from Hampton joined Peterborough Regional College on a Level 2 Apprenticeship programme in hospitality, supervision and leadership','Karolina works full-time with her employer ISS Food & Hospitality based at the Travelex building, while studying for her qualification and also looking after her young family. She successfully completed the Level 2 qualification, progressed into a supervisory position with her employer and is now working hard to complete her Level 3 Apprenticeship.\r\nPeterborough Regional College’s Apprenticeship Centre staff form a critical link between apprentices and their employers. They have been very impressed with Karolina’s commitment: “Even during her maternity leave, Karolina continued to attend her functional skills maths and English classes, showing true determination to complete this element of her qualification.\r\n“Karolina works to a very high standard and has never failed to impress tutors and Apprenticeship staff at the college. She always takes on board ways to improve her written work and enjoys getting involved in cross-college activities during her day-release, always sharing her passion for her work with those around her. She is fortunate to work with an employer who supports her with the attendance of additional courses to further enhance and develop her knowledge.\r\n“We are very pleased with Karolina and have found her to be above expectation. At work she is constantly busy and uses her own initiative all of the time – we are very proud of her.”\r\nKarolina is already looking forward to her next qualification and would love to move to a Level 4 Apprenticeship.','www.peterborough.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'Peterbrough Regional College CS photo_Karolina Morkunaite','2013-12-16 13:44:58','2013-12-16 13:44:58');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (83,'The SWAC','4','The SWAC','A passion for food and cooking','Kyle Lewis began training to be a chef through an Apprenticeship at the Roman Baths Kitchen (Searcys) in Bath','Working for a restaurant that is a café by day and a social hub restaurant at night Kyle Lewis had to adapt quickly to a constantly changing role.\r\nDue to the diversity of the restaurant, Kyle’s role is very varied. “My main role is to offer support as requested throughout the services,” he says. “Sometimes I’ll be working on main meals, sometimes starters and sometimes desserts. It is a very varied job but always busy.”\r\nKyle heard about the Apprenticeship opportunity while looking on the National Apprenticeship Service website. He applied for the position and, after having a telephone interview and face-to-face interview with a SWAC Learner Account Manager, he went for a trial day at the Roman Baths Kitchen and was offered a position there.\r\nKyle has always had a passion for food and cooking so deciding on becoming an apprentice chef was an easy decision. He was keen to get an Apprenticeship at the Roman Baths because they are a well-known name in the food and hospitality industry and he knew he would get a high standard of training. “The environment was busy and they have many different chefs to learn from so I knew I would be supported well,” he adds. \r\nWhile completing his Apprenticeship, Kyle studied Professional Cookery with Lifetime training. Since then he has been working full time at the Roman Baths but is now considering a move to London to learn new experiences and push his training to a higher level. \r\nKyle has thoroughly enjoyed his experience as an apprentice: “I love service and getting the plates out on time to a high standard, and I like things to be presented well. I have got loads out of my Apprenticeship but mainly how to work within a professional environment. My knowledge of processes and procedures has greatly improved and I’ve been pushed to be my best on a daily basis.”\r\n','www.theswac.org.uk','','','','SWAC_web.png','The SWAC CS photo_Kyle Lewis','2013-12-16 13:46:54','2013-12-16 13:46:54');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (84,'Doncaster College','16','Doncaster College','The logical decision','Adam Wordsworth, 18, has begun an Apprenticeship at the electrical wholesalers Smith Brothers of Doncaster','Adam had always known what he wanted to do when he left school.\r\n“I want to make a career in logistics,” he says. “My father works as a warehouse manager so I have a family background in it.”\r\nNow on the first rung of the career ladder, Adam is doing a Level 2 Warehousing and Storage Apprenticeship at the Smith Brothers Warehouse and Distribution Centre in Friargate Doncaster.\r\n“I enjoy it,” he says. “I really like it here. Everybody is friendly and helpful.”\r\nAdam, from Bircotes near Doncaster, is observed and assessed in the workplace. He has goals and targets set as part of his individual learning plan in regular meetings with college staff, and evidence is gathered for his portfolio.\r\n“I have my individual learning plan and tutoring on site where I get set tasks and goals, and it all works really well,” says Adam.\r\nSmith Brothers is a family business and has been operating since 1814. Many of their workforce have been working there for years, so a bond is created of loyalty and trust. They are looking for the next generation of workers and Adam looks like he fits the bill.','www.don.ac.uk','','','','Doncaster_College_logo_web.png','Doncaster College CS photo_Adam Wordsworth','2013-12-16 13:50:11','2013-12-16 13:50:11');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (85,'YH Training','16','YH Training','The best way to start a career','Steven Glover recently completed his Intermediate Apprenticeship in Warehousing and Storage at Resin Building Products','“After leaving school, I knew I wanted to continue learning in a work-based environment as I wanted to follow a career in warehousing,” says Steven. “I initially joined YH Training Services on a Pre-Apprenticeship (now called Traineeships) provision so that I could develop my employability, maths and English skills; qualifications I hadn’t gained at school. Within 4 weeks of starting, YH Training Services helped me to get an interview with a local employer where I succeeded in securing Apprenticeship employment.\r\n“I have thoroughly enjoyed my Apprenticeship and have learnt all aspects of the role on the job, earning money, and at the same time gained the theory and skills and worked towards my qualification. From day one, my supervisors and the rest of the workforce treated me like one of the team and provided me with ongoing support and mentoring. The Sales Director has said that he’s impressed by my maturity and the speed that I have taken on all aspects of the role; I feel these qualities have been enhanced by undertaking an Apprenticeship and through the support of my trainer.\r\n“My employer is now looking to put me through my forklift truck licence and, because of my work ethic, they want to take on a further apprentice. Apprenticeships are definitely the way forward to start a career.”\r\nTo find out more about Apprenticeships and vacancies, call Debbie on 0800 542 2848 or email her at debbie@yh-group.co.uk.\r\n','www.yh-group.co.uk','','','','YH_Training_logo_web.png','YH Training CS photo_Steven Glover','2013-12-16 13:53:25','2013-12-16 13:53:25');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (86,'Royal Navy','15','Royal Navy','Royal Navy Officer','Training for a career as a Royal Navy officer, you will gain military and maritime skills as well as spending time at sea learning how warships operate','All Royal Navy officers begin their career at Britannia Royal Naval College (BRNC) in Dartmouth. They spend 30 training weeks here, with the course split into three 10-week phases: Military Skills, Maritime Skills and Initial Fleet Time.\r\nThe Military Skills phase includes learning leadership and teamwork skills and the principles of command and management. This is put into practice during several exercises on Dartmoor.\r\nDuring the Maritime Skills phase, young officers are taught to handle small ships on the River Dart and there are exercises to test the skills they’ve acquired.\r\nIn the third phase, Initial Fleet Time, 10 weeks is spent at sea, working in every department on board, learning how the ship operates and gaining first-hand experience of life in a warship.\r\nFinally, they return to BRNC for the passing-out parade, where family and friends have the opportunity to witness the student joining the Royal Navy as an officer.','www.royalnavy.mod.uk/careers','','','',NULL,'Royal Navy 1 photo','2013-12-16 13:56:34','2013-12-16 13:56:34');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (87,'Royal Navy','15','Royal Navy','Royal Navy Rating','A Royal Navy rating’s career begins with 10 weeks of basic training at HMS Raleigh','Trainees are placed in classes of about 30. Over the next action-packed and challenging 10 weeks, the teams complete targeted training which enables them to develop the Royal Navy’s core values of Commitment, Courage, Discipline, Respect, Integrity and Loyalty.\r\nRatings learn some basic skills, such as self discipline, teamwork and overcoming problems. In addition, they are taught how to fire an SA80 assault rifle and other skills required of all sailors. Recruits are given a taste of how to operate as a team tackling floods and fires at sea and they also have to pass a first aid course.\r\nFitness is crucial and a progressive regime tests individuals’ ability to climb high ropes and complete the assault and obstacle courses. Training is as practical and active as possible, using simulators and a decommissioned warship to give recruits a real taste of their future careers and the environments in which they will work and fight. The latest technology is used to make classroom learning interesting and interactive.\r\nThis initial training is physically and mentally challenging with a focus on teamwork and individual development. Most recruits think it’s rewarding, enjoyable and underpinned by a strong sense of military discipline, integrity and personal pride.','www.royalnavy.mod.uk/careers','','','',NULL,'Royal Navy 2 photo','2013-12-16 13:57:57','2013-12-16 13:57:57');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (88,'Royal Navy','15','Royal Navy','Royal Marines','The Royal Marines train thousands every year at their first-class facilities in Devon','Commando Training Centre Royal Marines is based at Lympstone in Devon. It trains new recruits and reserves, as well as delivering specialist trade training and continuation training.\r\nThe Royal Marines are the only armed force to train officers and other ranks in the same place, although they follow different courses. All Royal Marines return to Lympstone many times as they progress through their career. From the Potential Royal Marine Course (PRMC) to Regimental Sergeant Major (RSM), from Potential Officers Courses (POC) to Commandant they will return to Lympstone. Equally they will attend specialist qualification courses at Commando Training Centre Royal Marines (CTCRM) to improve their military skills.\r\nFacilities at Lympstone are wide-ranging. They include a first-class gymnasium complex and swimming pool for combat swimming tests, an indoor range simulator incorporating the latest laser technology, a modern urban combat training complex, a nearby 300-metre rifle range to hone recruits’ shooting skills and on-site training areas within the 95 acre base.\r\nIn addition CTCRM has access to 2,500 acres of nearby Woodbury Common, as well as the training areas of Dartmoor and others in Wales and Scotland. On average, 1,200 recruits and 2,000 potential recruits, and 400 potential officers attend training courses and acquaint courses at CTCRM every year.\r\n','www.royalnavy.mod.uk/careers','','','',NULL,'Royal Navy 3 photo','2013-12-16 13:59:17','2013-12-16 13:59:17');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (89,'UKSA','15','UKSA','Life at sea is an adventure','Chris Averis was awarded funding from Trinity House to do a Superyacht Cadetship at UKSA’s maritime training academy on the Isle of Wight','“A life at sea, travelling and earning, had been an ambition of mine for some time, and having worked on small commercial boats I decided to undertake sailing as a career. I started my cadetship at UKSA in 2010, training over a winter period, sailing small yachts around the south coast, the North Sea and Northern France. I returned to the academy for the second phase of training, which saw us sail out into the Atlantic and onto the Azores and Madeira. As well as practical sailing, the cadetship offers a lot of in-class time, learning navigation, radio communications, ship security and engineering skills among others.\r\n“What really sets UKSA apart from other schools is their second-to-none mentoring scheme throughout your training, and the knowledge gained about the industry as a whole. Upon leaving the academy after the first phase you feel set for the dog-eat-dog world that is known as dockwalking – walking port after port and offering your CV to each and every boat, looking for your first job. The skills you gain set you aside from the many people who have never set foot on a boat yet feel they can be a sailor, and the Yachtmaster ticket gained in the cadetship is a benchmark to getting a job.\r\n“I have had the pleasure of working on some fantastic boats, seeing some amazing sights and earning good money while doing so, all while getting a tan! I have worked on large boats, mid-sized exploration yachts and now I am the Mate onboard a 30m yacht. If a life of adventure on the sea is what you’re after then look no further than the cadetship. Who would want to work in an office anyway?”\r\n','www.uksa.org','','','','UKSA_web.png','UKSA CS photo_Chris Averis','2013-12-16 14:00:48','2013-12-16 14:00:48');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (90,'Institute of Swimming','14','Institute of Swimming','Kicking off a great career','Liam Bourke is pursuing a career as a swimming coach with an Institute of Swimming Apprenticeship','“I have always had a personal interest in sport and, being a keen sportsman myself, I decided to pursue this as a career,” says Liam.\r\n“I was attracted to Institute of Swimming Apprenticeships as they offered unique opportunities to experience a variety of working environments in the sport and leisure industry.\r\n“I teach swimming and a lot of the motivation to do a good job comes from witnessing the children develop each week thanks to my teaching; it gives me real satisfaction to know that I have helped them.\r\n“The best part about what I do is that I am never doing the same thing. At the weekends I am running children’s birthday parties and in the week I am teaching swimming lessons. I also maintain the pool quality by doing daily work in the plant room. Recently I have taken on a new role managing the lifeguard rota.\r\n“The company I work for is constantly expanding and I look forward to more opportunities to progress in my job role. We have recently branched out into facility management and holiday activities so the opportunity for growth for both me and the company in the future is massive.”','www.swimming.org/ios','','','','institute-of-swimming-new.png','IoS CS photo_Liam Bourke','2013-12-16 14:11:13','2013-12-16 14:11:13');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (91,'Leicester College','14','Leicester College','Covering the basics','Alex Orton, 25, joined The Leisure Trust and Nuneaton and Bedworth Borough Council as a Relief Leisure attendant in 2011 and took an Advanced Apprenticeship as a Personal Trainer','Alex began his first Apprenticeship in Intermediate Operating Services and then later progressed onto an Advanced Apprenticeship as a Personal Trainer with Leicester College.\r\n“An Apprenticeship is a great way to learn,” says Alex. “For me, I didn’t have to travel to the college, my trainer came to me; my timetable suited my work pattern and the qualification I will gain at the end will help progress my career. \r\n“After completing my first Apprenticeship course, I wanted to continue. The courses are designed to combine both the theory and practical elements and apply them into practice.\r\n“All the basics are covered for my job role, from how leisure centres are run, to how they operate and assist management with operations.”\r\nAlex says the options available to him as an apprentice have been great. He has managed to build on his skills portfolio and will also gain a recognised qualification at the end of his course.\r\nHe explains: “I believe my Apprenticeship will provide me with a vast knowledge of sports, fitness and management and will help open a lot of doors for me.\r\n“I have had a great experience of studying with Leicester College. I have had wonderful support from my trainers and assessors and it’s something I would highly recommend.”\r\n\r\nFor further information contact Leicester College:\r\nT: 0116 224 2240\r\nE: info@leicestercollege.ac.uk','www.leicestercollege.ac.uk','','','','Leicester_College_logo_web.png','Leicester College CS photo_Alex Orton','2013-12-16 14:14:01','2013-12-16 14:14:01');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (92,'Babcock International','5','Babcock International','Hard work and commitment reaps rewards','Chris Mulgrew, 24, took an Advanced Modern Apprenticeship in Vehicle Refinish with BMW','Chris left school at the age of 16 with low grades and an uncertain future. However, his passion for cars took him to his local college in Teeside to study Light Vehicle mechanics. Unfortunately the deteriorating economic climate meant Chris was not able to complete the qualification, but he eventually secured a valet role at Audi Teeside.\r\nIn 2009 Chris moved to BMW Cooper, Teeside, valeting cars for the BMW Preparation department. He joined the cosmetic repair team learning the skills of ‘SMART’ or Cosmetic Body repair. BMW identified Chris as a prime candidate for Babcock’s three year BMW Apprenticeship programme; although he did not have the usual entry qualifications, his work and commitment prompted the business to take him on in 2011.\r\nChris is now in his third year with BMW: “Body repair and paintwork is an art, there is a high degree of complexity needed in terms of mixing and balancing colours and formulations according to the surface you are working on.”\r\nChris has been preparing and painting a BMW 7 Series to show the different materials used in the vehicles construction. It will be exhibited at the BMW Apprentice graduation ceremony and the BMW Group Academy in Reading. He has also artworked a BMW MINI bonnet which is on display at Babcock’s training centre in Ruddington. If you’d like to follow in Chris’s footsteps or want to know more about the wide range of opportunities available in automotive, please visit the Babcock website.','www.babcockinternational.com/training','','','','Babcock_web.png','Babcock CS photo_Chris Mulgrew','2013-12-16 14:19:16','2013-12-16 14:19:16');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (93,'Central Sussex College','5','Central Sussex College','Passion for Porsches','Twenty-year-old Alex Brown’s life-long passion for Porsches helped him secure his dream role when he became an apprentice Vehicle Technician at a specialist Porsche garage','As a second year apprentice, Alex spends one day a week at Central Sussex College, and is based in the workshop for the rest of the time, carrying out servicing and repairs, plus routine and major bodywork jobs.\r\nAlex, who previously worked in farming, says: “It started about two years ago, when I bought a Porsche of my own. I went along to Nine Excellence [a specialist Porsche garage in Horley, Surrey] to talk about buying parts and managed to come away with a job offer – I’ve never looked back!”\r\n“The best thing about being an apprentice is using what I’m learning at College in my workplace. I didn’t have much experience of the motor industry before I started, so being able to understand the theory behind what I’m doing in the workshop has been fantastic. Coming to College once a week also gives me a break from my routine, and it’s good to meet-up with other apprentices and share experiences.” \r\n“I plan to finish the Level 2 qualification and progress to Level 3 – after that I’ll be a fully qualified Porsche mechanic, which is a dream come true. In the future I hope to own my own Porsche specialist centre, and I’d love to work abroad – opportunities that weren’t an option for me just two years ago. I would encourage anyone hoping to kick-start their career to look into becoming an apprentice, it’s been a great experience.”\r\nFor more on apprenticeships available at Central Sussex College, visit the college’s website or call 01293 442205.\r\n','www.centralsussex.ac.uk/apprenticeships','','','','Central_Sussex_College_logo_web.png','Central Sussex College CS photo_Alex Brown','2013-12-16 14:21:40','2013-12-16 14:21:40');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (94,'East Riding College','5','East Riding College','Motoring along nicely','Ricky Hookem, 20, is a Level 3 apprentice in Light Vehicle Service and Repair','Ricky Hookem completed his Level 2 Intermediate Apprenticeship in Light Vehicle Service and Repair and almost immediately progressed onto the Level 3 Advanced Apprenticeship.\r\nHis work was of such a high standard, both at college and for his employer, that he won Level 2 Apprentice of the Year in the Institute of the Motor Industry’s Hull and District Member Association Apprentice Awards.\r\nRicky, who works at M and M Autotech in Beverley and attends East Riding College one day a week, won the award for his outstanding grades, the hard work he puts into his job and his studies and his excellent attitude.\r\nHe says: “I was really happy to get the award. It’s a good thing to get on your record but you do have to work for it. I’ve always enjoyed the course and my job, and I think that helps a lot.”\r\nRicky’s tutor at the College, Glenn Jensen, adds: “Ricky has been on the Apprenticeship for 18 months and has put in a lot of effort and achieved a high standard of work.\r\n“He always gets a glowing report from his employers, who have supported him really well throughout the Apprenticeship.\r\n“He’s always up to date with his assignments and has a really good attitude, and he thoroughly deserves this award.”\r\n','www.eastridingcollege.ac.uk','','','',NULL,'East Riding College CS photo_Ricky Hookem','2013-12-16 14:24:00','2013-12-16 14:24:00');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (95,'Jaguar Land Rover','5','Jaguar Land Rover','On a pathway to success','Naomi Jennens-Bull joined Jaguar Land Rover as an Advanced Apprentice having just completed her GCSEs','Although Naomi knew she wanted to pursue a career in engineering, she wasn’t sure which specialism she’d like to follow. This made it difficult to choose a university course and the appropriate A-levels. When she discovered she could combine academic and vocational studies with an Apprenticeship at Jaguar Land Rover, the decision became easy.  She now would have the perfect balance between the two, while gaining a unique insight into the automotive industry.\r\nNaomi is currently in the third year of her Apprenticeship as an electrical maintenance technician in the Facilities and Site Services department at the company’s Advanced Engineering Centre in Warwickshire. So far, she has completed her NVQ2 in engineering and is now beginning her NVQ3 and foundation degree at Warwickshire College, fully sponsored by the business.\r\nSpeaking about her Apprenticeship, Naomi says: “The last three years at Jaguar Land Rover have been amazing. They’ve really opened my eyes to the endless possibilities and opportunities that are available within the automotive industry, and Jaguar Land Rover is at the very heart of it.\r\n“To be able to earn while learning from some of the most skilled and experienced engineers in the country has been incredible, and even though it was initially hard to adjust from a school environment to a working environment, I would recommend an Apprenticeship to anyone – in fact I have friends applying this year.”  \r\nTo find out more about an Advanced Apprenticeship at Jaguar Land Rover, please visit www.jaguarlandrovercareers.com\r\n','www.jaguarlandrovercareers.com','','','','Jaguar_Land_Rover_web.png','Jaguar Landrover CS photo_Naomi Jennens-Bull','2013-12-16 14:26:10','2013-12-16 14:26:10');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (96,'Paragon','5','Paragon','Garret gets motoring with Mercedes','Garret Grant is currently working on an Apprenticeship in HGV Maintenance and Repair at Mercedes in Fareham','“I was never academically minded at school but always loved working on cars,” says Garret. “When I was 16, and before leaving school, I contacted Paragon, my local training provider based at Blackbrook Business Park, Fareham, and asked for their help. They recommended a Motor Young Apprenticeship course, which is basically an introduction to the motor industry to see if it was something I wanted to do. It was a natural progression to continue onto a motor Apprenticeship which is what I am doing now.\r\n“I’m a real petrol head so I love my work! I have learnt all about the mechanical workings of a truck, how the air brakes operate, the large variety of electrical systems and general servicing. I have been involved in a number of engine and gear box rebuilds, and have worked on suspensions and differential work as well as body maintenance on trucks. \r\n“The responsibility can sometimes be a bit daunting but I am not on my own. I get a lot of good support from my Paragon training officer who comes to see me regularly. I also enjoy meeting up with the tutors and other students at the skills centre I attend, and I mustn’t forget Mercedes, they give me a lot of attention and make sure the jobs I am given help to progress my skills. When I finish my Apprenticeship I will be a fully qualified HGV Technician.\r\n“My future? I have dreams of moving to the United States and becoming a technician on those Mack truck ‘bad boys’ – why not?”\r\n','www.paragonskills.co.uk','','','',NULL,'Paragon CS photo_Garret Grant','2013-12-16 14:29:04','2013-12-16 14:29:04');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (97,'Remit Ltd','5','Remit Ltd','Local garage provided great Apprenticeship opportunity for school-leaver','Fidell Moran, 17, is a Light Vehicle technician apprentice','Fidell Moran has always had an interest in working in the motor industry. While at school, he was lucky enough to take part in a foundation training programme for light vehicle apprentices.\r\nNot many schools offer this sort of course to young people, but it made a huge difference to Fidell. Supported by his tutors, he achieved a Light Vehicle Level 2 Technical Certificate, which means he’s already a step ahead in working towards his NVQ Level 2 Intermediate Apprenticeship.\r\nWhen he left school, Fidell turned to Nottingham-based training provider, Remit, to help start his Apprenticeship and kick start his career. Remit worked with local garage owner, Nader Zakipour, of Redhill Service Centre, to provide an Apprenticeship.\r\nFidell’s manager at Redhill, Chris Anderson, is able to act as his mentor, helping him apply some of the skills he learns in college and with his Remit assessor to his day-to-day work.\r\nChris says: “Fidell’s been with us since last summer straight out of school, and his skills are improving all the time. Learning on the job, you not only pick up the technical skills, you also learn how to interact with customers and manage your workload.”\r\nRemit assessor, Nick Cooke, adds: “Fidell’s already doing really well with his Apprenticeship. He’s currently working towards his NVQ Level 2 qualification, and we expect he will go on to pursue Level 3 and become fully qualified. There’s a lot to learn as you go along, but there is support all along the way from Remit and his employer.”\r\n','www.remit.co.uk','','','','Remit_training_logO_web.png','','2013-12-16 14:32:09','2013-12-16 14:32:09');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (98,'Thatcham','5','Thatcham','Sky’s the limit','Adam Whitehouse is 22 years old and an MET apprentice at Solus Accident Repair Centre in Birmingham','“I’ve always been into cars and have a Ford Escort Mark 1 that I’ve been doing up in my spare time, so when I got the chance to put my hobby into practice, I didn’t need to think twice,” says Adam. “I first joined Solus as a car valeter and then was soon given the chance to be an MET [mechanical, electrical and trim] apprentice. I love it. Every day there’s a new challenge, different cars to work on, different jobs to do – no two days are the same.\r\n“I do my training in two-week blocks, four times a year at Thatcham Automotive Academy, where I learn real skills that I can put into practice when I go back to work. I really look forward to going there. I get to meet up with other apprentices and we enjoy the learning and showing each other what we can do. Thatcham have all the latest tools and equipment, modern vehicles to work on and the instructors are all really nice.\r\n“In less than 2 years I will have completed my Advanced Apprenticeship and gained a VCQ Level 3. Once I’ve got my qualifications, the sky’s the limit really. I suppose there may be opportunities in management one day, but I don’t want to go into the office – I’m happy on the shop floor and I’d like to think that one day I’ll be mentoring another apprentice just like myself.”\r\n','www.thatcham.org/apprentices','','','','Thatcham_Automotive_Academy_web.png','Thatcham CS photo_Adam Whitehouse','2013-12-16 14:37:56','2013-12-16 14:37:56');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (99,'Vision Apprentices','5','Vision Apprentices','It’s great to fix problems','Leanne Cooke, 27, took an Apprenticeship in Railway Engineering with Vision Apprentices','Leanne achieved both her NVQ Level 2 and 3 at West Nottinghamshire College’s campus dedicated to engineering and electronics. As Leanne was enrolling on the HNC in electronics and electrical engineering, her tutor pointed out that Nottingham Express Transit (NET) was seeking apprentice engineers to work on Britain’s newest light rail system, which opened in March 2004.\r\nShe applied and started work as an apprentice technician at NET’s Wilkinson Street depot in August 2010. Leanne says: “I was the only woman to be taken on at the time. But I soon discovered that there were other women at NET who had studied engineering and progressed with the company, such as our engineering manager.”\r\nLeanne’s role with NET is certainly varied: “I work on many aspects of the tram network using my engineering skills,” she says “I can be fixing the tracks and lines, fault-finding on the maintenance side or using my electronics skills on the CCTV cameras or information boards which you see at the tram stops.\r\n“I literally work on everything along the nine miles of track and 23 tram stops, except the trams themselves, which are maintained by Bombardier.\r\n“I enjoy the variety the job brings me and it’s great to be able to fix problems which can occur on the network. There’s such good camaraderie at NET and we all work together learning new things.”\r\nLeanne went on to study the HND in electronics and electrical engineering after completing her Apprenticeship and was the East Midlands VQ awards winner in 2011.','www.visionapprentices.co.uk','','','','Vision_Apprentices_Logos_web.png','Vision Apprentices CS text_Leanne Cooke','2013-12-16 14:40:54','2013-12-16 14:40:54');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (100,'Keith Williams','17','Chief Executive of British Airways','Driving businesses to greater achievements','Keith Williams explains why Apprenticeships are so important at British Airways','Benjamin Franklin, Jamie Oliver, Vincent Van Gogh. All world-famous in their respective fields of expertise. All started their influential careers as apprentices.\r\nThere is no under-estimating the value of apprentices. It is very important that companies commit to investing in people. Not only does this benefit individuals and their communities, but it also ensures that there is a talented workforce to take the reins in the future. Apprenticeships can set an individual on the path to excellence and drive a business to greater achievements.\r\nAt British Airways we recognise the value of apprentices. We are expanding our Apprenticeship programmes on an annual basis and exploring new areas of the business in which to develop future schemes. In 2013 British Airways recruited nearly 200 apprentices across a variety of different departments including 140 engineering positions. Over the last three years, the airline has transformed its apprenticeship offering, with more than 350 students currently undertaking courses, and this trend is set to continue in 2014.\r\nSafety is at the heart of everything we do and our engineering department is a vital cog in the safe operation of our aircraft. Our engineering apprentices develop their skills over a three-year period, both in an academic setting and in our maintenance hangars where they will be supervised by engineers with a wealth of experience – many of whom were themselves apprentices.\r\nThe apprentices of today will become the supervisors of the future and so the cycle of skill development will continue and British Airways will continue to deliver its legacy of providing a safe and secure operation.\r\nIf you are seeking an apprentice position I wish you the best of luck and commend you for choosing this path for the development of your career.\r\n','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 12:01:39','2013-12-17 12:01:39');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (101,'Rick Stein','4','Rick Stein','Cooking up a storm','Apprentices have the ability to achieve great things, says Rick Stein','Hospitality is a growing part of the economy of Great Britain. Joining an Apprenticeship scheme in our industry means you will gain a wealth of experience and knowledge; there is no substitute for learning while working because you rapidly develop the skills needed and are therefore more likely to get a first-class job at the end of your programme.\r\nWorking with our local colleges in 2013 we had ten chefs taking part in a Level 2 Professional Cookery Apprenticeship; this year we have a view to supporting a larger group. The course not only teaches cooking skills but also introduces the students to the world of personal development, vital when applying for more responsible roles in catering.\r\n','www.rickstein.com','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 12:44:04','2013-12-17 12:44:04');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (102,'Peter Rogers','2','Peter Rogers CBE is a Director and Co-founder of Stanhope plc','Building a great future','The construction industry offers a wide selection of apprenticeships to choose from. Peter Rogers explains how he started in the industry','Knowledge is the foundation to all that we are and do and this is particularly true for the UK construction industry, which for too long has been seen as the easy option and an industry you can ‘get into’ without skills or qualifications.\r\nBUT that is how I started! Like many at school I had had enough of ‘education’ and effectively dropped out of further education to work as a labourer on a building site, where I met many others in a similar position.\r\nI enjoyed the site-oriented, practical work and put a lot more effort into it than I did at school! But as well as effort and enthusiasm, I was lucky in that the construction company I worked for recognised I had ability – more than I thought I had – and they encouraged me to further my skills, even going as far as using their contacts to get me a place at a Polytechnic. There I passed with a commendation and the rest, as they say, is history.\r\nYou don’t need luck now, because the opportunities are available with a wide selection of Apprenticeships to choose from. You can make a reasoned choice that will change your life rather than rely on chance for your future.\r\nOnce qualified with the relevant skills, many opportunities arise, not only to do an interesting job but also to make money.\r\nThere are many varied jobs in different aspects of construction. I have worked on projects ranging from motorways to oil rigs, office buildings, residential and even opera houses and museums.\r\nThis work has taken me all over the UK and overseas to Europe, the Middle East and America. Few other industries offer as much choice and excitement.\r\nPick a skill that interests you, enjoy it and be successful.\r\n\r\nPeter Rogers is an engineer and property developer working with government and industry to improve environmental and working practices in construction. He was awarded a CBE for Services to Construction in 2007.\r\nPeter is a Director and Co-founder of Stanhope plc, one of the UK’s foremost property developers, where he was responsible for the seminal Broadgate development. He is a Fellow of the Royal Academy of Engineering and the Royal Society of Arts, and an Honorary Fellow of the RIBA. He also acts as advisor to numerous arts organisations, the Ashmolean Museum, Tate Gallery, Royal Opera House and the Mayor of London for the Olympic Orbit. He is a past Trustee of the Victoria & Albert Museum and Chairman of the Building Strategy Committee and a Trustee of the Serpentine Gallery.\r\n\r\n','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 12:50:57','2013-12-17 12:50:57');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (103,'Steve Holliday','18','Steve Holliday is CEO of the National Grid','Power to the people','Steve Holliday of National Grid explains why apprenticeships play such a key role in the energy industry','I have the privilege of leading National Grid. Our job is to connect people to the energy they use. National Grid owns and manages the grids to which many different energy sources are connected in the UK and the Northeast of the United States, employing over 27,000 people. The energy industry is today an increasingly exciting place to work because it’s at the heart of a modern economy and future UK growth. With so many crucial engineering, investment and environmental challenges to meet, the future can only be delivered through people, and Advanced and Higher Apprenticeships play a key role in our workforce strategy.\r\nI have worked in energy for over 30 years and at National Grid for over 10 years, which reflects my own personal passion for this industry. When I first started out, what I valued the most was the opportunity to get involved early on and develop my skills, through a mix of varied practical experiences and formal training, and support and encouragement from my manager – and this remains key to our Apprenticeships today.\r\nAt National Grid we have a long history of delivering leading-edge Apprenticeship programmes which are graded by Ofsted as Outstanding in every category and recognised as a Beacon by the LSIS (Learning and Skills Improvement Service). A critical element of the Apprenticeship framework is the support structure, whereby Co-ordinators, Mentors and Line Managers give personal support to our apprentices within a work-based education framework, managed by our Technical Learning & Development team. I believe this is why we continue to achieve very high retention rates (95%), endorsed in the excellent feedback we receive from apprentices, both formally and informally.\r\nWhen you qualify following your Apprenticeship at National Grid you will have the defined knowledge, skills and qualifications for your job and destination role. But, more importantly, you will have the opportunity to develop further into craftsperson roles where you can build your experience and knowledge towards Engineering Technician registration. Professional registration at all levels is encouraged and sponsored to develop your capability.\r\nThe energy industry has had a long-standing ‘grow our own’ approach, with Apprenticeships being a key aspect of this. We teach young people the skills that we require and grow our own talent for the future. It’s an exceptional experience for learners and creates a sustainable talent feed into our organisations by providing long-term value to companies, replenishing essential specialised engineering skills within the UK energy infrastructure.\r\n','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 12:54:55','2013-12-17 12:54:55');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (104,'Simon Jenkins','3','Simon Jenkins is Chairman of the National Trust','National treasures','National Trust chair Simon Jenkins outlines why Apprenticeships are vital to create a supply of experts who will protect our heritage','Apprenticeships matter – to people starting careers, to employers who want to be competitive and to our economy. And they matter as much in charities as they do to other sectors. As Chairman of the National Trust, I am proud of the commitment to Apprenticeships that we and our sector are making.\r\nYouth unemployment is the highest it has ever been and our economic future remains uncertain. Many young people are looking to move into the world of work sooner and are finding opportunities limited. That’s why we need Apprenticeship schemes.\r\nAt the National Trust we look after special places forever, for everyone. We need apprentices because we need a supply of experts to look after our wonderful places. These are jobs requiring specialist knowledge and skills. Apprenticeships play an important role in developing these skills. They also provide opportunities for people from different backgrounds looking for proper, fulfilling jobs. In May 2012 we were delighted to receive funding from the Heritage Lottery Fund to create new Building Apprenticeships. We are aiming to hire apprentices who have been made unemployed as a result of the recession.\r\nWe aim to provide our apprentices with excellent training and an enjoyable experience. We hope that many of them will stay with us to pursue careers that will protect our heritage for future generations. Other charities have similarly noble causes. This is typical of the charitable sector. I hope you will consider an Apprenticeship with one of the wide range of charities now offering them and I wish you every success.','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 14:28:03','2013-12-17 14:28:03');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (105,'Sarah Beeny','2','Sarah Beeny','Succeed like Sarah','TV personality Sarah Beeny explains why apprentices make happy employees','There is nothing like learning on the job. Not only does it make you far more confident, it gives you much more experience and makes you far more likely to succeed. Everything that I’ve learnt, I’ve learnt from watching other people, and this has been the solid grounding for everything I’ve achieved. An Apprenticeship enables you to learn from experienced professionals which is just a fantastic way to start your career. In my opinion there would be many more happy employees right now if they had learnt their trade as apprentices.\r\n\r\nSarah Beeny set up her own property development and investment companies at the age of 24 with her brother and her partner (now husband) Graham. With her business a success, Sarah was approached to be the presenter of Channel 4’s prime-time TV show Property Ladder.\r\nEnjoying the opportunity to bring property to the nation, Sarah has fronted many other shows such as Streets Ahead and Britain’s Best Home.\r\nSarah regularly writes for magazines and The Sunday Times, and has written several bestselling books, as well as a blog for Sainsbury’s website.\r\nIn 2005, she created the online website www.mysinglefriend.com which has been a phenomenal success and has changed the attitude to online dating in this country. Sarah has recently re-launched her property website www.tepilo.com as an online estate agent.\r\nShe continues to be the nation’s ‘go to’ face for all things property-related and her Channel 4 series Double Your House for Half the Money has received great attention.\r\n','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 14:43:10','2013-12-17 14:43:10');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (106,'Joseph Massie','12','Joseph Massie','Coming up roses','Joseph Massie’s career is blooming, thanks to a passion for floral design and a strong work ethic','My career was never planned. There was no great master plan, no splendidly glorious complete vision, and in some ways, there still isn’t. I started working within the floristry industry aged 13, scrubbing buckets every weekend. I’ve always had a strong work ethic, and I got stuck right in, desperate to learn everything I could from the very first day. It was there that I fell in love with floral design, and I decided to make it my career.\r\nI studied for a Level 2 certificate in floral design at my local college after completing my GCSEs. My college course was two and a half days a week and I spent the rest of my time working on an open-air flower stall in Liverpool city centre. It was not the most glamorous of places to start but I absolutely loved it, and the studio where I work today is just down the road from that stall.\r\nAfter finishing at college, I began entering vocational competitions as a way to progress my career (my college wasn’t running a Level 3 course and it was up to me to invest in my own future). Don’t get me wrong: I enjoyed college and I am quite academic, but when college couldn’t provide me with a route to get where I wanted to go, entering competitions provided an alternative pathway, albeit a risky one.\r\nMy initial experience of competing at a regional level was not very successful, but after a while I began to come third, then second, and finally to win, which would take me through to national finals. At this point I started to take my career seriously. I began investing my monthly wages into my education – I booked myself onto day courses, bought design books and begged to assist top UK designers at shows and installations. I literally immersed myself into the industry, and it began to pay off.\r\nAt 19, I won my first National award, and I have never looked back. I continued to work in both retail and event floristry and my work began to attract international attention from publications and clients. I spent six months working in New York in 2012, then returned to the UK in January 2013 to launch my own company, Joseph Massie Creative. I now specialise in couture floral design for clients such as Sky, Universal Studios, ASDA and Kildare Village, creating art and design installations for a huge variety of projects. I regularly demonstrate and lecture at the colleges throughout the UK, and I’ve just come back from a second tour of China, demonstrating my skills in a host of cities in association with the British Council.\r\nI didn’t follow an Apprenticeship scheme – it simply wasn’t offered to me and I didn’t know what an Apprenticeship was – but I now know that an Apprenticeship is a really beneficial way of achieving a qualification while gaining on-the-job training, especially for a hands-on skill such as floral design.\r\nI think my career is a good example of how starting small and working with what you love can lead to bigger and better things. My advice to anyone would be to start your career in the very same way: from the ground up.\r\n\r\nJoe Massie is a floral designer and the owner of Joseph Massie Creative, a unique art, design and lifestyle brand that focuses on the innovative use of fresh flowers, plants and botanical materials. He has won a host of national and international awards, including five gold medals and four Best in Show awards at the RHS Chelsea Flower Show.\r\n\r\n','www.josephmassiecreative.com\r\n','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 14:45:44','2013-12-17 14:45:44');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (107,'Shavata Singh','13','Shavata Singh','Plucked to perfection','Hard graft and excellent customer service skills helped Shavata Singh to build her eyebrow-shaping empire','I wanted to be a beauty therapist, so after leaving school I trained for three years doing a hairdressing and beauty course at City & Guilds. I worked at Fenwicks, followed by the Michaeljohn salon on Albemarle Street in London’s Mayfair district. I was a junior therapist and I had to work incredibly hard, as I wasn’t bringing my own client base and the other therapists all had their own clients. I took a different approach to working from everyone else, using up every moment of the Michaeljohn opening hours (8 am till 8 pm) and not taking a lunch break, which meant I was available to pick up all last-minute appointments. At the time, most people took a more traditional approach and worked from 9 am to 5 pm with an hour for lunch. This strategy worked incredibly well for me and I soon became the highest grossing therapist. I was the only eyebrow threader on the team of therapists and my clients loved the results and kept coming back.\r\nMy next step was to become self-employed and that is when the Shavata brand began. I set up my first studio in Urban Retreat in Harrods and began to grow the business, setting up studios in leading department stores nationwide. I believe I was successful because I specialised in something others didn’t offer.\r\nThis year we are aiming to consolidate the Shavata brand and really build our training academy; it’s crucial that the entire Shavata team are able to offer the same exceptional levels of customer service and standards.\r\nMy achievements have come as the result of hard graft, good service and specialising in one thing. Every one of my studios offers excellent service and the very best treatments. I maintain this as a central part of my business, and see the benefits which are reaped for both clients and staff.\r\n\r\nWant to follow in Shavata\'s footsteps?\r\nLearning on the job is the best way to get experience in the beauty and wellbeing industry. Click here to find out more about an apprenticeship in this sector.','www.shavata.co.uk','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-17 14:49:31','2013-12-17 14:49:31');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (108,'Jamie Stevens','13','Jamie Stevens','Get ahead with hairdressing','As an award-winning hairdresser and celebrity favourite, Jamie Stevens can testify to just how rewarding a career in hairdressing can be','I owe my success to my early training. Apprenticing was a massive part of my own career and I was lucky to have gained experience in my mother’s salon from the age of 10. Here, I learnt all aspects of the trade, from barbering to styling Afro hair. Apprenticeships are the basic foundation of your training, which set you up for the rest of your career.\r\nHairdressing wasn’t always the direction I had been heading in. As a child, I dreamt of playing professional football. But at age sixteen, my hopes were scuppered when an ankle injury ended my professional career. This setback gave me the determination to succeed elsewhere in my life. Having grown up in a household of hairdressers, it seemed only natural that I should turn towards hairdressing. And so I did. I attended Somerset College of Arts and Technology (SCAT), passing my NVQ Levels 1, 2 and 3, and shortly afterwards opened my own salon in Somerset aged just 18.\r\nWhen I was 22, I headed to London and success was not far away. I worked under the likes of Beverley C, Daniel Hersheson and Errol Douglas, and was Art Director at Errol Douglas for seven years. Since then, I have had the luck to be able to style celebrities from Kylie, Elle Macpherson and Myleene Klass to Christian Slater, Gok Wan, Hugh Grant and Olly Murs, to name but a few. I have worked as hairdresser-in-residence for TV shows such as This Morning, Gok’s Fashion Fix and How to Look Good Naked, and for the last three years have been the official backstage hairstylist for The X Factor. I juggle this responsibility with owning and running my own salons and fulfilling my role as ambassador for Matrix Haircare.\r\nEver since starting in the industry, I have wanted to own my own salons and start my own empire. And through hard work (seven day weeks) and determination I am well on my way to getting there. I appreciate how hard it can be to start out in this industry and recognise the value Apprenticeships can have.\r\nWe run a day-release scheme in my salon because I fully believe that hands-on, salon experience is a more valuable learning tool than theory. You’ll be amazed how much you can learn from just watching. If you’re an aspiring apprentice then you will need to have passion, determination, dedication and drive. If you have these in abundance then why not give it a go!\r\n\r\nJamie Stevens is at 9 Russell Gardens, London, and Sedgemoor Road, Woolavington, Somerset. He was the joint youngest ever nominee for the industry\'s most coveted accolade last year (HJ’s British Hairdresser of the Year 2012) and was nominated again for the award this year.\r\n','www.jamiestevenshair.com','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 11:50:46','2013-12-19 11:50:46');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (109,'Andy Clarke','22','Andy Clarke is President and CEO of Asda','Start the journey of a lifetime with a career in retail','Andy Clarke, President and CEO of Asda, had a less than glamorous start to his retail career','What do most people think a career in retail involves?\r\nShelf stacking? Checkouts? Possibly a routine job without much to offer in terms of prospects or excitement?\r\n\r\nAre they right?\r\nThey couldn’t be more wrong. After all, I worked my way through the ranks to become President and CEO of one of Britain’s biggest retailers. It’s an industry of huge opportunities regardless of your ambition.\r\nIn fact, I started my career at 17 years old stacking shelves in my local supermarket with one O-level to my name. And while I had a strong work ethic and will to succeed, I would never have believed that my career could have taken me down this particular path.\r\nI started on the shop floor, sweeping floors and stacking shelves. It wasn’t glamorous, but my enthusiasm to learn new skills and make the most of opportunities meant that after a while I was able to take on different roles and eventually run my own store. Now, 30 years on, I have learnt more than I could have imagined about what a career in retail really means – from managing a store with hundreds of colleagues and a turnover of millions – to knowing how to make sure shelves are stacked with products from all over the world at the right time.\r\nMy own experience is why I am so passionate about giving young people the opportunity to make the most of their potential, whatever their background, and why I believe a career in retail could take you in a direction you never thought possible.\r\nAt Asda, we recruit our colleagues for their attitude and train them for skill – so we look for people who have a great attitude and passion for doing a good job, rather than just exam grades. Once you are part of the team, we invest in your development through initiatives like our Apprenticeship scheme to make sure you have the technical skills that match your enthusiasm. Then, equipped with a great attitude and the right knowledge, we work with you to make sure you fly. \r\nThe best part of my job is going out to our stores and meeting the amazing young people who are helping to drive our business forward. They join us from all walks of life and I see so much of my younger self in them. In fact, I hope that among them is someone who could end up in my job. Or perhaps that someone is you.','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 12:05:27','2013-12-19 12:05:27');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (110,'Aaron Carlo','13','Aaron Carlo','Creating beautiful styles','When you love your job as much as Aaron Carlo does, it never seems like work','I actually never wanted to be a hairdresser. I was training as a performer at school and the plan was to be a singer, but I worked in a salon on a Saturday and literally fell in love with the whole industry and salon life. I was lucky to work with an amazing boss and salon that really looked after its staff, and I just loved creating beautiful styles.\r\nI did an Apprenticeship and got my NVQs (Levels 1, 2 and 3) at Bournemouth College, which is where I’m from. I am the least studious person ever, so I loved the idea of getting a qualification while being able to work and earn money – and most of all being treated like an adult.\r\nI’ve been in this industry for over 10 years on and off, and my career has been a bit of a crazy whirlwind really, especially over the last few years. I’ve gone from working in a salon full time to being an Art Director for the international salon group Headmasters. I get to spend every day working with different fashion brands, magazines, models and celebrities, like Little Mix, the girl band I look after. I worked as a model for a few years, which really helped when I started doing more work in fashion and editorial, rather than being so salon based.\r\nFor me, it’s about creating beautiful characters that inspire women. I want every style I create to be aspirational yet obtainable. What’s the point if women don’t want to recreate it themselves?\r\nMy job takes me all over the world and it’s never dull. The travel is insane as I’m always in a different country and I rarely have any free time, but when you love your job as much as I do it never seems like work. I never could have believed I would be doing this when I was stuck in college writing about the epidermis.\r\n\r\nAaron Carlo is an international freelance session stylist signed with Frank Agency. He has worked with magazines like Elle, Look, Company and Glamour, and brands such as l’Oréal, Next and YSL. When he is not doing fashion and beauty shoots and tending to the locks of celebrities including Little Mix, he works with different brands including Headmasters and Hair Rehab London as Creative Image Consultant.\r\n','www.aaroncarlo.com','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 12:15:12','2013-12-19 12:15:12');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (111,'Peter Jones CBE','1','Peter Jones CBE','Go for it in business and ignite your future','Apprenticeships have a vital role to play in addressing the ambition gap of our future workforce, says Peter Jones CBE','What I am constantly blown away by is the talent and ambition of this country’s young people and that makes me happy because Britain’s economic future is in their hands.\r\nThroughout my career, some of the best people I have worked with have been those that have learned their skills through a practical, learning-by-doing approach. These individuals have often bypassed traditional educational routes and come to the workplace with a solid understanding of the real world and the confidence and resilience to succeed.\r\nMy Enterprise Academy is committed to encouraging entrepreneurial activity in the UK by equipping young people with the skills to kick-start their careers. We have found that one of the most successful ways of doing this is through work- and knowledge-based Apprenticeships, arming our young people with first-hand experience.\r\nJust look at Karen Millen, the British fashion designer, and Sir Anthony Bamford, the JCB billionaire, both of whom learned their crafts via Apprenticeship schemes. These Apprenticeship schemes also generate a sustainable economic growth: recent figures show that for every £1 spent on Apprenticeships, £18 is generated for the economy.\r\nThe Apprenticeships of the 21st century provide access to opportunities that other routes may preclude. Take the enterprise Apprenticeships run by us at the Peter Jones Foundation – they are centrally focused on giving young people the practical skills needed to either make or take a job and ignite their future career success.\r\nThis has been our mission since we started and we are fiercely addressing the ambition gap in the UK with Apprenticeship schemes that are dedicated to providing top business and innovation training, at the same time as motivating young people to realise their dreams.\r\nWe are proud to have recently launched the Level 5 Higher Apprenticeship in Innovation and Growth. It is a unique programme, which is designed to nurture ‘intrapreneurial’ qualities – the abilities and skills needed to energise and innovate a company from within.\r\nYoung people that choose this route are offered the opportunity to combine learning in the classroom with real life practical experience that will fast-track them into jobs with promising progression prospects.\r\nApprenticeships have a vital role to play in the education and preparation of our future workforce, the growth and innovation of our businesses and, ultimately, the economic growth of our country.\r\nThese same Apprenticeships will be the key to creating more entrepreneurs in Britain. I am committed to encouraging this next generation of entrepreneurs to go for it in business and gain the skills needed to succeed in our changing workplace.\r\n\r\nPeter Jones CBE is one of Britain’s best known and respected entrepreneurs. He owns a portfolio of businesses ranging from telecoms and leisure, to publishing, media and recruitment. The Dragons’ Den star founded the Peter Jones Enterprise Academy in 2009 with a view to encourage more entrepreneurial activity in the UK based on a philosophy of ‘learning by doing’. The Academy aims to equip future generations of entrepreneurs with the skills and mindset to run their own businesses, thereby supporting the future of the British economy.','www.pjea.org.uk','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 12:23:26','2013-12-19 12:23:26');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (112,'Harriet Vine, Tatty Devine','20','Harriet Vine, Tatty Devine','We believe life should be fun','Harriet Vine, co-founder of jewellery designers Tatty Devine, explains how apprenticeships enable the sharing of technical skills and advice and an exchange of perspectives and ideas','The first thing an aspiring apprentice will learn is that working in the creative industry is totally unpredictable. You could be making giant cherry blossom props for a photo shoot, sampling brand new pieces for an upcoming collection or creating a perspex fried egg bonnet for a fashion show!\r\nWhen we were studying Fine Art at Chelsea School of Art, Rosie and I discovered bin bags full of leather samples in all colours of the rainbow and, after graduation, we turned them into wrist cuffs that we sold on our own stall at Portobello and Spitalfields markets in London. Soon, they appeared in the Millennium issue of Vogue and we were selling them to Harvey Nichols, Urban Outfitters and Whistles. Fourteen years on, we have two London stores, on Brick Lane and Monmouth Street, and a concession in the Oxford Street branch of Selfridges. We create our original designs from scratch and almost all of our jewellery is made by hand in our own workshops in London and Kent.\r\nRight from the start, we’ve never had a big plan or investors – we always thought we were going to be artists. We didn’t have any formal training so we just learnt from experience. When Rosie and I founded Tatty Devine, we had no idea of the ‘proper’ way to do things so we just picked up skills and knowledge as we went along. That’s the great thing about apprenticeship schemes – you’re working alongside and learning first hand from people who have already made the journey. So many creatives go through education thinking they don’t need to learn about running a business, but you definitely do!\r\nApprenticeships play a hugely important role for businesses and those entering the creative industry, enabling the sharing of technical skills and advice and an exchange of perspectives and ideas. More importantly, they also give you the chance to get involved in the day-to-day processes behind a creative business and provide invaluable practical experience. Whether you want to start your own enterprise or become part of a creative collective, it will give you an idea of the level of hard work, determination and passion needed to make it a success.\r\n\r\nTatty Devine is an independent British company designing and micro-manufacturing original jewellery in the UK. Their jewellery blurs the boundaries between art, fashion and culture, with perhaps the most recognisable pieces being their personalised, perspex Name Necklaces, which are available in 30 colours.\r\nHarriet Vine and Rosie Wolfenden met at art school and founded Tatty Devine together in 1999. They continue to run things from a studio in London’s East End, where it all started, and almost all the jewellery is made by hand in their workshops in London and Kent. In 2013 Harriet and Rosie were awarded MBEs for services to the fashion industry. They are proud to represent British design around the world and, as Tatty Devine continues to grow, they stick to their principles of keeping production in the UK. Above all, they are always motivated by fun.','www.tattydevine.com','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 12:28:52','2013-12-19 12:28:52');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (113,'Jo Mackie','22','Jo Mackie','A super way to start in retail','There are real benefits to taking an Apprenticeship, says Superdrug’s Jo Mackie','Superdrug and Savers have established a real heritage in investing in the Apprenticeship programme and have been involved since 2007, since when over 700 people have gained an Apprenticeship.\r\nI believe there are real tangible benefits to taking an Apprenticeship, including motivation, staff retention and career progression. We launched our 16- to 18-year-old School Leaver Apprenticeship Programme in 2012 and currently have around 100 young people completing their Retail Level Two Apprenticeship. This new programme offers teenagers the opportunity to gain valuable work experience in the retail world on a 12 month fixed-term contract, as well as a qualification. While there is no guarantee apprentices will be offered a role at the end of the year, 72% of young people who joined the first wave of the programme in Savers were offered a permanent position.\r\nCurrently we have around 300 colleagues on Apprenticeships in Superdrug and Savers, working towards qualifications including Retail (Levels 2 and 3), Team leading (Level 2), Management (Level 3), Business administration (Levels 2 and 3) and, finally, Warehousing and storage (Level 2).\r\nAnyone interested in finding out more about the Superdrug School Leaver Apprenticeship programme should visit their local store.\r\n\r\nJo Mackie is HR Director for Superdrug and Savers. The beauty chain has more than 1000 stores nationwide. Jo has worked for A.S. Watson since 2005. She started off working for Savers in the office in Darlington and had a really great time working with the team there. In 2007 she moved south with her family to take up the role of HR Director for Health and Beauty UK – Superdrug and Savers.\r\n“What a great opportunity!” says Jo. “I\'ve had a fantastic 5+ years with both businesses. We\'ve done loads of work and I\'m so proud of what the team have achieved.\r\n“We’re very focused now on how we can really engage people with the business. For me it’s all about getting the right person in the first place, giving the right learning and development opportunities, making sure that the rewards and benefits fit and that the policies and procedures wrap it all up.”','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:08:34','2013-12-19 14:08:34');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (114,'John Pettigrew','18','John Pettigrew is the UK Chief Operating Officer of National Grid','Powering the grid','Apprenticeships bring creative, determined, team-led individuals to the energy industry, says John Pettigrew of National Grid','At National Grid our job is to connect people to the energy they use, safely. We own and manage the grids to which many different sources of energy are connected in the UK and the northeast of the United States, and employ over 27,000 people.\r\nOur ‘connecting’ role puts us at the heart of one of the greatest engineering and scientific challenges facing our society – delivering clean energy to support our world long into the future. We are proud that our work and our people underpin the prosperity and wellbeing of our customers and communities, and we are committed to developing and nurturing a range of people with the awareness, skills and enthusiasm to rise to this challenge.\r\nThe energy sector has a long-standing ‘grow our own’ approach, with Advanced and Higher Apprenticeships being a key aspect of this. Apprenticeships are an exceptional experience for learners, offering a blend of on- and off-the-job training and experiences. They also create a sustainable talent feed into our organisations, bringing in creative, determined, team-led individuals who want to make the most of their potential.\r\nThis talent feed will become ever more important in the coming years, as Apprenticeships will play a major part in addressing critical skills issues such as an ageing workforce, replacement and growth of electrical infrastructure, rapid advancement of new technologies and strong competition for talent in the marketplace – all of which will impact the industry over the next 5–15 years.\r\nTo support growth in Apprenticeships, at National Grid we are investing in our training facilities, building further practical gas and electricity training workshops, increasing our Internal Apprenticeship Trainer capability and our on-site accommodation facilities. All this will ensure that we continue to deliver leading-edge Apprenticeship programmes which are graded by Ofsted as Outstanding in every category, endorsed in the excellent feedback we receive from apprentices, both formally and informally.\r\nI started my personal journey in the energy industry 20 years ago and in that time I have benefited greatly from the development opportunities provided by National Grid’s programmes. The mix of practical experience, training support and advice has been invaluable and those themes remain at the heart of our Apprenticeships today.\r\n','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:13:07','2013-12-19 14:13:07');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (115,'Tim Williams','6','Tim Williams is Financial Controller for Manchester United','Not just a numbers game','Tim Williams is financial controller for Manchester United and knows a thing or two about the best ways into the accountancy profession','If you look back to the relatively recent history of the accounting profession, there are a few key innovations and developments that have changed the job we do beyond recognition. First, there was the electronic calculator, which made the simple adding up of numbers much quicker and far more accurate. Secondly, more importantly, and actually during my lifetime, was the advent of the computerised spreadsheet. This changed everything about my profession. Suddenly, even the most junior accountant could generate relatively complex pieces of financial analysis and, even more suddenly, the accounting profession grew wings, escaped from the desk and became a true business advisor, with the raised profile and the opportunities that came with it.\r\nYou don’t have to do a great deal of research to find that Chartered Accountants regularly transcend the numbers and the finances in companies. In my organisation alone, our chief executive, managing director and chief operating officer are all Chartered Accountants. If you look at other large organisations, the chances are that the head of risk will be a Chartered Accountant, as are many operations directors and chief operating officers. And that’s not an accident; it’s the nature of the work we do and the training we receive – which could arguably be the best training in general business you could ever receive. That’s what appealed to me when I started my career over 20 years ago, and that’s what still appeals to me now.\r\nGoing back 20 years, the standard route into the profession was through A-levels, a degree and then a training contract with an accountancy firm. While that is still the route many take, over the years I have come across many school-leavers who have joined the Apprenticeship and school-leaver programmes offered by the ICAEW through the biggest firms to become excellent accountants. It’s a brilliant route to take if you want to start working, training and learning straight away and are fearful of the burden of three years of tuition fees and university debt, or just simply don’t want to go! In today’s world, it’s far less of a stigma not to have a degree. A Higher Apprenticeship in Assurance/Audit will give you a great insight into what an exciting and varied career accountancy is. Or you can study levels 1 to 4 of the AAT’s Diploma in Accounting as an Apprenticeship. This will give you valuable knowledge and experience that will count towards the ACA qualification if you decide you want to become an ICAEW Chartered Accountant.\r\nAs a recruiter of many qualified professionals over the years, I put huge emphasis on the ability to communicate effectively across finance and non-finance people, to be able to think creatively about ways around problems and, increasingly, to be able to write and speak well – and I worry far less about the route a candidate took to get there.\r\nAnyone with a spreadsheet can call themselves an accountant. It’s the wider skills we’ve learned during our training and in the workplace that mean we can be proud to call ourselves Chartered Accountants.\r\n\r\nA passion for a great brand and an exciting organisation full of equally passionate people led Tim Williams to his current role as Financial Controller for Manchester United. He looks after the day-to-day running of a busy finance department of some 30 people, comprising financial reporting, payables, receivables and payroll (including all player wages). His days are incredibly varied, and can involve anything from ad hoc analysis of the overall business, updating budgets and forecasts when players are bought and sold to making sure that all the cash from a match the day before has been counted. The aspect of his role that takes up a lot of time, but isn’t strictly down to the numbers, is to ensure that, as far as possible, each one of the 30 or so members of his staff are happy, challenged and working to the best of their abilities and that the mix of skills is right for the current and future business needs.','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:17:30','2013-12-19 14:17:30');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (116,'Raymond Blanc','4','Raymond Blanc','Best of British','Britain must develop its home-grown talent says Raymond Blanc','I am completely self-taught and it was hard. I longed for a mentor to guide me through my career.\r\nSince opening Le Manoir aux Quat\' Saisons in 1984 I have taken great pride in training young people. I am so proud that some 30 or so of these chefs have gone on to win Michelin stars and hundreds of others are now head chefs. My oldest apprentice started in 1979 and now he is a Director of the Raymond Blanc Cookery School.\r\nI have continued this process at all 19 of my Brasserie Blanc restaurants and when I heard about the Mayor of London’s Apprenticeship programme I saw a way in which I could contribute still further.\r\nThe food and hospitality sector employs around 300,000 people in London alone: of these only 5,000 are apprentices. As such there is potential for businesses to get involved and help introduce young people to a sector that offers such a range of fantastic opportunities.\r\nAt Brasserie Blanc we are taking on 21 apprentices, not only in London but across the UK. They will work in a range of hospitality roles, including trainee chefs and front of house staff.\r\nAged between 16 and 19, the apprentices will be assigned a mentor within the business and will also be assessed and supported by the De Vere Training Academy, representatives from which will meet with them on a monthly basis.\r\nOur Apprenticeship programme will be split into modules, some of which are based around NVQs. Each apprentice will receive a final certificate on completion.\r\nAs employers, we want to provide a nurturing, caring environment to give young people the very best chance to succeed. I know that all of my colleagues also believe that it is vital that the restaurant and hospitality sector develops our home-grown talent and that we pass on the necessary skills for the future. Long term, our businesses will gain from it.\r\n\r\nRaymond Blanc was born in Besançon in eastern France. The area boasts some of the best dairy, meat and fish of France, and his mother used only fresh, local and seasonal produce to cook tasty meals for her family. Raymond arrived in England in 1972, to work as a waiter at the Rose Revived near Witney. When the Head Chef became ill, Raymond took over in the kitchen. Using the knowledge and love of food that he inherited from his mother, the restaurant soon gained an entry in the Michelin Guide. His success continues to this day, and Le Manoir Aux Quat’ Saisons and his Brasserie Blancs have won many awards.','www.brasserieblanc.com','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:20:22','2013-12-19 14:20:22');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (117,'Sajid Javid MP','23','Sajid Javid MP','Upgrading the nation’s skills base','Sajid Javid MP took on an apprentice to help deal with his parliamentary and constituency responsibilities','During my time as Parliamentary Private Secretary to the then Skills Minister John Hayes, I saw for myself how his energy and dedication resulted in the reinvigoration of our approach to, and provision of, Apprenticeships. He relentlessly promoted and expanded Apprenticeships and was determined to make sure that vocational learning was recognised as being of equal value to academic education. The new Skills Minister, Matthew Hancock, has continued this good work with equal enthusiasm.\r\nIt was very apparent to me that apprentices bring real benefits to the organisations that take them on, while developing skills and earning qualifications for themselves, so I decided to hire an apprentice for my Westminster office. Not only would this help me to deal even more efficiently with my Parliamentary and constituency responsibilities, it would also be an excellent opportunity for a young and motivated person starting out on their career path to gain significant experience of the workplace.\r\nWorking with the National Apprenticeship Service, I quickly found an exemplary apprentice, Dominic Woodbridge, who greatly aided the functioning of my office. Dominic had just completed his A-levels and had decided to take the vocational route rather than go to university. He was employed as my apprentice at the House of Commons, and spent the first three months being introduced to the parliamentary calendar and associated deadlines. He was responsible for the management of appointments requests and visited my constituency in Bromsgrove on several occasions to gain a clear understanding of the environment I work in and the people I represent.\r\nDominic was a perfect example of everything that an apprentice should be. He quickly proved himself to be an extremely capable young man and his dedication to learning and improving himself while at work was clear.\r\nTo anyone considering becoming an apprentice, I would urge you to grasp this opportunity. It takes a great deal of confidence and self-awareness to decide that you would rather pursue professional experience instead of further study at university, and most employers will value this mature and foresightful approach.\r\nApprenticeships are a sure-fire route to both upgrading the nation’s skill base and helping younger people start their working lives, and I have absolutely no hesitation in recommending them as a first-class way of starting a career.\r\n\r\nSajid Javid is Member of Parliament for Bromsgrove and Financial Secretary to the Treasury. Born in Rochdale, England, his father was a bus driver, and he attended state schools before winning a place at Exeter University to study Economics and Politics. He joined the Conservative Party in 1988 and has been an active volunteer ever since.\r\nDominic Woodbridge was employed as Sajid’s apprentice in the House of Commons. When Sajid was made Parliamentary Private Secretary (PPS) to George Osborne, this provided Dominic with increased responsibility, which has gone on to develop following Sajid’s promotion to Economic Secretary to the Treasury.','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:27:07','2013-12-19 14:27:07');
INSERT INTO `case_studies` (`id`,`heading`,`sector_id`,`company_name`,`title`,`standfirst`,`description`,`website`,`hyperlink`,`email_address`,`telephone_number`,`logo_image`,`photo`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (118,'Ollie Hynd','14','Ollie Hynd','Strokes of success','Paralympic swimmer Ollie Hynd believes that completing an Advanced Apprenticeship in Sporting Excellence (AASE) was an important step to becoming an elite athlete','As part of the Advanced Apprenticeship in Sporting Excellence (AASE) programme I was able to focus on a lot of aspects of my sport, like nutrition, sport science and mental edge strategies. This was a massive help for me, especially in the lead up to the London 2012 Games. It was great to get to work with different people and share knowledge, and it enabled me to bring together all of the aspects that go into being an elite athlete.\r\nThe programme worked so well alongside my training as it enabled me to focus on the aspects that enhance my all-round performance. Along with the flexibility and massive help I received from the programme staff, the AASE programme was ideal for me as an elite athlete, and I was so happy to gain the qualification as well as my sporting achievements.\r\nIn the future, I plan to continue swimming and representing Great Britain at an international level. I hope to compete at Rio 2016. Outside of the pool I want to use the knowledge I gained from my Apprenticeship to pursue more coaching qualifications, and use my skills to give back to the sport by helping young people learn to swim.\r\n\r\nOllie Hynd won gold, silver and bronze medals in his Paralympic debut at the London 2012 Games. Following this success, the 18-year-old was delighted to be recognised in the National Apprenticeship Service’s Hall of Fame, which showcases the rise and accomplishments of England’s most successful apprentices. As an AASE graduate and triple medallist, Ollie cites his Apprenticeship as an important step in realising his potential and reaching the level of an elite athlete.\r\n\r\nOllie completed his Apprenticeship with IoS Training. For further information on IoS Apprenticeships and to view current vacancies visit swimming.org/ios/apprenticeships/about-apprenticeships','','','','',NULL,'','2013-12-19 14:30:14','2013-12-19 14:30:14');
INSERT INTO `choosing_an_apprenticeships` (`id`,`skills`,`travel`,`employers`,`qualifications`,`training`,`money`,`created_at`,`updated_at`) VALUES (1,'<p>Taking an Apprenticeship doesn’t restrict you to one specific job role.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You’ll pick up a number of skills that’ll make you more attractive to other employers, basic ones like <b>teamwork</b> and <b>health and safety awareness</b>, as well as more <b>specialised</b> skills.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>All Apprenticeships include:</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A <b>competencies qualification</b> – to show that you can perform the skill, trade or occupation your Apprenticeship requires. You’ll need to achieve this to qualify for your Apprenticeship certificate.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>A <b>technical knowledge qualification</b> – to show you have the necessary technical skills, knowledge and understanding of theoretical concepts as well as knowledge and understanding of the relevant industry and its market.</p>\r\n\r\n<p><b>Key Skills</b> (e.g. team-working, problem solving, communication and using new technology) or <b>Functional Skills</b> to help you achieve a good standard of literacy and numeracy. </p>','<p>Except for obvious exceptions like seafishing, most\r\nApprenticeships are offered all over the country.</p><p>You should be able to find something that suits you in your local area – but\r\nif you want to move somewhere new, an Apprenticeship could be the\r\nideal springboard.\r\n</p>\r\n','<p>Search for employers that offer Apprenticeship schemes by industry sector or use the regional map to find employers in your area.</p>\r\n','<p>There are three levels of Apprenticeship:</p><p><b>Intermediate Level</b> – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 2 NVQ (equivalent to five GCSEs at grades A–C).</p><p><b>Advanced Level</b> – gain a work-based qualification such as a Level 3 NVQ (equivalent to two A-levels).</p><p><b>Higher Apprenticeship</b>\r\n – work towards a work-based qualification such as a Level 4 NVQ and, in\r\n some cases, a knowledge-based qualification such as a Foundation \r\nDegree.<br></p>\r\n','<p>All Apprenticeships deliver <b>high-quality, nationally\r\nrecognised qualifications</b> relevant to the skill, trade or occupation of the learner\r\nand employer.</p><p>As an apprentice you will receive <b>at least 280 hours of\r\nguided learning every year</b>.</p><p>Apprenticeships offer appropriate training to achieve a good\r\nstandard of <b>literacy</b> and <b>numeracy</b> (and <b>ICT</b> where relevant to the skill, trade\r\nor occupation).</p><p><b>Keeping up standards</b></p><p>The Specification of Apprenticeship Standards for England (SASE)\r\nsets out the minimum requirements to be included in a recognised\r\nApprenticeship, ensuring that every Apprenticeship delivers <b>training that\r\ndirectly meets the needs of employers and learners</b>.\r\n</p>','<p><b>Salary</b>\r\n</p><p>The National Minimum Wage is £2.65 per hour for apprentices under 19, or those who are aged 19 or over but are in the first year of their Apprenticeship.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Many employers will pay you more as you develop your skills and the average apprentice takes home around £170 per week.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Research shows that apprentices earn, on average, around £73,000 more over their lifetime than other employees, and this figure rises to £100,000 for those who have completed an Advanced Level Apprenticeship.</p><p><b>Funding</b><br></p><p>Your employer will pay your salary and support you in your training.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>Most of your learning will happen at work, but some might take place with a training provider.</p>\r\n\r\n<p>You won’t have to pay any fees: if you are aged between 16 and 18, the Government will pay the full cost of your training (if you’re over 19, your employer may be expected to contribute to your training costs).</p><p>If you’re\r\naged 24 or older, you can apply for a<span> 24+ Advanced Learning Loan\r\n</span>to help with the costs of a\r\ncollege or training course. See www.gov.uk/advanced-learning-loans for more details.<br></p>\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n<p>Your employer will work with you to try and support your individual requirements.</p><p><br></p>\r\n','2012-09-28 16:08:24','2013-02-05 11:11:13');
